<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="ACT" stage="Final" version="N">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="John Wimbish" created="2009-10-05 05:46:44Z" when="2009-10-05 05:46:44Z" stage="Draft">CRS, UKAW; first drafted by Lazarus Aplugi; consultants/advisors C&amp;B Grimes; team revision from Kupang by Lazarus and Michael Sina; Ayub and Chuck in Darwin March 2002 (Acts 1-17); Lazarus Aplugi, Michael Sina and Chuck in Kupang May 2002 (Acts 18-28); UNS 2-@ June 2003 in Kupang at Gereja Paulus with Chuck, Michael, Lazarus A., Lazarus L., and Paul (UNS's below); consultant checked by Marge Crofts, October 2003 in Kupang; checked *priest, a'a-ari, Jahudi, June 2007</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Lii Lole nèti Dhèu Pajuu-Paleha sèra</p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Lii Lole<bt>Story(s)</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">nèti dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus<bt>from/about *apostles (servants/emissaries) of the *Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua moa pa'adhu mai Roh Mola-Mèci Na<bt>*God (Lord Father) promises to send the *Holy Spirit</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1-3" />Ama Teofilus<bt>Father Teofilus</bt><note reference="1:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ngara <span class="Italic">Teofilus </span>ètu d'ara Lii Yunani, sasoa na, &lt;dhèu dhu sue Ama Lamatua&gt;. Ne'e ne, buku ka dua dhu Lukas suri hia Teofilus. Ladhe kahèi <span class="Italic">Lukas </span>1:1-4.<bt>The name Teofilus in the Yunani (Greek) language, &lt;Teofilus&gt; means, &lt;person who loves God&gt;. This here is the second book which Lukas has written to Teofilus. See also Lukas 1:1-4.</bt></note>dhu be'a. Lii maho'o nèti ja'a, Lukas.<bt>who is good [= letter convention like "dear Theo"]. Greetings from me, Lukas.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'adhu = / pa-adhu / ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pa'adhu = / pa-adhu / ; maho'o =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ètu d'ara sasuri ja'a dhu uru èèna, ja'a suri aa'i mèu-mèu lula-nèti mamuri Lamatua Yesus. Nuka, ngaa dhu Na tao, dènge ngaa dhu Na aj'a-nori, karèi nèti uru tèka. Na hag'e nare dhèu pajuu-paleha Na. Masi ka dhèu paj'èra Ne, aa ra pamadhe Ne, te ngaa Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne. Ropa Na kèd'i nèti mamadhe, Na pad'elo iisi mi dhèu pajuu-paleha Na. Ra rèdhi Ne padhutu-dhutu toke d'ai èpa nguru lod'o, ka ra re'a, Na mamuri hari tare'a. Nèngu peka dènge rèngu, na, Ama Lamatua sama sèmi Dhèu Aae dhu nèd'u paredha. Ka Na pua rèngu kahèi pake koasa nèti Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci. Lii dhu ja'a suri ne, lole ngaa-ngaa dhu Na tao nèti uru, toke d'ai Na ca'e hari asa sorga.<bt>In my previous writing/letter, I wrote everything about the life of the *Lord Yesus. That is, everything He did, and everything He taught, since the beginning. That, He chose His *apostles. Even though people cause Him to suffer, and they killed Him (impersonal construction; non-referential "they"), nevertheless God caused Him to live again.When He got up from death, He revealed Himself to His *servants/disciples. They saw Him repeatedly for 40 days, so they knew He was really alive again. He taught them that God was like a *King who holds rule (=governs). And He sent/commissioned/instructed them using power/authority from the Spirit of God which is Holy. Up until He went up again to *heaven (loan).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhutu = berikut ; padhutu-dhutu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">padhutu = berikut ; padhutu-dhutu = ulang-ulang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Se'e se ka dhu ja'a suri kèdhi le.<bt>It is all that which I have already written.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ètu dara sasuri ja'a dhu uru"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Ètu dara sasuri ja'a dhu uru na, ja'a suri aa'i ngaa dhu Lamatua Yesus sab'e, sèmi èèna kahèi, dènge ngaa dhu Na aj'a-nori, karèi nèti Na bhoke sasab'a,; 3: toke dai Na ca'e hari asa sorga. Masi ka ra pamadhe Ne le, te ngaa Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne. Ropa Na kèdi nèti mamadhe, Na pad'elo iisi mi ana-ana pajuu-paleha Na. Ra rèdhi Ne padhutu-dhutu toke dai èpa nguru lod'o, ka ra re'a, Na mamuri hari tare'a le. Na peka dènge rèngu na, Ama Lamatua èèna, sama sèmi Dhèu Aae dhu nèd'u paredha. Ka dhèu-dhèu dhu Na hag'e nare sèra, Na pua-paleha si, pake koasa Ama Lamatua.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4-5" />Ca lod'o hari, ropa Yesus pa'èci dènge dhèu pajuu-paleha Na ètu dedha Ledhe Saitun, Na hia si paredha peka na,<bt>One day, when Yesus was together with His emissaries/apostles on the Saitun Mountain [setting stage from vs.12], He gave them a command saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Sanèd'e! Uru èèna, Yohanis sarani dhèu pake dhoka èi di, te ngaa ladhe miu mate hari pèri-pèri lod'o, èèna na Lamatua tao ngaa dhu kapai risi eele hia miu. Lula Na hia miu Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci. De baku tèke eele kota Yerusalem kahèi. Te ngaa miu mate mi ne'e, toke d'ai Ama Ku papuru Roh Na mi dedha miu, sèmi dhu Na moa le uru èèna. Aa miu tadèngi le nèti Ja'a kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;Remember! Previously Yohanis *baptised people using only water, but if you(pl) wait several days, then the Lord will do something even greater/better for you(pl). Cause He (will) give you His Spirit (loan) who is *Holy (doublet). And/but2 you must not leave behind the city of Yerusalem first. But you should wait here until My Father sends down His Spirit upon you, as He has promised before. And you here have also heard Me say this (previously).&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="1:4-5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 24:49, Mateos 3:11, Markus 1:8, Lukas 3:16, Yohanis 1:33</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus ca'e asa sorga<bt>The Lord Yesus ascends to heaven</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ropa Yesus pakaboko dènge dhèu pajuu-paleha Na era, ra karèi Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i neo karèi: Ama sanèd'e era, sina ma, dhu uru èèna, kabarai èdhi Isra'el paredha unu na? De Ama neo patabuli èdhi nèti dhèu leo deo ne'e, do, mate hari lod'o leo?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yesus gathered together again with His servants/disciples. And they asked Him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! We(exc) want to ask: Do you (Father) remember long ago, when the <span class="Italic">kabarai</span> (1) citizens/populace, 2) kingdom/country) of Isra'el was still governing itself? Are you going to free us(inc) from other (foreign) people now, or should (we) wait for a different time?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabarai = masyarakat ; pakèdi kabarai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kabarai = masyarakat ; pakèdi kabarai ...dhu èra = bangun masyarakat yg kuat;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Deo ne'e ne ka, Ama neo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Deo ne'e ne ka, Ama neo pakèdi hari kabarai Isra'el dhu èra, sèmi uru èèna kèna, do mate lod'o mia hari?&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01882b.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:none">Lamatua Yesus padhai lii dènge ana madhutu Na<bt>The Lord Yesus speaks with His *disciples/followers</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu pakarèi ia ka lod'o èèna! Dhoka Ama ku di, dhu pama'ète j'aj'aj'i lod'o èèna na.<bt>Then Yesus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;You(pl) don't need to inquire after the timing! It is only My Father, who decides/sets the time of that happening.</bt><v n="8" />Te ngaa ladhe Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci mai maso asa d'ara miu, heka miu abhu koasa kèna. Hèia miu hud'i lami palolo dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra lula-nèti Ja'a. Miu peka dènge dhèu ètu kota Yerusalem, ètu rae aa'i-aa'i ètu propensi Yudea dènge propensi Samaria, taruu toke d'ai suu-suu rai-haha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>But later if/when the Spirit of God who is Holy comes, and enters into you(pl), only.then will you get power (assim. loan). So then you must go tell2/report to everybody/all people about Me. Tell everybody in the city of Yerusalem, and also in the villages in the province of Yudea, and the province of Samaria, on until the corners of this world.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="1:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 28:19, Markus 16:15, Lukas 24:47-48</note><v n="9" />Ropa Na padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, Ama Lamatua paca'e Yesus asa dedha-liru la'e ètu katanga madha rèngu. Ra ladhe taruu, toke d'ai ra'i-liru hutu nare Ne, ka rèngu rèdhi heka.<bt>When He had finished speaking like that, suddenly God caused to ascend Yesus up into the upper sky/heaven right in front of them. They kept watching until the clouds enclosed Him, and they no longer saw (Him).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lula = tentang ; propensi; |b9:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lula = tentang ; propensi; <span class="Bold">9:</span> katanga madha = muka idong, deng mata kapala ; katanga = complex, polysemous</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 16:19, Lukas 24:50-51</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa rèngu ladhe asa dedha-liru era, cag'ag'a laa, dhèu dua titu ètu karasa rèngu, dhu pake mèdha-papake pudhi lao-lao.<bt>While they were still looking up into the sky, suddenly2, two people clothed in clean white (=Max degree) stood next to them.</bt><v n="11" />Dhèu dua sèra peka dènge rèngu, na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Miu dhèu Galilea! Nga tao ka miu tangare taruu asa dedha-liru? Deo na miu mèdhi le Yesus ca'e toke d'ai ra'i-liru hutu nare Ne. Miu mèdhi unu mi dènge musi madha miu, Na ca'e la'e deo na. Sèmi mia dhu miu ladhe mèdhi Na ca'e la'e èèna, sèmi èèna kahèi èèna na Nèngu mai hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>Those two people spoke to them like this, &lt;&lt;Wee! You Galilea people here! Why do you keep staring up at the sky? You Just now saw Yesus go up, until the clouds closed over Him. You saw yourselves with your own eyes Him going up just now. Just as you saw (Him) go up, in the same way also He will come again in the future.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ladhe = lihat ; ladhe èna"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ladhe = lihat ; ladhe èna = nanti ; ladhe leru = piara/ jaga ; tangare = memperhatikan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra tenge dhèu leo ho gati Yudas<bt>They look for a different person to replace Yudas</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu pajuu-paleha Yesus sèra puru nèti ledhe Saitun lèpa lasi asa kota Yerusalem. Ledhe Saitun èèna, ele boe kaj'èu nèngu d'ai ca kilo di nèti d'ara kota.<bt>After that, the servants/emissaries of Yesus descended from Saitun (loan: Arab &gt; Indo) mountain returning to the city of Yerusalem. That Saitun mountain, its distance was approx (Idiom) one kilo from the city.</bt><note reference="1:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lod'o èèna, mese agama Yahudi sèra tao atora, peka na, ètu lod'o a'oro sasab'a, dhèu Yahudi bisa boe kako kaj'èu. Ra ator ho dhèu baku kako risi nèti dua kilo (lasi-mai). Sasuri lii Yunani dhu uru tèka, peka na, kaj'èu ledhe ne nèti Yerusalem, sama dènge &lt;&lt;bagi dua j'ara nèti kakako lod'o a'oro sasab'a&gt;&gt;. De èdhi te'a, kaj'èu ledhe èèna nèti kota, ca kilo di.<bt>At that time, Jahudi religious teachers made a regulation saying that on the day of resting from work, Jahudi people could not walk far. They regulated that people must not walk more than two kilos. The old Yunani writings, said that this mountain's distance from Yerusalem was &lt;&lt;dividing in two the distance of a walk on the day of stopping work&gt;&gt;. Thus, we(inc) know that mountain's distance from the city is one kilo.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />D'ai nèi, ka ra lasi asa d'ara èmu dhu rèngu pea. Ka ra ca'e asa kama èci ètu èmu dedha. Ngara dhèu pajuu-paleha sèra, nuka:<bt>Arriving yonder, they went into the house where they were staying. And they went up to a room at the top of the house. The names of those servants/emissaries, were like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Petrus,<bt>Petrus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yohanis,<bt>Yohanis,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yakobis,<bt>Yakobis,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Anderias,<bt>Anderias,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pelipus,<bt>Pelipus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tomas,<bt>Tomas,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Bertolomeos,<bt>Bartolomeos,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Mateos,<bt>Mateos,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yakobis (ana Alpius),<bt>Yakobis (child of Alpius),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Simon (dhu madhutu partei Selot),<bt>Simon (who follows the Selot party (loan)),</bt><note reference="1:13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Partei &lt;Selot&gt; dènge ngara na èci hari, &lt;Patriot&gt;. Simon ne maso anggota partei politik dhu neo cab'ub'u eele dhèu paredha Roma ngèti kabarai Isra'el rèngu.<bt>The word &lt;Selot&gt; and &lt;Patirot&gt; mean, this Simon was a member (loan) of a political party which wanted to expel the Roma government people from their country.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge Yudas (ana Yakobis).<bt>and Yudas (child of Yakobis).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalaga dedha = loteng atas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kalaga dedha = loteng atas</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:2-4, Markus 3:16-19, Lukas 6:14-16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra dhu tema pakaboko ho manèngi-mangaj'i dènge d'ara èci. Maria, ina Yesus, aa dhèu bhèni-dhèu bhèni leo, dènge a'ari Yesus sèra pakaboko dènge rèngu kahèi.<bt>All of them usually gathered to *pray (doublet: request-worship) with one inside (=purpose &amp; spirit). Maria, the mother of Yesus, and other women, with Yesus siblings also gathered with them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ca tèka hari, rèngu pakaboko, ele boe dhèu d'ai cangasu dua nguru dhèu sa. Ka Petrus kèd'i titu, ka na padhai lii, aku nèngu na,<bt>One time, they were gathered, there were approx 120 people. And Peturs stood up, and spoke, saying,</bt><v n="16" />&lt;&lt;Ina-ama, a'ari aa'i-aa'i ti! Èle boe miu sanèd'e Yudas era, dhu uru èèna nèti anga na canau, ho lasi kèpe Yesus. Ngaa dhu Yudas tao, mema hud'i j'aj'i sèmi èèna ku. Te nèti uru ka, Roh Ama Lamatua peka le, dènge dhèu aae Daud, ho suri tatao Yudas.<bt>&lt;&lt;Mother-father, elder-younger siblings (inclus)! You(pl) certainly still remember Yudas, who had brought his group to catch Yesus. That which Yudas did, really had to happen like that. Cause from long ago, The Spirit of God had spoken, through *King Daud, to write about those deeds of Juda's .</bt><v n="17" />Te Yudas èèna, dhèu èdhi dhu sab'a pa'èci dènge èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cause that Yudas, was our(inc) person, who worked together with us.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />(Te ngaa ropa Yudas pahie eele Yesus, ka rare doi papana èèna, lasi hèli rare rai cue. Rai èèna ka dhu j'aj'i era mamadhe nèngu. Na bèbhe sagèb'a ètu era èèna, ka masèke eele kabake na, hèia tanèi na talala.<bt>(But, when Yudas sold out Yesus, they took that hot money, and went to buy a piece of land. It is that land which was the place of his death. He fell face.down at that place, and his abdomen split open, so.that his guts spilled out.</bt><v n="19" />Ka dhèu palolo lème, toke d'ai isi kabarai kota Yerusalem re'a aa'i mèu-mèu mamadhe Yudas èèna. Nèti èèna ka, ra pangare rai èèna madhutu lii Aram, ngara na <span class="Italic">&lt;Akeldama&gt;,</span> sasoa na, &lt;rai raa&gt;.)<bt>And people told that story around, until all the contents/inhabitans of the city of Yerusalem knew all about that death of Juda's. That is why they called that land according to the Aram language, its name is, &lt;<span class="Italic">Akeldama</span>&gt;, meaning, &lt;blood land&gt;.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sag'èba = matono ; tanèi ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sag'èba = matono ; tanèi = tali paru, papana</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:18-19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 27:3-8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Petrus tuhu hari lii padhai na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Uru-uru sèra, dhèu aae Daud suri tèke le ètu d'ara sasuri Lii Sod'a Koa-kio, peka na,<bt>Petrus continued to speak, saying, &lt;&lt;Long ago, King Daud wrote in the book of Masmur (loan: Arab &gt; Indo), saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Hud'i sène era pea nèngu, j'aj'i mi era dhu pa'ela eele;<bt>&lt;Let his residence/living place, become a place which is abandoned/empty;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="era dhu kalau-karèto boe = tampa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">era dhu kalau-karèto boe = tampa sunyi, (lt: place which doesn't move)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bisa heka dhèu èci sa pea ètu èèna.&gt;<bt>not one person may stay in that place.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Aa na suri kahèi, aku nèngu na,<bt>And he also wrote, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Hud'i sène, sasab'a nèngu ra hia asa dhèu leo la'e.&gt;<bt>&lt;May it be that his work they give to a different person.&gt;</bt><note reference="1:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 69:25, 109:8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21-22" />De èdhi hud'i tenge dhèu èci ho gati Yudas. Èdhi tenge dhèu dhu bera-bera dènge èdhi nèti uru ka mai. Dhèu èèna, hud'i dhèu dhu nèbhu le madhutu Yesus la'e-mai, mulai nèti Yohanis sarani Yesus. Aa nèngu èèna, hud'i dhèu dhu nèdhi dènge musi madha, na, Yesus kèd'i hari nèti mamadhe Na, toke d'ai lod'o Yesus ca'e hari asa dedha-liru ètu talora èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So we(inc) should look for a person to replace Yudas. We should look for a person who accompanied us from long ago/the beginning. That person, must be someone who for a long time followed Yesus all over the place (lit: going-coming), beginning from Yohanis *baptising Yesus. And that one must be a person who saw with his own eyes that Yesus rose again from His death, until the day Yesus ascended back up to *heaven from among us.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nèti era èci dai era èci,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">nèti era èci dai era èci,</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 3:16, Markus 1:9, 16:19, Lukas 3:21, 24:51</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ropa Petrus peka nare sèmi èèna, ka dhèu dhu pakaboko sèra, pamaso ngara dhèu dua. Èci ngara na Matias, aa èci hari ngara na Yusuf (dhu tema le ra paroa na Barsabas; ngara na leo èci hari, na, Yustus).<bt>When Petrus spoke like that, those people who were gathered, put in the names of two people. One was named Matias, and the other one was named Yusuf (who they normally called Barsabas, the sibling of Yustus).</bt><v n="24-25" />Hèia ra sabaj'a, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama ètu dedha-liru! Ama dhu me'a iie d'ara dhèu aa'i-aa'i. Yudas madhe le, tèke eele sasab'a na. De Ama paj'uj'u hia ji'i dhèu èci nèti rèngu dua se, mia dhu Ama d'èi, ho ji'i ded'e ne j'aj'i mi dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they prayed2 saying, &lt;&lt;Father in heaven! Father knows well everyone's insides/thoughts/character. Yudas has died leaving behind his work. So Father point/designate for us(exc) a person, from these two here, which (one) Father desires, so we can appoint him to be a servant/emissary of the Lord Yesus.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="26" />Ka ra ère lot, pake ngara dhèu dua sèra. Hèia dhu lèke ka Matias. Ka ra ded'e ne j'aj'i dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus, ho na pa'èci dènge rèngu dhèu canguru èci sèra.<bt>And they drew lots (assim. loan) using the names of those two people. Then it matched Matias. And they appointed him to be a servant/emissary of the Lord Yesus, to be united/one with those eleven people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="d'ed'e = angkat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">d'ed'e = angkat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu parcaya abhu Roh Ama Lamatua<bt>People who get the Spirit of God</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1-2" />Lèke lod'o babe'a dhèu Yahudi, dhu ra pangare na &lt;Lod'o Pantekosta&gt;,<bt>On the Jahudi people's holiday [lexicalised &lt; good day], which they name &lt;Pantekosta Day&gt;,</bt><note reference="2:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu Yahudi pa'ige Lod'o Pantekosta, mulai nèti Lod'o Paska, tabha pidhu migu. De èdhi te'a, na, mamadhe Lamatua Yesus lèmi nguru lod'o le.<bt>The Jahudi people count Pantekosta Day, beginning from Paska (=Passover/Easter) Day, adding 7 weeks. So we(inc) know that the Lord Yesus' death had already been 50 days.</bt></note>dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu madhutu Lamatua Yesus pakaboko ètu d'ara èmu cue.<bt>everyone who followed the Lord Yesus gathered in one house. Suddenly, they heard a sound come from the sky, like a wind.storm. That sound was extremely loud, so they couldn't hear other people speaking.</bt><note reference="2:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 23:15-21, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 16:9-11</note>Cag'ag'a laa, ra tadèngi lii dhu mai nèti dedha-liru, sama sèmi bohe. Lii èèna mèdhu titu kèna, ka rèngu bisa boe tadèngi lii dhèu leo dhu ètu sèra.<v n="3" />Hèia rèngu ladhe rèdhi sèmi heo ai sa, dhu puru mi dedha rèngu èci-èci.<v n="4" />Ka rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra abhu Roh Ama Lamatua. Ka ra padhai lii, pake lii dhèu rai-rai leo, madhutu ngaa dhu Roh hia si peka-padhai.<bt>Then they saw as if there were flames which descended on top of each of them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bohe = angin ribut ; mèdhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">bohe = angin ribut ; mèdhu = 1) muntah, 2) keras, kencang; <span class="Bold">3:</span> heo = manyala ; he'o = lidah</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01890b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none">Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, puru mi dedha dhèu unu Yesus sèra<bt>The Lord's *Holy Spirit is divided.out on to Yesus' followers</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu Yahudi ae titu kèna dhu mai nèti lème rai ètu rai-haha ne, pakaboko ètu Yerusalem. D'ara rèngu neo madhutu Ama Lamatua.<bt>That day/time, there were a great many Jahudi people who came from every country/land on this earth, gathering in Yerusalem. Their insides/hearts wanted to follow God.</bt><v n="6" />Ropa ra tadèngi rare lii èèna, ka ra mai lingu rare era èèna. Ka rèngu ca dhèu-dhèu ka, tadèngi lii dhu ana madhutu Lamatua Yesus sèra padhai, èci èèna ka dènge lii rai rèngu. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu sèra malaa-maloha.<bt>When they heard that sound, they came clustering around that place. And each of those people heard the language that the Lord Yesus' followers were speaking, exactly like the language of their own land/country. Because of that those people were amazed/impressed.</bt><v n="7" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra hèb'a nganga-nganga sène, ka ra papeka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Te dhèu se, dhèu Galilea, sina ma?<bt>They were all agape, and they spoke among themselves, saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! These people are Galilea people, right?</bt><v n="8" />Tasamia ka, rèngu bisa padhai lii, tao lii èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti?<bt>So how is it that they are speaking using each/all of our(inc) languages?</bt><v n="9" />Èdhi se'e, mai nèti propensi Partia, Media, Elam, Mesopotamia, Yudea, Kapadokia, Pontus, Asia,<bt>We here, come from the prvinces (loan) of Partia, Media, Elam, Mesopotamia, Yudea, Kapadokia, Pontus, Asia,</bt><v n="10-11" />Frigia, Pamfilia, Masir, nèti Libia dhu dètu dènge kota Kirene, aa èdhi cahag'e mai nèti kota Roma. Aa cahag'e kahèi mai nèti pulu Kreta, dènge nèti rai Arab. Èdhi cahag'e dhèu Yahudi, cahag'e dhèu rai leo dhu maso agama Yahudi. Te ngaa èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti tadèngi rèngu padhai lii, pake lii èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti, lula-nèti j'ara-j'ara kapai titu kèna, dhu Ama Lamatua tao. Te aa'i-aa'i se pamalaa èdhi, nga!&gt;&gt;<bt>Frigia, Pamfilia, Masir, from Libia near the city of Kirene, and some of us(inc) come from the city of Roma. And some also come from the island of Kreta, and from the land/country of Arab. Some of us are Jahudi people, and some are people from other lands who have entered the Jahudi religion. But all of us are hearing them speak using each of our languages, from/about extraordinary things which God has done. This is amazing to us!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lingu = mengelilingi ; karobho ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lingu = mengelilingi ; karobho = makarubu; <span class="Bold">8:</span> tao lii = 1) bekin perkara, 2) omong pake bahasa ; tao lii èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti? = kita semua pung bahasa masing-masing; <span class="Bold">11:</span> pulu = pulau</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="maps\Bible\Hk-pent.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none">Dhèu mai nèti rai-rai kaj'èu, pakaboko ètu Yerusalem<bt>People came from far-away lands, gathering in Yerusalem</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra hèb'a nganga-nganga sène, ka ra pakarèi isi aanga ra, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka j'aj'i sèmi ne'e? Sasoa na, ngaa ka ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>All of them were agape, and they questioned each other, saying, &lt;&lt;How is it that it can happen like this, ee? What is its meaning/significance?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lingu = mengelilingi ; nyanyei ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lingu = mengelilingi ; nyanyei = mengolok = menjulurka lidah ; padhai-kakoli = menceritakan nama baik orang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa abhu dhèu leo dhu mari si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Weeh! Baku pusi dènge dhèu sèi! Te ra mahu nèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>But other people laughed at them, saying, &lt;&lt;We! Don't pay any attention to those people! Cause they're drunk!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padadari = adu ; mari ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">padadari = adu ; mari = 1) ketawa, 2) ejek, olok</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus padhai lii ètu madha dhèu ae<bt>Petrus speaks in front of the crowd</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ètu era èèna, Petrus dènge dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus dhèu canguru èci leo sèra. Ka nèngu kako la'e asa madha, hèia na mulai padhai lii mi dhèu ae dhu lingu ètu èèna. Na padhai lii mèdhu bia, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ina-ama, a'ari aa'i-aa'i ti! Miu dhèu Yahudi, dènge miu dhu mai nèti mia-mia pea ètu kota Yerusalem! Pasa dhilu paie, ho mi nanene lii padhai lii ja'a ne, te ja'a neo peka j'ara hua iia mi miu aa'i-aa'i mi.<bt>At that place, there was Petrus and the other eleven servants/emissaries of Yesus. And Petrus went forward and began to speak to the many people who were clustered there. He spoke loudly/forcefully, saying, &lt;&lt;Mu mother-father, elder-younger siblings [formulaic]! Those of you who are Jahudi people, and those of you who have come from many places to stay here in the city of Yerusalem. Pay close attention, so you can listen to what I have to say here, cause I want to say something important to all of you.</bt><v n="15" />Mage mi pangee, na, dhèu se mahu. Sèmi boe èèna! Mad'ae aae era, dhèu mahu boe. Ngaa hari, heka hake ceo kèna.<bt>Don't think that these people are drunk. It's not like that! It's still early in the morning, people don't get drunk. Especially with it just being 9 strikes (=o'clock).</bt><v n="16" />Deo na miu tadèngi, na, dhèu se padhai lii pake lii miu aa'i-aa'i mi. Dhu lèke, sèmi ne'e ka: uru èèna, Ama Lamatua moa tèke le j'ara ne'e re dhèu nèti lii padhai lii Nèngu, ngara na Yoel, peka na:<bt>Just now you(pl) heard these people speaking using all of your languages. What is correct is like this: Long ago, God already promised this event/happening by means of His *spokesperson/prophet, named Yoel, saying:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="17" />&lt;Ama Lamatua peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe lod'o rai-haha oe èle,<bt>&lt;God says, &lt;&lt;When the days/time of the earth are about to end,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a neo hia Roh Ja'a mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i.<bt>I will give My Spirit to all people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="udhu-bhori"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">udhu-bhori</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ana ngèru miu sèra, bhèni-mone,<bt>Your young people, female-male,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a ded'e si, j'aj'i dhèu rèti lii padhai Ja'a.<bt>I will elevate/appoint them to be My spokespeople.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ana ngèru miu sèra,<bt>Your young people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bèli-camèd'a ladhe rèdhi ngaa dhu Ja'a neo pad'elo mi rèngu.<bt>will see that which I will reveal to them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Sèmi èèna kahèi, dhèu heka miu sèra,<bt>Similarly, your older people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">bèli-camèd'a ra abhu nii, ngaa dhu Ja'a neo pad'elo hia ra rèdhi.<bt>will be able to dream, that which I will reveal for them to see/perceive.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nii = mimpi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">nii = mimpi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="18" />Ladhe lod'o rai-haha oe èle,<bt>When the days/time of the earth is about to end,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a hia Roh Ja'a mi ana pua-paleha Ja'a sèra.<bt>I will give My Spirit to all My children.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Hia dhèu mone,<bt>To the males,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa dhèu bhèni kahèi.<bt>and also to the females [gapping construction].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gapping construction"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">gapping construction</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sèna ka ra peka-padhai ngaa dhu Ja'a peka le dènge rèngu.<bt>And so, they will speak that which I tell them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="19-21" />Bèli-camèd'a, d'ai Lod'o Lamatua. Masi ka Lod'o èèna dhae d'ai mèka,<bt>In the future the Day of the Lord will arrive. Even though that Day has not yet arrived,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bèli camèda"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">bèli camèda</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa Ja'a tao uru tadha-tadha malaa ètu dedha-liru.<bt>nevertheless, I will do *amazing signs in the sky-above.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai-dedha ~ rai-haha OR dedha-liru ~"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rai-dedha ~ rai-haha OR dedha-liru ~ dedha-rai</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Tadha malaa sèmi madha lod'o j'aj'i maroga kiu-kiu,<bt>Amazing signs such as the sun becoming pitch dark [=dark to the Max].</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dènge hèru mea sèmi raa sa kahèi.<bt>and the moon also becoming red like blood.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mea gèu-gèu = sungguh-sungguh merah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">mea gèu-gèu = sungguh-sungguh merah</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ja'a neo tao j'ara-j'ara kapai seli eele kahèi, ètu dedha-rai.<bt>And I will also do incredible things on the earth-below.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="oo ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">oo =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">J'ara sèra sa, sama sèmi raa, ai, dènge sèb'u poka-poka ca'e la'e asa dedha.<bt>Those things are like blood, fire, and smoke billowing upwards into the sky.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="poka-poka = 1) asap membubung 2)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">poka-poka = 1) asap membubung 2) orang naik terus sonde barenti</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ladhe d'ai Lod'o Lamatua dhu kapai seli èèna, dhèu cee dhu manèngi Ama Lamatua soru-bara ne,<bt>When the extraordinary Day of the Lord arrives, whoever requests help from God,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="manèngi tolo/tulu = minta tolong (tolo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">manèngi tolo/tulu = minta tolong (tolo KM = kemaluan laki-laki) maena = mengharapkan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">nèngu èèna ka dhu abhu mamuri.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>s/he is the one(s) [singular from 'whoever', but generic], who will get life/salvation/deliverance.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="2:17-21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yoel 2:28-32</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Sèmi èèna ka, dhu uru èèna, Yoel suri le.<bt>Like that is what Yoel said long ago.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01891b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none">Petrus padhai lii dènge dhèu ae sèra<bt>Petrus speaks to many people</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />A'ari dhèu Isra'el aa'i-aa'i ti! Mai pasa dhilu miu, ho nanene paie ngaa dhu ja'a neo padhai lii dènge miu. Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u nare le Yesus, dhèu Nasaret. Ji'i nge'a le j'ara èèna j'aj'i tare'a, lula ji'i ka dhu ladhe ngèdhi unu mi, na, Ama Lamatua pake Yesus ho tao tadha malaa dènge tatao kapai seli eele. Miu me'a le j'ara ne'e kahèi, lula Yesus tao le tadha malaa sèra ètu talora miu.<bt>Naa! My elder-younger siblings of Isra'el people! Fasten on your ears, so you can listen carefully to what it is I want to say to you now. God has chosendesignated Yesus, that Nasaret person. We(exc) already know that this (has really happened/has become true), because we are the ones who saw for ourselves that God used Yesus to do those impressive signs and unusual deeds. You(pl) already know these things also, because Yesus did those impressive signs in your midst.</bt><v n="23" />Te ngaa miu pamadhe Ne, dènge j'ara miu dadugu-rariu dhèu bhelu-katub'a, ho paku Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Aa te ngaa, sèra sa pamèci dènge naneo Ama Lamatua nèti uru ka mai.<bt>But you(pl) killed Him, in the way that you cajoled evil people to nail Him to the *crossed wood. But, they were fulfilling/matching with the will of God from long ago.</bt><note reference="2:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 27:35, Markus 15:24, Lukas 23:33, Yohanis 19:18</note><v n="24" />Lula tatao miu, ka Nèngu madhe tare'a. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua d'èi boe ho Yesus madhe taruu. Nèti èèna ka, Lamatua patalale eele Nèngu nèti koasa mamadhe, ka pamamuri hari Ne. Te koasa mamadhe bisa boe segi Ne.<bt>Because of these deeds of yours, He really died. But God didn't want Yesus to continue to stay in the place of the dead people. So therefore, the Lord released Him from the place of those dead people, and (gave Him life again/made Him alive again).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ti = Pro we inc; |b23:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ti = Pro we inc; <span class="Bold">23:</span> rariu = buju ; pamèci = cocok; <span class="Bold">24:</span> patalale eele = kasi lapas ;</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 28:5-6, Markus 16:6, Lukas 24:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Nèti uru ka mai, dhèu aae Daud suri tèke le lula-nèti Yesus ne, peka na:<bt>Long ago, King Daud had written about this path/way that Yesus shoulder-carried (=events that Y experienced), like this:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ja'a ke'a, na, Lamatua sama-sama taruu dènge ja'a.<bt>&lt;I know, the Lord is always with me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bera-bera = sama-sama (bahasa tinggi)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">bera-bera = sama-sama (bahasa tinggi)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti èèna ka, ngaa èci sa bisa boe pamanahu ja'a,<bt>That is why there is nothing that can cause me to fall,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula Ama Lamatua ètu baboa ja'a taruu.<bt>because God is always beside me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baboa = samping"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">baboa = samping</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="26" />Nèti èèna ka, d'ara ja'a karej'e,<bt>That is why my insides are happy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ka ja'a koa-kio Ne taruu,<bt>And I do not cease my praises,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa ja'a mate Lamatua dènge d'ara mera-milu.<bt>and I wait for God2, with peaceful/calm (doublet: flat-smooth) insides.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="27" />Te Nèngu soro tèke boe samanga ja'a pea taruu ètu era dhèu madhe sèra.<bt>Cause, He does not give.over/allow my *soul to continue to stay in the place of the dead people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa Ama Lamatua tèke eele boe ngi'u aae Dhèu Nèngu dhu D'ara Mola-Mèci, ele iie ètu d'ara rai.<bt>And the Lord God does not abandon the corpse of His Person with Holy Insides, to decay in the ground.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Dara Hua Iia = hati mulia"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Dara Hua Iia = hati mulia ; ele iie = rusak, busuk ; laho = utk benda</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="28" />Lamatua pad'elo le ja'a j'ara mamuri dhu mola.<bt>The Lord has revealed to me, the way of life which is straight/correct.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti èèna ka d'ara ja'a karej'e d'ai seli,<bt>That is why my insides are overjoyed,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">lula Lamatua bera-bera dènge ja'a.&gt;<bt>because the Lord accompanies2/is together with me.&gt;</bt><note reference="2:25-28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 16:8-11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ne'e ne ka dhu dhèu aae Daud suri tèke nèti uru ka mai.<bt>That is what King Daud wrote long ago.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />A'ari aa'i-aa'i! Miu mata ku ho ja'a lole paie ku dènge miu lula-nèti dhèu aae Daud. Na peka sèmi èèna, te ngaa na lole boe ngi'u nèngu. Èdhi te'a, lula nèngu madhe le, aa ra padhane ne. Ro'a na abhu ètu talora èdhi toke d'ai sange ne'e.<bt>So, all elder-younger siblings! Allow me to speak to you thoroughly/frankly about King Daud. He spoke like that, but he was not speaking about himself. He died, and they buried him, (and) his hole/grave can be found among us)inc) to this day.</bt><v n="30" />Dhèu aae Daud ne j'aj'i dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Aa na ne'a, na, Ama Lamatua dhu moa le pake lii subha, ho limuri mai èci nèti ana-èpu Daud nèd'u paredha. Nèngu èèna ka dhu Lamatua paj'uj'u mema nèti uru ka mai.<bt>King Daud, was God's spokesperson. And he knew that the Lord God had promised using an oath, for one of Daud's descendents to later one hold govenrment/rule. It is He that the Lord had designated beforehand from long ago.</bt><note reference="2:30" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 132:11, 2 Samuel 7:12-13</note><v n="31" />Lod'o èèna, Daud pangee madhera. Aa na peka uuru lula-nèti Dhèu dhu Lamatua paj'uj'u tèke le. Èena na Dhèu èèna madhe, te ngaa mamuri hari kahèi. Aa Daud peka kahèi, na, Dhèu èèna pea taruu boe ètu era dhèu madhe, aa ngi'u Na ele iie boe kahèi.<bt>At that time, Daud was thinking far (=farsighted). That's why he foretold about the Person who the Lord had designated. Later on, that Person would live again from His death. And Daud also said that that person would not continue to stay in the place of dead people, and His body would not decay.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karèi 1) tanya 2) sejak; |b31:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">karèi 1) tanya 2) sejak; <span class="Bold">31:</span> hèu boe = sonde baboo</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Dhèu dhu Daud peka-padhai ne, nuka Yesus! Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne nèti mamadhe Na. Ka ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi ngèdhi le dènge musi madha ji'i!<bt>The person whom Daud was talking about was that Yesus! God brought Him back to life from death. And we(exc) have all seen this with our own eyeballs!</bt><v n="33" />Ka limuri ne, Ama Lamatua ded'e le Yesus, ho nèd'u paredha dhu dedha risi eele. Aa Na madhèdi ètu baboa g'ana Ama Lamatua, ètu era dhu Lamatua sadia tèke le. Aa Ama Na hia le Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci, sama sèmi dhu Na moa tèke nèti uru ka. Aa Na moa neo hia Roh Mola-Mèci Na mi èdhi kahèi. Èèna ka dhu miu tadèngi dènge laladhe mèdhi deo na, nuka Ama Lamatua hia Roh Na.<bt>And now/later, God has designated Yesus to hold the highest rule/power. And He sits at the right side of God, where the Lord has already prepared (it). And His Father has given His Spirit which is Holy just as the He promised long ago. And He has promised to give that Holy Spirit to us(inc) as well. So then, that is what you(pl) are hearing and seeing now.</bt><v n="34" />Daud mesa na ca'e boe la'e asa sorga, te ngaa na suri, peka na,<bt>Daud did not ascend up to heaven2, but he spoke, saying:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ama Lamatua padhai lii dènge Lamatua ja'a, peka na,<bt>&lt;God speaks to my Lord, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;&lt;Madhèdi mi sebhe g'ana Ja'a, ètu era dhu Ja'a sadia mema,<bt>&lt;&lt;Sit at My right side, at the place I have prepared beforehand,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">
      <v n="35" />toke Ja'a tao musu Èu sèra, pahaha iisi mi Èu.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>until I make Your enemies, lower/humble themselves to You.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahaha iisi = bekin rendah diri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pahaha iisi = bekin rendah diri</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:34-35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Nèti èèna ka dhèu Isra'el aa'i-aa'i ra hud'i re'a ku tare'a-re'a, lula-nèti Yesus dhu miu paku pamadhe ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Nèngu, nuka Kristus dhu Ama Lamatua hag'e nare le. Aa Nèngu ne'e ka dhu j'aj'i Kètu èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is why all people of Isra'el must know truly that Yesus whom you(pl) nailed to that crossed wood, is Yesus whom God elevated Him, to be the Person whom He has chosen. He is the one who is our(inc) Lord/master.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ropa tadèngi rare lii Petrus ne, d'ara dhèu sèra roe. Ka ra karèi Petrus dènge dhèu pajuu-paleha leo sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;A'ari! Ji'i hud'i tao tasamia ku?&gt;&gt;<bt>When they heard what Petrus had said, the insides of those people wilted. And they asked Petrus and the other servant/emissaries, saying, &lt;&lt;Elder-younger siblings! What should we do?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Hèia Petrus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu èci-èci hud'i ele-ho'a ku, aa tèke eele ku sasala-sasigo miu aa'i-aa'i mi, ho miu lèpa hari madhutu Lamatua. Hèia soro iisi mi ho sarani, sèna ka j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, miu lèpa hari le madhutu J'ara Mamuri Yesus Kristus. Aa èèna j'aj'i tadha kahèi, peka na, Lamatua saku eele le sasala-sasigo miu. Èle èèna, miu sèmi mere Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci.<bt>Then Petrus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;You(pl) must stop-deeds (+/-repent) and you must leave behind all of your *wrongs (doublet), to turn again and follow the Lord. And you must turn.over yourselves to be baptised, as a sign that you have turned again to follow/obey the Life Way of Yesus Kristus. And that is also a sign saying that the Lord has wiped away your wrongs. After that, you will receive God's Spirit which is Holy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ele-ho'a = tobat, barenti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ele-ho'a = tobat, barenti</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Te Ama Lamatua moa le hia Roh Na mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu j'aj'i le dhèu unu Na. Dènge j'ara ne'e, lii mamoa lula-nèti Roh Na, j'aj'i hia miu dènge ana-èpu miu kahèi. Na moa hia mi dhèu leo kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>(Because) God has promised to give His Spirit to all people who are/become His people. In this way, this promise about His Spirit is in effect for you yourselves and also for your descendents. He promised this for other people [can mean 'foreigners'] as well.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii mamoa = (n) ; dhèu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lii mamoa = (n) ; dhèu leo</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Aa Petrus padhai lii ae hari mi rèngu, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Limuri ne, dhèu ae sero le nèti j'ara mamuri dhu mola. De miu mage-mage, sèna ka miu baku madhutu tatao dhèu bhelu sèra. Te ngaa miu hud'i madhutu dhoka j'ara mola nèti Ama Lamatua di. Dènge j'ara èèna, miu abhu mamuri taa-taa dènge Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Petrus spoke at length (going-coming) with them, saying, &lt;&lt;Now, many people are far from that straight/true way of life. So you must be careful, so that you don't follow the deeds/behaviour of those bad people. But you must follow only the straight way from God. In that way, you will live continually with Him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhai lii ae titu kèna ~"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">padhai lii ae titu kèna ~ padhai lii la'e-mai</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu ae sèra sèmi rare lii padhai lii Petrus èèna dènge d'ara kateme. Ka ra madhutu J'ara Mamuri Yesus, hèia ra soro iisi ra sèna ka abhu sarani. Lod'o èèna, pe d'ai tèlu riho dhèu mai pa'èci dènge dhèu-dhèu unu Yesus sèra.<bt>So then many of those people received what Peturs had said wholeheartedly. And they followed Yesus' Way of Life, and they surrendered themselves to get baptised. That day/time, there were around three thousand people who came and united with Yesus' people.</bt><v n="42" />Rèngu d'èi pa'èci dènge dhèu-dhèu leo dhu madhutu Yesus. Aa rèngu mamuri mera-milu èci dènge èci. Bèli-bèli èèna, rèngu maj'èni nanene lii holo-nori nèti dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus. Rèngu d'èi manèngi-mangaj'i sama-sama kahèi. Aa rèngu d'èi ra'a-rinu mei èci.<bt>They liked to be together with the other people who followed/obeyed Yesus. And they lived at peace/right relationships with each other. Every day, they diligently listened to the teachings of the servants/emissaries of the Lord Yesus. They also liked to pray together. And they like to eat-drink with each other (lit: at same table).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pe dai = kira-kira; |b42:|r mei"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pe dai = kira-kira; <span class="Bold">42:</span> mei èci = with each other (&lt;satu meja)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">J'ara-j'ara mamuri dhèu parcaya<bt>The ways of living of the believing people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua sèra tao tadha malaa ae-ae, ka dhèu dhu ètu sèra sa malaa dènge madha'u.<bt>That day/time, those servants/emissaries of the Lord, did many amazing signs, and the people around them were amazed and afraid.</bt><v n="44" />Dhèu-dhèu dhu madhutu J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus, aa'i-aa'i ra mamuri pakaboko dènge d'ara èci, ka ngaa dhu unu dhèu èci, j'aj'i unu rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra, ho ra pake sama-sama.<bt>The people who followed the Way of Life of the Lord Yesus, all of them lived together with one inside (=united, like-minded, same purpose), and what one person owned became owned by them all for them to use together.</bt><note reference="2:44" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 4:32-35</note><v n="45" />Abhu cahag'e pahia mèdha-panyau ra, ho ra pala-bagi doi kab'ua na mi dhèu parcaya sèra, madhutu èci-èci dhu parluu.<bt>There were some who sold their possessions, and its price (=the money they got for it), they divided to the believing people, according to each person's needs (assim. loan).</bt><v n="46" />Bèli-bèli èèna, rèngu pa'èci ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Rèngu ra'a-rinu boko-boko mue-mue dènge d'ara karej'e-karae, nèti èmu èci asa èmu èci, dènge boe ka'uu-kamuki. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra mamuri èci tulu èci, dènge boe kire-kome.<bt>Every day, they gathered inside the *Temple [&lt;Central House of Prayer]. They ate-drank changing places (idiom) with happy (doublet) insides, from one house to another without grumbling. They all lived one helping the other, with no stinginess/reservation [end literary].</bt><v n="47" />Bèli-bèli èèna, rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra ma'ète boe koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua dènge d'ara kateme. Dhèu leo sèra d'èi rèngu titu kèna. Nèti ca lod'o asa ca lod'o Ama Lamatua hia mamuri mi dhèu sèra, ho ra pa'èci dènge dhèu-dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus. Ka rèngu asa ka ae.<bt>Every day, they all did not cease to praise (doublet) the name/reputation of God wholeheartedly. Other people really liked them. Day after day God gave life/saved people, so they united with the Lord Yesus' people. And they kept increasing (in number).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boko-boko = ; mue-mue = ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">boko-boko = ; mue-mue = ; ka uu-ka moke ~ ka uu-ka muki = sungut-sungut, kikir ; kire-kome = hemat ; mèu-moke = sakikir, kake'ek ;; <span class="Bold">47:</span> nèti calodo dai calodo dhu maète boe. = hari-hari sonde putus-putus ; calod'o = hari, sehari, satu hari ; pala-bagi mamuri =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus puri-pa'èle dhèu karuku èci<bt>Petrus heals a crippled person</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Ca lod'o, pe d'ara hake tèlu nihia sa, Petrus dènge Yohanis lasi asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ho neo sabaj'a dènge dhèu leo sèra.<bt>One day, around 3 in the afternoon, Petrus and Yohanis were going into the *Temple, wanting to pray with other people there.</bt><v n="2" />Rèngu neo maso re hèb'a oka, dhu ngara na &lt;Hèb'a Saraga&gt;. Ètu èèna, rèngu rèdhi dhèu mone karuku èci, dhu karuku nèti ina na nara iisi ne. Bèli-bèli mai, na, dhèu nedhe rèti ne asa era èèna, ho na kanata kacui-aai manèngi ngaa-ngaa nèti dhèu cee dhu neo maso asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i re èèna.<bt>They were about to enter by a gate (&lt;fnece door) which is named &lt;Beautiful Door&gt;. At that place, they saw a crippled man, who had been crippled from since his mother gave birth to him. Every day people lifted bringing him to that place, so that he could stretch out his hand asking for whatever from anyone who was about to enter into that Temple.</bt><v n="3" />Ropa na ladhe nèdhi Petrus dènge Yohanis oe maso asa d'ara, ka na kanata kacui-aai, manèngi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama, ee! Sue ku ja'a laa. Hia ku ja'a ngaa, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>When he saw Petrus and Yohanis about to go inside, he stretched out his hand, begging, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers! Pity me. Give me something, ya!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kacuu = piggy-back"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kacuu = piggy-back</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="masi ka ciki oo'e èèna ka,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">masi ka ciki oo'e èèna ka, sèna ka ja'a abhu mamuri.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01895b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Petrus dènge Yohanis ladhe asa dhèu karuku<bt>Petrus and Yohanis see that crippled person</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ka dua ra ladhe kaloo ka dhèu ne'e, hèia Petrus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ku mai!&gt;&gt;<bt>The two of them looked inspecting this person, and then Petrus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Look here!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia nèngu boti kètu na, ladhe asa rèngu dua ra, ka na pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Ele boe dua ra neo hia ja'a ngaa-ngaa ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he lifted his head [also can mean "felt relieved"], looking at the two of them, thinking, &lt;&lt;Waa! The two of them probably want to give me something.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ele boe = mangkali ; boti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Ele boe = mangkali ; boti kètu = 1) angkat kepala, 2) rasa beban diangkat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Te ngaa Petrus peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a dènge boe doi hualaa ho hia mi èu! Te, ngaa dhu ja'a unu, èèna ka dhu ja'a neo hia mi èu. De nanene paie-iie! Dènge koasa Yesus Kristus, dhèu Nasaret, ja'a pua èu kèd'i titu, ho kako!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Petrus spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I have no (silver or gold) coins [NOTE: Ndao men are renowned as goldsmiths, so lexicalised items implying silver or gold as opposed to lesser materials is not wierd.] to give to you! But what I have/own, that is what I want to give to you. So listen carefully! With the power of Yesus Kristus, that Nasaret person, I command you to stand up, to walk!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="anamaa = remis (dari jaman Belanda),"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">anamaa = remis (dari jaman Belanda), di bawah satu sen, thought young people know, but no longer in circulation ; doi dhari = money, currency (uang tali) ; doi dhari (ca anamaa) ; doi walaa = uang dari emas/perak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Hèia Petrus kèpe ai g'ana dhèu karuku èèna, ka na pakèd'i patitu ne. Kaca'a laa, haga dhèu ne'e be'a dènge ka, ètu d'ara ciki ood'e èèna kahèi.<bt>Then Petrus took hold of the right hand of the crippled person, and stood him up. Suddenly the legs of this person were strong in a moment of time (idiom).</bt><v n="8" />Cag'ag'a laa, na pasoka titu, hèia na kako la'e-mai neo ne'a, haga nèngu be'a le, do dhae. Èle èèna ka, na la'e palere dènge rèngu dua ra asa d'ara Èmu Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Na kako pasoa-pasoka dènge koa-kio Ama Lamatua.<bt>Suddenly2 he lept up, and then he walked bakc-and-forth (going-coming) to know whether his legs were already good, or not yet. After that, he went accompanying the two of them into the Temple. He went/walked jumping and leaping and praising God.</bt><v n="9" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i sèra ladhe rèdhi dhèu ne'e kako la'e-mai, aa koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua.<bt>Everybody there could see this person going back-and-forth and praising the name of God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ètu dara ciki oode na kahèi."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ètu dara ciki oode na kahèi. = dalam waktu singkat/itu ju ; Kaca'a laa = suddenly (focus on time) ; Cag'ag'a laa, = suddenly (focus on unexpected event from perspective of person); <span class="Bold">8:</span> palere = bersama ; pasoa-pasoka = jumping and leaping</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa dhèu ae sèra tadhe ne, ka ra malaa, hèia peka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ne'e ka dhèu karuku dhu madhèdi ètu Hèb'a Saraga, ho manèngi ngaa-ngaa èèna, sina ma? Tasamia ka na j'aj'i sèmi ne'e?&gt;&gt;<bt>When those many people recognised him, they were amazed, then spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;This one here, he is the crippled person who sat at the Beautiful Door, to ask for things there, right? How is it that he can be like this?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus padhai lii ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i<bt>Petrus speaks inside the Temple</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu dhu èle nèti karuku èèna, madhutu Petrus dènge Yohanis. Ka tèlu ra lasi d'ai èmu taleo cue, ngara na &lt;Èmu Taleo Dhèu Aae Soleman&gt;. Ètu èèna, dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mai lingu rare rèngu malaa titu kèna.<bt>After that, the person who was healed from his crippledness, accompanied Petrus and Yohanis. The three of them went arriving at an open-aired house, called, &lt;Open-aired House of King Solemaa&gt;. In that place many people came gathering with them, and were very amazed.</bt><v n="12" />Ropa Petrus nèdhi rèngu, ka na padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu Isra'el aa'i-aa'i mi! Nga tao ka miu malaa, lula j'ara ne'e ne? Nga tao ka miu ladhe kaloo ji'i? Miu ngee, na, dhèu ne kako lula ji'i pake na'i, do, lula ji'i maj'èni madhutu Ama Lamatua? Do, tasamia?<bt>When Petrus saw them, he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Wee! All of you people of Isra'el! Why are you amazed because of this event? Why do you keep staring checking us(exc) out? Do you think that this person is walking because we used tobacco/medicine/charm/magic/sorcery), or, because we are diligent to follow/obey God? Or what?</bt><v n="13" />Ja'a neo peka dènge miu sèmi ne'e: bèi-baki èdhi Abraham, Isak dènge Yakob manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua. Lamatua èèna ka dhu ded'e padedha-dedha Dhèu Nèngu dhu Na pili nare, nuka Yesus. Yesus èèna ka dhu miu tule eele Ne, ka saraka Ne asa gubernur Pilatus. Ka gubernur neo patabuli Ne, te ngaa miu ka dhu palab'a, sèna ka na baku patabuli eele Yesus.<bt>I want to tell you like this: Our(inc) ancestors Abraham, Isa and Jako pryaed/worshipped God. It is that God2 who elevated His Person whom He chose, that is Yesus. Yesus is that one whom you(pl) rejected, and turned over to Gubernor Pilatus. And the Gubernur wanted to release Him, but you are the ones who opposed, so that he didn't release Yesus.</bt><note reference="3:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 3:15</note><v n="14" />Te ngaa Yesus, Dhèu dhu sala boe. D'ara Nèngu be'a. Gubernur neo patabuli eele Dhèu dhu sala boe ne, te ngaa miu aa'i-aa'i mi lab'a ne. Aa dhu bhelu risi hari ka, miu dadugu-rariu ne, sèna ka na patabuli hia miu dhèu bhelu-katub'a èci dhu pamadhe nèdhi dhèu.<bt>But that Yesus is a person who had/did no wrong. His insides were good. The Gubernur wanted to release this person who had done no wrong, but you all opposed him. And what is even worse, you cajoled/incited him to release to you an evil person who characteristically killed people.</bt><note reference="3:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 27:15-23, Markus 15:6-14, Lukas 23:13-23, Yohanis 19:12-15</note><v n="15" />Miu ka dhu pamadhe Yesus! Aa te ngaa Nèngu ka dhu hia èdhi mamuri. Mema tare'a Nèngu madhe le, te ngaa Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne. Nèngu ka dhu ji'i ladhe ngèdhi le dènge musi madha ji'i.<bt>You are the ones who killed Yesus! But He is the one who gives us(inc) life/salvation/deliverance. It is true that He really died, but God brought Him back to life. He is the one whom we(exc) have seen with our own eyeballs.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èmu taleo = rumah luas; |b12:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">èmu taleo = rumah luas; <span class="Bold">12:</span> maj'èni = rajin; <span class="Bold">13:</span> palab'a = melawan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Miu tadhe dhèu karuku ne. Nèngu èra le, te ngaa ji'i boe ka dhu puri-pa'èle ne. Ji'i se dènge boe koasa ngaa-ngaa. Koasa èèna mai nèti Yesus. Dhèu ne'e ne èra, lula nèngu parcaya Lamatua Yesus. Yesus ka dhu pa'èle ne, ètu katanga madha miu aa'i-aa'i mi.<bt>You know/recognise this crippled person! He is now strong, but we(exc) did not heal him. We don't have any power. The power just came from Yesus. This person is strong, because he believe in the Lord Yesus. Yesus is the one who healed him right in front of all of you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />A'ari aa'i-aa'i ti! Limuri ne, ja'a ke'a le, miu dènge dhèu aae-dhèu kapai miu, tao bhelu mi dedha Yesus, te ngaa miu me'a boe ngaa dhu j'aj'i lèpa limuri.<bt>All you elder-younger siblings! Now I know that you and your leaders did evil to Yesus, but you(pl) do not know what will/would happen later on.</bt><v n="18" />Te ngaa Ama Lamatua peka mema nèti uru ka mai, pake dhèu nèti lii padhai Nèngu, peka na, Kristus, nuka Dhèu dhu Na hag'e nare èèna, hud'i d'ui ku j'aj'èra. Ka j'aj'i le, sèmi èèna ka!<bt>But God foretold from long ago, using His spokesperson, saying, the Child whom He had selected out must shoulder-carry suffering. And it has happened like that!</bt><v n="19" />Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i ele-ho'a, tèke eele sasala-sasigo miu, hèia lèpa asa Ama Lamatua, ho Na saku eele aa baku ngee ia ka sasala miu sèra.<bt>Because of that, you must stop/repent, getting rid of your wrongs (doublet), and return to God so that He does not remember any more those wrongs of yours.</bt><v n="20" />Pe Ama Lamatua pa'èra d'ara miu. Ka Na neo pua Kristus dhu Na hag'e nare èèna, mai hari asa miu. Kristus èèna, nuka Yesus, dhu Na pua le mai asa miu.<bt>God strengthens your insides. And He will send back to you His Child whom he selected out. That Child is Yesus. God has already sent Him to you previously.</bt><v n="21" />Nèti uru ka mai, Lamatua padhai lii re dhèu nèti lii padhai Na, peka na, &lt;Bèli-camèd'a, Ama Lamatua pamola j'ara aa'i-aa'i, sèna ka j'aj'i hiu.&gt; Yesus hud'i mate ku ètu Era Mola-Mèci toke d'ai lod'o Nèngu mai hari, ho Na pahiu ngaa-ngaa aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>From long ago, God2 spoke by means of His spokesperson, saying, &lt;In the future God will straighten out all things, so that they become new.&gt; Yesus must wait in that Holy Place, until the day/time He comes back again, so that He renews all things.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ue = buat ~ tao ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ue = buat ~ tao ; ngee = pikir ; baku ... ia ka = tidak lagi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Uru èèna, baki Musa peka le dènge dhèu Isra'el, aku nèngu na,<bt>Long ago, Grandfather/forefather Musa said to the people of Isra'el, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Lamatua miu, nuka Ama Lamatua, bèli-camèd'a Na pua Dhèu èci nèti talora miu, ho j'aj'i dhèu nèti lii padhai Na, sama sèmi Na pake ja'a, ho j'aj'i dhèu kèti lii padhai Na. De miu hud'i pasa dhilu, sèna ka mi nanene paie, ngaa-ngaa dhu Na neo peka mi miu.<bt>&lt;Your(pl) Father, that is, God, in the future He will send one of you(pl) to be His spokesperson, just like He used me, to be His spokesperson. So, you here must fasten your ears so that you listen well to whatever He wants to say to you.</bt><note reference="3:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 18:15, 18</note><v n="23" />Te ngaa dhèu cee dhu ro'o boe nanene paie, lii padhai lii Dhèu èèna, èèna na cèri eele nèti dhèu unu Lamatua sèra. Dènge heka hak ètu talora rèngu.&gt;<bt>But whoever does not want to listen well to the words of that Person, God2 will forcefully evict him from among his society/nation/people.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Horo-Parahi = yang maha besar (kuno);"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Horo-Parahi = yang maha besar (kuno); <span class="Bold">23:</span> lalète eele = usir dgn keras</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Horo-Parahi miu, nuka Ama Lamatua,; |b23:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Horo-Parahi miu, nuka Ama Lamatua,; <span class="Bold">23:</span> nèngu na bisa boe j'aj'i unu Ama Lamatua.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 18:19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Mesa boe baki Musa di dhu peka sèmi èèna. Te Lamatua pake dhèu leo kahèi, j'aj'i dhèu nèti lii padhai Na. Rèngu peka sèmi èèna kahèi. Sama sèmi uru èèna, Lamatua pake baki Samuel, ho lolo j'ara-j'ara dhu limuri ne èdhi tèdhi dènge musi madha èdhi.<bt>It was not only Grandpa Musa alone who spoke like that. But God2 used other people as well to be His spokespeople. They also spoke like that. For example, long ago God2 used Grandpa Samue, to tell about the things which we(inc) now are seeing with our own eyeballs.</bt><v n="25" />Ama Lamatua moa tèke le, mi baki Abraham, peka na,<bt>God is the one who promised to Grandpa Abraham, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Samue"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Samue</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Bèli-camèd'a, re ana-èpu èu èci, Ja'a hia mèngi-nale mi dedha suku aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne.&gt;<bt>&lt;In the future I will give *blessing (loan) by means of one of your descendants, to all the tribes/clans/ethnic groups on this world.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="re = lewat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">re = lewat</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 22:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lii moa dhu Ama Lamatua peka le mi dhèu rèti lii padhai Na, limuri ne, j'aj'i le mi dedha miu, nuka a'ari ja'a dhèu Isra'el sèra.<bt>Naa! Those promises from our forefathers, now have happened for you, the people of Isra'el now.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="NRSV: You are the descendants of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z" status="Information">NRSV: You are the descendants of the prophets and of the covenant that God gave to your ancestors, saying to Abraham, ‘And in your descendants all the families of the earth shall be blessed.’</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Ama Lamatua pua Ana Na dhu Na hag'e nare èèna, ho paj'uj'u j'ara, sèna ka miu tèke eele sasala-sasigo miu. Dènge sèmi èèna, Na pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi miu. Lamatua pua uuru Ana Na mai asa miu, èle èèna, heka Na pua Ne asa suku leo sèra. Èèna ka dhu j'aj'i mèngi-nale mi èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Lord God sent His Child whom He set apart/chose, to show the path for you to leave behind your *wrongs (doublet). In that way, He revealed His goodness/kindness to you. The Lord sent first that Child coming to you, after that, only then He sent Him to other people (outsiders/non-Jews).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nuka = yaitu, yakni; |b26:|r mamèngi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">nuka = yaitu, yakni; <span class="Bold">26:</span> mamèngi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ama Lamatua neo hia miu berkat."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Ama Lamatua neo hia miu berkat. Nèti èèna ka, Na pajuu Ana Na dhu hag'e nare na, ho paj'uj'u j'ara. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, Na bhoke j'ara, ho sèna ka miu se tèke eele sasala-sasigo miu. Lamatua pajuu uuru Ana Na mai sa miu, èle èèna, heka Na pajuu Ne asa dhèu leo sèra.&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kètu agama Yahudi paroa Petrus dènge Yohanis<bt>The religious leaders who decide religious cases summon Petrus and Yohanis</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, ropa Petrus dènge Yohanis padhai lii era dènge dhèu ètu sèra, dhèu kapai canau mai. Rèngu sèra, kètu agama Yahudi, dhèu nèti partei Saduki, dènge komedhaa j'aga Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Rèngu mai neo patao dènge Petrus dènge Yohanis.<bt>When Petrus and Yohanis were still speaking with the people who were there, suddenly several important people came. Those were, Jahudi religious fathers (=leaders), the commander of the guards of the Temple, and people from the Saduki party. They came to quarrel with Petrus and Yohanis.</bt><v n="2" />Dhèu sèra nasa, lula rèngu dua ra d'èi peka dènge dhèu ae, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yesus mamuri hari le nèti mamadhe Na. Dènge j'ara èèna, Nèngu bhoke j'ara hia dhèu madhe sèna ka bisa mamuri hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>Those people were angry, because the two of them liked to tell so many people, saying, &lt;&lt;Yesus is alive again from His death. In this way, He opened the way for dead people to live again.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="4:1-2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu partei Saduki lèka boe dhèu madhe bisa mamuri hari.<bt>People of the Saduki party do not believe2 that dead people can live again.</bt></note><v n="3" />Ka ra paredha dhèu rèngu lasi kèpe dua ra. Te ngaa, lula lod'o oe cèna kèna, ka ra pamaso taha si asa d'ara bèdho. Ho bèli èèna, heka ra neo parisa si kèna.<v n="4" />Te ngaa ètu talora dhèu dhu d'èi nanene dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus sèra, ae ka dhu mangaku, na, lii aj'a-nori rèngu sèra lèke tare'a. Nèti èèna ka dhèu parcaya asa tabha ae, pe d'ai lèmi riho dhèu sa.<Annotation class="General" selectedText="parcaya"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">parcaya</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01901b.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Dhèu kapai sèra pasala Petrus si<bt>The religious leaders accuse/criticise Petrus (coll.)</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Asa bèli èèna, dhèu kapai Yahudi sèra pakaboko ètu kota Yerusalem, nuka dhèu paredha, dhèu heka-dhèu heka ad'a Yahudi, dènge mese agama Yahudi sèra.<bt>The next day, the Jahudi important people gathered in the city of Yerusalem, that is, government people, Jahudi clan leaders, and Jahudi religious teachers.</bt><v n="6" />Kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi, dhu ngara na Hanas, ètu èèna kahèi. Dhèu kapai leo, sèmi Kayafas, Yohanis, Aleksander, dènge a'ari leo sèra nèti kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi ètu èèna kahèi.<bt>The *Big Father of the Jahudi religion, whose name was Hanas, was also there. Other important people like Kayafas, Yohanis, Aleksander, and other relatives of the Big religious Boss were also there.</bt><v n="7" />Ropa ra tesa aa'i, ka ra paredha dhèu lasi rare Petrus dènge Yohanis, ho rèti mai asa madha ama-ama dhèu kapai se'e. Ropa rèngu mai, ka ra karèi si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka miu bisa puri-pa'èle dhèu karuku? Miu pake koasa nèti cee? Aa cee ka dhu pua miu ka miu bani tao j'ara èèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>When they were all complete, they commanded people to go get Petrus and Yohanis to bring them before these important religious leaders. When they came, they asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;How did you(pl) heal (doublet) that crippled person? Whose power did you use? And who gave the order for you to be bold enough to do this matter?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia Roh Ama Lamatua pa'èra d'ara Petrus, ka na dhaa, aku nèngu na,<bt>Then God's Spirit strengthened Petrus' insides, and he responded, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ama-ama! Miu ka dhèu kapai, dènge dhèu heka kabarai Isra'el! Baku nasa ladhe ji'i ako malaa ciki.<bt>&lt;&lt;Fathers (collective)! You important people, and traditional leaders of the society of Isra'el! Don't be angry if we(exc) are a bit amazed/confused.</bt><v n="9" />Ji'i ladhe, na, ama-ama si neo tao lii langu, lula ji'i puri-pa'èle dhèu karuku èci. Aa miu neo me'a ji'i pake koasa nèti cee?<bt>It appears to us that you fathers want to make a dispute/litigation, because we healed a crippled person. And you(pl) want to know whose power we used?</bt><v n="10" />De ja'a neo peka sèmi ne'e: tatu ama si sanèd'e era dhèu Nasaret, dhu ngara Na Yesus. Nèngu èèna, Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u mema nèti uru ka mai. Te ngaa miu paku pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne. De ja'a d'èi sèna ka ama si dènge dhèu Isra'el aa'i-aa'i mi me'a, na, ji'i puri-pa'èle dhèu karuku èèna, pake dhodhoka koasa Yesus.<bt>So, I want to speak like this: You probably still remember the Nasaret person who was named Yesus. He is Kristus, who God designated beforehand from long ago. But you nailed Him to death on the crossed wood. Even though it was like that, God brought Him back to life again. So, I want for father (coll) and all the people of Isra'el to know, we healed that crippled person using only the power of Yesus.</bt><v n="11" />Yesus ne'e ka dhu ra suri tèke le ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, peka na,<bt>This Yesus is the one they wrote about in God's writings, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kolo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kolo</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Abhu hadhu cue dhu tuka core eele;<bt>&lt;There is a rock which the craftmen threw out;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te ngaa limuri mai, hadhu èèna j'aj'i hadhu padhèdi.&gt;<bt>But now, that same rock has become the foundation stone (between pole and ground).&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hadhu toru = ?? (probably not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hadhu toru = ?? (probably not widely known, grave stone)</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 118:22</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />Ètu palème rai-haha ne, Ama Lamatua bhoke boe j'ara leo dhu bisa patabuli èdhi nèti koasa sasala-sasigo èdhi. Dhodhoka j'ara èci di, nuka Yesus. Abhu boe dhèu leo èci sa dhu bisa hia mamuri mi èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Throughout this world, God2 has not made any other way/path which can give use life/salvation/deliverance and redeem our(inc) wrongs (doublet). The one and only way it Yesus. There is not one other person who can give life/salv to us.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sui = 1) tebus, 2) belah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sui = 1) tebus, 2) belah (ikan)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Dhèu dhu madhèdi ètu sèra sa re'a, na, Petrus dènge Yohanis se, dhoka dhèu biasa di, èci èèna ka dènge dhèu dhu re'a boe baca-suri. Te ngaa dhèu sèra malaa dènge babani dua ra, lula rèngu padhai lii dhu dènge boe pahuni-pahuni. Tabha hari, ra re'a, na, dhèu dua se, dhèu pa'èci nèti Yesus.<bt>People who were sitting there knew that Petrus and Yohanis were only common people, just like people who don't know how to read-write. But, those people were amazed with the boldness of the two of them. Because they spoke without holding back (lit: not taking note of the faces of people). Furthermore, they knew that these two people had been closely united with Yesus.</bt><v n="14" />Nèti èèna ka, hèb'a dhèu se kutu mèno, toke ra padhai lii heka ae-ae, lula dhèu dhu èle nèti karuku èèna, titu dhii-dhii patoo madha dènge madha.<bt>Because of that, the mouths of these people were locked tightly shut. And they didn't say anything more, because that person who had been healed from being crippled, was also standing right there, staring them in the face.</bt><v n="15" />Èle èèna ka, ra pua dhèu pajuu-paleha Yesus dhèu dua sèra, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dua mi lami ku asa li'u ciki.&gt;&gt; Ka ra padhue ho neo tenge j'ara aapa.<bt>After that, they ordered those two servants/emissaries of Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;The two of you go outside for a little bit.&gt;&gt; And they discussed how to find a way (implied: evil purposes).</bt><v n="16" />Ka ra padhue-padhai, peka na, &lt;&lt;A'ari aa'i-aa'i ti! Èdhi hud'i tao dhèu dua se samia? Te dhèu Yerusalem aa'i-aa'i ra re'a le, na, rèngu dua se ka dhu tao tadha malaa deo na. Èdhi pasili tare heka, lula bukti nèngu abhu le!<bt>So they discussed, saying, &lt;&lt;All you elder-younger siblings! What are we(inc) going to do to these two people? Because everybody in Yerusalem already know that the two of them are the ones who did this amazing sign earlier. We can no longer deny this, because the proof (loan) is there!</bt><v n="17" />De hua iia èdhi tenge j'ara, sèna ka lii ne'e baku ra lolo palème asa mia-mia la'e. Be'a risi èdhi pamadha'u si, sèna ka ra baku aj'a ia ka J'ara Mamuri Yesus. Ladhe ra nanene boe, na, re'a mema!&gt;&gt;<bt>So it would be better if we look for a way so that this matter does not get told around everywhere else. It is best if we frighten them, so that they don't teach any more this Life Way of Yesus. If they don't listen/obey, na, they will truly know! [Language of threat]&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sakola boe = sonde sakola ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sakola boe = sonde sakola ; malaa ko'a-ko'a = \lf Max; <span class="Bold">14:</span> kutu = tutu ; mèno = keras ; kutu mèno = terkatup ; dhii-dhii = tegak ;; <span class="Bold">15:</span> apa ; j'ara aapa = jalan jahat / tar bae; <span class="Bold">17:</span> ale = carita</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hèia ra paroa dua ra maso hari asa d'ara, ka ra peka dènge si, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu ladhe unu mi, ee! Miu bisa heka lolo, do, aj'a-nori dhèu leo lula-nèti Yesus!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they summoned the two of them to enter again inside, and they told them, saying, &lt;&lt;You just watch! [Threat] You may no longer narrate or teach other people about Yesus!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ladhe unu miu = bosong lia"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Ladhe unu miu = bosong lia sandiri</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Te ngaa Petrus dènge Yohanis b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Cob'a ama-ama si pajiko ku laa. Mia dhu be'a risi? Madhutu paredha ama si, do, madhutu paredha Ama Lamatua?<bt>And Peturs and Yohanis responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers (coll) try to weigh the options. Which is better? Follow/obey your commands, or follow/obey God's commands?</bt><v n="20" />Te ji'i ngèdhi le dènge musi madha ji'i, aa tadèngi le dènge ro'a dhilu ji'i madha j'ara ae. De tasamia ji'i kutu hèb'a, ho baku lolo dènge dhèu leo!&gt;&gt;<bt>Cause we(exc) have seen with our own eyeballs, and have heard with our earholes. So, how can we lock our mouth's shut, to not tell this to other people!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Dhèu dhu madhèdi pama'ète lii langu èèna, kai hari rèngu. Ka ra patalale eele dua si, lula ra re'a heka j'ara ho huku si. Rèngu madha'u kahèi, mage dhoka dhèu ae ètu li'u sèi pagama. Te dhèu ae sèra koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua, lula dhèu karuku èèna èle le.<bt>Those who were sitting to decide this dispute forbade them again. Because they knew there was no way to punish them, they released the two of them. They were also afraid lest the people outside would revolt (violently). Cause those many people praised the name of God, because the aforementioned crippled person was now good.</bt><v n="22" />(Dhèu èèna karuku èpa nguru risi tèu le, ka heka bisa kako kèna.)<bt>That person had been crippled for more than 40 years, and only now could walk.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uku (3) = hukum ; mangamo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">uku (3) = hukum ; mangamo (dhasi mangamo, dhèu mangamo)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sèra abhu boe alasan èci sa,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sèra abhu boe alasan èci sa, dhu bisa tao paj'èra Petrus dènge Yohanis. Hèia ra ancam dua ra ka ra patabuli eele si, te dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu sèra koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua, lula dhèu karuku na èle pèda èèna.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus sabaj'a manèngi d'ara bani<bt>Believing people pray asking for bold insides</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ropa ra patabuli eele Petrus dènge Yohanis, dua ra lèpa lasi asa angalai rèngu. Hèia dua ra lole aa'i-aa'i ngaa dhu kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu kapai leo sèra kai rèngu ho baku palolo.<bt>When they released Petrus and Yohanis, the two of them returned going to their friends. Then the two of them told everything that the religious fathers and the other leaders had forbidden that they not tell-around.</bt><v n="24" />Ropa ra tadèngi rare lii lolo èèna, ka angalai rèngu aa'i-aa'i sèra pakaboko dènge d'ara èci, ho ra manèngi-mangaj'i, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua dhu Koasa Kapai Risi Eele. Ama dhu paj'aj'i dedha-liru dènge rai-haha, dènge isi ra aa'i-aa'i.<bt>When they heard that report, all their friends gather with one inside (purpose), for them to pray, saying, &lt;&lt;God! Father is the one who made the heaven and earth, and their contents.</bt><note reference="4:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:11, Nehemia 9:6, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 146:6</note><v n="25" />Uru-uru sèra, Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci pake le baki Daud ho j'aj'i dhèu nèti lii padhai Na, sèna ka suri mema lula-nèti dhèu lab'a Yesus, peka na,<bt>Long ago, God's Holy Spirit used Grandpa Daud to be His spokesperson, to write beforehand about people opposing Yesus, saying,</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01903b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Petrus si manèngi-mangaj'i<bt>Petrus (coll) pray</bt></fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Dhèu nèti rai leo sèra nasa lula lii lai-ngèlu;<bt>&lt;People from other lands are angry because of rumours;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii lai ngèlu = kabar angin,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lii lai ngèlu = kabar angin, kabar burung</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu se'e tao lèke boe, ho tao lii langu dhu dènge boe kolo-kapua.<bt>These people do things aimless/pointless, they make disputes that have no base-tip (botanical metaphor meaning no reason or purpose).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kolo-kapua = ujung (phon) - batang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kolo-kapua = ujung (phon) - batang (pohon) = asal-asal sa</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="26" />Dhèu aae rai-haha sèra pakaboko ho neo pamusu lab'a Ama Lamatua;<bt>The kings of this earth hold weapons so they can war.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hela-samala = weapons (?) ; papara-pakèj'i"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hela-samala = weapons (?) ; papara-pakèj'i = bapotong-batikam = baparáng</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Dhèu Aae rai-haha sèra kèpa hela-samala"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Dhèu Aae rai-haha sèra kèpa hela-samala ho papara-pakèj'i.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèmi èèna kahèi, dhèu kapai sèra rare lii èci neo lasi lab'a Ama Lamatua dènge Kristus,<bt>In the same way, the leaders are in agreement to go oppose God and Kristus, the Person who God2 designated from long ago.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">nuka Dhèu dhu Lamatua paj'uj'u mema karèi nèti uru ka mai.&gt;<note reference="4:25-26" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:1-2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ka ngaa dhu baki Daud suri na, limuri ne j'aj'i le. Aa sasoa na led'a le. Ètu kota ne'e, dhèu aae Herodes, gubernur Pontius Pilatus, dhèu heka-dhèu heka ad'a Isra'el, dènge dhèu kapai suku leo sèra, pakaboko le. Rèngu pare'a lii ho lab'a Yesus, dhu Ama Lamatua hag'e nare le.<bt>So, that which Grandpa Daud wrote then is now fulfilled/happened. And its meaning/significance has now become clear. King Herodes, Gubernur Pontius Pilatus, our(inc) traditional clan leaders of Isra'el, and the leaders of other/foreign ethnic groups, gathered here in this city. They are in agreement to oppose Yesus, that person whom God chose.</bt><note reference="4:27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 27:1-2, Markus 15:1, Lukas 23:1, 7-11, Yohanis 18:28-29</note><v n="28" />Te ngaa limuri ne, èdhi te'a aa'i le j'ara sèra lèke mola-mola dènge dad'èi Lamatua, madhutu ngaa dhu Lamatua peka tèke nèti uru ka.<bt>But now we(inc) know/understand all of those things, they happened in accord with the will of God2, according to that which God2 said long ago.</bt><v n="29" />Lamatua, Èu me'a rèngu dhoka padhai lii neo pamadha'u ji'i di. De ji'i manèngi ho Lamatua hia ji'i d'ara bani. Sèna ka ladhe ji'i la'a padhue-padhai asa dhèu ètu mia-mia Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua lula-nèti Yesus, d'ara ji'i madha'u boe.<bt>God2, You know that they are only speaking to try and frighten us(exc). So, we ask that God2 give us bold insides. So that if/when we go speak to people anywhere/everywhere, about the Good News of Yesus, our insides will not be afraid.</bt><v n="30" />Ji'i manèngi Lamatua hia ji'i koasa kahèi, sèna ka ji'i bisa puri-pa'èle dhèu pèd'a. Ji'i manèngi kahèi koasa ho tao rupa-rupa tadha malaa, sèna ka dhèu re'a, koasa èèna mai nèti Dhèu Mola-Mèci dhu Lamatua pua mai, nuka Yesus. Lamatua, d'ai sange èèna ka lii sabaj'a ji'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>We also2 ask God2 to give us power, so that we can heal sick people. We also ask for power to do amazing signs, so that people will know the power comes from the Holy Person who God2 sent here, that is, Yesus. God2, this is as far as our prayer2 goes.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="j'eke = pamadha'u (Lii Pacele)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">j'eke = pamadha'u (Lii Pacele)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ropa ra manèngi-mangaj'i rare, ka èmu dhu rèngu sabaj'a na gaged'o. Hèia rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra abhu Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci. Èle èèna ka, rèngu kalua, lasi lole Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua, dènge d'ara bani.<bt>When they finished praying, the house where they were praying was shaken. Then they all got/the Holy Spirit of God. After that, they went out, going and telling the Good News of God, with bold insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gaged'o = goncang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">gaged'o = goncang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu parcaya sèra mamuri sama-sama pasae j'aj'èra dènge karej'e<bt>[Whether] happy or suffering, the believers shoulder-carry it together</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Èle èèna, dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu parcaya Yesus sèra, mamuri d'ara èci, aa mamuri pasue èci dènge èci. Abhu boe dhèu èci sa dhu mèu-moke, aa rèngu biasa pahia-paj'ola. Dhèu dhu dènge mèdha-panyau, na uri ho ra pake sama-sama.<bt>That day/time, the people who believed in Yesus lived with one inside. And they loved each other. There was noone who was greedy/stingy, and they often shared (things) with each other. A person who had belongings, would give (it) for them to use together.</bt><note reference="4:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 2:44-45</note><v n="33" />Ka Lamatua hia koasa mi dhèu pajuu-paleha Na, ho ra lole mi dhèu, peka na, Lamatua Yesus mamuri hari nèti mamadhe Na. Aa rèngu ka dhu rèdhi dènge musi madha unu ra. Ka Lamatua udhu-bhori berkat hia rèngu.<bt>And the Lord gave power to His servant/emissaries, for them to tell people that the Lord Yesus died, but is alive again. They were the ones who saw these things with their own eyeballs. And God2 heaped (doublet) blessings on them.</bt><v n="34-35" />Nèti rèngu se, abhu kahèi dhu pahia rai, do èmu ra. Ho kab'ua na, ra hia mi dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua sèra. Ra pake ho hia mi dhèu dhu parluu. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu kura boe ngaa-ngaa.<bt>Among them were also those who sold their land or houses. Its price they gave to the servant/emissaries of God2 (coll). And they divided it out to people who had no possessions. That is why they were not lacking anything.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahia-paj'ola = baku kasi; |b33:|r udhu-bhori"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pahia-paj'ola = baku kasi; <span class="Bold">33:</span> udhu-bhori = po'a-tumpuk</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36-37" />Conto sèmi Yusuf. Nèngu ne, ana-èpu Lewi, nèti pulu Siprus. Dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua se pangare na &lt;Barnabas&gt;, dhu sasoa na, &lt;dhèu dhu d'èi pa'èra d'ara dhèu leo&gt;. La'e pahie rai na ca kasib'i. Ka nèti mai kab'ua na hia dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua sèra.<bt>This is how it was with Yusuf. He was a descendent of Lewi, from the island of Siprus. The servant/emissaries of God2 called him &lt;Barnabas&gt;, meaning, &lt;a person who strengthens the insides of other people&gt;. He went and sold a piece of his land. And he brought it to the servant/emissaries of God2 (coll).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cakasib'i = sepotong (kecil)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">cakasib'i = sepotong (kecil)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ananias dènge Safira madhe, lula rèngu neo cob'a Roh Lamatua<bt>Ananias and Safira died, because they tried to test God2's Spirit</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1" />Te ngaa lod'o èèna, abhu kahèi dhèu èci, ngara na Ananias, dènge dhèu èmu na, Safira. Rèngu dua ra pahie rai ra ca kasib'i kahèi.<bt>But at that time there was a person named Ananias, and his wife, named Safira. The two of them sold a piece of their land.</bt><v n="2" />Te ngaa dua ra pare'a ho huni kab'ua rai èèna cahag'e. Pahie rare, ka Ananias la'e peka dènge dhèu pajuu-paleha Yesus sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i heka pahie ngare rai ji'i ca kasib'i kèna. De ji'i neo hia kab'ua na asa Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the two of them agreed to hide a portion of the price of that land. After they sold it, Ananias went and told the servants/emissaries of Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;We(exc) have just sold off a tiny bit of our land. So, we want to give its price to God.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01905b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Ananias hia doi kab'ua rai asa Petrus<bt>Ananias gives the price of some lang to Petrus</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Te ngaa Petrus tao dènge ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ananias! Nga tao ka èu huni doi kab'ua rai èèna cahag'e? D'ara èu mema karehe, lula èu madhutu dad'èi dhèu aae nidhu. Èu bani kapod'e-kabèli Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci!<bt>But Petrus scolded him, saying, &lt;&lt;Ananias! Why do you hide part of the price of that land? Your insides are very evil, because you are following the will of the *devil (=king of evil spirits). You dare to deceive the Holy Spirit of God!</bt><v n="4" />Sèmi ne'e! Rai na unu èu. De èu neo pahia, do aad'o, èèna na madhutu dad'èi èu. Ladhe èu pahia le, èu neo hia doi kab'ua na aa'i-aa'i, do aad'o, èèna na madhutu dad'èi èu kahèi. Te ngaa tasamia ka èu bisa tao sèmi ne'e? Èu neo pagoa ji'i dhèu rai-haha, te ngaa abhu boe dhèu dhu bisa leko-monya Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>It's like this! That land was your property. So if you want to sell it or not, that is at your insides (=up to you). If you sell it and you want to give its entire price, or not, that is according to your will. But how is it that you can do this? You wanted to con us(exc) humans, but you can't deceive God2!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tao 1) bekin, 2) marah; |b4:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tao 1) bekin, 2) marah; <span class="Bold">4:</span> goa = bodoh ; pagoa = bekin bodoh</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ropa na tadèngi Petrus padhai lii sèmi èèna, cag'ag'a laa Ananias bèbhe, ka madhe dènge. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu dhu tadèngi lii ne'e, madha'u titu kèna.<bt>When he heard Petrus speak like that, suddenly Ananias fell down, dying on the spot. Then people who heard about that matter were terribly afraid.</bt><v n="6" />Hèia ana ngèru dhèu pèri mai, ka ra pahutu ngi'u Ananias, ka nedhe rèti lasi padhane.<bt>Then several young people came and they wrapped up Ananias' body, and took him to go bury him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhe dènge = mati memang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">madhe dènge = mati memang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Pe d'ai tèlu jam sa, dhèu èmu Ananias mai. Te ngaa na ne'a boe ngaa dhu j'aj'i deo na.<bt>After three hours, Ananias' wife came. But she didn't know what had happened earlier.</bt><v n="8" />Hèia Petrus karèi ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia, ina? Miu pahie le rai èèna, kab'ua sange ne'e ka, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>So then Petrus asked her, saying, &lt;&lt;How is it, mother? You(pl) sold that land, its price was like this, right?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a, ama. Kab'ua nèngu sange èèna ka.&gt;&gt;<bt>And she answered, saying, &lt;&lt;Correct, father. Its price was like that.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia Petrus tao dènge ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka èu dènge dhèu èmu mu pame'a ho neo cob'a Roh Lamatua? Mu ladhe, ee! Dhèu dhu heka padhane dhèu èmu èu sèra, lèpa hari mai le. Ciki ood'e hari na, rèngu nedhe rèti hari ngi'u èu, ho lasi padhane ètu karasa dhèu èmu èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus scolded her, saying, &lt;&lt;How is it that you and your husband agreed to try to test-the-metal of the Spirit of God? You will see, ee! The people who just buried your husband have come back again. Soon they will take your body back to go bury it beside your husband.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mere lii èci = ambil satu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">mere lii èci = ambil satu suara, ba'akor ; pame'a = basakongkol, baku tahu, baku atur ; sèku = 1) ukur, 2) coba (test metal, 2nd sense not widely used) ; bèka = rebis</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa tadèngi nare lii padhai lii Petrus, cag'ag'a laa dhèu bhèni ne bèbhe, ka madhe dènge ètu era èèna. Ropa ana-ana ngèru sèra maso hari asa d'ara èmu, ladhe rèdhi bhèni ne madhe le. Ka j'èru rèti ka ngi'u bhèni ne, lasi padhane ètu karasa dhèu èmu na.<bt>When she heard what Petrus said, suddenly the woman fell down, and died (on the spot--manner) in that place (location). And they carried out the corpse of that dead woman, going to bury her beside her husband.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="j'èru 2 = pikol peti mayat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">j'èru 2 = pikol peti mayat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01908b.tif" rtfFormat="width:9.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:center">Safira madhe dènge, ètu era èèna<bt>Safira dies on the spot in that place</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu parcaya Yesus sèra madha'u. Dhèu-dhèu leo dhu tadèngi lii lolo nèti mamadhe Ananias dènge Safira, madha'u kahèi.<bt>After that, the people who believed in Yesus were frightened. Other people who heard the story about the death of Ananias and Safira, were also afraid.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="li lolo Ananias = 1) yg"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">li lolo Ananias = 1) yg Ananias cerita</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus si puri-pa'èle dhèu ae<bt>Peturs(coll) heal many people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu pajuu-paleha Yesus sèra tao ae tadha-tadha malaa. Ka dhèu ae sèra ladhe rèdhi. Dhèu pajuu-paleha sèra biasa lasi asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Lamatua. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra pakaboko dènge d'ara èci ètu d'ara Èmu Taleo Dhèu Aae Soleman.<bt>That day/time, the servants/emissaries of Yesus did many kinds of amazing signs. And many people was them. The servants/emissaries of Yesus often went into the Temple. They all gathered with one inside, in the Open-aired House of King Solemaa.</bt><v n="13" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu ae ka dhu koa dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus sèra. Te ngaa dhèu leo cahag'e bani boe maso pakaboko dènge rèngu ètu èmu èèna.<bt>That day/time, many people praised the servants/emissaries of the Lord Yesus. But some other people (outside the group) were not bold enough to come in an gather together with them in that building.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rae lesa = kampong, karabat, isis"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rae lesa = kampong, karabat, isis kampong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Te dhèu dhu parcaya Yesus, bhèni-mone, asa tabha ae.<bt>But/and people who believed in Yesus, female-male, continued to increase in number.</bt><v n="15" />Lula tadha malaa ae dhu j'aj'i èèna, ka dhèu ae rèti dhèu pèd'a lasi ho ra pamadhèdi mi dedha dhèpi ètu sebhe j'ara. Te ra pangee, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Petrus dènge Yohanis kako re era ne'e, sad'i mamaho ra lèke rèngu di, dhèu pèd'a se èle dènge nèti papèd'a rèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because so many amazing signs had happened, many people brought sick people to sit them on mats by the side of the road. Cause they thought, saying, &lt;&lt;If Pete and Yohanis walk by this place, as long as even their shadow hits them there, these sick people will be healed of their disease.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="16" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu ae mai taruu nèti rae-rae ètu sebhe kota Yerusalem. Rèti dènge dhèu-dhèu pèd'a, ka dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua se puri-pa'èle si aa'i-aa'i ra. Rèngu rèti dhèu-dhèu dhu nidhu tao kahèi, ka dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua se babège eele aa'i nidhu-nidhu sèra.<bt>At that time, a great many people came from villages nearby the city of Yerusalem. They brought various sick people, and the servants/emissaries of the Lord healed them all. They also brought people whom *evil-spirits had done [collocating with evil-spirit this term has sense of bother/possess/mistreat/abuse], and the servants/emissaries of the Lord evicted all those evil-spirits.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus abhu j'aj'èra<bt>The servants/emissaries of the Lord Yesus get difficulty/trouble</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Lula tatao dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus sèra, nèti èèna ka kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi, dènge angalai nèngu nèti partei Saduki sèra, tèka d'ara.<bt>At that time, people who came to unite with the servants/emissaries of Yesus kept increasing in number. But the *High Priest (&lt;Top Leader of the Jahudi religion) and his companions from the Saduki party, had sick insides (=angry, jealous, annoyed).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lod'o èèna, dhèu dhu mai pa'èci dènge ana pajuu-paleha Yesus sèra tabha ae hari. Te ngaa, "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-12-14 01:01:40Z" status="Anyone">OV</Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Nèti èèna ka, ra kèpa dhèu pajuu-paleha Yesus sèra, ka ra pamaso si asa d'ara bèdho.<bt>That is why they arrested the servants/emissaries of Yesus, and put them in prison.</bt><note reference="5:18" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani ne'e, sasoa na, &lt;&lt;pamaso asa d'ara bèdho kabarai.&gt;&gt; Sasoa leo, peka na, &lt;&lt;pamaso asa d'ara bèdho ho pamakae si ètu katanga madha dhèu ae.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Yunani language here means &lt;&lt;put them into the public jail.&gt;&gt; Another meaning says, &lt;&lt;put them into jail to shame them before many people.&gt;&gt;</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Te ngaa mèda èèna kahèi, ana pajuu Lamatua èci mai nèti sorga asa d'ara bèdho èèna, ka na bhoke eele babèdho. Hèia na lere nèti si asa li'u. Ka na peka, aku nèngu na,<bt>But that night, a messenger of God2 came from heaven (*angel) into that prison, and opened up the closing-barriers (=cell doors). Then he led them outside. And he spoke, saying,</bt><v n="20" />&lt;&lt;Lami dènge ka asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Lami peka aa'i dènge dhèu-dhèu ètu nèi, sèna ka ra madhutu J'ara Mamuri dhu hiu nèti Lamatua Yesus.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;Go directly to the Temple, Go tell everything to the people yonder, so that they follow/obey the new Way of Life/Salvation from the Lord Yesus.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="babèdho = tutupnya"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">babèdho = tutupnya</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Bèli mad'ae èèna, ako maroga era, rèngu madhutu ka lii paredha nèti ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga deo na. Ka ra maso asa d'ara madha Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, hèia ra aj'a-nori dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra.<bt>The next morning, whle it was still dark, they followed the recent orders of God2's messenger from heaven. And they went into the front/yard/courtyard of that Temple, and they taught the people there.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01911b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Petrus si kalua nèti èmu bèdho<bt>Petrus (coll) [get] out of prison</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Nèbhu boe, hèia kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi dènge angalai na sèra mai palere dènge dhèu kapai dènge dhèu heka-dhèu heka ad'a Isra'el. Rèngu pakaboko ho parisa lii langu nèti dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus sèra. Hèia ra pua dhèu lasi rare Petrus si nèti d'ara bèdho, ho ra parisa lii langu ra.<bt>Not long after that, the High Priest of the Jahudi religion and his companions came together with the leaders of Isra'el. They gathered to examine the case of the servants/emissaries of the Lord Yesus. Then they ordered people to go get Petrus (coll) from in the prison so they could examine their case.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa ropa rèngu d'ai èmu bèdho, Petrus si aad'o heka ètu d'ara. Ka ana j'aga sèra lèpa hari lasi peka dènge dhèu kapai sèra.<bt>But, when they arrived at the prison, Petrus (coll) were no longer inside. And the guards returned again to speak with the leaders.</bt><v n="23" />Ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama si, baku nasa. Ropa ji'i d'ai èmu bèdho, ji'i ladhe, na, babèdho dhu patèke. Aa dhèu j'aga sèra titu ètu era èèna. Te ngaa ropa ji'i pua ra goe babèdho ho ji'i la'a asa d'ara, ji'i ngèdhi boe dhèu èci sa ètu d'ara.&gt;&gt;<bt>They said, &lt;&lt;Fathers (coll), don't be angry. When we arrived at the prison, we saw the doors locked. And the guards were standing in that place. But, when we ordered them to unlock the doors so we could go inside, we saw nobody inside.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patèke = kunci ; goe ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">patèke = kunci ; goe = buka dgn kunci ; gagoe = anak kunci</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa tadèngi rare, hèia kètu agama Yahudi sèra, dènge kapala j'aga Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i malaa, aa sèmi dhèu dhu ele ngangee sa.<bt>When they heard that the religious leaders and the head guard of that Temple, they all became amazed/confused, and were like people who had lost their thinking.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ele ngangee = hilang pikiran"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ele ngangee = hilang pikiran</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Nèbhu boe, hèia dhèu èci mai peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama si, nanene ku laa! Dhèu dhu miu bèdho sèra, ètu li'u si, ra titu ho aj'a-nori dhèu ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Not long after that a person came and said, &lt;&lt;Fathers (coll), listen up! The people who you(pl) imprisoned, they are right outside, standing and teaching people inside this Temple!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ropa tadèngi rare, ka kapala j'aga Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i èèna paroa dhèu j'aga pèri-pèri ho lasi kèpe hari Petrus dènge angalai na sèra. Te ngaa dhèu j'aga sèra madha'u, lula dhèu dhu nanene lii padhai-padhue Petrus sèra, ae seli. Ra pajiko, na, mage dhoka dhèu ae sèra patao-palaha, ho ra pèci si. Nèti èèna ka, ropa rèngu kèpe hari Petrus si, ra bani boe pake j'ara sakaa.<bt>When they heard that, the head guard of that Temple ordered several guards to go arrest Petrus and his companions again. But those guard were afraid, because the people who were listening to what Petrus (coll) were saying were very many. They evaluated-the-situation, lest those many people run amuck and throw (rocks) at them. That is why, when they arrested Petrus (coll) again, they did not dare use force/roughness.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pèci = throw (with rocks)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pèci = throw (with rocks)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Èle èèna ka, ra lere rèti Petrus si asa era pama'ète lii langu. Ka kètu kapai risi agama mulai karèi si,<bt>So they brought Petrus (coll) to the place of examining disputes. And the Top Religious Leader began to ask them,</bt><v n="28" />peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i kai le miu, sèna ka aj'a ia ka dhèu lula-nèti Dhèu dhu neo tao j'ara mamuri hiu èèna, sina ma! Te ngaa miu palab'a! Miu pusi-pahae boe dènge lii paredha ji'i, te ngaa miu tao madhutu dad'èi miu di! Miu lami aj'a-nori palème dhèu ètu kota Yerusalem ne. Èèna sama dènge miu core sasala mi dedha ji'i, peka na, ji'i se ka dhu pua dhèu lasi pamadhe Yesus.&gt;&gt;<bt>saying, &lt;&lt;We(exc) have forbidden you(pl) from teaching people any more about that person wants to make a new way of life, right! But you are rock heads (=stubborn)! You pay no attention to our orders, but you just follow your own wishes! You go teach people all over this city of Yeruslaem. It is as if you are throwing the wrong on top of us, saying that we here are the ones who ordered people to kill that Yesus.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="5:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 27:25</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Hèia Petrus kèd'i titu j'aj'i dhèu dhu padhai lii nèti angalai na sèra. Ka na dhaa, peka na,<bt>Then Petrus stood up to be the spokesperson for his companions. And he repsonded, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ama-ama! Ladhe abhu paredha nèti dhèu rai-haha dhu palab'a dènge dad'èi Ama Lamatua, ji'i ngo'o boe madhutu. Te ngaa ji'i madhutu dhoka paredha Ama Lamatua di!<bt>&lt;&lt;Fathers (coll)! If there is a command from earthly humans which opposes the will of God, we(exc) cannot obey it. But we only follow the commands of God!</bt><v n="30" />Dhèu dhu bhoke j'ara mamuri hiu èèna, nuka Yesus. Nèngu èèna ka dhu miu paku pamadhe ètu dedha aj'u palolo-palèbha. Nèti uru ka mai, bèi-baki èdhi manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua. Ama Lamatua èèna ka dhu pamamuri hari Yesus nèti mamadhe Na!<bt>The person who opened that new way of life is just Yesus. He is the one whom you(pl) nailed to death on the crossed wood. From long ago, our(inc) ancestors prayed to/worshipped God. It is that God who brought Yesus back to life from His death!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="31" />Limuri ne, Ama Lamatua ded'e le Yesus j'aj'i ai g'ana Na. Ka Yesus nèd'u le paredha sama sèmi dhèu aae kapai. Nèngu bhoke le j'ara, sèna ka Lamatua patabuli eele dhèu nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra. Na neo hia j'ara mi èdhi dhèu Isra'el se'e, sèna ka èdhi ae eele nèti sasala èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, d'ara Ama Lamatua pacuhi, ho Na ige heka sasala èdhi dhèu Isra'el.<bt>Now God has elevated Yesus to be His right hand (=trusted representative). And Yesus holds government as a king. He opened the way so that God2 could wipe away people's wrongs (doublet). He wants to provide a way for we(inc) people of Isra'el, for us to stop doing all of our wrongs. In that way God's insides are cooled/appeased, so that He no longer counts the wrongs of our people of Isra'el.</bt><v n="32" />Te èdhi tèdhi le dènge musi madha èdhi, Yesus mema madhe tare'a, te ngaa Na mamuri hari kahèi. Limuri ne Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci peka le dènge dhèu dhu madhutu J'ara Mamuri Yesus.&gt;&gt;<bt>For we(inc) have seen with our own eyeballs that Yesus really did die, but He is alive again. Now God's Holy Spirit has spoken (this) to people who follow/obey Yesus' Way of Life.&gt;&gt; [Element of "God gave HS" not explicit here].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ai g'ana = 1) tangan kanan,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ai g'ana = 1) tangan kanan, 2) wakil, orang yg terpercaya ; tabuli = lepas ; pacuhi = 1) dingin (udara), 2) dara pacuhi = sonde mara, sonde panas</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Tadèngi rare lii padhai lii Petrus sèmi èèna, ka dhèu dhu madhèdi ètu era pama'ète lii langu èèna nasa titu kèna, ka ra neo pamadhe dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua sèra.<bt>After hearing Petrus speak like that, the people who sat in that place of exmining court-cases were furious, and they wanted to kill the servants/emissaries of the Lord.</bt><v n="34" />Te ngaa ètu talora rèngu, abhu kahèi dhèu èci dhu madhèdi parisa lii, ngara na Gamaliel. Dhèu ae pakab'ua ne, lula nèngu ne mese dhu d'èlu-mèu nèti partei agama Parisi. Ropa Petrus padhai lii nare, ka dhèu sèra neo pamadhe ne, hèia Gamaliel kèd'i titu, ka na pua dhèu ho lere taha Petrus si asa li'u.<bt>But among them there was a person who sat examining disputes, named Gamaliel. Many people respected him, because he was a wise (=clear thinking) teacher from the Parisi religious party. When Petrus finished speaking, and people there wanted to kill him, Gamaliel stood up, and he ordered people to temporarily take Petrus (coll) outside.</bt><v n="35" />Ropa Petrus si d'ai li'u, ka Gamaliel padhai lii dènge ama-ama ètu sèra, aku nèngu na,<bt>When Petrus (coll) arrived outside, then Gamaliel spoke to the fathers (=leaders) that were there, saying,</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01913b.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Gamaliel padhai lii<bt>Gamaliel speaks</bt></fig>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;A'ari ti! Èdhi hud'i pajiko paie ku! Mage dhoka èdhi malai ae tao bhabhelu mi dedha dhèu se'e. Èdhi hud'i pangee madhera.<bt>&lt;&lt;My elder-younger siblings! We(inc) must carefully evaluate first! May it not be that we are in a hurry to do evil to these people. We must think long (=think it through, looking at consequences).</bt><v n="36" />Ele boe miu sanèd'e era, dhèu dhu ngara na Teudas. Nèngu madhe nèbhu le, te ngaa lod'o na mamuri era, na ded'e ngi'u na j'aj'i dhèu kapai, pe d'ai dhèu èpa ngasu sa madhutu nèngu. Te ngaa ropa ra pamadhe ne, ana-ana madhutu na paj'ala asa haa asa dhimu. Toke d'ai sange ne'e, dhèu rèdhi heka rèngu. Ra rai aa'i mèu-mèu le!<bt>You(pl) probably still remember tha person named Teudas. He's been dead for a long time, but when he was still alive he elevated himself to be a leader, and around 400 people followed him. But, when they killed him, his followers dispersed to the west and the east. To this day, people no longer see them. Every single one of them has run away (and disappeared)!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="37" />Aa miu sanèd'e hari ku lii lole èci. Uru èèna, lèke lod'o dhèu paredha ige dhèu ètu d'ara kabarai. Abhu dhèu èci, ngara na Yudas, nèti propensi Galilea. Dhèu ae madhutu nèngu kahèi. Te ngaa ra pamadhe ne kahèi. Hèia ana-ana madhutu na rai paj'ala kahèi, ka d'ai sange ne'e tèdhi heka dhèu èci sa.<bt>Ans you also remember another story. Long ago, it happened when the government people counted the people in their country. There was a person named Yudas, from the province of Galilea. Many people also followed him. But they killed him as well. Then his followers also scattered, so that to this day we no longer see a single one of them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="38" />De a'ari! Madhutu ngangee ja'a, baku pamadhe dhèu se'e. Hud'i rèngu sène. Te a'aj'a dènge kakako rèngu, ladhe mai nèti dhèu rai-haha, na, nèbhu boe, ele unu na.<bt>So elder-younger siblings! According to my thinking, don't kill these people. Let them be. Cause their teaching and their movement, if it comes from earthly humans, it will not last long, it will disappear itself.</bt><v n="39" />Te ngaa ladhe a'aj'a rèngu tare'a-re'a nèti Ama Lamatua, miu taha mere boe. Nèti èèna ka, miu pajiko paie ku. Mage dhoka miu palab'a dènge Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, if this teaching of theirs is truly from God, you(pl) will not be able to restrain them. Therefore because of that, you must weigh the options carefully. May it not be that you are opposing God.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Tadèngi rare sèmi èèna, rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra lèka, ka ra madhutu lii Gamaliel.<bt>Having heard that, they all agreed, and they followed what Gamaliel had just said.</bt><v n="40" />Èle èèna ka, ra paroa hari dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua sèra, ka ra pua dhèu ho hake si. Hèia ra kai si, ho baku ale-ale ia ka kolongara Yesus. Ka ra patabuli si.<bt>After that, they again summoned the servants/emissaries of the Lord, and they ordered people to beat them. Then they forbade them to no longer go around mentioning the name/reputation of Yesus. And they released them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="taha = tahan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">taha = tahan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Hèia dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua se tèke eele era pama'ète lii langu èèna. Ra pangee, na, masi ka kolongara rèngu ele iie lula madhutu Lamatua Yesus, te ngaa rèngu karej'e kahèi, lula rèngu hud'i abhu j'aj'èra sèmi èèna. Nèti èèna ka, d'ara rèngu karej'e titu kèna.<bt>Then the servants/emissaries of the Lord left behind that place of making disputes. They thought even though their names/reputations were damaged because they followed the Lord Yesus, nevertheless they were also happy, because they must get suffering in that way. That is why their insides were very happy.</bt><v n="42" />Bèli-bèli èèna, rèngu lasi aj'a-nori dhèu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u nare nèti uru ka mai, nuka Yesus di.&gt;&gt; Ka ra peka padhue taruu, nèti ca èmu d'ai ca èmu, sèmi èèna kahèi ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i.<bt>Every day they went to teach people, saying, &lt;&lt;The Person whom God designated from long ago, that is Yesus.&gt;&gt; And they spoke discussing from one house to another, and also in that Temple.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra hag'e rare dhèu pidhu, ho lalau nganga'a bhèni balu ana-lalu<bt>They set aside seven people, to serve the food of the widows and orphans [double doublet covering unfortunate people in need]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu sala = orang miskin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhèu sala = orang miskin</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu dhu parcaya Yesus asa tabha ae. Te ngaa rèngu pake dua lii. Dhèu Yahudi cahag'e, pake lii Aram. Aa cahag'e hari, pake lii Yunani. Nèbhu boe ka, j'aj'i lii langu ètu talora dua kaboko dhèu se'e. Dhèu dhu pake lii Yunani, d'ara be'a boe dènge dhèu dhu pake lii Aram. Ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Ne'e ne, lèke boe! Ladhe miu papala nganga'a bèli-bèli, miu bia cabèka. Bhèni balu ji'i abhu boe nganga'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>At that day/time, people who believed in Yesus continued to increase in number. But they were using two languages. Some of the Jahudi people were using the Aram language. And others were using the Yunani language. Eventually a dispute happened between these two groups. People who used the Yunani language did not have good insides toward the people who used the Aram language. They said, &lt;&lt;This thing/matter is not right! If/when you(pl) are dividing up the daily food, you are are heavy on the side (=biased, favouritism). Our(exc) widows don't get food.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii langu = bertengkar ; kaboko"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lii langu = bertengkar ; kaboko = kalompok</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Lula èèna ka, dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua dhèu canguru dua, pakaboko dhèu dhu parcaya Lamatua Yesus aa'i-aa'i ra. Ka ra peka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari aa'i-aa'i ti! Ladhe ji'i ae eele nèti sasab'a ji'i, ho lalau dhoka nganga'a-nginu miu di, bisa kahèi, te ngaa, lèke boe! Lula ji'i se hud'i aj'a-nori taruu Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua.<bt>Because of that, the 12 servants/emissaries of the Lord gathered all the people who believed in the Lord Yesus. And they told them, saying, &lt;&lt;All you elder-younger siblings! If we(exc) stop (doing) our work, to just serve your food-drink, we could do that, but it is not right! Because we must continue to teach God2's Good News.</bt><v n="3" />De madhutu ngangee ji'i, sèmi ne'e ka. Be'a risi, hag'e mere dhèu pidhu nèti talora miu. Tenge dhèu dhu kolongara be'a, dhu d'èlu-mèu, aa Roh Lamatua ator mamuri na. Ladhe mi pili mere dhèu sèmi sèra, pe ji'i ded'e si, ho ra lalau nganga'a-nginu.<bt>So according to our thinking it is like this. It would be best for you to choose seven people from among you. Look for people who have a good name/reputation. Who are wise/smart, and God2's Spirit arranges/manages their lives. When you have selected them, then we(exc) will appoint them to serve food-drink.</bt><v n="4" />Ladhe sèmi èèna, ji'i abhu tebho ae ho manèngi-mangaj'i aa aj'a Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>When it is like that, we will have more time to tell God2's Teachings, and to pray.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahaha iisi = tau rendah hati"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pahaha iisi = tau rendah hati ; madha j'ara ae</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia dhèu se'e sèmi rare kahèi lii padhai lii Petrus si. Ka hag'e rare dhèu pidhu, nuka:<bt>Then these people accepted what Petrus had just said. And the chose seven people, who were:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhèu èci, ngara na Stefanus. Nèngu ne parcaya tare'a-re'a Lamatua Yesus, dènge Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci pake nèngu. Aa angalai nèngu na, nuka:<bt>a person named Stefanus. He truly believed the Lord Yesus, and God2's Holy Spirit used him. And his companions were:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pelipus,<bt>Pelipus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Prokorus,<bt>Prokorus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nikanor,<bt>Nikanor,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Timon,<bt>Timon,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Permenas,<bt>Permenas,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge Nikolas, nèti kota Antiokia. Nèngu dhèu Yahudi boe, te ngaa na maso agama Yahudi.<bt>and Nikolas who was not a Jahudi person, but had entered the Jahudi religion. He came from the city of Antiokia.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia lere rèti dhèu pidhu dhu ra pili rare sèra, asa madha dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua. Ka ra bane ai dènge manèngi-mangaj'i hia si, ho ded'e si j'aj'i dhèu ladhe-leru bhèni balu ana-lalu, sèna ka aa'i-aa'i ra abhu pala dhu pamera.<bt>Then they brought those seven people whom they had selected before the servants/emissaries of the Lord. And they laid their hands and prayed for them, to appoint them to be people who looked-after/served the widows and orphans (emic category), so that everybody would get their fair share.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baa ai = buka tangan (open"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">baa ai = buka tangan (open wide, not touch); ladhe-leru = urus ; bane = touch, lay hands on</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Èèna ka, dhèu tadèngi Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua ètu mia-mia. Hèia dhèu-dhèu dhu madhutu J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus, asa tabha ae ètu kota Yerusalem. Aa ama agama Yahudi sèra, ae kahèi dhu j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus.<bt>So, the Lord's Teachings, they spoke all over the place. The people who followed the Life Way of the Lord Yesus kept increasing in number in the city of Yerusalem. And the religious father/leaders, many also became followers of Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra kèpe Stefanus<bt>They arrest Stefanus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Lod'o èèna, Ama Lamatua hia berkat ae mi Stefanus. Na hia Stefanus koasa kahèi, ho na tao tadha-tadha malaa dènge j'ara-j'ara kapai, sèna ka dhèu ae rèdhi unu ra.<bt>At that time/day, God gave many blessings to Stefanus. He also gave Stafanus power so he could do many kinds of amazing signs and extraordinary things, so that many people could see for themselves.</bt><v n="9" />Ètu era èèna, abhu pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi dhu mai nèti rai-rai kaj'èu, nuka: kota Kirene, kota Aleksandria, propensi Kilikia, dènge propensi Asia. Uru èèna, rèngu j'aj'i ènu dhèu leo, te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu ka lamatua rèngu patabuli si. Èle èèna ka, dhèu se'e pakaboko ètu Yerusalem. Rèngu tema le lasi asa èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhu ra patitu unu ra. Èmu manèngi-mangaj'i èèna, ra pangare ne, &lt;J'aj'i Heka Ènu&gt;. Ropa ra tadèngi lii padhai lii Stefanus, dhèu se d'èi boe, ka ra pab'ala dènge ne.<bt>In that place there were several Jahudi people who came from far-away lands. They were the city of Kirene, the city of Aleksandria, the province of Kilikia, and the Province of Asia. Previously they had been other people's slaves, but eventually their masters freed them. So then these people gathered in Yerusalem. They were in the habit of going to the house of worship which they had made themselves. That house of worship, they called it, &lt;Being No Longer Slaves&gt;. When they heard what Stefanus was saying, these people didn't like it, and they argued with him.</bt><v n="10" />Stefanus ne, dhèu d'èlu-mèu, lula nèngu padhai lii pake koasa Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu se'e segi boe nèngu.<bt>This Stefanus was a (1-pure-hearted/2-smart/clever) person, because he spoke using the power of God2's Holy Spirit. Because of that, these people couldnt win an argument with him.</bt><v n="11" />Ka ra tenge j'ara aapa mi dedha Stefanus. Ra lasi b'ae dhèu ho j'aj'i sakasii leko-monya, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i tadèngi, na, dhèu ne'e padhai lii pahaha Musa dènge Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>So, then they looked for a way (negative connotations) to beat Stefanus. They went and paid people to be false witnesses, saying, &lt;&lt;We heard this person speaking degradingly about Musa and God!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ènu = budak; ètu dara TB"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ènu = budak; ètu dara TB dènge BIS peka jelas boe na dhèu se uru na ènu dhèu ; dhèu kapai = master; <span class="Bold">10:</span> dèlu-mèu = 1) dalam hati barisi, 2) orang yg pintar; <span class="Bold">11:</span> omo-koso =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Rèngu dadugu dhèu, toke d'ai dhèu heka ad'a Yahudi dènge mese agama sèra tadèngi kahèi. Ka ra nasa. Nèti èèna ka, lasi kèpe rare Stefanus, hèia ra nuni ne asa era pama'ète lii langu agama.<bt>They incited people to the point that the Jahudi adat leaders, and the religious teachers also heard about it. And they were angry. Because of that, they went and arrested Stefanus, and dragged him to the place where they examine religious disputes.</bt><v n="13" />Sakasii leko-monya rèngu sèra, ue lii langu ho pamanahu Stefanus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne loe boe padhai lii pakarehe Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Aa na peka pa'ele iie lii paredha Ama Lamatua, dhu Musa papuru mi èdhi.<bt>Those false witnesses created disputes to bring down Stefanus, saying, &lt;&lt;This person never stops speaking slander about the Temple. And he's saying he's going to get rid of the commands of God, which Musa has brought down to us(inc).</bt><v n="14" />Ji'i tadèngi kahèi, na peka, na, Yesus, dhèu Nasaret, neo sag'e eele Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ne. Aa nèngu ne neo pa'ele iie atora ad'a dhu baki Musa tao tèka hia èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>We(exc) also heard him speak about Yesus, that Nasaret person, wanting to tear apart this Temple. And he is the one who wants to get rid of all the adat regulations that Grandpa Musa made for us(inc).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sag'e èmu = bongkar (rumah)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sag'e èmu = bongkar (rumah)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu madhèdi ètu era pama'ète lii langu agama èèna ladhe kaloo Stefanus, lula rèhu na sama sèmi rèhu ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga.<bt>After that, all the people who were sitting in that place of examining religious disputes, looked inspecting Stefanus, because his face was like the face of the Lord's servants from heaven.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Stefanus siri iisi na ètu era j'ue lii agama<bt>Stefanus defends himself in the place where they settle religious disputes</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="7" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi karèi Stefanus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu se'e galaa èu ne, lèke do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the High Priest of the Jahudi religion asked Stefanus, saying, &lt;&lt;These people are accusing you, [is it] true or not?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01915b.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:center; verticalPosition:bottom">Stefanus padhai lii dènge dhèu kapai ètu era pama'ète lii langu agama Yahudi<bt>Stefanus talking to the leaders at the place of settling Jahudi religious disputes</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2-3" />Ka Stefanus b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama, aa a'ari aa'i-aa'i! Miu nanene ku ja'a. Uru-uru sèra, bèi-baki èdhi Abraham dhae tèke eele mèka rai èta-èsu na. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua dhu kapai risi pad'elo iisi Na mi nèngu. Lamatua hia ne paredha, peka na, &lt;Pakèd'i nèti rai èta-èsu èu; tèke eele a'ari èu. Lamu ka asa era èci, dhu bèli-camèd'a Ja'a paj'uj'u hia èu!&gt; Hèia na pakèd'i ka nèti rai èta-èsu na, ètu rai Mesopotamia, la'e asa kota Haran.<bt>So Stefanus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers, elder-younger siblings! Listen to me now. Long ago, our(inc) forefather Abrahama had not yet left behind the land of his birth (lit: land of cutting the umbilical cord). But God who is greater than all revealed Himself to him. God2 gave him a command, saying, &lt;Depart from this land of your birth; leave behind your relatives. (parallelism). Go to a place, which in the future I will point out to you!&gt; Then he departed from that place of his birth, in the land of Mesopotamia, going to the city of Haran.</bt><note reference="7:2-3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Rai Mesopotamia èèna, limuri ne ra pangare na, rai Irak. Kota Haran èèna, limuri ne abhu sisa nèngu ètu rai Siria. Parisa <span class="Italic">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 12:1</span>.<bt>That land/country of Mesopotamia these days is called the country of Irak. That city of Haran, today its remains can be found in the country of Siria. Examine <span class="Italic">Genesis 12:1r.</span></bt></note><v n="4" />Hèia na tèke eele rai dhèu Kasdim, ka la'e pea ètu kota Haran. Ropa ama d'èlu na madhe, ka Ama Lamatua lere ne asa rai ne'e ne, dhu ama-ama a'ari pea toke d'ai sange ne'e ne.<bt>So then he left the land of the Kasdim people, and went to live in the city of Haran. When his birth father died, God brought him to this land, where you fathers and elder-younger silbings live to this day.</bt><note reference="7:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 11:31, 12:4</note><v n="5" />Lod'o èèna, Ama Lamatua hag'e boe rai ca kasib'i sa hia ne ho j'aj'i rai pusaka na. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua moa tèke le, na, Nèngu hia rai ne'e, j'aj'i rai pusaka ana-èpu na. Te ngaa lod'o èèna, Abraham dènge mèka ana.<bt>At that time, God did not select one tiny plot of land to give to him to be his land inheritance. But, God promised that He would give this land to be land inheritance to the descendants of his. But at that time, Abraham did not yet have any children.</bt><note reference="7:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 12:7, 13:15, 15:18, 17:8</note><v n="6" />Ka Ama Lamatua peka dènge ne, &lt;Bèli-camèd'a ana-èpu èu lasi pea ètu rai dhèu. Ho dhèu rai èèna ènyi si, aa tao rèngu j'aj'i ènu, dènge paj'èra si toke d'ai èpa ngasu tèu.<bt>And God spoke to him, In the future your descendants will go stay in the land of (other) people. The people of that land will make them slaves, cause them to suffer for 400 years.</bt><v n="7" />Ho ladhe èle èpa ngasu tèu èèna, Ja'a huku dhèu kabarai dhu tao ana-èpu èu j'aj'i ènu sèra. Hèia ana-èpu èu tèke eele rai èèna, ho rèngu mai asa era ne'e ne, sèna ka ra manèngi makasi mi Ja'a.&gt;<bt>And after those 400 years, I will punish the people of the society that makes your descendants slaves. Then your descendants will leave that land behind, so they will come to this land here, so that they can give thanks (loan) to Me.&gt;</bt><note reference="7:6-7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 15:13-14; Kalua nèti Masir 3:12</note><v n="8" />Padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, ka Na hia tadha lii moa Ne dènge j'ara suna ana mone,<bt>After speaking like that, He gave a sign for that promise with the way of *circumcising (loan) [NOTE: see ftn below--they are the biggest prudes :)] their sons/males,</bt><note reference="7:8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Dhao &lt;suna&gt; èèna, &lt;bèka&gt;. Te ngaa, lula &lt;bèka&gt; èèna, lii makae, ka ji'i suri boe.<bt>In the Dhao language &lt;circumcise(loan)&gt; is &lt;cut open/circumcise(vernacular)&gt;. But, because this vernacular word is embarrassing, we do not write it.</bt></note>j'aj'i tadha dhu sasoa na, Abraham j'aj'i le dhèu unu Ama Lamatua. Èle èèna ka, ropa ana na, Isak, d'ai umur aru lod'o, hèia na suna ne. Aa Isak suna ana na, Yakob kahèi. Aa Yakob suna ana-ana mone na, dhèu canguru dua sèra, ladhe umur rèngu d'ai aru lod'o. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i sèra, bèi-baki èdhi dhèu Yahudi.<bt>as a sign meaning Abraham has become a person belonging to God. After that, when his child, Isa, was eight days old, then he circumcised him. And Isa also circumcised his child, Jako. And Jako circumcised his 12 sons, when they were eight days old. All of them, are the forefathers of our(inc) Jahudi people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai èta èsu = tanah potong"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rai èta èsu = tanah potong pusar; <span class="Bold">4:</span> ama matana ~ ama dèlu = bapa barana; <span class="Bold">8:</span> bèka</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 17:10-14, 21:2-4, 25:26, 29:31--35:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ca tèka, bèi-baki èdhi sèra d'ara pèd'a dènge ari ra Yusuf, ka ra pahie eele ne ka j'aj'i ènu ètu rai Masir nèi. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa Ama Lamatua tèke eele boe ne.<bt>Then our(inc) ancestors were jealous/hated their younger sibling Yusuf, and they sold him off to be a slave in the land of Masir yonder. Even that being the case, God did not abandon him.</bt><note reference="7:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 37:11, 28, 39:2, 21</note><v n="10" />Nèti èèna ka Lamatua patabuli eele ne nèti j'aj'èra nèngu. Ama Lamatua hia ne d'èlu-mèu, ka ne'a j'ara ae-ae, ka Dhèu Aae Masir sue ne. Nèti èèna ka, na ded'e ne j'aj'i gubernur ètu rai Masir. Aa na nèd'u koasa kahèi ètu d'ara èmu dhèu aae.<bt>That is why God2 freed him from his suffering. God gave him wisdom/smarts, and he knew/understood many things, so the King of Masir [=Egypt] loved/pitied him. Because of that, he elevated ne to be gubernur of the land/country of Masir. And he also held power/authority in the house of the King.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Yusuf = Jusu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Yusuf = Jusu</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 41:39-41</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia tèu manganga lèke rai Masir dènge rai Kana'an. Tèu-tèu manganga mad'èu èèna, bia titu kèna. Nèti èèna ka dhèu ètu mia-mia j'èra d'ai seli. Sèmi èèna kahèi, bèi-baki èdhi abhu heka nganga'a.<bt>Then a year/season of hunger hit the land of Masir and the land of Kanaan. Those years of hunger were very heavy (=severe). Because of that people everywhere were suffering horribly. In the same way also, our(inc) ancestors also had no more food.</bt><note reference="7:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 42:1-2</note><v n="12" />Te ngaa baki Yakob tadèngi lii, na, ètu rai Masir abhu nganga'a. Ka na pua ana-ana na sèra, nuka bèi-baki èdhi, ho lasi hèli nganga'a ètu rai Masir.<bt>But, Grandpa Jako heard news that there was food in Masir. So he ordered his children, that is our ancestors, to go buy food in the land of Masir.</bt><v n="13" />Hèli rare, hèia ra lèpa. Ropa oe èle nganga'a sèra, ka ama ra pua hari lasi hèli nganga'a ètu Masir. Lod'o èèna ka, heka Yusuf bhoke d'ara, peka na, nèngu ne ari d'èlu rèngu. Ka na patadha a'ari na sèra dènge dhèu aae Masir.<bt>[When] they had finished buying it, then they returned home. When they were almost out of food, their father sent them back to go buy food in Masir. At that time, only.then did Yusuf open his insides (reveal himself), saying that he was their younger blood brother. And he introduced his elder-younger siblings to the King of Masir.</bt><note reference="7:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 45:1, 16</note><v n="14" />Èle èèna ka, Yusuf manèngi ama na dènge a'ari na aa'i-aa'i lasi pea asa rai Masir. Rèngu dhu lasi asa nèi, aa'i-aa'i ra pidhu nguru lèmi dhèu.<bt>After that, Yusuf asked his father and elder-younger siblings to go live in the land of Masir. They are the ones who went yonder, all of them were 75 people.</bt><note reference="7:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 45:9-10, 17-18, 46:27</note><v n="15" />De baki Yakob pidha asa nèi, toke d'ai bèi-baki èdhi sèra madhe ètu Masir.<bt>So, Grandpa Jako moved yonder, and those ancesters of ours died Masir.</bt><note reference="7:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 46:1-7, 49:33</note><v n="16" />Ka nèbhu aae ku, heka rèti rui bèi-baki èdhi sèra lèpa hari asa rae Sikem ètu rai Kana'an. Ka ra tèke rui sèra ètu era dhu uru èèna baki Abraham hèli nare nèti ana-èpu Hemor.&gt;&gt;<bt>And after a long time, only.then did they take the bones of our ancestors, returning back to the village of Sikem in the land of Kanaan. And they stored those bones, in the place which Grandpa Abraham had previously bought from the descendants of Hemor.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patadha ~ patadhe = (RECIP) kasi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">patadha ~ patadhe = (RECIP) kasi kanal ; patabe = kasi pegang tangan; <span class="Bold">16:</span> aae = @@ different use from 'king' ; kèi = gali</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 23:3-16, 33:19, 50:7-13, Yosua 24:32</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Stefanus b'ala lula-nèti Musa dènge dhèu dhu ro'o boe nanene ne [\s2]<bt>Stefanus tells about Musa and those rock-headed (stubborn) people [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Stefanus tuhu hari lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Se'e se j'aj'i, lula Ama Lamatua moa tèke le, na, èèna na limuri hari Nèngu neo hia rai pusaka mi baki Abraham ètu era èèna. Ropa oe d'ai lod'o dhu Ama Lamatua moa èèna, èdhi dhèu Yahudi tabha ae titu kèna ètu rai Masir nèi.<bt>These things happened, because God2 had promised beforehand, saying, that later on He would give an/the inheritance land to Grandpa Abraham in that place. When it came near to the day/time which God had spoken His promise, we(inc) Jahudi people had increased greatly in number in that land of Masir yonder.</bt><v n="18" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu aae hiu èci paredha ètu nèi. Te ngaa nèngu tadhe boe Yusuf.<bt>At that time, there was a new king there. He did know know (about) Yusuf.</bt><note reference="7:17-18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 1:7-8</note><v n="19" />Dhèu aae ne'e ènyi ruri dhèu èdhi sèra. Aa na bhelu titu kèna dènge bèi-baki èdhi. Na laka-seti rèngu ho core eele ana rèngu dhu rara iisi hiu, sèna ka madhe.<bt>This king, oppressed our(inc) people. And he did many evil things to our ancestors. And he forced them to throw away their newborn infants, so they would die by themselves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamèci = bekin bae ; padai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pamèci = bekin bae ; padai = bekin sampai; <span class="Bold">19:</span> j'èli = injak , oppress ; j'èli-ruri = step and twist into ground ; paksa ; ènyi = tindas ;</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 1:10-11, 22</note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01918b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Ana bhèni dhèu aae Masir ded'e nare Musa nèti d'ara loko<bt>The daughter of the king of Masir lifts Musa from the river</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Lod'o èèna, d'ai lod'o ina Musa nara iisi ne. Musa kabèb'u titu kèna! Ina dènge ama na madhutu boe lii paredha dhèu aae. Ra piara pahuni ne, toke d'ai tèlu hèru.<bt>That time was around the time that Musa's mother gave birth. Musa was really healthy/well-formed/attractive! His father and mother did not follow the command of that king. They raised him in secret, until three months.</bt><note reference="7:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 2:2</note><v n="21" />Ropa rèngu bisa heka pahuni ne ètu d'ara èmu, ka ra panangi eele ne. Te ngaa ana bhèni dhèu aae Masir rage nare ne, ka sa'u nèti asa èmu, ka na ladhe-leru ne sèmi ana d'èlu nèngu.<bt>When they could no longer hide him in their house, they set him adrift [CHECK fv:panangi, includes instrument or not?]. But the daughter of the king of Masir stumbled upon him, and cuddled him into her house, and considered him as her own birth child.</bt><note reference="7:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 2:3-10</note><v n="22" />Nèti èèna ka, dhèu rai Masir aj'a aa'i ne dènge mamèu ra, toke d'ai na j'aj'i dhèu d'èlu-mèu. Nèngu ne d'èlu-mèu ètu d'ara lii padhai, aa ètu d'ara sab'a-la'a.<bt>Because of that, the people of Masir taught him everything about their knowledge/science, to the point that he became a wise/knowledgeable person. This he was skilled at speaking, and skilled in (many kinds of) work.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabèbu = montok, gemuk (babies) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kabèbu = montok, gemuk (babies) ; isi adhu ; palu'u; <span class="Bold">21:</span> palu'u = kasi sembunyi ; keler = ; panangi = kasi berenang (pake alat); rage = kebetulan katumu, stumble upon; <span class="Bold">22:</span> mamèu = ilmu, pengetahuan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Musa ne'a lii, dènge ne'a sab'a."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Musa ne'a lii, dènge ne'a sab'a.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ropa Musa d'ai umur èpa nguru tèu, hèia na neo patadha dènge dhèu Isra'el nèngu sèra.<bt>When Musa was 40 years (old), then he wanted to meet with his own Isra'el people.</bt><v n="24" />Ropa na la'e, ka na nèdhi dhèu Masir èci dhu game dhèu Isra'el ca dhèu. Ka na sarii dhèu Isra'el èèna, aa na hake pamadhe dhèu Masir èèna.<bt>When he went out, he saw a Masir person who was beating1 an Isra'el person. And he defended that Isra'el person, and he beat tot death that Masir person.</bt><v n="25" />Te Musa ngee, na, dhèu nèngu sèra re'a le, na, Ama Lamatua pua ne ho patabuli rèngu nèti j'aj'èra ra. Te ngaa rèngu re'a mèka.<bt>Now [background explan] Musa thought that his people knew that God had sent him to release them from their suffering. But they did not yet understand that.</bt><v n="26" />Bèli èèna, Musa la'e hari ladhe dhèu Isra'el na sèra. Ka na rage dhèu dua pagama. Aa na neo padame dhèu dua se, peka na, &lt;Weh! Miu dua mi se, pa'a'ari. Nga tao ka miu dua mi patao?&gt;<bt>The next day, Musa went out again to see his Isra'el people. And he stumbled upon two people having a fistfight. And he wanted to bring peace between these two people, saying, &lt;We! The two of you are reciprocally elder-younger siblings. Why are you quarreling/fighting?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rage ; pa'a'a-ari = basodara, bakelu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rage ; pa'a'a-ari = basodara, bakelu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu game angalai na, dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;Cee ka dhu ded'e èu j'aj'i kètu ji'i! Aa cee ka dhu paj'uj'u èu, ho j'aj'i mi dhèu j'ue lii langu ji'i?<bt>But the person who was beating his companion responded, saying, &lt;Who is it that elevated you to be our(exc) head! And who is it that designated you to be a person who decides our(exc) disputes (=judge)?</bt><v n="28" />Èu ngee, na, èu bisa pamadhe hari ja'a, sama sèmi èu pamadhe dhèu Masir med'a na?&gt;<bt>You think that you can kill me too, just like you killed that Masir person yesterday?&gt;</bt><v n="29" />Ropa Musa tadèngi nare lii ne'e, hèia na rai eele nèti rai Masir, la'e pea ètu rai dhèu Median. Na leo-èmu ètu èèna, ka ra abhu ana mone dhèu dua.<bt>When Musa heard what he said, then he fled from the land of Masir, going to stay in the land of the people of Median. He married there, and they had two sons.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heo ai = nyala api ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">heo ai = nyala api ; paheo ai = kasi manyala api ; kamale = layu ; rai nèti = 1) lari dari, 2) lari bawa</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:23-29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 2:11-15, 18:3-4</note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01919b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Musa dènge ana aaj'u dhu ai na'e, te ngaa kèpu boe<bt>Musa with the tree that is on fire but doesn't burn</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />D'ai èpa nguru tèu, hèia Musa la'e asa d'ara mamoo èci, padètu dènge ledhe èci, ngara na ledhe Sinai. Ètu èèna, ana pajuu Ama Lamatua èci puru mai nèti sorga, ka pad'elo iisi na nèti d'ara ai dhu heo ètu ana aaj'u iiki ca kapua. Ai na'e ana aaj'u èèna, te ngaa kèpu boe.<bt>After 40 years, then Musa went to an empty/remote place, near a mountain named Sinai Mountain. In that place, a servant of God descended from heaven, and revealed himself from inside fire that was burning/shining in a small tree. That tree had fire burning2, but it wasn't burnt3(result).</bt><v n="31" />Ladhe nèdhi sèmi èèna, ka Musa loo-loo sène. Ka na la'e padètu ho neo ne'a, ngaa ka ne. Kabèdhi laa, na tadèngi Ama Lamatua padhai lii nèti d'ara ai, peka na,<bt>Seeing that, Musa stood gawking. And he went and approached so he could know what it was. Suddenly, he heard God2's speak from inside the fire, saying,</bt><v n="32" />&lt;Ja'a ne, Ama Lamatua nèti bèi-baki èu! Lamatua nèti baki Abraham, baki Isak, dènge baki Yakob.&gt; Tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, ka na madha'u toke d'ai isi karèbha. Aa na bani heka doa kètu ho ladhe ana aaj'u dhu ai na'e èèna.<bt>&lt;I here, and the God2/Lord/Master of your ancestors! The God2 of your grandpa/ancestor Abraham, your grandpa Isa, and your grandpa Jako.&gt; Hearing that, he was so frightened that his body shook. And he did not have the courage to lift his head to look at that tree in which the fire was burning.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pad'a = padang ; cakapua ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pad'a = padang ; cakapua = satu pohon (counter) ; na'e = makan; <span class="Bold">31:</span> titu loo-loo = badiri kosong-kosong (=sonde tau mau bekin karmana) ; titu rii-rii =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Èle èèna ka, Lamatua peka hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;We, Musa! Era dhu èu titu ne, era luri. Bhoke eele salapa èu!<bt>After that, God2 spoke again, saying, &lt;We, Musa! The place here where you are standing, is a *sacred place. Open/take off your footwear!</bt><v n="34" />Baku pangee, na, Ja'a bhèlu eele le dhèu Isra'el unu Ja'a ètu Masir sèi. Aad'o! Ja'a sanèd'e si era. Ja'a ke'a j'aj'èra rèngu. Ja'a tadèngi le lii roma iisi rèngu manèngi sasue. De Ja'a neo puru ho patabuli eele si. Mai ku asa ne'e! Ja'a neo pua èu lèpa hari asa Masir nèi.&gt;<bt>Don't you think that I have forgotten My Isra'el people in Masir yonder. No! I still remember them. I know their suffering. I have heard their complaints/pleas asking for love/mercy. So, I am going to descend to deliver/release them. Come over here! I am going to send you back again to Masir yonder.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="luri = karamat, tabu (dgn agama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">luri = karamat, tabu (dgn agama kafir); <span class="Bold">34:</span> roma iisi = keluhan ; sasue = 1) love, 2) pity</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:30-34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 3:1-10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, ka Lamatua dhu pad'elo iisi nèti d'ara ai èèna, Na paredha Musa ho lèpa hari asa Masir. Lamatua paj'uj'u nèngu ho patabuli eele dhèu Isra'el nèti d'ara j'aj'èra rèngu. Musa ne ka dhu uru èèna dhèu karèi, peka na, &lt;Cee ka dhu ded'e èu j'aj'i kètu ji'i?&gt; Te ngaa ne'e ne, Lamatua ka dhu ded'e ne!<bt>In that way, the God2 who revealed himself from inside that fire, He is the one who commanded Musa to go back again to Masir. God2 designated him to deliver/release the people of Isra'el from their suffering. This Musa is the one who formerly the person had asked, saying, &lt;Who is it that elevated you to be our head?&gt; So now, it was God2 who elevated him!</bt><note reference="7:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 2:14</note><v n="36" />Nèti èèna ka, Musa lèpa hari asa rai Masir. Ètu nèi, na tao tadha-tadha malaa ae. Ka na kalua eele dhèu Isra'el nèti Masir. Nèti si kako re Dhasi Mea, ka ra kako palème d'ara mamoo d'ai èpa nguru tèu.<bt>Because of that Musa went back again to the land of Masir. In that (remote) place he did great many kinds of amazing signs. And he brought the Isra'el people out from Masir. He brought them walking by way of the Red Sea, and they walked around the empty/remote place for 40 years.</bt><note reference="7:36" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 7:3, 14:21, Sensus 14:33</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ka Musa peka dènge dhèu Isra'el, aku nèngu na, &lt;Èèna na Lamatua ded'e dhèu èci nèti talora miu, ho Na paj'aj'i ne dhèu nèti lii padhai Nèngu, sama sèmi Na ded'e nare ja'a.&gt;<bt>And so Musa spoke to the people of Isra'el, saying, &lt;You will see that God2 will elevated a person from among you for Him to make him/her and spokesperson of His, just like He has elevated me.&gt;</bt><note reference="7:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 8:15, 18</note><v n="38" />Musa pa'èci dènge dhèu Isra'el èdhi sèra ètu d'ara mamoo. Nèngu èèna ka dhu j'aj'i kalete mi bèi-baki èdhi dènge ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga. Te ana pajuu èèna ka dhu nèti Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua asa Musa. Sèra sa ka dhu pad'elo j'ara mamuri dhu lèke. Lii Holo-Nori sèra ka dhu Lamatua papuru ètu ledhe Sinai.<bt>Musa was united with our(inc) people of Isra'el in that empty place. He is the one who is/became the bridge spanning between our ancestors and God2's messenger from heaven. And that messenger/angel is the one who brought God's Words/Message to Musa. That is the Message that told us thr true/correct Way of Life. Those are the Words that God2 handed down on the Sinai mountain.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu talora = perantara (but perhaps"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhèu talora = perantara (but perhaps fabricated)</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 19:1--20:17, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 5:1-33</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa bèi-baki èdhi sèra ro'o boe nanene Musa. Aa ra tule eele ne, ho ra neo lèpa hari asa rai Masir.<bt>But even that being the case, our ancestors did not want to listen to/obey Musa. And they rejected/pushed away him, wanting to return back to the land of Masir.</bt><v n="40" />Ka ra lasi rarange Harun, aku rèngu na, &lt;Ari mu Musa ka dhu pakalua eele èdhi nèti rai Masir. Te ngaa èdhi te'a heka nèngu ètu ro'a mia. De ji'i manèngi èu tao mèdha sogo-tagu èci hia èdhi, sèna ka mèdha sogo-tagu èèna lere èdhi.&gt;<bt>And they went persuading Harun, saying, &lt;Your younger brother Musa is the one who brought us out from the land of Masir. But we don't know what hole he's disappeared into :). So we(exc) are requesting you to make a thing of traditional-worship for us(inc), so that that object of traditional worship (=*idol) can lead us(inc).&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rarange"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rarange</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:40" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 32:1</note><v n="41" />Ka ra tao ka mèdha sogo-tagu èci, rupa sèmi ana sapi ci'u. Èle èèna ka, ra para badha hia mèdha sogo-tagu èèna. Ka ra ra'a-sisi rame-rame, lula rèngu karej'e nèti mèdha sogo-tagu dhu rèngu tao unu ra.<bt>And so they made an idol, shaped like a cow offspring. After that, they sacrificially-slaughtered animals to that idol. And they feasted (&lt;eat-meat) in celebration, because they were pleased with the idol that they had made themselves.</bt><note reference="7:41" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 32:2-6</note><v n="42" />Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua soro kabodho hia si. Ka ra mulai sogo-tagu ka mèdha dedha-liru, sèmi madha lod'o, hèru, dènge hua-hètu. Te ngaa Lamatua soro tèke si sèmi èèna. Èèna na lèke sèmi lii dhu dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua suri tèke, peka na,<bt>Because of that, God2 turned his back on them. And they began to traditionally-worship things in the sky, like the sun, moon, and stars. But God2 handed/gave them over (=permitted) to do that. That was like what a spokesperson of God had written beforehand from long ago, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sogo &gt; sasogo ; tagu ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sogo &gt; sasogo ; tagu ; sogo-tagu; <span class="Bold">40:</span> range = buju; <span class="Bold">41:</span> para ~ pare = potong, sembelih (horo)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Weh! Miu dhèu Isra'el sèra!<bt>&lt;We! You(pl) people of Isra'el!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">D'ara èpa nguru tèu, miu kako palème d'ara mamoo.<bt>For 40 years you have wandered around the empty place.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Aa miu para badha sèra, neo sogo-tagu mi Ja'a, do,<bt>And you sacrificially-slaughter animals, wanting to traditionally-worship Me, or,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">neo sogo-tagu mi cee?<bt>wanting to traditionally-worship who?</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="43" />Miu koa-kio boe Ja'a!<bt>Me, you are not praising!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Bèli-bèli miu sogo-tagu dhoka mèdha sogo-tagu miu sèra di.<bt>Every day you are only traditionally worshipping your idols.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sogo-tagu = menyembah ; tagu (no"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sogo-tagu = menyembah ; tagu (no meaning) ; tatagu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Miu maso-kalua taruu d'ara èmu mèdha sogo-tagu nidhu, ngara na Molok.<bt>You are going in and out of your houses of traditional-worship of the evil spirit named Molok.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Miu biasa sogo-tagu nidhu hua-hètu èci kahèi, ngara na Refan.<bt>You also are in the habit of traditionally-worshipping the evil spirit of a star, named Refan.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nidhu hua-hètu (@@cosmology)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">nidhu hua-hètu (@@cosmology)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">De miu d'èi dhoka sogo-tagu mèdha pa'ue-ai miu.<bt>So, you only want to traditionally worship hand-crafted idols.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'ue-aai = hasil buatan tangan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pa'ue-aai = hasil buatan tangan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti èèna ka, limuri mai Ja'a bhabhoo miu lami asa cabèka Babel nèi.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>because of that, I will kick you(pl) out to the other side of Babel yonder!&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="7:42-43" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Amos 5:25-27</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Stefanus b'ala lula-nèti Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i [\s2]<bt>Stefanus speaks about the Temple [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Stefanus padhai lii taruu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u rupa nèti era manèngi-mangaj'i èci mi Musa. Hèia Musa si patitu Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i èci,<bt>Stefanus continued speaking, saying, &lt;&lt;God gave instructions to Musa for the form a a place of prayer/worship. So then Musa erected a Prayer/Worship Tent/Shelter (=*Tabernacle), which was made from animal skins and cloth, in the shape that God2 had recently revealed to him. And the people of Isra'el came to pray2 to God in that place. When they moved from one place going to another place, they dismantled that Tabernacle, and they tied it up, and they shoulder-carried it to a new place. In that new place, they erected again that Tent.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ho ladhe = lalu kalo ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Ho ladhe = lalu kalo ; sag'e eele = bongkar ; nèu = dia pung bahan ; jèru = pikul ; j'èru = 1) tongkat, 2) jeruk</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:44" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ama Lamatua d'ule Canguru Atora ètu hadhu kab'ela, hèia saraka mi baki Musa, sèna ka dhèu Isra'el tao madhutu aa'i. Hadhu kab'ela èèna, ra peka, na, &lt;Sakasii&gt;. Ra tèke hadhu kab'ela èèna ètu Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Nèti èèna ka rèngu peka Paleo èèna, &lt;&lt;Paleo Sakasii&gt;&gt;. Ètu ayat ne, suri peka na, Paleo Sakasii kahèi.</note>dhu tao nèti ka'uri badha dènge bèla, sama sèmi rupa dhu Lamatua pad'elo le. Ka dhèu Isra'el sèra mai sabaj'a mi Ama Lamatua ètu era èèna. Ho ladhe rèngu pidha nèti ca'era asa era leo lasi, na, ra sag'e eele Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i èèna, aa ra èki nèu ne, aa ra jèru rèti asa era hiu. Ètu era hiu, ra patitu hari Paleo èèna.<note reference="7:44" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 25:9, 40</note></p>
    <fig path="hk-lb\lb00259c.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:center">Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i dhèu Isra'el<bt>The Tent of Worship of the Isra'el people</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Limuri mai, lod'o Yosua si pamusu dènge dhèu rai leo ètu rai Kana'an, Ama Lamatua babège eele si. Ka Na pabagi rai Kana'an èèna hia bèi-baki èdhi. Lod'o rèngu parame rare rai èèna, rèngu rèti Paleo Manèngi-Mangaj'i Lamatua asa era èèna. Paleo èèna titu taruu ètu èèna, toke d'ai lod'o dhèu aae Daud nèd'u paredha.<bt>Eventually, when Yosua (coll) were at war with people of other lands in the land of Kanaan, God kicked them out. And He divided up that land of Kanaan to our(inc) ancestors. When they snatched up that land, they brought God2's Tabernacle to that place. That Tent continued to stand in that place until the time when King Daud held government.</bt><note reference="7:45" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yosua 3:14-17</note><v n="46" />Dhèu aae Daud manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua, sama sèmi baki Yakob si. Ka Daud pakarej'e d'ara Lamatua, hèia Lamatua hia nèngu berkat. Ka na manèngi ho Lamatua paj'uj'u nèngu sèna ka patitu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i dhu hiu.<bt>King Daud worshipped God, just like Grandpa/ancestor Jako (coll). And Daud pleased God2's insides, and God2 gave him blessing(s). And he prayed/asked that God2 would designate him to erect the new Central House of Worship (=Temple).</bt><note reference="7:46" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Samuel 7:1-16, 1 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 17:1-14</note><v n="47" />Te ngaa ana nèti Daud, ngara na Soleman ka dhu patitu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Lamatua èèna.<bt>But the child of Daud, named Solemaa, is the one who erected that Temple.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Paleo dhu ra pake manèngi-mangaj'i èèna"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Paleo dhu ra pake manèngi-mangaj'i èèna bèi-baki èdhi sèra rèti dènge lod'o dhu rèngu dènge Yosua lasi parame rare rai èdhi ne'e nèti dhèu leo dhu Lamatua babèga eela si nèti katanga madha èdhi. Paleo èèna ra sag'e eele boe toke dai lod'o dhèu aae Daud nèd'u paredha.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hia nèngu berkat ~ hia berkat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hia nèngu berkat ~ hia berkat mi dedha nèngu</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:47" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 6:1-38, 2 Sejara nèti Isra'el dènge Yahuda 3:1-17</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Te ngaa èdhi te'a, na, Ama Lamatua pea boe ètu d'ara èmu dhu dhèu rai-haha tao, lula uru èèna, dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua èci suri tèke le, peka na,<bt>But, we(inc) know that God does not live in houses/buildings which earthly humans make, because long ago, a spokesperson of God2 wrote, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="49" />&lt;Dedha-liru èèna, kadera era Ja'a madhèdi paredha.<bt>&lt;The sky, is the seat where I sit governing.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadera era madhèdi paredha Ja'a ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kadera era madhèdi paredha Ja'a = my throne</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa rai-haha èèna, era hue haga Ja'a.<bt>And this earth, is the place where I prop up My feet/legs.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="j'ajèli = injak ; hue ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">j'ajèli = injak ; hue = muat, alas ; rai-dedha &gt; dedha-liru</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">De tasamia ka miu bisa tao èmu èci dhu be'a hia Ja'a pea ètu d'ara? Bisa boe!<bt>So, how is it that you(pl) can make a house which is good enough for Me to live inside? Can't be done!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="50" />Lula dedha-liru, rai-haha, dènge isi aa'i-aa'i sèra, Ja'a ka dhu paj'aj'i!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Because the sky, the earth, and all their contents, I am the one who made them!&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="7:49-50" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 66:1-2</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Stefanus pasala mi dhèu kapai sèra, lula rèngu tadhe boe Dhèu Mola-Mèci nèti Ama Lamatua [\s2]<bt>Stefanus rebukes those leaders, because they did not recognise the Holy Person from God [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51" />Hèia Stefanus tuhu hari lii padhai na, ka na jèke si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu dhèu kètu hadhu! Miu se, èci èèna ka dènge dhèu dhu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua, dènge dhèu dhu nanene boe Nèngu. Miu dhèu dhu palab'a dènge Ama Lamatua, èci èèna ka dènge bèi-baki miu dhu soro kabodho asa Ne! Ka limuri ne, miu neo hari palab'a dènge Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, do?<bt>Then Stefanus extende his speaking, and scolded them, saying, &lt;&lt;You(pl) are rock-headed people (=stubborn)! You here are just like people who don't even know God, and people who don't listen to/obey Him. You here are people who oppose God, just like your(pl) ancestors who truned their backs on Him! And now do you also want to oppose that Holy Spirit of God2!</bt><note reference="7:51" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 63:10</note><v n="52" />Bèi-baki miu sèra ka dhu paj'èra taruu dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua sèra. Miu peka ku! Dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua mia ka dhu rèngu paj'èra boe? Aad'o, sina ma! Uru èèna dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua peka mema, aku rèngu na, limuri mai Ama Lamatua pua Dhèu Nèngu dhu Mola-Mèci. Te ngaa bèi-baki miu pamadhe dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua sèra. Ka miu tenge j'ara kahèi ho hia dhèu leo pamadhe Dhèu Mola-Mèci nèti Lamatua.<bt>Your ancestors are the ones who kept persecuting God's spokespeople. Tell me this! Which of God2's spokespeople did you not persecute? There aren't any (exceptions), right! Long ago God2's spokespeople foretold, saying, later one God would send His Person who is Holy. But your(pl) ancestors killed those spokespeople of God's. And you also looked for a way to have other/foreign people kill that Holy Person from God2.</bt><v n="53" />Aa ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga sèra dhu rèti mai atora ad'a dhu Lamatua neo hia mi èdhi, te ngaa miu pusi-pahae boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>And God's servants from heaven are the ones who brought the adat regulations which God2 wanted to give to us(inc), but you didn't care (doublet) about them.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tuhu = sambung; |b53:|r pahai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tuhu = sambung; <span class="Bold">53:</span> pahai</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra tabhie pamadhe Stefanus<bt>They stone Stefanus to death</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="54" />Ropa dhèu dhu pama'ète lii langu sèra nanene rare lii padhai lii Stefanus, ka re'a mema, na, nèngu pasala si. Ka ra kadhi ngutu aa tèka d'ara.<bt>When the people who decided disputes heard what Stefanus was saying, they immediately knew that he was accusing them. And they were furious (Idiom: land on their insides), and the ground their teeth (=furious).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tèka dara = ; kadhi ngutu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tèka dara = ; kadhi ngutu = makan gigi (sangat marah)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="55" />Te ngaa Roh Mola-Mèci Lamatua sab'a ètu d'ara Stefanus. Na doa kètu ka ladhe asa dedha-liru. Ètu nèi, na ladhe nèdhi dadedha Ama Lamatua, dènge nèdhi kahèi Lamatua Yesus titu ètu sebhe g'ana Na ètu era dhu kab'ua risi.<bt>But, Stefanus, whom the Holy Spirit of God2 was working in his insides, raised his head and he looked up into the sky. Up yonder he saw the beauty/glory of God [the 1st group UNS's got it!], and also saw the Lord Yesus standing at His right side in the best place yonder.</bt><v n="56" />Hèia Stefanus padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e ku, ama aa'i-aa'i. Ja'a kèdhi liru bhoke eele, aa Dhèu Rai-Haha Tare'a-re'a titu ètu era hua iia, re sebhe g'ana Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Stefanus spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, all you fathers. I see the sky opened, and the *Child of Humans standing in the most beautiful place at the right side of God.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hua iia = UNS's got it!;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hua iia = UNS's got it!; <span class="Bold">56:</span> liru bhoke = clearing after the rain</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="57" />Ropa ra tadèngi sèmi èèna, hèia dhèu pama'ète lii langu sèra hutu ro'a dhilu ra. Ka ra jèke ne, sèna ka kai Stefanus baku bhoke hèb'a. Ka ra mangamok neo game ne.<bt>When they heard that, then those people who examined disputes covered their earholes. And they scolded-spittin-mad him, so that Stefanus should open his mouth. And they rushed forward (with violence) to beat him.</bt><v n="58" />Èle èèna ka, ra nuni-pa'oro ne rèti asa li'u kota. D'ai nèi, ka sakasii sèra bhoke eele kodho li'u ra, ho ra hia mi ana mone ngèru èci nèd'u. Ngara na Saulus, dhu j'aj'i dhèu dadugu-rariu dhèu. Èle èèna ka, ra tabhie Stefanus dènge hadhu.<bt>Then they dragged him along the ground, taking him outside the city. Arriving yonder, the witnesses took off their outer shirts/clothes and gave them to a young man to hold. His name was Saulus, who was their ring-leader (provocateur). Then they stoned Stefanus with stones.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasoka = melompat; |b58:|r pa'oro ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pasoka = melompat; <span class="Bold">58:</span> pa'oro = seret, drag on ground ; tabhie = lempar ulang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02154b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;verticalPosition:top;horizontalPosition:center">Ra tabhie Stefanus<bt>They stone Stefanus</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="59" />Ropa ra tabhie, hèia Stefanus pa'oo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua Yesus! Lod'o ja'a d'ai kèna. Sèmi more ku samanga ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>As they were stoning him, Stefanus called out, saying, &lt;&lt;Lord Yesus! My time has come. Receive/accept my *spirit/soul!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="60" />Èle èèna ka, na bèbhe-lèpe urutuu, ka na pa'oo hari dènge lii mèdhu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Baku hia si d'ui sasala ne'e!&gt;&gt; Hèia na ma'ète a'ae dènge ka.<bt>Then he fell down on his knees, and he called out with a loud voice, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Don't give them to shoudler-carry this wrong!&gt;&gt; Then his breathing stopped right then.</bt><c n="8" /><v n="1a" />Aa Saulus ètu èèna kahèi, ka nèngu d'èi ra pamadhe Stefanus kahèi.<bt>And Saulus was also there in that place, and he also wanted them to kill Stefanus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'oo = batarea panggil orang, summon"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pa'oo = batarea panggil orang, summon</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Saulus paj'èra dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus<bt>Saul causes suffering/persecutes the people who belong/affiliated with the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="1b-2" />Lod'o Stefanus madhe, abhu pèri-pèri dhèu dhu mamuri d'ara d'èi dènge Lamatua. Lasi rare ngi'u aae Stefanus ho ra padhane. Ka ra tangi ne.<bt>When Stefanus had died then, there were several people who yearned for God2. They went and took Stefanus' corpse to bury it. And they wept for him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ngi'u aae = jenazah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ngi'u aae = jenazah</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Nèti lod'o èèna, ka dhèu paj'èra dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus ètu kota Yerusalem, toke d'ai rèngu j'èra bia. Èle èèna ka, rèngu rai pahag'a lasi asa propensi Yudea dènge propensi Samaria. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i rai, te ngaa tèke eele dhoka dhèu pajuu-paleha Yesus di ètu Yerusalem.<bt>From that day/time, people persecuted/cause suffering to the people who belonged to /were affiliated with the Lord Yesus in the city of Yeruslaem, to the point that they suffered terribly. Because of that, they ran off scattering going to the province of Yudea and the province of Samaria. They all ran, but left behind only the servants/emissaries of Yesus in Yerusalem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahag'a = bapisa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pahag'a = bapisa</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Te ngaa Saulus tenge j'ara taruu ho pa'èle dhèu unu Yesus sèra. Na tenge si ètu mia-mia. Na maso-kalua èmu dhèu ho na tenge si. Sad'i abhu dhèu mone, do dhèu bhèni, na kèpe si, ho na cèlu si asa d'ara bèdho.<bt>But Saulus continued to look for a way to wipe out Yesus' people. He hunted them everywhere. He entered-exited people's houses to look for them. It didn't matter if they were men or women, he just arrested them anyway, so he could toss them (forcibly) in jail.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cèlu = masuk dgn paksa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">cèlu = masuk dgn paksa</Message></Annotation><note reference="8:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 22:4-5, 26:9-11</note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02155b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none">Ra kèpe dhèu bhèni-dhèu mone ho pamaso bèdho<bt>They arrest males-females to put in jail</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p" />
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Pelipus lole Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus ètu propensi Samaria<bt>Pelipus tells the Good News of the Lord Yesus in the province of Samaria</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Masi ka ra paj'èra dhèu unu Yesus sèra ho ra rai asa haa asa dhimu, te ngaa rèngu loe boe peka-padhai Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus asa mia-mia.<bt>Even though they persecuted the people who belonged to Yesus, so that they fled to the west and the east, nevertheless they didn't stop telling (doublet) the teachings of the Lord Yesus everywhere.</bt><v n="5" />Conto sèmi, ca tèka, Pelipus la'e asa d'ara kota èci ètu propensi Samaria, ho peka dènge dhèu ètu sèra, na, Yesus, nuka Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u nèti uru ka mai.<bt>Like at that time, Pelipus went to a city in the province of Samaria, to tell the people there the story about Yesus, the Person who God designated from long ago.</bt><v n="6" />Ropa dhèu ae ladhe rèdhi tadha-tadha malaa dhu na tao, ka ra pakaboko ho nanene paie ngaa dhu Pelipus peka-padhai.<bt>When many people saw the various sorts of amazing signs which he was doing, they gathered to listen to what Pelipus was saying.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Conto sèmi, ètu èèna, abhu kahèi dhèu-dhèu dhu nidhu tao. Nidhu sèra rai eele dhèu se'e dènge pakii-pakèce. Dhèu karuku dènge dhèu haga roe cabèka, èle dènge nèti papèd'a.<bt>In that place, there were also people whom evil spirits had done (=bothered/possessed). Those evil spirits fled from these people with screams (of protest). Paralysed people and people with limps were healed from their sickness/pain.</bt><v n="8" />Nèti èèna ka, dhèu-dhèu ètu d'ara kota èèna karej'e titu kèna.<bt>Because of that, people in that city were very happy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'oo-parodha = batarea pange (bukan mara)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pa'oo-parodha = batarea pange (bukan mara) ; pakii = hewan, scream, squeel pakii aae = squeel loudly (in protest)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ètu kota èèna, abhu dhèu èci dhu pake na'i, ngara na Simon. Nèbhu le na pake na'i ètu talora dhèu Samaria sèra. Ka na padedha iisi na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a dhèu èra!&gt;&gt;<bt>In that city there was a person who used sorcery/medicine, named Simon. For a long time he had used his magic/science among those people of Samaria. And he bragged about himself (lit. kept elevating himself, saying, &lt;&lt;I am a strong/powerful/incredible person!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu pake na'i = suanggi, orang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhèu pake na'i = suanggi, orang pintar, orang pakai ilmu hitam, healer (using real med), pake obat nona ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10-11" />Ka nèti kota èèna, ana iiki do dhèu kapai, dhèu mone do bhèni, palolo dhoka dhèu ne'e di, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ele-madha, nga! Ngaa-ngaa dhu na tao ne, mai nèti koasa Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt; Lula nèngu pake na'i, nèti uru ka mai dhèu ae lèka ne.<bt>So, from that city, whether small kids or adults, male or female, they all spoke about this person saying, &lt;&lt;This person it really great (idiom: disappearing eyes)! Whatever he does, comes from the power of God!&gt;&gt;Because of him using his magic, from previously until recently/now many people trusted/believed in him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ele-madha = talalu hebat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ele-madha = talalu hebat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Te ngaa limuri ne, rèngu nanene Pelipus aj'a rèngu j'ara paredha Ama Lamatua. Aa na peka j'ara ho rèngu rèti kolongara Yesus, sèna ka rèngu bisa j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua. Ropa ra tadèngi rare sèmi èèna, dhèu ae parcaya, ka j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua. Bhèni-mone aa'i-aa'i sèra j'aj'i sèmi èèna. Nèti èèna ka, ra abhu sarani.<bt>But now they were listening to Pelipus teaching the way of God's Kingdom/Commands. And he told the way for them to use the name/reputation of Yesus so that they could become people who belong to God. When they heard that, many people wanted to become people who belonged to God2. All those female-males wanted to become like that, That is why they got baptised.</bt><v n="13" />Te ngaa Simon parcaya kahèi, ka manèngi j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus. Ka ra sarani ne. Hèia na madhutu Pelipus asa mia-mia. Ropa nèdhi tadha-tadha malaa dhu Pelipus tao, hèia na pangètu kètu na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Sèmi ne'e ne, risi eele!&gt;&gt;<bt>But [=contrary to expectation], Simon also requested to become a person belonging to the Lord Yesus. And they baptised him [non-referential they]. Then he followed Pelipus everywhere. When he saw the amazing signs which Pelipus was doing, he nodded his head (implies agreement), saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! This stuff is incredible!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakareko kètu = implies tidak setuju"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pakareko kètu = implies tidak setuju ; pangètu kètu = nods head (forward and backward, implies agreement or appreciation)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus dhu ètu Yerusalem sèra, tadèngi, na, dhèu ae parcaya le Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua ètu propensi Samaria. Ka ra manèngi Petrus dènge Yohanis lasi asa nèi.<bt>At that time, the servant/emissarries of the Lord Yesus who were in Yerusalem heard that many people had believed in the Good News of the Lord/God2 in the province of Samaria. And they asked Petrus and Yohanis to go yonder.</bt><v n="15-17" />Ropa dua ra d'ai nèi, rèngu heka re'a kèna, dhèu ètu nèi abhu mèka Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci. Rèngu dhoka abhu sarani pake kolongara Yesus di. Hèia Petrus dènge Yohanis bane ai mi dhèu sèra, ka ra manèngi-mangaj'i sèna ka dhèu Samaria sèra sèmi rare Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci kahèi. Ka dhèu se'e abhu dènge Roh kahèi.<bt>When the two of them arrived yonder, only then did they know that those people there had not yet gotten the Holy Spirit of God2, because they had only gotten baptised using the name of Yesus. So then Petrus and Yohanis placed their hands on them, and they prayed asking that those people of Samaria also receive the Holy Spirit of God2. And these people also got the Spirit.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Lod'o èèna, Simon ladhe nèdhi rèngu dua ra bane ai mi dhèu se'e, ka dhèu sèra sèmi rare Roh Lamatua. Hèia na j'ole doi asa Petrus dènge Yohanis, dènge lii manèngi, peka na,<bt>At that time, Simon saw the two of them place their hands on these people, and they got the Spirit of God2. And he handed money over toward Petrus and Yohanis, with a request, saying,</bt><v n="19" />&lt;&lt;Ama-ama! Miu hia ku ja'a koasa èèna. Sèna ka ladhe ja'a bane ai mi dhèu, na, ra abhu Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;Fathers! You(pl) give me that power. So that I will be able to place hands on people, and they will also get God2's Holy Spirit.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa Petrus jèke ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a dhoo èu dènge doi èu! Èu ngee, na, èu bisa hèli koasa Roh Mola-Mèci dènge doi dhari, do? Aad'o! Dhèu bisa boe hèli Roh Lamatua!<bt>But Peturs scolded him, saying, &lt;&lt;I curse you and your money! You think that you can buy the power of the Holy Spirit with money, huh? No way! People cannot buy the Spirit of God2!</bt><v n="21" />Èu dènge boe hak mi Roh Lamatua, lula d'ara èu mola boe. Èu dhoka tenge-tenge j'ara di.<bt>You do not have the right to God2's Spirit, because your insides are not straight. You are only looking for an opportunity/scheming.</bt><v n="22" />Èu hud'i ae eele ku nèti sasala-sasigo èu sèra. Hua iia èu sabaj'a ho teko-teko Lamatua saku eele ngangee aapa èu.<bt>You must stop from those wrongs of your. It would be best for you to pray that God would wipe away your evil scheming.</bt><v n="23" />Ja'a ke'a, na, d'ara èu aapa, aa j'ara karehe ae dhu èki èu!&gt;&gt;<bt>I know that your insides are evil, and all the evil2 things that bind you!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhoo = 1) kutuk, 2) sumpah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhoo = 1) kutuk, 2) sumpah ; subha; <span class="Bold">23:</span> aapa = buruk</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ka Simon manèngi dua si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama! Ladhe sèmi èèna, miu dua mi sabaj'a ku hia ja'a, sèna ka lii dhoo dhu miu peka èèna, baku lèke ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Simon asked the two of them, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers! If that is the case, the two of you pray for me, so that the curse which you just uttered will not happen to me.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Èle èèna, hèia Petrus dènge Yohanis lole aa'i Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus, aa ra lole Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua ètu d'ara kota èèna. Hèia rèngu lèpa hari asa Yerusalem. Ra kako re rae-rae ètu propensi Samaria, ho lole Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus mi dhèu ètu rae sèra.<bt>After that, Petrus and Yohanis spoke in detail about the Good News of the Lord Yesus, and they told the Teachings/Words of God there in that city. Then they returned back to Yerusalem. They walked by way of the villages in the province of Samaria, to tell the Good News of the Lord Yesus to people in those villages.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Pelipus paraga dènge pegawi kapai nèti Afrika<bt>Pelipus meets with an important person from Afrika</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Èle èèna ka, ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga pua Pelipus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamu ku madhutu j'ara asa balèu. Madhutu j'ara dhui, dhu nèti kota Yerusalem la'e asa rai Gasa.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, a messenger of the Lord from heaven ordered Pelipus, saying, &lt;&lt;Go follow the road to the south. Follow the old road, which is from the city of Yerusalem going to the land/country of Gasa.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="27-28" />Ropa tadèngi nare lii paredha èèna, ka na pakèd'i dènge ka. Lod'o nèngu kako ètu j'ara èèna, ladhe nèdhi dhèu èci. Dhèu èèna, pegawi kapai nèti rai Etiopia.<bt>When he heard that command, he left immediately. When he was walking on that road, he saw a person. This person was an important person/official from the land/country of Etiopia.</bt><note reference="8:27-28" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani peka, na, pegawi kapai ne'e ne, dhèu dhu ra j'ue eele kanadhu na (kabiri). Etiopia èèna, rai èci ètu Afrika dhimu.<bt>The Yunani language says that this official was a person whom they had cut off his testicles ("castrated" [loan]). That Etiopia is a country in eastern Afrika.</bt></note>Nèngu ne ka dhu ladhe-leru mèdha-panyau dhèu aae bhèni, ngara na Kandake. Pegawi èèna heka sabaj'a nare ètu Yerusalem, ka na lèpa èmu ca'e kareta. Ropa Pelipus nèdhi ne, nèngu madhèdi baca ètu dedha kareta. Na baca sasuri dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, ngara na Yesaya.<bt>He is the one who looked after/managed the wealth/possessions of the queeen, named Kandake. That official had just finished praying2/worshipping in Yerusalem, and was returning home on a cart (loan). When Pelipus saw him, he was sitting reading on top of the cart. He was reading from the Word of the Lord which Grandpa Yesaya had written.</bt><v n="29" />Èle èèna ka, Roh Lamatua pua Pelipus la'e padètu asa kareta èèna, sèna ka na paraga dènge dhèu èèna.<bt>After that, the Spirit of God2 ordered Pelipus to go near that cart, so that he could meet with that official.</bt><v n="30" />Ropa na dètu, ka na tadèngi, na, dhèu èèna baca sasuri Yesaya. Ka Pelipus karèi ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ama ku me'a, do aad'o, ngaa dhu ama baca èèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>When he neared, he heard that person reading the writings of Grandpa Yesaya. And Pelipus asked him, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Does father know/understand, or not, what it is you are reading there?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu aae bhèni = queen ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhèu aae bhèni = queen ; bhèni aae = king's wife</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2012-01-28 03:52:14Z">hua dhèlu = testicles</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ka dhèu ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o, ja'a ke'a boe. Hud'i abhu ku dhèu dhu peka-padhai dènge ja'a, heka ja'a ke'a kèna. Ca'e mai ho madhèdi dènge ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>And that person responded, saying, &lt;&lt;No, I don't understand it. There must be a person who explains it to me, only then will I really understand it. Climb up here to sit with me.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="32" />Sasuri dhu na baca èèna, sèmi ne'e ka,<bt>The words he was reading there were like this,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ra nuni rèti Ne, sama sèmi nuni kahib'i-kalèbho,<bt>They pulled taking Him, just like leading a sheep [yes, they have them and know them! :)]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho neo roro Ne.<bt>to slaughter Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu j'aj'i sama sèmi ana kahib'i-kalèbho dhu dhèu g'ute rèu Ne,<bt>He is like a sheep offspring which people scissor His fur,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="g'ute = gunting ; kalebho ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">g'ute = gunting ; kalebho = domba</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa nèngu mau-mau sène, na kabee boe.<bt>but he nevertheless remains quiet, not bleating at all.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii ugu-ge'e = bersungu,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lii ugu-ge'e = bersungu,</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Hèb'a Na kutu mèno,<bt>His mouth remains locked shut,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kutu mèno = tutup keras/kuat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kutu mèno = tutup keras/kuat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">aa na kalua boe lii ca lamusi sa.<bt>and not a single little word comes out.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii calamusi = suara satu biji"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lii calamusi = suara satu biji juga</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="33" />Ka ra lalangu Ne,<bt>And they slander Him,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lalangu = hina"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lalangu = hina</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ra j'ue lii langu Na lèke boe.<bt>They do not settle His dispute correctly/fairly.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Lod'o èèna, ra pamadhe Ne,<bt>At that time, they kill Him,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">masi ka Nèngu dènge boe sasala-sasigo.<bt>even though He did no wrong/sin (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">De èdhi peka ngaa hari lula-nèti ana-èpu Na?&gt;&gt;<bt>So what else can we say?&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="8:32-33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 53:7-8</note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01932b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none">Pelipus aj'a Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua mi pegawi kapai nèti Afrika<bt>Pelipus teaches the Lord's Word to an official from Afrika</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ropa na baca nare, hèia na karèi Pelipus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia, ee? Sasuri Yesaya ne, lèke mi nèngu, do, lèke mi dhèu leo?&gt;&gt;<bt>When he had finished reading, then he asked Pelipus, saying, &lt;&lt;How is it, ee? This word of Grandpa Yesaya, does it happen to him or, happen to another person?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ka Pelipus aj'a ne Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus. Na lolo nèti lii sasuri Yesaya, ho pad'elo j'ara madhutu Yesus.<bt>So Pelipus taught him the Good News of the Lord Yesus. He explained from those aforementioned writing of Yesaya, so that he could reveal the way to follow Yesus.</bt><v n="36" />Lod'o rèngu ètu d'ara kakako era, rèngu rage loko èci dènge èi. Ka dhèu èèna peka dènge Pelipus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama. Ladhe ku èi ka nèi. Ladhe èu ngee, na, cadhui boe, mai puru lati, ho èu sarani ku ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>While they were still going, they enocuntered a small streambed with water. And the official spoke to Pelipus, saying, &lt;&lt;Father. Look over there, there is water yonder. If you can think of no objection, let's go down there so you can baptise me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rage"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rage</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />[Hèia Pelipus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ama tare'a-re'a parcaya Lamatua Yesus, na, cadhui boe. Mai dua ti puru ho ja'a sarani èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>[Then Pelipus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;If you truly believe [in] the Lord Yesus, then, there is no problem. Let's the two of us(inc) get down so I can baptise you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cadhui boe = gampang, sonde susah,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">cadhui boe = gampang, sonde susah, sonde sulit, bisa diatur ; cèla</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a parcaya tare'a-re'a, na, Yesus èèna Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u nèti uru ka mai. Nèngu èèna, Ana Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;]<bt>And he responded, saying, &lt;&lt;I truly believe that Yesus is the person whom God designated from long ago. He is the Child of God.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="8:37" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ayat 37 ne, abhu boe ètu d'ara sasuri Yunani dhu uru risi sèra.<bt>This verse (loan) 37, is not found in the oldest Yunani writings.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Hèia pegawi èèna, paredha ho patitu kareta. Ka dua ra puru asa d'ara èi èèna, ka Pelipus sarani ne.<bt>Then that official commanded to stand (=stop) the cart. And the two of them got down into the water, and Pelipus baptised him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ropa ra kalua mai nèti d'ara èi, kabèdhi laa Roh Lamatua ded'e nèti Pelipus asa era leo. Ka dhèu èèna nèdhi heka Pelipus. Hèia pegawi kapai èèna lèpa dènge d'ara karej'e-karae.<bt>When they came up out of the water, suddenly the Spirit of God2 lifted Pelipus to another place. And that official no longer saw Pelipus. Then this official went on with rejoicing insides.</bt><v n="40" />Ka Pelipus cèu ètu rae èci, ngara na Asotus.<bt>And, Pelipus appeared at a village, named Asotus.</bt><note reference="8:40" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ngara rae èèna, ètu d'ara lii Yunani, na, Asotus. Te ngaa uru-uru sèra, lod'o dhèu Pilistin rèd'u paredha ètu Isra'el, rae èèna, ngara na Asdod.<bt>The name of that village in the Yunani language is Asotus. But previously it was named, Asdod.</bt></note>Nèti rae èèna, ka na la'e padhue-padhai taruu Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus. Na dhuli rae-rae ètu rai èèna, toke d'ai kota Kaisarea.<bt>In that village he kept going around explaining the Good News of the Lord Yesus. He stopped in at village after village in that land/country, until arriving at the city of Kaisarea.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cèu = muncul"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">cèu = muncul</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Saulus j'aj'i dhèu madhutu Yesus<bt>Saulus becomes a follower of Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 22:6-16, 26:12-18)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="9" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, Saulus paj'èra taruu dhèu-dhèu dhu madhutu Yesus. Na tenge j'ara ho neo pamadhe si. Nèti èèna ka, la'e asa kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi,<bt>At that time, Saulus continued to persecute the people who followed Yesus. He looked for a way to kille them. Because of that, he went to the Big Boss (=High Priest) of the Jahudi religion,</bt><v n="2" />ka manèngi pèri-pèri sasuri koasa, ho nèti la'e asa ama-ama èmu manèngi-mangaj'i agama Yahudi ètu kota Damsik nèi. Na manèngi, ladhe nèngu rage dhèu dhu madhutu J'ara Mamuri Yesus ètu nèi, bhèni-mone, nèngu kèpe ho èki si, sèna ka ère nèti hari si asa Yerusalem.<bt>and asked for several letters giving authority (POA letters-loan), so that he could go to the leaders of the Jahudi houses of worship in the city of Damsik yonder. He requested that if he encountered people who follow Yesus' Way of Life there, female-male, he could arrest and bind them, so that he could drag/bring them back to Yerusalem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ère = tarik ; kèpe ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ère = tarik ; kèpe = subyek tunggal ; kèpa = subyek jamak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ropa sèmi nare sasuri koasa sèra, ka nèngu dènge angalai na lasi asa kota Damsik. Ropa oe dètu dènge kota èèna, cag'ag'a laa, saraa puru nèti dedha-liru sarimu nare Saulus.<bt>When he had received those letters of authority, he and his companions went to the city of Damsik. When they were nearing that city, suddenly, brightness descended from the sky blanketing Saulus.</bt><v n="4" />Ka na bèbhe rai la'e. Hèia na tadèngi lii èci padhai lii dènge ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Saulus! Saulus! Nga tao ka èu paj'èra Ja'a sèmi ne'e?&gt;&gt;<bt>And he fell down on the ground. Then he heard a voice speaking to him, saying, &lt;&lt;Saulus! Saulus! Why do you persecute Me like this?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sarimu = tutup, (selimut)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sarimu = tutup, (selimut)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia Saulus karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhu padhai lii ne, cee ka èu?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Saulus asked, saying, &lt;&lt;Lord/Master/Boss who is speakeing here, who are you?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lii èèna, peka hari, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, Yesus, dhu èu paj'èra aae ne.<bt>That earlier voice spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;I here, am Yesus, whom you keep persecuting.</bt><v n="6" />Kèd'i, ho lamu asa d'ara kota. D'ai nèi, pe Ja'a peka dènge èu, ngaa dhu èu hud'i tao.&gt;&gt;<bt>Stand up to go into the city. Arriving yonder, I will tell you what you are to do.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02022b.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Saulus bèbhe asa rai la'e<bt>Saulus falls on the ground</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Aa angalai nèngu sèra tadèngi kahèi lii èèna, te ngaa rèdhi boe cee-cee. Dhèu se'e malaa, ka re'a heka padhai lii ngaa-ngaa.<bt>And his companions also heard that voice, but didn't see anybody. These people were amazed/confused, and didn't/couldn't say anything.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia Saulus kèd'i titu. Ka na neo bhoke musi madha na, te ngaa nèdhi heka ngaa-ngaa. Ka ra sarad'e rèti ne asa d'ara kota Damsik.<bt>Then Saulus stood up. And he tried to open his eyeballs, but he couldn't see anything. And they guided him into the city of Damsik.</bt><v n="9" />Ètu d'ara tèlu lod'o, na bisa boe nèdhi ngaa-ngaa. Aa na'a-ninu boe ngaa-ngaa kahèi.<bt>For three days he couldn't see anything. And he didn't eat-drink (=consume) anything.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sarad'e = pegang (topang)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sarad'e = pegang (topang)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ètu d'ara kota èèna, abhu dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus èci, ngara na Ananias. Lamatua mai pad'elo iisi dènge ne, sama sèmi tanila sa. Na paroa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ananias!&gt;&gt;<bt>In that city, there was a person belonging to the Lord Yesus, named Ananias. The Lord came and revealed himself to him, as in a vision/trance. And called.attention, saying, &lt;&lt;Ananias!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Ananias dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Oo, Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Ananias responsed, saying, &lt;&lt;Ia, Lord/Master!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tanila = bayangan, halusinasi, penglihatan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tanila = bayangan, halusinasi, penglihatan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Lamatua peka, na, &lt;&lt;Nanene ku! Èu lamu tenge ku dhèu unu Ja'a èci. Kako lamu asa j'ara èci, dhu ngara na J'ara Mola. Lamu asa èmu dhèu èci, ngara na Yudas. Ètu èèna, karèi rèngu dhèu èci nèti kota Tarsus, ngara na Saulus. Dhèu èèna sabaj'a era.<bt>The Lord said, &lt;&lt;Listen up! You must go look for a person who belongs to Me. Go to a street, which is called Straight Street. Go to the house of a person named Yudas. There, ask them for a person named Saulus, from the city of Tarsus. That person is busy praying.</bt><v n="12" />Ja'a hia ne tanila kahèi, na, èèna na dhèu mone èci neo mai paraga dènge ne, nuka èu, Ananias. De lamu ho bane ai èu mi nèngu, sèna ka na bisa nèdhi hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>I will also cause him to see a man wanting to come meet with him, that is you, Ananias. So go to lay your hands on him, so that he can see again.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaba kètu = tempurung kepala"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kaba kètu = tempurung kepala</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa Ananias b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, Lamatua! Ji'i tadèngi le lii palolo lula-nèti dhèu èèna. Nèngu èèna ka dhu paj'èra dhèu-dhèu unu Lamatua ètu Yerusalem. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu bani heka bhodho baboro!<bt>But Ananias responded2, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, Lord! We(exc) have heard reports about this person. He is the one who has persecuted the people belonging to God2/Lord in Yerusalem. Because of that, nobody dares appear outside any more!</bt><v n="14" />Limuri ne, ji'i tadèngi hari, peka na, kètu agama Yahudi sèra hia ne koasa ho mai kèpa dhèu-dhèu dhu madhutu J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus.&gt;&gt;<bt>Now/recently we have also heard that the religious leaders have given him authority to come here and arrest people who follow the Life Way of the Lord Yesus.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lula = tentang ; baboro ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lula = tentang ; baboro = keluar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa Lamatua padhai lii hari dènge Ananias, peka na, &lt;&lt;Masi ka sèmi èèna, èu hud'i lamu ku! Te Ja'a hag'e kore nèngu le, ho na bhoke j'ara, sèna ka na lole Lii Lolo Be'a Ja'a hia dhèu kabarai leo sèra, hia dhèu aae-dhèu aae, dènge dhèu Isra'el kahèi.<bt>But the Lord spoke again to Ananias, saying, &lt;&lt;Even that being the case, you must go! Cause I have selected him out to open the way, so that he can tell My Good News to those people of other societies, to kings, and also to the people of Isra'el.</bt><v n="16" />Aa èèna na, Ja'a pad'elo dènge ne, sèna ka nèngu ne'a mema j'aj'èra tasa mera mia ka dhu bèli-camèd'a nèngu pasae, lula nèngu madhutu Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>And furthermore, I will reveal to him so that he will know beforehand the various sorts of suffering which he will shoulder.carry in the future, because he follows Me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tasamera-mia = macam apa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tasamera-mia = macam apa</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Tadèngi nare lii padhai lii Lamatua, hèia Ananias la'e ka maso asa èmu èèna. Ka na bane ai na mi Saulus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Angalai Saulus! Lamatua Yesus dhu pad'elo iisi mi èu ètu talora j'ara lod'o èu mai asa ne'e, Nèngu èèna ka dhu pua ja'a mai paraga dènge èu ètu ne'e. Na pua ja'a kahèi ho sabaj'a dènge tao kacui-aai mi dedha èu, sèna ka èu bisa mèdhi hari. Aa Na d'èi ho èu sèmi more Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci.&gt;&gt;<bt>Having heard what the Lord said, Ananias left and went into that house. And he placed his hands on Saulus, saying, &lt;&lt;Friend Saulus! The Lord Yesus who revealed himself to you on the road when you were coming here, He is the one who ordered me to come meet with you here. He also ordered me to pray and place hands on you, so that you can see again. And He wants for you to get His Spirit who is Holy.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Cag'ag'a laa, Saulus rasa ngaa èci bèbhe eele nèti musi madha nèngu, sèmi nai i'a. Hèia na ladhe nèdhi hari. Ka na kèd'i, aa ra sarani dènge ne.<bt>Immediately, Saulus felt something fall from his eyes, like fish scales. Then he looked and saw again. And he stood, and2 they baptised him.</bt><v n="19a" />Èle èèna ka, na na'a-ninu. Ka na abhu hari a'èra.<bt>After that, he ate-drank. And he got his strength back.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Saulus lole Lii Lolo Be'a ètu kota Damsik<bt>Saulus tells the Good News in the city of Damsik</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19b" />Ka Saulus pea hari dènge dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus pèri-pèri lod'o ètu kota Damsik.<bt>And Saulus stayed on with of the Lord Yesus' people for several more days in the city of Damsik.</bt><v n="20" />Aa la'e asa d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi, ka na peka dènge si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mi nanene paie! Mema Yesus tare'a-re'a Ana Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>And he went into the Jahudi people's house of worship, and he spoke to them, saying, &lt;&lt;Listen well! Yesus really is the Child of God.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02153b.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none">Saulus padhai lii ètu d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi<bt>Saulus speaks in the Jahudi people's worship house</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra malaa dènge bingu, ropa ra tadèngi Saulus padhai lii sèmi èèna. Hèia ra papeka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ka dhu paj'èra dhèu unu Yesus ètu Yerusalem, sina ma? Aa mamai ne, sèna ka na kèpe dhèu se'e ho nèti asa kètu agama Yahudi sèra! Na, tasamia ka ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>And all the people were amazed and confused, when they heard Saulus speak like that. Then they spoke to each other, saying, &lt;&lt;This guy here, is the one who was destroying the people who belong to Yesus in Yerusalem, right? And he came here so that he could arrest these people to take them to the Jahudi religious leaders! Na, what's going on with him?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa Saulus padhai lii taruu, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yesus èèna, nuka Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua moa nèti uru, ho pua Na mai.&gt;&gt; Saulus padhai lii dènge d'èlu-mèu aa d'ara adhu, toke dhèu Yahudi sèra segi boe nèngu. Nèti èèna ka, a'èra Saulus asa tabha kapai.<bt>But Saulus continued speaking, saying, &lt;&lt;That Yesus, he is the Person who God promised from long agog that He was going to send Him here.&gt;&gt; Saulus spoke with hard insides (idiom: confidence), and the Jahudi people there couldn't win/beat him. Because of that, Saulus' strength/influence increased greatly.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dènge dara adhu = yakin, percaya"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dènge dara adhu = yakin, percaya diri tinggi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Nèbhu boe ka, dhèu Yahudi sèra sanunu ho neo pamadhe ne.<bt>But not long after that, these Jahudi people hated and wanted to kill him.</bt><v n="24" />Te ngaa Saulus ae nare ngangee aapa rèngu èèna, dhu peka na, ra mate ne mèu-mèda ètu hèb'a-hèb'a tebho kota, ho ra neo pamadhe ne.<bt>But Saulus got wind of (lit. smelled) their evil plot, that they were waiting for him day-night, at the doors/gates of the city wall, so they could kill him.</bt><v n="25" />Ka ca tèka hari, d'ara mèda, angalai Saulus pèri-pèri dhèu mai rare ne, ka ra papuru ne ètu d'ara kadhari cue, re karasa li'u tebho kota. Dènge j'ara èèna ka, nèngu rai nèti kota Damsik.<bt>And one time, during the night, several of Saulus' friends came and took him, and they lowered him in a basket, via beside the outside of the city (rock/concrete) wall. In that way, he fled from the city of Damsik.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sanunu = benci, lalu rencana jahat;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sanunu = benci, lalu rencana jahat; <span class="Bold">24:</span> sangèdu = uu = cium ; ae nare = cium; <span class="Bold">25:</span> dulu = sorong ; tebho = tembok ; tedhe ; kadhari</Message></Annotation><note reference="9:23-25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Korintus 11:32-33</note></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00333c.tif" rtfFormat="width:8.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Ra papuru Paulus pake kadhari<bt>They lower Paulus using a basket</bt></fig>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Saulus la'e asa Yerusalem<bt>Saulus goes to Yerusalem</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Èle èèna ka, Saulus la'e asa Yerusalem. D'ai nèi, ka na neo pa'èci dènge dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus. Te ngaa dhèu sèra madha'u dènge nèngu, lula ra pangee, na, nèngu dhoka sangaja di, j'aj'i dhèu parcaya dhu madhutu Lamatua Yesus. Èle èèna na, nèngu kabèli hari ho neo kèpe rèngu.<bt>After that, Saulus went to Yerusalem. Arriving there (remote), he wanted to join with the people who belonged to the Lord Yesus there. But, those people were afraid of him, because they thought that he was only deliberately deceiving them, becoming a person who followed the Lord Yesus. After that, he would turn back so he could arrest them.</bt><v n="27" />Te ngaa dhèu èci, ngara na Barnabas, nèngu ka dhu nèti Saulus ho patadhe mi dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua ètu èèna. Na lole ngaa dhu j'aj'i mi dedha Saulus ètu talora j'ara. Na peka, na, Saulus paraga le dènge Lamatua Yesus kahèi. Aa Yesus padhai lii dènge nèngu kahèi. Na lolo kahèi babani Saulus padhai lii J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus mi dhèu Damsik sèra.<bt>But one person, named Barnabas, he is the one who took Saulus to introduce to the servants/emissaries of the Lord in that place. He told what had happened to Saulus on the road/trip. He said that Saulus had also met with the Lord Yesus. And Yesus had also spoken to him. He also told them of Saulus' boldness in speaking the Life Way of the Lord Yesus to those people of Damsik.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palaleko &lt; /pa-RED-leko/"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">palaleko &lt; /pa-RED-leko/</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa ra tadèngi rare Barnabas peka sèmi èèna, heka ra sèmi rare Saulus kèna. Ka ra pea pa'èci ètu kota Yerusalem. Saulus bani lole Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus kahèi, sad'i dènge dhèu cee èèna ka. Nèngu madha'u boe.<bt>When they heard Barnabas speak like that, then they received/accepted Saulus. And they stayed together in the city of Yerusalem. Saulus also spoke boldly the Good News of the Lord Yesus to whoever/anybody. And he had no fear.</bt><v n="29" />Na pakarèi dènge pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi dhu padhai lii Yunani. Te ngaa rèngu ro'o boe sèmi rare lii padhai lii nèngu. Nèti èèna ka, ra tenge j'ara neo pamadhe ne.<bt>He debated/discussed with several Jahudi people who spoke the Yunani language. But they did not want to accept what he said. Because of that, they looked for a way to kill him.</bt><v n="30" />Ropa dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus re'a ngangee karehe dhèu sèra, hèia lasi rare Saulus rèti asa kota Kaisarea. D'ai nèi, ka ra pua ne lèpa asa kota na, Tarsus.<bt>When the followers of the Lord Yesus knew their evil intent, then they took Saulus to the city of Kaisarea. Arriving there, they ordered him to return to his city, Tarsus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus ètu propensi Yudea, propensi Galilea, dènge propensi Samaria, mamuri dènge mera-milu. Rèngu asa tabha ae. Rèngu mamuri madhutu dad'èi Lamatua. Ka Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci pa'èra d'ara rèngu.<bt>After that time, the people who belonged to the Lord Yesus in the province of Yudea, the province of Galilea, and the province of Samaria, lived in peace. They continued to increase in number, because they lived according to the will of God2. And the Spirit of God2 who is Holy strengthened their insides (=encourage).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus puri-pa'èle dhèu mone èci ètu rae Lida<bt>Peturs heals a man in the village of Lida</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Lod'o-lod'o sèra, Petrus biasa kako palème asa mia-mia, ho pa'èra d'ara dhèu unu Lamatua sèra. Ca lod'o ka na la'e ngad'o rèngu ètu rae Lida.<bt>Those days, Petrus often walked around to many places, to strengthen the people who belonged to the Lord. One day he went visiting them in the village of Lida.</bt><v n="33" />Ètu nèi, na paraga dènge dhèu mone èci, ngara na Eneas. Dhèu ne, karuku aru tèu kèna, ka na kèd'i nare heka nèti era j'unu na.<bt>There (remote), he met with a maned named Eneas. This person had been paralysed for eight years, and he couldn't stand from the place of his laying down.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ngad'o = kunjungi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ngad'o = kunjungi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Hèia Petrus peka dènge ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Eneas! Limuri ne, Lamatua Yesus Kristus pa'èle èu. De kèd'i ka! Lalau paie era j'unu èu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Petrus spoke to him, saying, &lt;&lt;Eneas! Now the Lord Yesus Kristus heals you. So get up! Fix up your sleeping place!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lalau paie = kasi rapi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Lalau paie = kasi rapi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Nanene nare sèmi èèna, hèia na kèd'i dènge ka.<bt>Hearing that, then that person stood up immediately.</bt><v n="35" />Ropa ladhe rèdhi Eneas èle le, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rae Lida dènge rae Saron parcaya Lamatua Yesus.<bt>All the people in the village of Lida and the village of Saron, when they saw Eneas already healed, then they beleieved in the Lord Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus pamamuri hari Tabita<bt>Petrus brings back to life Tabita who had died</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu bhèni èci, ngara na Tabita, pea dètu dènge nebhe dhasi ètu kota Yope. (Madhutu lii Yunani ra paroa bhèni ne, ngara na Dorkas. Sasoa na &lt;rusa&gt;.)<bt>At that time, a woman named Tabita was living near the coast in the city of Yope. (According to the Yunani language they called this woman, Dorkas. It means &lt;deer&gt;.)</bt><note reference="9:36" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ngara bhèni ne, dua, te ngaa sasoa nèngu èci. <span class="Italic">Tabita, </span>lii Aram, sasoa na &lt;rusa&gt;. <span class="Italic">Dorkas,</span> lii Yunani, sasoa na &lt;rusa&gt; kahèi.<bt>The name of this woman, was two, but their meaning is the same. Tabita, is in the Aram language, meaning &lt;deer&gt;. Dorkas, is in the Yunani language, meaning &lt;deer&gt; also.</bt></note>Bhèni ne parcaya Lamatua Yesus. Tatao bhèni ne be'a mi dedha dhèu leo, aa na tema laladhe dhèu j'èra.<bt>This woman believed in the Lord Yesus. The deeds of this woman were good toward other people, and she often looked after people who were suffering/in difficulty.</bt><v n="37" />Lod'o èèna, Tabita ne pèd'a aae, ka madhe. Ka dhèu padiu ne èi. Èle èèna ka, ra papake ne mèdha-papake, ka ra paj'unu ne ètu kama dedha.<bt>At that time, Tabita was seriously sick, and died. And people bathed her with water. After that, they clothed he with her clothes, and they laid her down in (her) upper room.</bt><v n="38" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu se tadèngi, na, Petrus ètu rae Lida, dhu kaj'èu nèti kota Yope, sèmi kako haga na ele boe ca'èta lod'o sa. Ka ra pua dhèu dua lasi paroa Petrus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i manèngi ama mai ku lai-lai asa kota Yope.&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, these people heard that Petrus was in the village of Lida, whose distance from the city of Yope was around half a day's walk. And they ordered two people to go summon Petrus, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! We(exc) request father to come quickly to the city of Yope.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padiu èi (lexicalised) = kasi mandi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">padiu èi (lexicalised) = kasi mandi air ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, ka Petrus kèd'i dènge ka, la'e madhutu rèngu. D'ai nèi, ka na maso taruu asa d'ara kama Tabita. Ètu d'ara kama na, pènu le dènge bhèni balu dhu mai tangi. Bhèni balu sèra pad'elo mi Petrus kodho dènge mèdha-papake leo, dhu Dorkas j'au hia rèngu, lod'o na mamuri era.<bt>When he heard that, Petrus got up straightaway, and went following them. Arriving yonder, he went straight into Tabita's room. In that room, it was full with the widows who came to weep. Those widows showed to Petrus the shirts/dresses and other clothes which Dorkas had sewn for them, when she was still alive.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="j'au = jahit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">j'au = jahit</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01940b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Petrus pamamuri hari dhèu madhe<bt>Petrus brings back to life mother Tabita</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Hèia Petrus pua si kalua nèti kama. Ka na patitu urutuu ho na manèngi-mangaj'i. Hèia na ladhe asa dhèu madhe ne, ka na padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tabita! Kèd'i ka!&gt;&gt; Cag'ag'a laa, Tabita bhoke musi madha na. Ropa ladhe nèdhi Petrus, ka na kèd'i madhèdi.<bt>Then Peturs ordered them to go out of the room. And he kneeled to pray. Then he looked at the dead person, and he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Tabita! Get up!&gt;&gt; Suddenly, mother Tabita opened her eyes. When she saw Petrus, she sat up.</bt><v n="41" />Hèia Petrus kèpe kacui-aai na, ho hia ne titu. Ka Petrus paroa bhèni balu sèra dènge dhèu-dhèu leo ètu èèna, ho na hia bhèni dhu mamuri hari ne asa rèngu.<bt>Then Petrus took her hand, to help her stand. And Petrus summoned those widows and the other people that were there, to Petrus turned over the woman who was living again to them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Ka lii lole ne, dhèu lolo palème d'ara kota Yope, toke d'ai dhèu ae parcaya Lamatua Yesus.<bt>And this story, people told it all over the city of Yope, to the point that many people believed in the Lord Yesus.</bt><v n="43" />Èle èèna ka, Petrus pea pèri-pèri lod'o ètu èmu dhèu èci, ngara na Simon. Dhèu ne'e, tuka pamèu ka'uri badha.<bt>After that, Petrus stayed several days in the house of a person named Simon. This person, was a cleaner of animal skins.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Komedhaa sordad'u Roma, ngara na Kornelis, paroa Petrus<bt>A commander (assim. loan) of Roma soldiers (assim. loan), named Kornelis, summons Petrus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="10" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, abhu komedhaa sordad'u Roma dhèu èci, ngara na Kornelis. Nèngu ne, komedhaa nèti sordad'u cangasu dhèu. Rèngu mai nèti kaj'èu, nèti rai Italia, ka ra pea ètu kota Kaisarea.<bt>At that time, there was a commander of Roma soldiers, named Kornelis. This one was a commander of 100 soldiers. They came from far away, from the land/country of Italia, and they lived in the city of Kaisarea.</bt><v n="2" />Nèngu dènge isi èmu na d'èi padètu dènge Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa ae ka dhèu Roma leo sèmi boe èèna. Nèngu biasa soru-bara dhèu j'èra, aa na maj'èni sabaj'a mi Ama Lamatua.<bt>He and his household, desired to be near to God. But, many other Roma people were not like that. He often helped people in difficulty, and he was diligent to pray to God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patèta = bapotong (bahasa Pacele ana"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">patèta = bapotong (bahasa Pacele ana patèta = tentara; ana kabhuu = polisi) kabhuu = k.o. fish, (bahu) amis ; Kornelis &gt; Ne'i; <span class="Bold">2:</span> ladhe-leru = asuh, piara ; maj'èni = rajin</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01943b.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Komedhaa Kornelis sabaj'a mi Ama Lamatua<bt>Commander Kornelis praying to God</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ca lod'o hari, pe d'ara hake tèlu nihia sa, na abhu tanila. Na ladhe nèdhi iia-iia ana pajuu Ama Lamatua èci puru mai nèti sorga, ka na paroa ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Kornelis!&gt;&gt;<bt>One day, around three in the afternoon, he had a vision. He saw clearly a messenger of God come down from heaven, and he called his name, saying, &lt;&lt;Kornelis!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tanila = mimpi dalam keadaan setengah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tanila = mimpi dalam keadaan setengah sadar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ropa Kornelis ladhe nèdhi ana pajuu nèti sorga, ka na madha'u titu kèna. Hèia na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia, ama?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Kornelis saw the messenger from heaven, he was terrified. Then he asked, saying, &lt;&lt;What is it, father? [father used to avoid clash with next verse]&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ana pajuu ne dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua tadèngi le lii manèngi-mangaj'i èu, aa Na ne'a le d'ara hua iia èu mi dedha dhèu leo. Ka Na sanèd'e èu.<bt>And the messenger responded, saying, &lt;&lt;God2 has heard your prayer/request, and He knows your generosity to other people. And He remembers you. (=is giving attention to)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="babe'a dara èu = ; dara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">babe'a dara èu = ; dara hua iia = kemurahan hati</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />De pua dhèu lasi asa kota Yope, ho paroa rèti dhèu èci, ngara na Simon Petrus.<bt>So, order people to go to the city of Yope, to summon a person, named Simon Petrus.</bt><v n="6" />Dhèu èèna manubha ètu èmu cue ètu sebhe dhasi, unu Simon, tuka pamèu ka'uri badha.&gt;&gt;<bt>That person is temporarily staying in a house by the side of the ocean, owned by Simon, a cleaner of animal skins.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ropa ana pajuu nèti sorga ne tèke eele Kornelis, ka na paroa ana sab'a na dhèu dua, dènge sordad'u èci dhu d'èi padètu dènge Lamatua kahèi.<bt>When the messenger from heaven left Kornelis, he summoned two of his workers/underlings, and a soldier who also desired to be near to God2.</bt><v n="8" />Kornelis lolo aa'i ngaa dhu nèngu nèdhi èèna, ka na pua si lasi asa kota Yope.<bt>Kornelis told them everything that he had just seen, and he ordered them to go to the city of Yope.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus la'e paraga dènge Kornelis<bt>Petrus goes to meet with Kornelis</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka asa bèli èèna, pe d'ara lod'o titu mera sa, dhèu paleha nèti Kornelis sèra oe d'ai le Yope. Lod'o èèna, Petrus ca'e la'e neo manèngi-mangaj'i asa kalaga dedha èmu Simon.<bt>The next day, around noon (idiom), the emissaries from Kornelis we already near Yope. At that time, Petrus had gone up to pray on the upper platform of Simo's house.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lod'o nètu = siang ; lod'o"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lod'o nètu = siang ; lod'o titu mera = tengah hari ; kalaga = ; èmu dedha = loteng (inside house)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01944b.tif" rtfFormat="width:9.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:center">Petrus sabaj'a ètu èmu dedha<bt>Petrus praying on top of the house</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa na manèngi-mangaj'i, na rasa manganga. Na mate dhèu lalau nganga'a-nginu. Ropa nèngu manèngi-mangaj'i era, na abhu tanila kahèi.<bt>While he was still praying, contrary to expect he felt hungry. He was waiting for people to serve food-drink. While he was still praying, he had a vision.</bt><v n="11" />Na nèdhi sèmi liru bhoka. Ka hahèla-koi bhèla aae ca bèla puru mai, dhu èki re suu-suu èpa na.<bt>He saw like the sky opened. And a wide cloth-sheet, tied by its four corners, coming down.</bt><v n="12" />Ètu d'ara hahèla-koi èèna, nèngu ladhe nèdhi rupa-rupa badha, nuka badha ai èpa, badha rod'o-kakara, dènge rupa-rupa manu-bhui kahèi.<bt>Inside that sheet, he saw all sorts of animal, that is four-legged animals, chest-crawling animals, and also various sorts of birds.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hahèla koi = sprei/kain pembungkus kasur"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hahèla koi = sprei/kain pembungkus kasur ; hèla = bungkus dgn kain ; bèla = kain ; bhèla = lebar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01945b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;verticalPosition:top">Petrus ladhe nèdhi rupa-rupa badha ètu d'ara hahèla-koi<bt>Petrus seeing all.kinds.of animals inside the sheet</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Hèia na tadèngi lii èci pua ne, &lt;&lt;Petrus! Kèd'i ka! Kèj'i badha se, ho mu'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he heard a voice commanding him, &lt;&lt;Pete! Get up! Cut/slaughter these animals to eat them!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Te ngaa Petrus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Bisa boe, Ama! Baku sèmi èèna! Te ja'a ku'a kèdhi mèka sisi badha sèmi se'e! Ji'i dhèu Yahudi luri sisi badha se'e aa'i-aa'i ra!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Petrus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Can't do it, Lord! Don't do that! Cause I have never eaten meat of animals like these! Jahudi people are forbidden the meat of all these animals here!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa lii ne b'ala hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ama Lamatua peka mèdha ngaa dhu mèu, èu baku peka kaj'alu!&gt;&gt;<bt>But, the voice responded again, saying, &lt;&lt;If God says something is clean, you cannot say in turn that it is unclean/defiled!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="16" />Hahèla-koi èèna cèu tèlu hari, èle èèna ka ca'e hari asa dedha-liru la'e.<bt>That aforementioned sheet appeared three times, and then it went back up into the sky above.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèu-milu = halal; |b16:|r cèu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">mèu-milu = halal; <span class="Bold">16:</span> cèu = muncul</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia Petrus pajiko la'e-mai sasoa tanila deo na. Kabèdhi laa, ana paleha Kornelis sèra d'ai madha èmu Simon. Ra titu ètu hèb'a èmu.<bt>Then Petrus was evaluating coming-going the meaning of that recent vision. At that moment, the emissaries of Kornelis arrived in front of Simo's house. They stood in front of the door.</bt><v n="18" />Ka ra lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i tenge dhèu èci dhu manubha ètu èmu ne'e. Ngara na, Simon Petrus. Ele boe ama tadhe, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>And they called out, saying, &lt;&lt;We(exc) are looking for a person who is staying temporarily in this house. His name is Simon Petrus. Perhaps you know him, or what?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pajiko = berpikir, merenungkan ; sasoa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pajiko = berpikir, merenungkan ; sasoa = arti; <span class="Bold">18:</span> sina ma = barangkali, mungkin</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ropa Petrus pajiko sasoa tanila na era. Ka Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Petrus. Dhèu<bt>That was while Petrus was still evaluating the meaning of that vision. And the Holy Spirit of God2 spoke to him, &lt;&lt;We, Pete. Person/people</bt><note reference="10:19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani pèri-pèri peka na, &lt;dhèu tèlu&gt; dhu mai. Sasuri leo èci, peka na, dhoka &lt;dhèu dua&gt; dhu mai. Te ngaa sasuri ae ka dhu ale boe dhèu pèri dhu mai tenge Petrus.<bt>Several writings in the Yunani language say, &lt;three people&gt; came. Another writing says only &lt;two people&gt; came. But, many writings do not say how many people came looking for Pete.</bt></note>mate èu ka haha si.<bt>are waiting for you below.</bt><v n="20" />De puru ho lamu ka dènge si. Èu baku mage-mage ia ka. Masi ka ad'a Yahudi aj'a, na, dhèu Yahudi hud'i madenge dènge dhèu leo, te ngaa èu baku madenge dènge rèngu, lula Ja'a ka dhu pua rèngu mai rare èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>So go down to go with them. You must not be anxious. Jahudi adat teaches that Jahudi people must loath/avoid other (kinds of) people. But, you must not loath/avoid them. Because I am the one who sent them to come and get you.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="21" />Ka Petrus puru la'e paraga dènge dhèu sèra. Hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne'e ka dhu miu tenge. De miu parluu ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Petrus went down to meet with those people. Then he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I here am the one who you(pl) are looking for. So what is your need?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madenge = jijik"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">madenge = jijik</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Komedhaa sordad'u Roma èci pua ji'i mai asa ne'e. Nèngu èèna, komedhaa nèti cangasu sordad'u. Dhèu ne d'ara mola, aa na d'èi padètu dènge Ama Lamatua. Dhèu Yahudi ae dhu re'a le babe'a dhèu ne'e. Med'a na, heka ana pajuu Ama Lamatua puru mai nèti sorga, ho pua lamatua ji'i manèngi èu lamu asa èmu na, ho na neo nanene unu na nèti èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they answered, saying, &lt;&lt;A commander of Roma soldiers ordered us to come here. He is the commander of 100 soldiers. This person has straight (pure) insides, and he desires to be close to God. Many Jahudi people already know this person's goodness. Just yesterday, a messenger of God descended from heaven, to tell our(exc) master to request you to go to his house, so he could listen for himself from you.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ropa tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, hèia Petrus manèngi rèngu ho j'unu taha mèda ne ètu èèna. Bèli mad'ae èèna, ra pakèd'i, lasi palere. Dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus pèri-pèri nèti Yope lasi kahèi.<bt>When he heard like that, then Petrus asked them to sleep overnight at that house. The next day, they got up, and they left together. Several people who belonged to the Lord Yesus from Yope also went.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Mèda èèna rèngu j'unu ètu j'ara. Bèli èèna, heka rèngu d'ai kota Kaisarea kèna. Ropa rèngu d'ai, Kornelis mate mema rèngu. Na pakaboko nare le a'ari na dènge mone-aanga angalai na ètu èmu nèngu.<bt>That night they slept on the road (=journey). Only the following day did they arrive at the city of Kaisarea. When they arrived, Kornelis was already waiting for them. He had gathered his relatives and his close friends in his house.</bt><v n="25" />Ropa Petrus d'ai hèb'a èmu, Kornelis mai soru ne, ka madhèdi patitu kètu urutuu ètu haga Petrus, ho na pahaha iisi.<bt>When Petrus arrived at the door of the house, Kornelis came to greet/welcome him, and kneeled at the feet of Petrus, to humble himself before/worship him.</bt><v n="26" />Te ngaa Petrus pakèd'i ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Baku sèmi èèna! Baku pahaha iisi mi ja'a. Te ja'a ne, dhèu rai-haha sama sèmi èu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Petrus stood him up, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Don't do that! Don't prostrate yourself before/worship me. Cause I here, am a human just like you.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mone-aanga = kawan akrab, kawan satu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">mone-aanga = kawan akrab, kawan satu kaki ; mone-aanga angalai (fixed phrase); <span class="Bold">25:</span> pahaha iisi = 1) merendahkan diri, 2) sembah ; sogo =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ropa tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, Kornelis kèd'i titu dènge. Ka dua ra padhai lii, kako lasi asa d'ara èmu. D'ai d'ara èmu, Petrus nèdhi dhèu ae pakaboko mate nèngu.<bt>When he heard that, Kornelis stood up immediately. And the two of them spoke as they entered into the house. Arriving there, Petrus saw many people gathered waiting for him.</bt><v n="28" />Na ladhe palème dhèu sèra, ka na padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;A'ari aa'i-aa'i mi! Miu me'a mema ad'a ji'i dhèu Yahudi. Madhutu ad'a ji'i, na, ji'i bisa boe pa'èci dènge dhèu leo. Ngaa hari, maso asa d'ara èmu ra. Te ngaa Ama Lamatua pad'elo le dènge ja'a, ladhe mèdha ngaa dhu Nèngu peka na mèu, ja'a baku peka na mèdha èèna kaj'alu. De limuri ne, ja'a madenge heka dènge dhèu leo. Ja'a hud'i tao dhèu leo sama sèmi a'ari ja'a kahèi.<bt>He looked around at those people, and he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;All you elder-younger siblings! You(pl) already know our(exc) Jahudi people's adat. According to our adat, na, we are not allowed to join together with other people. Especially enter into their houses. But, God revealed to me, if something that He says is clean, I should not say that thing is filthy/impure. Consequently, now, I can no longer loath/avoid other people. I must treat other people just like my own elder-younger siblings.</bt><v n="29" />Nèti èèna ka, lod'o miu lami paroa, ka ja'a mai dènge. Ja'a pamata heka, lula Lamatua peka nare le dènge ja'a sèmi èèna. Miu peka ku laa. Miu parluu ngaa nèti ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that, when you went to summon me,, I came immediately. I did not delay any more, because God2 had already spoken to me like that. Now go on and speak. What is it that you need from me?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kapod'e heka, = sonde cari-cari alasan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kapod'e heka, = sonde cari-cari alasan ; pamata = tunggu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Hèia Kornelis lole aa'i mèu-mèu, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èpa lod'o dhu la'e èèna, ropa lod'o nihia, ja'a manèngi-mangaj'i ètu èmu ja'a. Cag'ag'a laa, dhèu mone èci titu ètu madha ja'a. Mèdha-papake na heo loa-loa.<bt>Then Kornelis spoke in detail, saying, &lt;&lt;Four days ago, when the sun was slanting down (=afternoon), I was praying/worshipping in my house. Suddenly a man stood in front of me. His clothes were radiant.</bt><v n="31" />Ka na paroa ja'a, aku nèngu na, &lt;Kornelis! Lamatua tadèngi le lii manèngi èu, aa Na ne'a le d'ara hua iia èu mi dedha dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>And he called me, saying, &lt;Kornelis! God2 has heard your request/prayer, and He knows the good things you do to/for all the people.</bt><v n="32" />De lod'o ne'e, pua dhèu lasi rare dhèu èci asa kota Yope. Ngara na, Simon Petrus. Nèngu manubha ètu èmu cue ètu sebhe dhasi, ètu èmu tuka pamèu ka'uri badha. Ngara na, Simon kahèi.&gt;<bt>So, now/today, send people to go get a person in the city of Yope. His name is Simon Petrus. He is staying temporarily in a house by the edge of the ocean, in the house of a cleaner of animal skins. His name is also Simon.&gt;</bt><v n="33" />Nèti èèna ka, ja'a pua dhèu dhiu rare ama. Ji'i manèngi makasi ae, lula ama mai dènge, ropa tadèngi lii paroa ji'i. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i pakaboko ètu ne'e, ho neo nanene ngaa dhu Ama Lamatua pua ama peka dènge ji'i!&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of that, I sent people to go fetch father. We(exc) are very grateful, because father came immediately when you heard our summons. Because of that, we have gathered in this place, to want to hear whatever God tells you to say to us!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Èpa lod'o dhu la'e na ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Èpa lod'o dhu la'e na = (try it out) ;; <span class="Bold">32:</span> sabi = skin (animal); <span class="Bold">33:</span> dhiu = pi ; paroa ~ paroe</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus lole J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus hia dhèu Yahudi boe [\s2]<bt>Petrus explains the Lord Yesus' Way of Life to other (foreign) people [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Hèia Petrus padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Limuri ne, ja'a heka ke'a kèna, na, ètu madha Ama Lamatua, dhèu rai-haha sama èci èèna ka. Lamatua ladhe boe rèhu, mia ka dhèu Yahudi, aa mia ka dhèu leo.<bt>Then Petrus spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Now, only now2 do I understand that before God humans here are the same. God2 does not see faces (=is not biased), about who is a Jahudi person, and who is a different (non-Jahodi) person.</bt><note reference="10:34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 10:17</note><v n="35" />Dhèu mia dhu d'ara mola, dhu maj'èni manèngi-mangaj'i mi Lamatua, aa madhutu dad'èi Nèngu, rèngu sèra pakarej'e d'ara Na.<bt>Whoever has a straight/pure insides, and they are diligent to pray to God2, and follow His will, they are the ones who please His insides.</bt><v n="36" />De miu me'a, ngaa dhu Lamatua peka le dènge ji'i dhèu Isra'el, peka na, Nèngu pua le Kristus, nuka Yesus. Ka Yesus madhe ho padame dhèu rai-haha dènge Ama Lamatua. Aa Nèngu j'aj'i Kètu mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i.<bt>So you(pl) knowwhat God2 has said to we(exc) people of Isra'el, that He sent the Kristus, that is Yesus. And Yesus died to bring peace(right relationships) between humans and God. And He is Lord over humanity [EXEG: pantown kurios = lord of humanity].</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Miu tadèngi kahèi, ngaa dhu j'aj'i le ètu palème propensi Yudea. Lii lole èèna mulai nèti Yohanis tuka sarani dhèu, aj'a dhèu ho ra ele-ho'a nèti sasala-sasigo rèngu. Aa rèngu hud'i abhu sarani kahèi, sèna ka j'aj'i tadha, peka na, rèngu pabe'a le dènge Ama Lamatua.<bt>You have also heard what has happened all over the province of Yudea. That story began with Yohanis the Baptiser of People, teaching people to stop doing their wrongs (doublet). And they must also get baptised, so that it is a sign saying they are good with God.</bt><v n="38" />Èle èèna ka, Ama Lamatua hia Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci mi Yesus, dhèu Nasaret. Lamatua hia koasa Na mi Yesus kahèi. Ka Yesus maso-kalua rae-rae, tao j'ara be'a mi dhèu-dhèu. Aa Na puri-pa'èle dhèu dhu dhèu aae nidhu paj'èra si. Na tao sèmi èèna, lula Ama Lamatua sama-sama dènge Ne taruu.<bt>After that, God's gave His Holy Spirit to Yesus, that person of Nasaret. God2 gave His power/authority to Yesus as well. And Yesus went in and out of villages doing good things to those people. And He healed various people whom the King of evil spirits was persecuting/troubling. He did those things, because God was always with Him.</bt><v n="39" />Te ji'i se'e ka dhu ladhe ngèdhi unu mi, ngaa dhu Na sab'a ètu kota Yerusalem, aa palème kabarai Yahudi.<bt>Cause we(exc) here are the ones who saw for ourselves what it was that He worked in the city of Yerusalem, and throughout Jahudi society here.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa dhèu paku pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha.<bt>Even though it was like that, (nevertheless) people nailed Him to death on crossed wood.</bt><v n="40" />Nèngu madhe tare'a, te ngaa asa camèd'a, Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne. Ka Na pad'elo iisi Na, ho dhèu rèdhi, sèna ka ra re'a Nèngu mamuri hari tare'a-re'a le.<bt>He really died, but the day-after-the-next-day, God brought Him back to life. And He revealed Himself, for people to see, so that they would know that He truly was alive again.</bt><v n="41" />Te ngaa dhèu ae cahag'e dhu rèdhi boe Ne, dhoka ji'i di. Lod'o Nèngu mamuri hari le, ji'i biasa nga'a-nginu dènge Ne. Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u ji'i ho la'a lole palème Lii Lolo Be'a Yesus mi dhèu ae ètu mia-mia.<bt>But, not everyone [dhèu ae cahag'e = not everyone] saw Him, only us(exc). While He was alive again, we often ate-drank with Him. God appointed us to go all over the place to tell the Good News of Yesus to people everywhere.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="la'a = 1pe-pergi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">la'a = 1pe-pergi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Aa Lamatua ka dhu pua ji'i la'a lole peka pasaraa mi dhèu, lula-nèti Dhèu dhu Na paj'uj'u nèti uru ka mai, nuka Yesus. Aa Lamatua ded'e Ne j'aj'i Dhèu J'ue Lii Langu, ho pama'ète, na, cee ka dhu bisa mamuri taruu dènge Ama Lamatua, aa cee aad'o. Yesus èèna ka dhu j'ue lii dhèu dhu madhe le, dènge dhèu dhu mamuri era.<bt>And God2 is the one who ordered us to go all over the place and explain clearly to people, about the Person whom He designated from long ago, that is this Yesus. And God2 elevated Him to be the Judge (&lt;Person who Settles Disputes), saying who it is that can live continuously with God, and who can't. That Yesus, is the one who decides the case of people who are already dead, and people who are still alive.</bt><v n="43" />Nèti uru ka mai, dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua aa'i-aa'i ra lole le Yesus, peka na, dhèu cee dhu parcaya Nèngu, na, Ama Lamatua sèmi nare si, aa saku eele sasala-sasigo rèngu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>From long ago, all of God's spokespeople are the ones who have pointed to this Yesus, saying that whoever believed in Him, God would receive/accept them, and wipe away their wrongs.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="peka pataraa = kasi tau tarang-tarang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">peka pataraa = kasi tau tarang-tarang ; pasaraa</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu Yahudi boe, abhu Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci [\s2]<bt>Non-Jahudi people, get God's Holy Spirit [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Lod'o Petrus padhai lii nare mèka, cag'ag'a laa, Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci maso asa d'ara dhèu se'e aa'i-aa'i ra dhu nanene lii padhai lii na.<bt>While Petrus was still speaking, suddenly God2's Holy Spirit entered the insides of all these people who were listening to him speak.</bt><v n="45" />Ètu èèna, abhu kahèi dhèu Yahudi angalai Petrus dhu mai palere dènge ne nèti kota Yope asa èmu Kornelis ètu kota Kaisarea. Ropa rèngu rèdhi dhèu ae sèra abhu Roh Ama Lamatua, ka ra malaa, lula rèngu heka re'a kèna, na, Lamatua hia Roh Na mi dhèu Yahudi boe kahèi.<bt>In that place, there were also Petrus' Jahudi companions who had come accompanying him from the city of Yope to Kornelis' house in the city of Kaisarea. When they saw those many people get God's Spirit, they were amazed/confused, because they were just for first time understanding that God2 gave His Spirit to non-Jahudi people as well.</bt><v n="46" />Rèngu tadèngi dhèu ètu d'ara èmu Kornelis sèra padhai lii, pake lii dhu baka-leo. Aa ra koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua.<bt>They heard those people there inside Kornelis house speaking using various different languages (=different from each other/of a different sort). And they praised the name/reputation of God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bakaleo = balaen-laen ; lii bakaleo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">bakaleo = balaen-laen ; lii bakaleo = bahasa yg beda-beda, bahasa-bahasa asing, bahasa manusia yg berbeda-beda</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Petrus padhai lii, peka na,<bt>Then Petrus spoke, saying,</bt><v n="47" />&lt;&lt;Miu mèdhi unu mi! Dhèu se'e se, sèmi rare le Roh Lamatua èci èèna ka dènge èdhi kahèi. De mai ka, sèna ka èdhi sarani si. Dhèu èci sa dhu bisa heka taha rèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;Look for yourselves! These people have received the Spirit of God2 just like we(inc) did also. So, let's baptise them. There is noone who can restrain/prevent them.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="48" />Hèia Petrus pua si ho sarani Kornelis dènge dhèu ètu sèra sa, ho ra j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus. Ka ra manèngi Petrus pea dènge rèngu pèri-pèri lod'o hari. Èle èèna ka, heka ra hia ne lèpa asa Yerusalem.<bt>Then Petrus ordered/told them to baptise Kornelis and the people who were there, to become people belonging to the Lord Yesus. And they asked Petrus to stay with them for several days. After that, only then did they release them to return to Yerusalem.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Abhu heka j'ara dhu mage ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Abhu heka j'ara dhu mage = Sonde ada jalan yang awas-awas (not natural)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus siri iisi na, lula na sarani dhèu Yahudi boe<bt>Petrus defends himself, because he baptised non-Jahudi people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="11" />
      <v n="1" />Petrus dhae lèpa mèka, te ngaa dhèu pajuu-paleha Yesus dènge dhèu parcaya Yesus dhu leo sèra, dhu pea ètu Yerusalem, tadèngi rare le, peka na, dhèu Yahudi boe sèmi rare le Lii Lole Be'a Lamatua.<bt>Before Petrus arrive back there, the servants/emissaries of Yesus and the other people who belonged to Yesus who lived in Yerusalem heard that non-Jahudi people had received the Good News of God2/Lord.</bt><v n="2" />Ropa Petrus d'ai kota Yerusalem, dhèu nèti partei Yahudi<bt>When Petrus arrived at the city of Yerusalem, people from the Jahudi Patry who believed in Yesus came to accuse him, saying,</bt><note reference="11:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ladhe dhèu Yahudi boe neo madhutu Yesus, dhèu nèti partei agama ne, peka na, rèngu hud'i suna ku, madhutu ad'a Yahudi. Aa rèngu hud'i madhutu aa'i ku atora agama Yahudi dhu leo sèra kahèi.<bt>When non-Jahudi people wanted to follow Yesus, people from this religious party said they must be circumcised according to the Jahudi adat. And the must follow all of the Jahudi religious regulations.</bt></note>dhu parcaya Yesus mai pasala ne,<v n="3" />peka na, &lt;&lt;Weh! Èu tao samia kèna? Èu me'a ad'a-tatao èdhi, do aad'o? Èu ne bani titu kèna, maso asa d'ara èmu dhèu leo! Aa èu mu'a-minu dènge rèngu kahèi! Baku tao sèmi èèna, te rèngu madhutu mèka ad'a suna èdhi! Èdhi bisa boe pa'èci dènge rèngu sèra!&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;We! What have you done? Dont' you(sg) know our(inc) adat regulations? You are really bold, entering inside the house of other (=non-Jahudi) people! And you eat-drink with them too! Don't do like that, cause they have not yet followed our circumcision adat! We cannot join together with them!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Hèia Petrus lole aa'i-aa'i dhu j'aj'i le, peka na,<bt>Then Petrus told everything that had happened, saying,</bt><v n="5" />&lt;&lt;Lod'o ja'a ètu kota Yope, ja'a laku sabaj'a, ka ja'a abhu tanila. Ja'a kèdhi liru bhoka, ka hahèla-koi bhèla aae ca bèla, dhu èki re suu-suu èpa na, puru mai asa ja'a.<bt>&lt;&lt;When I was in the city of Yope, I went to pray2, and I had a vision. I saw the sky open, and a broad sheet which was tied by its four corners, descend toward me.</bt><v n="6" />Ropa ja'a patigi asa d'ara hahèla-koi èèna, ja'a kèdhi rupa-rupa badha, nuka badha ai èpa, badha rod'o-kakara, dènge rupa-rupa manu-bhui kahèi. Badha se'e se, dhu èdhi dhèu Yahudi luri.<bt>When I stretch-to-look into that sheet, I saw various sorts of animals, that is four-legged animals, belly-crawling animals, and various sorts of birds. These animals are the ones who we(iinc) Jahudi's taboo/avoid.</bt><v n="7" />Hèia ja'a tadèngi lii èci pua, peka na, &lt;Petrus! Kèd'i ka! Kèj'i badha se, ho mu'a!&gt;<bt>Then I heard a voice command, saying, &lt;Pete! Get up! Ritually-slaughter these animals to eat (them)!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patigi = stretch to see into"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">patigi = stretch to see into s.t.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa ja'a dhaa, peka na, &lt;Bisa boe, Ama! Baku sèmi èèna! Te ja'a ku'a kèdhi mèka sisi badha sèmi se'e! Dhèu Yahudi luri sisi badha se'e aa'i-aa'i ra!&gt;<bt>But I responded, saying, &lt;No way, Lord! Not like that! Cause I have never eaten the meat of animals like these! Jahudi people taboo/avoid the meat of all these animals!&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Te ngaa lii ne b'ala hari, peka na, &lt;Ladhe Ama Lamatua peka mèdha ngaa dhu mèu, èu baku peka na kaj'alu!&gt;<bt>But, the voice came back again, saying, &lt;WhenGod says something is clean, you don't say it is filthy/impure!&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ja'a kèdhi hahèla-koi èèna cèu padhutu tèlu hari, ka ca'e hari asa dedha-liru la'e.<bt>I saw this sheet appear three times in succession, and ascend again back up into the sky.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Lod'o èèna kahèi, dhèu tèlu d'ai èmu dhu ja'a pea. Rèngu nèti Kaisarea mai tenge ja'a.<bt>At that same time, three people arrived at the house where I was staying. They came looking for me from Kaisarea.</bt><v n="12" />Hèia Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci peka dènge ja'a, aku nèngu na, &lt;Puru ho lamu ka dènge dhèu sèra. Èu baku mage-mage ia ka. Èu baku madenge dènge rèngu.&gt; Ka a'ari èdhi dhèu èna palere dènge ja'a kahèi asa Kaisarea. Ètu èèna, ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi maso asa d'ara èmu komedhaa sordad'u Roma.<bt>Then the Hopy Spirit of God2 spoke to me, saying, &lt;Do down to go with those people. You are not to be anxious about it. You are not to loath/abhor/avoid them.&gt; And our(inc) elder-younger siblings there, also accompanied me to Kaisarea. There, we all entered inside the house of the Roma commander of soldiers.</bt><v n="13" />Na lolo, peka na, pèri-pèri lod'o dhu la'e èèna, nèngu nèdhi ana pajuu Lamatua puru nèti sorga, titu ètu d'ara èmu na. Ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;Pua dhèu lasi asa kota Yope, ho paroa mèti dhèu èci, ngara na Simon Petrus.<bt>He spoke saying several days previously, he had seen a messenger of God2 come down from heaven, standing in his house. And he spoke saying, &lt;Send people to go to the city of Yope, to summon bringing a person named Simon Petrus.</bt><v n="14" />Sèna ka dhèu èèna ka dhu pad'elo mi dedha èu dènge isi èmu èu aa'i-aa'i ra, j'ara Lamatua dhu hia miu mamuri, dènge saku eele sasala-sasigo miu sèra.&gt;<bt>So then, that person will reveal to you(sg) and to all your household, the way of God2 for you(pl) to live, and to wipe away your(pl) sins (doublet).&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Nèti èèna ka, ja'a pad'elo J'ara Mamuri Lamatua mi dedha rèngu. Ka rèngu abhu dènge ka Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, sama sèmi èdhi abhu ca hari na.<bt>After that, I explained God2's Way of Life to them. And they got the Holy Spirit of God2, just like we(inc) did that day.</bt><v n="16" />Ropa ja'a kèdhi rèngu abhu Roh Lamatua kahèi, ka ja'a sanèd'e lii padhai lii Lamatua Yesus uru èèna, dhu peka na, &lt;Yohanis sarani dhèu pake dhoka èi di, te ngaa ladhe miu mate hari pèri-pèri lod'o, èèna na Lamatua neo tao dhu kapai risi eele hia miu. Nuka, Na hia miu Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci.&gt;<bt>When I saw they had also gotten God2's Spirit, I also remembered what the Lord Yesus had said previously, that, &lt;Yohanis baptsied people just using water, but when you wait several days, God2 will do something even greater to/for you(pl). That is, He will give you His Holy Spirit.&gt;</bt><note reference="11:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 1:5</note><v n="17" />Te Lamatua unu Na ka dhu hia Roh Na mi dedha dhèu leo sèra, sama sèmi Na pala-bagi mi èdhi se. De madhutu dad'èi miu, ja'a hud'i palab'a dènge Ama Lamatua, do tasamia? De ja'a peka ngaa hari?&gt;&gt;<bt>So2 God Himself is the one who gave His Spirit to these other (non-Jahudi) people, just like He divided (Him) out to us(inc) here. So (consequently) according to your desire/thinking, must I oppose God, or what (should I do)? So, what else can I say?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padelo = kasi tunju, menerangkan, explain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">padelo = kasi tunju, menerangkan, explain</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ropa tadèngi rare, Petrus siri iisi na sèmi èèna, ka rèngu pasala heka ne. Hèia ra koa-kio Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Nia kahèi, nga! Lamatua bhoke le j'ara hia dhèu leo ho ra tèke eele j'ara mamuri rèngu dhu sala, ho Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo rèngu. Sèna ka rèngu abhu mamuri taruu dènge Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they heard Petrus defend himself like that they no longer accused/condemned him. Then they praise God, saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! That's incredible! God2 opened the path for other people to leave behind their life of wrong, for God2 to wipe away their wrongs (doublet). So that they could live continually with Him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Nia kahèi nga! = hebat oo!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Nia kahèi nga! = hebat oo!</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus paj'ala asa mia-mia. Cahag'e pakaboko hari ètu kota Antiokia<bt>People belonging to the Lord Yesus scatter everywhere. Some regroup in Antiokia</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Uru èèna, lod'o ra pamadhe rare Stefanus, ka ra paj'èra dhèu unu Yesus. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu se'e rai paj'ala asa mia-mia. Cahag'e rai asa propensi Finisia. Cahag'e rai asa pulu Siprus, aa cahag'e hari rai d'ai kota Antiokia ètu propensi Siria. Dhèu dhu rai sèra, lole taruu Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus asa mia-mia. Te ngaa ra lole dhoka dènge dhèu Yahudi rèngu sèra. Ra lole boe dènge dhèu leo.<bt>Previously, when they had killed Stefanus, they persecuted the people belonging to Yesus. After that, these people fled scattering in all directions. Some fled to the province of Finisia. Some fled to the island of Siprus, and some others fled arriving at the city of Antiokia in the province of Siria. Those people who fled, kept telling the Good News of the Lord Yesus everywhere. But, they only told it to the Jahudi people. They didn't tell other people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paj'ala ; magèla = usir"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">paj'ala ; magèla = usir</Message></Annotation><note reference="11:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 8:1-4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa abhu kahèi dhèu unu Lamatua dhu mai nèti pulu Siprus dènge kota Kirene. Rèngu cahag'e rai taruu lasi asa kota Antiokia ètu propensi Siria. Rèngu se'e ka dhu lole Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus hia dhèu Yahudi boe ètu era èèna.<bt>But there were also people belonging to the Lord who came from the island of Siprus and the city of Kirene. Some of them kept fleeing until they arrived at the city of Antiokia in the province of Siria. These are the ones who told the Good News of the Lord Yesus to non-Jahudi people in that place.</bt><v n="21" />Lamatua hia si koasa Na, nèti èèna ka, dhèu ae titu kèna parcaya Lamatua Yesus.<bt>God2/Lord gave them His poiwer/authority, and because of that, a great many people believed in the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01925b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Dhèu unu Yesus sèra rai lasi asa mia-mia<bt>People belonging to Yesus go run all.over.the.place</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22-24" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus ètu Yerusalem tadèngi, na, dhèu leo ètu kota Antiokia parcaya Yesus kahèi. Ka ra pua Barnabas la'e ladhe si ètu nèi. Barnabas ne, dhèu d'ara be'a, aa parcaya tare'a-re'a Ama Lamatua. Aa Roh Lamatua dènge nèngu kahèi.<bt>At that time, people belonging to the Lord Yesus in Yerusalem heard that other people in the city of Antiokia were also believing in Yesus. And they sent Barnabas to go see/look after tham yonder. This Barnabas had good insides/character, and truly believe God. And God2's Spirit was also with him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa nèngu d'ai nèi, na nèdhi tare'a Ama Lamatua sab'a ètu d'ara mamuri dhèu leo sèra. Ka d'ara nèngu karej'e. Ka na pa'èra d'ara rèngu, sèna ka rèngu madhutu taruu J'ara Mamuri Lamatua dènge tare'a-re'a. Dènge j'ara ne'e, dhèu unu Lamatua ètu èèna asa tabha ae.<bt>When he arrived yonder, he saw that God was really working inside the lives of those other (non-Jahudi) people. And his insides were pleased. So he strengthened their insides (=encouraged them), so they would continue to follow the Lord's Way of Life in earnest. In this way, people belonging to the Lord in that place kept increasing in number.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'adhu ~ meyakinkan ; pa'èra ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pa'adhu ~ meyakinkan ; pa'èra = bekin kuat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Èle èèna ka, Barnabas la'e tenge Saulus asa kota Tarsus.<bt>After that, Barbabas went to look for Saulus in the city of Tarsus.</bt><v n="26" />Lod'o paraga dènge ne, ka na pamako Saulus ho lasi pea ètu Antiokia. Ka dua ra pea ètu nèi ca tèu, pa'èci dènge dhèu unu Lamatua sèra. Bèli-bèli èèna, rèngu dua ra aj'a-nori J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus mi dhèu ae. (Ètu kota Antiokia ne'e ka, dhèu mulai pangare dhèu parcaya Lamatua Yesus, &lt;dhèu Kristen&gt;).<bt>When he met with Saulus, he cajoled Saulus to go live in Antiokia. And the two of them stayed yonder for a year joining with those people who belong to the Lord. Every day, the two of them taught the Life Way of the Lord Yesus to many people. (In this city of Antiokia, people began to call/name these people who believed in the Lord Yesus, &lt;Kristen people&gt;).</bt><note reference="11:26" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii &lt;Kristen&gt;, kapua nèti lii &lt;Kristus&gt;. Sasoa na, &lt;dhèu madhutu Kristus&gt;. Kristus, sasoa na, &lt;Dhèu Mola-Mèci dhu Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u nèti uru ka mai&gt;.<bt>This word &lt;Kristen&gt;, is based on the word &lt;Kristus&gt;. It means, &lt;a person who follows/obeys Kristus&gt;. Kristus means, &lt;the Holy Person who God designated from long ago&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Lod'o rèngu dua ra pea ètu Antiokia era, pèri-pèri dhèu mai nèti Yerusalem. Ama Lamatua tema le pake dhèu se'e ho rèti lii padhai Na.<bt>While the two of them were still living in Antiokia, several people came from Yerusalem. God often used these people to be His spokespeople.</bt><v n="28" />Nèti rèngu se, dhèu èci, ngara na Agabus. Roh Lamatua peka dènge ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Bèli-camèd'a abhu lod'o manganga-mad'èu lèke palème toke d'ai suu-suu rai-haha.&gt;&gt; Hèia la'e peka hari dènge dhèu-dhèu. (Lii dhu na padhai na, mema j'aj'i tare'a, lod'o dhèu aae kapai risi ètu Roma, ngara na Klaudius, nèd'u paredha. Ra paroa dhèu aae kapai risi ne, Keser.)<bt>Among them was a person named Agabus. The Spirit of God2 spoke with him, saying, &lt;&lt;In the future there will be a time of famine happen all over, to the corners of the earth.&gt;&gt; Then again spoke with those people. (This word/message that they spoke, really truly happened when the Top King (=ceasar) of Roma, named Klaudius, held rule. These people called this Top King, Keser.)</bt><note reference="11:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 21:10</note><v n="29" />Ropa tadèngi rare lii Agabus ne, dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus ètu Antiokia sèra, rare lii èci ho pa'oru doi, sèna ka ra hia mi a'ari dhu parcaya Lamatua Yesus, dhu abhu j'aj'èra ètu propensi Yudea. Èci-èci hia madhutu a'abhu ra.<bt>When they heard the word/message of this Agabus, those people who belonged to the Lord Yesus in Antiokia, came to consensus to collect money so they could give it to the elder-younger siblings who believed the Lord Yesus, who were suffering in the province of Yudea. Each one gave according to their ability.</bt><v n="30" />Ropa ra pa'oru rare, ka ra pua Barnabas dènge Saulus rèti doi sèra asa dhèu j'èra sèi.<bt>When they had collected it, they sent Barnabas and Saulus to take those moneys, to those suffering people yonder.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madèu = famine; |b29:|r pa'oru ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">madèu = famine; <span class="Bold">29:</span> pa'oru = kolekte (kkt)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra pamadhe Yakobis; ra pamaso Petrus asa d'ara bèdho; aa dhèu parcaya Lamatua Yesus sabaj'a<bt>They kill Yakobis; they put Petrus into prison; and people who believe in the Lord Yesus pray2</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="12" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu aae Herodes<bt>At that time, King Herodes</bt><note reference="12:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu aae Herodes ne, ngara na <span class="Italic">Herodes Agripa.</span> Baki na, ngara na <span class="Italic">Herodes Kapai Risi.</span> Herodes Kapai Risi ne ka dhu hia paredha ho pamadhe ana iiki-ana iiki lod'o ina Maria nara iisi Lamatua Yesus ètu rae Betlehem.<bt>This King Herodes, was named <span class="Italic">Herodes Agripa.</span> His grandfather was called <span class="Italic">Herodes the Greatest.</span> That Herodes the Greatest is the one who gave the command to kill the small children when mother Maria gave birth to the Lord Yesus in the village of Betlehem.</bt></note>mulai paj'èra dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus cahag'e.<bt>began to persecute some of the people who belonged to the Lord Yesus.</bt><v n="2" />Nèngu paredha dhèu lasi pare pamadhe Yakobis pake samala. Yakobis ne, a'a Yohanis.<bt>He commanded people to go cut killing Yakobis with a fighting-sword. This Yakobis was the younger sibling of Yohanis.</bt><v n="3" />Ropa Herodes ne'a, na, d'ara dhèu kapai Yahudi sèra karej'e nèti mamadhe Yakobis, ka asa na hino. Lèke lod'o hua iia dhèu Yahudi dhu ra pangare na, Pesta Roti dhu Pake Boe Ragi,<bt>When Herodes knew that the insides of the leaders of the Jahudi people were please about the death of Yakobis, he wanted to do even more. When it was the festival of the Jahudi people they call Feast (loan) of Bread that Doesn't Use Yeast,</bt><note reference="12:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lod'o hua iia ne, padètu dènge lod'o hua iia Paska.<bt>This festival was close to the festivala of Paska (Passover/Easter).</bt></note>ka na pua dhèu lasi kèpe Petrus.<bt>he ordered people to go arrest Petrus.</bt><v n="4" />Kèpe rare ne, ka ra pamaso asa d'ara bèdho. Ka ra pua sordad'u èpa kaboko ho j'aga Petrus pagati-gati mèu-mèda. Ca kaboko sordad'u èèna, dhèu èpa. Ladhe èle lod'o hua iia, heka Herodes neo pama'ète lii Petrus ètu madha dhèu ae.<v n="5" />Lod'o ra pamaso Petrus asa d'ara bèdho, dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus sèra sabaj'a ma'ète boe manèngi ho Lamatua ladhe-leru Petrus.<bt>Having arrested him, they put him into prison. And they designated four groups of soldiers to guard Petrus in cycles/shifts day and night. Each of those groups of soldiers was four people. On the day of this festival, only then did Herodes want to decide Petrus' case in front of many people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jama'at; |b3:|r hino = foe ,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">jama'at; <span class="Bold">3:</span> hino = foe , makin ganas ; kalela ; tatao</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 12:1-27</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua pakalua Petrus nèti d'ara bèdho<bt>God2 gets Petrus out of prison</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Bèli èèna, Herodes neo pama'ète lii langu Petrus ètu madha dhèu ae. Te ngaa mèda èèna, ra èki Petrus pake rate dua ètu d'ara èmu bèdho. Na j'unu ètu talora sordad'u dhèu dua. Aa sordad'u leo sèra j'aga ètu hèb'a babèdho.<bt>The next day, Herodes wanted to decide Petrus' case in front of many people. But, that night, they tied/bound Petrus using two chains (loan) inside the prison. He slept between two soldiers. And other soldiers were guarding at the door of the cell.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01953b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none">Ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga kalua eele Petrus nèti d'ara bèdho<bt>The Lord's messenger from heaven takes Petrus out of jail</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Cag'ag'a laa, ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga, mai titu ètu èèna. Ka d'ara kama na saraa bia. Hèia ana pajuu èèna parèi Petrus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Petrus! Kèd'i mèri!&gt;&gt; Kaca'a laa, rate bèsi sèra bhoke eele unu na nèti kacui-aai Petrus.<bt>Suddenly, a messenger of God2 came down from heaven, standing in that place. And inside that room was extremely bright. Then that messenger woke Petrus up, saying, &lt;&lt;Pete! Get up quickly!&gt;&gt; At that moment, the iron chains opened by themselves from Petrus arms/hands.</bt><v n="8" />Ka ana pajuu èèna pua ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Pake kodho dènge salapa èu!&gt;&gt; Pake nare, ka ana pajuu èèna peka hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pake kodho li'u èu, ho mai madhutu ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then that messenger ordered, saying, &lt;&lt;Put on your shirt/clothes and your footwear!&gt;&gt; After putting them one, the messenger spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;Put on your outer clothes, to come follow me!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karohe = cepat-cepat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">karohe = cepat-cepat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia Petrus madhutu ana pajuu ne lasi asa li'u. Petrus ngee, na, nèngu nii di. Te ngaa mema j'aj'i tare'a.<bt>Then Petrus followed this messenger, going outside. Petrus thought that he was just dreaming. But it was really happening.</bt><v n="10" />Ropa rèngu seli eele era j'aga partama dènge ka dua, hèia rèngu d'ai hèb'a babèdho bèsi. Babèdho èèna bhoke unu na, ka dua ra kalua madhutu ka j'ara asa d'ara kota. Cag'ag'a laa, ana pajuu Lamatua ne ele, ka tèke eele Petrus mesa na ètu era èèna.<bt>When they passed by the first and second guard places, then they arrived at the iron gate of the enclosure/prison. That gate (was) opened itself, and the two of them went out following the road into the city. Suddenly that messenger from God2 disappeared, and left Petrus behind alone in that place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="seli = lewat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">seli = lewat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa ana pajuu ne ele, hèia Petrus heka mase'a kèna. Ka na ngee, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mema tare'a! Ja'a heka ke'a kèna. Lamatua pua ana pajuu Na mai, ho patalale eele ja'a nèti kacui-aai Herodes. Lamatua tao j'ara ne'e, sèna ka kahadhu karehe dhèu Yahudi sèra, lèke boe ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>When that messenger disappeared, then Petrus only then understaood. And he thought, saying, &lt;&lt;It's really true! Only now do I understand. God2 sent His messenger to come to release me from the hand of Herodes. God2 has done this thing so that the evil scheme of those Jahudi people does not happen.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mase'a = sadar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">mase'a = sadar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Èle èèna ka, Petrus la'e asa èmu Maria. Maria ne, ina Yohanis. Ngara leo Yohanis ne, Markus. Ètu èmu èèna, dhèu ae pakaboko ho sabaj'a manèngi Ama Lamatua ladhe-leru Petrus ètu d'ara lii langu èèna.<bt>After that, Petrus went to the house of Maria. This Maria was the mother of Yohanis. Another name for this Yohanis, was Markus. At that house, many people were gathered to pray asking God to look after Petrus in his dispute/case.</bt><v n="13" />Ropa Petrus d'ai madha hèb'a oka èmu èèna, ka na paroa dènge d'eu hèb'a oka. Ka ana bhèni sab'a èci, ngara na Rode, neo ne'a dhèu cee ka dhu mai.<bt>When Petrus arrived in front of the fence gate at that house, he called and knocked on the fence gate. And a working girl, named Rode, wanted to know who is was that came yonder.</bt><v n="14" />Ropa na tadèngi lii Petrus, na tadhe dènge. Na karej'e bia. Ka rai asa d'ara èmu la'e, peka dènge dhèu ètu sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nanene ku! Petrus nuka li'u!&gt;&gt; Te ngaa lula nèngu bingu, ka na bhèlu eele bhoke hèb'a oka hia Petrus.<bt>When she heard Petrus' voice, she recognised it immediately. She was very happy. And she ran inside the house, speaking with the people there, saying, &lt;&lt;We! Pete is the one outside there!&gt;&gt; But because she was confused, she forgot to open the fence gate for Petrus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ro'a kadidhi = lobang dinding ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ro'a kadidhi = lobang dinding ; patigi = intip ko lia</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa dhèu ae sèra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o, sina ma! Baku paleko!&gt;&gt;<bt>But, those many people responded, saying, &lt;&lt;No way! Don't tease/deceive us!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paleko = maen gila"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">paleko = maen gila</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa bhèni ne peka hari, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a! Èèna lii Petrus! Nuka li'u nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But this woman spoke again, saying, &lt;&lt;Really! It's Pete's voice! That's him outside.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka dhèu se'e lèka boe, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ele boe, dhèu nèi ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga, dhu mai madhenge Petrus.&gt;&gt;<bt>And these people didn't believe, saying, &lt;&lt;It's probably one of God2's messengers from heaven who has come to guard Pete.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Rèngu patule-pajuku taruu, te ngaa Petrus loe boe paroa, toke lasi bhoke hèb'a oka hia ne. Ropa ra bhoke rare, ka rèngu malaa, lula Petrus tare'a-re'a di.<bt>They kept arguing back-and-forth, but Petrus didn't stop calling, until they went and opened the fence door for him. When they opened it, they were agape, because it was really Petrus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèb'a boo-boo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hèb'a boo-boo</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Hèia na hia tadha dènge kacui-aai na, sèna ka rèngu mau-mau. Ka na lole tasa mera mia Ama Lamatua kalua eele nèngu nèti d'ara èmu bèdho. Hèia na pua si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lami lole lii ne'e aa'i-aa'i mi Yakobis dènge dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua leo sèra.&gt;&gt; Èle èèna ka, Petrus la'e asa era leo.<bt>Then he gave a sign with his hand, so that they would be quiet. And he narrated how God had gotten him out of prison. Then he told them, saying, &lt;&lt;Go tell all of this matter to Yakobis and the other servants/emissaries of the Lord.&gt;&gt; After that, Petrus went to another place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patule-pajuku = batola-bahela"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">patule-pajuku = batola-bahela</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Asa bèli mad'ae aae èèna, ropa sordad'u j'aga sèra ladhe, na, Petrus aad'o heka, ka rèngu ele ngangee dènge madha'u titu kèna, lula rèngu re'a boe ngaa dhu j'aj'i mi dedha rèngu.<bt>Early the next morning, when those guard soldiers saw that Petrus was no longer there, they lost their thinking and were terrified, because they did not know what would happen to them.</bt><v n="19" />Ropa Herodes tadèngi lii ne'e, ka na paredha si lasi tenge Petrus. Te ngaa rèdhi boe ne. Ka Herodes hia paredha ho parisa sordad'u j'aga sèra. Parisa rare, ka Herodes pua pamadhe aa'i sordad'u j'aga sèra.<bt>When Herodes heard this matter, he commanded them to go look for Petrus. But they didn't see him. And Herodes gave a command to examine/interrogate those guard soldiers. After examining them, Herodes ordered to kill all those guard soldiers.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Èle èèna ka, Herodes pakèd'i nèti propensi Yudea, ka la'e pea ètu kota Kaisarea.<bt>After that, Herodes left the province of Yudea, and went to stay in the city of Kaisarea.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mamadhe Herodes Agripa<bt>The death of Herodes Agripa</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu-dhèu nèti dua kota, èci ngara na Tirus, aa èci ngara na Sidon, biasa hèli nganga'a nèti rai dhèu aae Herodes. Te ngaa nèbhu aae le, dhèu aae musu dènge rèngu. Hèia ra padhue ho tenge j'ara padame dènge ne. Ka ra pili dhèu canau ho lasi paraga dènge Herodes. D'ai kota Kaisarea, rèngu pa'angalai dènge dhèu Herodes èci, ngara na Blastus. Nèngu ne, dhèu kapai ètu d'ara èmu dhèu aae. Rèngu pare'a dènge Blastus ho nèngu bhoke j'ara sèna ka rèngu paraga dènge dhèu aae Herodes.<bt>At that time, people from two cities, one named Tirus and one named Sidon, normally bought their food from the land/country of king Herodes. But already for awhile, that king had been enemies with them. Then they discussed to find a way to be at peace with him. And they chose a group of people to go meet with Herodes. Arriving in the city of Kaisarea, they made friends with one of Herodes' people, named Blastus. This one, was a leader inside the house of the king. They arranged with Blastus for him to open the way so they could meet with king Herodes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'angalai = berteman ; pare'a ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pa'angalai = berteman ; pare'a = ba'ator, barunding</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Hèia Herodes dhaa kahèi ho sèmi rare rèngu. Ka ra pare'a lod'o paraga. Lod'o èèna, rèngu tao tatao kapai. Herodes pake mèdha-papake dhèu aae, ka na madhèdi ètu kadera paredha na. Hèia na padhai lii dènge rèngu.<bt>Then Herodes also responded to receive them. And they mutually-agreed on a day to meet. That day, they made a big to-do [pretty literal]. Herodes wore the clothes of the king, and sat on the ruling seat. Then he spoke with them.</bt><v n="22" />Ropa rèngu tadèngi lii na, hèia dhèu se'e koa ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nanene ku lii na laa! Ne'e lii boe nèti dhèu rai-haha, te ngaa lii nèti dhèu dedha-liru!&gt;&gt;<bt>When they heard his voice, these people praised him, saying, &lt;&lt;Listen to his voice! This voice is not the voice of an earthly person, but rather a voice from a heavenly person!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="23" />Kaca'a laa, ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ca dhèu nèti sorga hia èi-papèd'a èci mi Herodes, lula nèngu sèmi lii koa rèngu, aa na seti eele Ama Lamatua. Ka kalati ra'e aa'i ngi'u Herodes, ka na madhe aapa.<bt>Suddenly, a messenger from God in heaven gave a disease to Herodes, because he accapted their praise, and he had elbowed out God. And worms ate up Herodes' body, and he died a cursed death.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu rai-dedha = dewa; |b23:|r èi-papèda"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhèu rai-dedha = dewa; <span class="Bold">23:</span> èi-papèda = penyakit ; seti eele = singkir buang ; madhe aapa = mati buruk (tidak wajar)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Dènge j'ara dhu j'aj'i sèra, dhèu palolo Lii Lolo Be'a Ama Lamatua d'ai asa mia-mia. Aa dhèu dhu madhutu J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus tabha ae kahèi.<bt>And with all those things that happened, people spread the Good News of God everywhere. And the people who followed the Life Way of the Lord Yesus also kept increasing.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ropa Barnabas dènge Saulus hia rare doi pa'oru nèti dhèu Antiokia mi dhèu Yerusalem, ka ra lèpa hari asa Antiokia. Rèngu gale rèti dènge ana ngèru èci, ngara na Yohanis. Ngara leo na, Markus.<bt>When Barnabas and Saulus had given the collected money from the people of Antiokia to the people of Yerusalem, then they returned back to Antiokia. They invited with them a young man name Yohanis. His other name was Markus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gale = ajak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">gale = ajak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu Antiokia pua Barnabas dènge Saulus<bt>The people of Antiokia send/commission Barnabas and Saulus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="13" />
      <v n="1" />Ètu kota Antiokia, dhèu ae parcaya le Lamatua Yesus. Lamatua pake pèri-pèri dhèu ho j'aj'i dhèu rèti lii padhai Na ètu èèna. Cahag'e hari, Na pake ho aj'a-nori dhèu. Rèngu se, nuka:<bt>In the city of Antiokia, many people already beleieved in the Lord Yesus. God2 used several people to be His spokespeople there. Some of the others He used to teach people. These were:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Barnabas,<bt>Barnabas,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Simeon, dhu ra biasa pangare ne, &lt;Mone Mèdhi&gt;,<bt>Simeon, who they usually called, &lt;Black/Dark Man&gt;,</bt><note reference="13:1a" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani peka na, &lt;Niger&gt;, sasoa na, &lt;mèdhi&gt;, do &lt;maroga&gt;.<bt>The Yunani language says, &lt;Niger&gt;, meaning, &lt;black&gt;, or &lt;dark&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lukius, nèti kota Kirene,<bt>Lukius, from the city of Kirene,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Menahem, dhu ra piara sama-sama dènge dhèu aae Herodes nèti ana iiki ka mai,<bt>Menahem, who they raised together with king Herodes since he was small,</bt><note reference="13:1b" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu aae Herodes ne, ra tadhe ne dènge ngara <span class="Italic">Herodes Antipas.</span> Nèngu ne ka dhu pamadhe Yohanis tuka sarani dhèu. Ama na, ngara na <span class="Italic">Herodes Kapai Risi.</span> Herodes Kapai Risi ne ka dhu hia paredha ho pamadhe ana iiki-ana iiki lod'o ina Maria nara iisi Lamatua Yesus ètu rae Betlehem. Dhèu aae Herodes leo ka dhu pamadhe Yakobis, ka dhu kalati ra'e aa'i toke madhe. Ra tadhe ne dènge ngara <span class="Italic">Herodes Agripa.</span><bt>This king Herodes, they knew by the name <span class="Italic">Herodes Antipas.</span> He is the one who killed Yohanis the Baptiser of People. His father, was named <span class="Italic">Herodes the Greatest.</span> This Herodes the Greatest is the one who gave the command to kill the small children when mother Maria gave birth to the Lord Yesus in the village of Betlehem. A different king Herodes in the one who killed Yakobis, the one who worms ate up until he died. They knew him by the name <span class="Italic">Herodes Agripa.</span></bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa dènge Saulus.<bt>and Saulus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ca lod'o, rèngu puasa, ka ra pakaboko ho manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua. Hèia Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Sasab'a Ja'a ae titu kèna. De hag'e mere Barnabas dènge Saulus, sèna ka rèngu pakako sasab'a Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time they were fasting (loan), and they gathered together to pray to God. Then the Holy Spirit of God2 spoke to them, &lt;&lt;I have much work. So set apart/select out Barnabas and Saulus, so that they will work what I give them to do.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ropa ra puasa dènge sabaj'a èle, hèia ra bane ai mi dedha Barnabas dènge Saulus, ho ra j'aj'i ana pua-paleha Lamatua. Èle èèna ka, ra pua rèngu dua ra ho lasi sab'a sasab'a-la'a Lamatua.<bt>When they had finished fasting and praying, then they placed their hands on Barnabas and Saulus, for them to be servants of the Lord. After that, they sent/commissioned the two of them to go work the work of the Lord.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Barnabas dènge Saulus lasi asa pulu Siprus<bt>Barnabas and Saulus go to the island of Siprus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4-5" />Ropa Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci pua Barnabas dènge Saulus lasi palème rai, ka ra dhuli uru asa kota èci ètu nebhe dhasi, ngara na Seleukia. Yohanis (dhu ngara leo na, Markus) la'e sama-sama dènge si. D'ai nèi ka, rèngu ca'e kapa asa pulu Siprus, ka ra puru ètu kota èci, ngara na Salamis. Ètu èèna, rèngu biasa maso asa d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi, ho aj'a-nori Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua mi dhèu ètu sèra.<bt>When the Holy Spirit of God2 ordered Barnabas and Saulus to go around to (other) lands, and stopped in first to a city at the edge of the ocean, named Seleukia. Yohanis (whose other name was Markus) went together with them. Arriving yonder, they got on (embarked) a ship (loan) to the island of Siprus, and they got off at a city named Salamis. In that place, they often entered into the house of worship of the Jahudi people to teach the Word/Sayings of God to those people.</bt></p>
    <fig path="maps\Bible\hksal-pf.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontal_position: right">Barnabas si lasi asa pulu Siprus<bt>They travel to Siprus island</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6-8" />Hèia rèngu lasi dhuli rae-rae, toke ra d'ai kota èci ètu suu haa pulu èèna, ngara na Pafos. Gubernur pea ètu kota èèna. Ngara gubernur èèna, Sergius Paulus. Nèngu ne, dhèu kahadhu mèu. Ropa na tadèngi Barnabas si d'ai d'ara kota, ka na hia dhèu lasi paroa si, te d'ara na neo nanene Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua.<bt>Then they went stopping in at various villages, until they arrived at a city on the west side of that island, named Pafos. The gubernur (loan) lived in that city. His name was Sergius Paulus. This governor was a clean-brained person (=wise, clear thinking). When he heard Barnabas (coll) had arrived in the city, he sent a person to go summon them, cause he wanted to hear the Word/Sayings of God2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dèlu-mèu = arif"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dèlu-mèu = arif</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa ètu era èèna, abhu dhèu Yahudi èci, ngara na Bar Yesus, (ngara leo na ètu d'ara lii Yunani, &lt;Elimas&gt;). Nèngu dhèu suagi. Na tema le kapod'e-kabèli dhèu, peka na, nèngu ne dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua. Aa na pa'angalai dènge gubernur. Ka ropa Barnabas si mai, na kakèj'i gubernur, sèna ka baku sèmi nare si. Aa na dadugu gubernur, sèna ka gubernur baku parcaya Yesus.<bt>But in that place there was a Jahudi person named Bar Jesus, (his other name in the Yunani language was &lt;Elimas&gt;). He was a *sorcerer. He often deceived people, saying he was God's spokesperson. And he was a friend/companion of the governor. And when Barnabas (coll) came, he poked/persuaded the governor so that he wouldn't receive them. And he was persuading the governor not to believe in Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tuka suagi dhèu = dhèu ka"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tuka suagi dhèu = dhèu ka uku dhèu ; pakapod'e = menipu ; kakèj'i = tusuk (bujuk)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02116b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Paulus nasa dènge tuka suagi dhèu<bt>Paulus scolds a sorcerer</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Te ngaa Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci hia koasa mi dedha Saulus (dhu ra paroa kahèi Paulus), ka na ladhe kaloo dhèu suagi ne, hèia na peka,<bt>But, the Holy Spirit of God2 gave power/authority to Saulus (who they also called Paulus), so he stared/glared at the sorcerer, and then said,</bt><v n="10" />&lt;&lt;Eeh, Elimas! Èu ne, ana nidhu! Tuka kapod'e-kabèli! Toke d'ai pèri lod'o hari èu kapod'e dhèu? Èu lab'a j'ara-j'ara dhu be'a. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i nge'a, na, èu madhutu dhèu aae nidhu. Tao ia ka sèmi èèna! Bhabhae ia ka j'ara mola Ama Lamatua!<bt>Ee, Elimas! You are the offspring of (an) evil spirit! You are a habitual deceiver! How long will you keep deceiving people! You oppose the ways of goodness. Because of that, we(exc) know that you follow the King of evil spirits. You must no longer do that! You must no longer prevent/block the straight/true way of God!</bt><v n="11" />De mu nanene! Nèbhu heka, Lamatua huku èu. Èèna na, èu bèdhu pèri-pèri lod'o!&gt;&gt;<bt>So, listen! Soon, God2 will punish you. That is, you will be blind in/for several days!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Baku ... ia ka = jangan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Baku ... ia ka = jangan lagi ; bhabhae = halangi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Musi madha èu èèna na j'aj'i"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Musi madha èu èèna na j'aj'i bèdhu.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa Paulus padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, dhèu èèna bèdhu dènge. Ka na kako kèpe leli, hia dhèu kadhèi ai, ho pakako ne.<bt>When Paulus had finished speaking, that person became blind immediately. And he walked groping aimlessly, letting people lead him by the hand, to guide him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kèpe leli = raba sambarang ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kèpe leli = raba sambarang ; kadhèi ai = gandeng tangan ; uku = suanggi pung tugas ; huku = punish</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa gubernur ladhe nèdhi unu na, aa na tadèngi Lii Holo-Nori Yesus nèti Barnabas si, ka na malaa-maloha, aa na parcaya Yesus.<bt>When the governor saw for himself, and he heard the Word of Yesus from Barnabas (coll), and was amazed (doublet), and he beleieved Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rèngu rèti Lii Lolo Be'a asa kota Antiokia leo, ètu propensi Pisidia<bt>They take the Good News to the other city of Antiokia, in the province of Pisidia</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Nèti kota Pafos ètu pulu Siprus, Paulus si ca'e kapa, pakèd'i asa kota Perga ètu propensi Pamfilia. Ropa ra puru nèti dedha kapa, Yohanis Markus tèke eele rèngu, ka lèpa asa Yerusalem.<bt>from the city of Pafos on the island of Siprus, Paulus (coll) embarked on a ship, leaving for the city of Perga, in the province of Pamfilia. When they disembarked from the ship, Yohanis Markus left them, and returned to Yerusalem.</bt><v n="14" />Nèti Perga, rèngu kako haga lasi asa kota Antiokia ètu propensi Pisidia.<bt>From Perga, they went by foot going to the city of Antiokia in the province of Pisidia.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Rèngu d'ai era èèna, lèke lod'o a'oro sasab'a dhèu Yahudi. Ka rèngu madhutu sabaj'a ètu èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi.<bt>They arrived in that place, on the Jahudi people's day of stopping work. And they went to pray in the Jahudi people's house of worship.</bt><v n="15" />Lod'o èèna, ra baca ètu sasuri Musa, dènge sasuri dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua dhu leo kahèi. Èle èèna ka, ama-ama èmu sabaj'a èèna, manèngi Paulus si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama! Ladhe miu dènge lii haholo ho pa'èra d'ara ji'i, na, ji'i manèngi sèna ka miu peka laa.&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, they read in the writings of Grandpa Musa, and also writings of other spokespeople of God2. After that, the leaders of that house of worship2 asked Paulus (coll) saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers! If you(pl) have a advice to strengthen our insides, we ask that you tell us.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lii nanori = advice"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lii nanori = advice</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus padhai lii mi dhèu Yahudi ètu Antiokia [\s2]<bt>Paulus speaks to the Yahudi people in Antiokia [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Hèia Paulus kako asa madha la'e. Ka na hia tadha dènge kacui-aai na, sèna ka rèngu mau-mau. Èle èèna ka, na padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;A'ari dhèu Isra'el ti! Dènge ina-ama dhèu leo dhu maso agama Yahudi, lula d'ara miu d'èi padètu dènge Ama Lamatua dhèu Isra'el. De ja'a manèngi sèna ka miu nanene paie lii padhai ja'a.<bt>Then Paulus went to the front. And he gave a sign with his hand so that they would be quiet. After that, he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Older-younger siblings of the people of Isra'el! And mother-fathers [= + respect] of other people who have entered the Jahudi religion, because your insides want to be close to the God of the people of Isra'el. I ask that you listen well to what I say.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ama Lamatua hag'e nare le bèi-baki èdhi dhèu Isra'el nèti uru ka mai. Lod'o rèngu pea ètu rai Masir, kabarai dhèu, Lamatua hia rèngu mamuri hua iia. Ana-èpu rèngu tabha ae ètu era èèna. Limuri mai, ka Lamatua pake koasa kapai Na, ho Na kalua eele rèngu nèti rai Masir.<bt>God set apart our(inc) ancestors of Isra'el from long ago. When they were living in the land of Masir (=Egypt), in other people's country, God2 gave them prosperous life. Their descendants increased in number in that place. Eventually God2 used His great power/authority, to get them out from the land of Masir.</bt><note reference="13:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 1:7, 12:51</note><v n="18" />Èle èèna ka, rèngu mamuri pidha-pidha ètu d'ara mamoo toke d'ai èpa nguru tèu. Masi ka rèngu kètu hadhu, te ngaa Lamatua lere si dènge d'ara dhu taleo.<bt>After that, they lived moving-moving (=nomadically) in an empty place (wilderness for 40 years. Even though they were rock-headed, God2 accompanied them with wide (=patient) insides.</bt><note reference="13:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 14:34, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 1:31</note><v n="19" />Èle èèna ka, Lamatua palaho aa'i pidhu suku ètu rai Kana'an. Ka Na pabagi rai rèngu mi bèi-baki èdhi ho j'aj'i rai pusaka ra.<bt>After that, God2 entirely destroyed seven societies from tha land of Kanaan. And He divided up their land to our ancestors to be the land of their inheritance (loan).</bt><note reference="13:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 7:1, Yosua 14:1</note><v n="20" />Bèi-baki èdhi mamuri sèmi èèna toke d'ai 450 (èpa ngasu lèmi nguru) tèu.<bt>Our ancestors lived like that for 450 years.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soda-mole = damai-sejahtera (&lt;Rote --&gt; Ndao)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">soda-mole = damai-sejahtera (&lt;Rote --&gt; Ndao) ; mamuri hua iia = prosperity; <span class="Bold">18:</span> ka'uu-kamoke = menggerutu, bersungut-sungut ; dara madhera = patiently ; ngangee madhera = patiently ; ngengee bab'a = pikiran pendek, sonde timbang bam-banya, cepat marah ; taleo ; lari</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Ama Lamatua padhèdi dhèu pama'ète lii langu, sèna ka paj'uj'u j'ara hia si, toke d'ai Na padhèdi hia si dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua èci, ngara na Samuel.<bt>And God appointed judges, so that they could show the way for them, until He appointed for them a spokesperson named Samue.</bt><note reference="13:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Tuka Pama'ète Lii Langu2:16, 1 Samuel 3:20</note><v n="21" />Lod'o Samuel j'aj'i dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua, bèi-baki èdhi neo abhu dhèu aae. Ka Lamatua padhèdi Saul, ana Kis, nèti suku Benyamin. Saul j'aj'i dhèu aae d'ai èpa nguru tèu.<bt>When Samue was God2's spokesperson, our ancestors wanted their own king. And God2 elevated Saul, and offspring of Kis, from the tribe of Benyamin. Saul was king for 40 years.</bt><note reference="13:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Samuel 8:5, 10:21</note><v n="22" />Èle èèna ka, Lamatua gao eele Saul. Ka Na padhèdi Daud, ana Isai, ho j'aj'i dhèu aae hiu. Lamatua ne'a tare'a d'ara Daud, ka Na peka na, &lt;Daud, ana Isai ne, lèke d'ara Ja'a. Limuri mai, tatu nèngu mamuri madhutu dad'èi Ja'a aa'i-aa'i.&gt;<bt>After that, God2 put Saul down. And He elevated Daud, the offspring of isai, to be a new king. God2 truly knew Daud's insides, and He said, &lt;Daud, the offspring of Isai, fits-well with My insides. He will certainly do according to all My will.&gt;</bt><note reference="13:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Samuel 13:14, 16:12, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 89:20</note><v n="23" />Lod'o èèna, Lamatua moa tèke le, ho Na hag'e nare ana-èpu Daud èci, sèna ka Na patabuli eele dhèu Isra'el nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra. Ja'a peka mi miu, ana-èpu Daud dhu Lamatua moa tèke èèna, nuka Yesus.&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, God2 promised to send a descendant of Daud so that He would give life/salvation/deliverance to the people of Isra'el. I tell you(pl) here, the descendant of Daud that God2 promised then, that is Yesus.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="padhèdi = lantik, (dudukkan) ; Ant"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">padhèdi = lantik, (dudukkan) ; Ant = gao eele = lepas buang (cabut dari kedudukan)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus peka na, Yesus èèna, Dhèu dhu Lamatua pajaji le [\s2]</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Paulus tuhu hari lii padhai na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lod'o Lamatua Yesus pakako mèka sab'a Na, abhu dhèu èci ngara na Yohanis, dhu la'e lole dènge dhèu Isra'el, sèna ka rèngu ele-ho'a nèti sasala-sasigo rèngu. Na peka kahèi, na, rèngu hud'i sarani ku, ho j'aj'i mi tadha, na, rèngu pabe'a le dènge Lamatua.<bt>When the Lord Yesus had not yet done/begun to work, there was a person named Yohanis, who went telling the people of Isra'el, so that they stopped/repented of their wrongs (doublet). He also said they must be baptised to be a sign that they were recip-good with God2.</bt><note reference="13:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Markus 1:4, Lukas 3:3</note><v n="25" />Te ngaa lod'o sasab'a Yohanis oe èle, na peka mi dhèu ae, aku nèngu na, &lt;Baku pangee, na, ja'a ne Dhèu dhu Lamatua moa nèti uru ka mai. Ngee paie! Miu hud'i mate hari ku dhèu èci, dhu mai limuri. Nèngu kapai risi nèti ja'a. Ja'a haha d'ai seli. De j'aj'i ana pua-paleha nèngu kahèi, ja'a nia boe.&gt;<bt>But when Yohanis' work was almost finished, he told those people, saying, &lt;&lt;Don't think that I here and the Person who God2 promised from long ago. Think carefully! You must wait further for another person who will come later. He is greater than I. I am very low/humble. To be even his servant, is not appropriate.</bt><note reference="13:25" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani dhu uru-uru sèra, suri peka na, &lt;pacud'u ho lècu dhari salapa Na kahèi, ja'a nia boe.&gt; Sasoa na, ladhe pasoro dènge Lamatua Yesus, Yohanis ne dhèu haha seli, de masi ka j'aj'i ana pua-paleha nèti Lamatua Yesus, nia boe sa hèi. Baca kahèi ètu Mateos 3:11, Markus 1:7, Lukas 3:16, Yohanis 1:20, 27</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />A'ari aa'i-aa'i ti! Miu dhu ana-èpu Abraham, aa miu dhèu leo, dhu neo padètu dènge Lamatua. Mi nanene ku ja'a! Ama Lamatua peka le j'ara ne dènge èdhi, sèna ka èdhi te'a j'ara mamuri Na. Nèngu patabuli èdhi nèti koasa sasala-sasigo èdhi.<bt>All you older-younger siblings! You(pl) who are the descendants of Abraham, and you other people, who want to be close to God2. Listen to me! God has told this matter to us(inc), so that we know His way of life. He is the one who frees us from our wrongs (doublet).</bt><v n="27" />Nèti uru ka mai, Ama Lamatua pake le dhèu rèti lii padhai Na, ho suri lula-nèti Dhèu dhu Lamatua moa neo hia mai. Te ama-ama agama èdhi, dènge dhèu leo ètu Yerusalem sèra baca pahari-pahari le, ngaa dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua suri tèke sèra. D'ai lod'o a'oro sasab'a, ra maso asa d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i, ho ra baca ètu d'ara sasuri Lamatua. Te ngaa rèngu re'a boe Dhèu dhu Lamatua paj'uj'u mema èèna, nuka Yesus. Ka ra tenge j'ara ho pamadhe Ne. Te ngaa tatao rèngu sèra kahèi, lèke nuka sèmi dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua sèra suri tèke le.<bt>From long ago, God used His spokespeople to write about the Person who God2 promised to send. And our religious leaders, and other people in Yeruslaem, keep reading (repeatedly) that which God2's spokespeople have written. On the days of rest (stopping work) they enter into the houses of worship to read in God2's writings. But, they do not know the Person who God2 designated beforehand, that is Yesus. And they looked for a way to kill Him. But, what they did also matched what God2's spokespeople had written.</bt><v n="28" />Ra tenge j'ara, neo pamanahu Yesus. Te ngaa rèngu abhu boe sasala Na. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa rèngu kakèj'i gubernur Pilatus ho pamadhe Ne.<bt>They fabricated issues/disputes wanting to bring down Yesus. But, they didn't encounter wrong in Him. Nevertheless, they persuaded governor Pilatus to kill Him.</bt><note reference="13:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 27:22-23, Markus 15:13-14, Lukas 23:21-23, Yohanis 19:15</note><v n="29" />Ka gubernur sèmi nare lii rèngu, hèia ra paku pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Te ngaa tatao rèngu sèra kahèi, lèke sèmi dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua sèra suri tèke le. Hèia ra papuru ngi'u aae Yesus nèti aj'u palolo-palèbha, ka nedhe rèti tao asa d'ara ro'a.<bt>And the governor accepted their words, then they nailed Him to death on the crossed wood. But those deeds of theirs also matched what God2's spokespeople had written. Then they lowered Yesus' corpse from the crossed wood, and took it to place in inside a hole/grave</bt><note reference="13:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 27:57-61, Markus 15:42-47, Lukas 23:50-56, Yohanis 19:38-42</note><v n="30" />Te ngaa Ama Lamatua pake koasa Na, ka pamamuri hari Yesus.<bt>But God used His power, and brought Yesus back to life.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tenge lii = cari parkara, cari-cari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tenge lii = cari parkara, cari-cari hal, cari alasan ; pasa sasii = pasang jerat; <span class="Bold">29:</span> palèke = bacocok</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Te ngaa aa'i-aa'i se palèke sama-sèmi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Te ngaa aa'i-aa'i se palèke sama-sèmi dhu dhèu padhai lii sèra suri tèke le.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Lod'o Yesus mamuri hari, Na pad'elo iisi Na pèri-pèri hari mi dhèu ae. Dhèu sèra nuka dhu mai sama-sama dènge Ne nèti propensi Galilea asa kota Yerusalem. Rèngu se ka lèpa limuri na, j'aj'i sakasii mi dhèu Isra'el.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus was alive again, He revealed Himself several times to various people. Those people were the ones who had come together with Him from the province of Galilea to the city of Yerusalem. These are the ones who are now witnesses (loan) to the people of Isra'el.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palere dènge = sama-sama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">palere dènge = sama-sama</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 1:3</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus peka na, Lamatua pake dhèu nèti lii padhai Na ho suri mema lula-nèti Yesus [\s2]</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32-33" />Paulus tuhu hari lii padhai na, peka na, &lt;&lt;De sèmi ne'e! Ji'i dua mi dènge Barnabas, mai nèti era kaj'èu ho lole dènge miu, sèna ka miu me'a ngaa dhu Lamatua moa mi bèi-baki èdhi sèra, limuri ne j'aj'i aa'i le. Lamatua pamamuri hari le Yesus nèti mamadhe Na. Ètu sasuri Lii Sod'a Koa-kio nomer dua, Lamatua pake dhèu ho suri lula-nèti Yesus, Dhèu dhu Na moa tèke ho Na mai. Na suri, peka na:<bt>So it's like this! The two of us(exc), (me) with Barnabas), came from far away to tell you(pl) so that you would know that what God2 promised to our ancestors, has now all happened. God2 brought Yesus back to life. In the writings of Masmur (loan-psalms) number two, God2 used a person to write about Yesus, the Person whom He promised to send. He wrote, that:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Èu ne'e, Ana Ja'a,<bt>&lt;You(sg) here, are My Offspring,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Doe ne'e, Ja'a ded'e Èu ho mèd'u paredha.&gt;<bt>At this time, I elevate you to hold power/rule.&gt; [From context of Psalm 2.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ji'i dua mi dènge Barnabas, ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Ji'i dua mi dènge Barnabas, = the two of us, me and B.</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 2:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Nèti uru èèna ka, Ama Lamatua moa le, peka na, Nèngu neo pamamuri hari Dhèu dhu Na moa tèke ho Na mai. Aa Dhèu èèna, madhe heka. Nèti èèna ka, Lamatua pake le dhèu nèti lii padhai Na ho na suri, peka na,<bt>From before, God had promised that He would bring back to life the Person that He promised to send. And that Person not die again. Because of that, God2 used His spokesperson to write, that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Nèti uru ka mai, Ja'a èki lii padhadha dènge dhèu aae Daud, sèna ka Ja'a hia ne berkat.<bt>&lt;From long ago, I bound a promise with King Daud, so that I would give him a blessing (loan).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">De limuri ne, Ja'a neo pa'èki dènge èu, lii padhadha èèna kahèi, lula èu ne, ana-èpu Daud.&gt;<bt>So, now, I want to bind with you(sg), that promise also, because you here, are the descendant of Daud.&gt;</bt><note reference="13:34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 55:3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Aa Lii Sod'a Koa-kio leo, peka na,<bt>And another praise in Masmur says,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="abhu lii = muncul parkara (dari"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">abhu lii = muncul parkara (dari orang maen serong)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Lamatua, Èu tèke eele boe ngi'u aae Dhèu Mola-Mèci Èu,<bt>&lt;You, Lord, do not abandon the corpse of Your Holy Person to decay inside His hole/grave!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laho = roe eele, ancor ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">laho = roe eele, ancor ; ele iie = decay (mayat)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ho ele iie ètu d'ara ro'a Na!&gt;<note reference="13:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 16:10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36-37" />Dhu lèke sèmi ne'e ka: Lii Sod'a Koa-kio ne'e, peka boe dhoka Daud di! Èdhi te'a sèmi èèna, lula dhèu aae Daud tao le j'ara be'a ae hia kabarai na, toke na madhe. Ropa na madhe, ka ra padhane ne. Ngi'u aae na ele iie le. De èdhi te'a, na, Lii Sod'a Koa-kio èèna, peka boe dhoka Daud di, te ngaa dhèu leo kahèi. Ladhe èèna na Dhèu dhu Na paj'uj'u èèna madhe, pe Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne. Nèti èèna ka, ngi'u aae Na ele iie boe ciki sa.<bt>What is correct is like this: this Masmur does not only speak about Daud! We(inc) know that, because King Daud did many good things for his people/society, until he died. When he died, they buried him. His corpse has decayed. So we know that this Masmur, does not only speak about Daud, but about another person also. The person that He designated when later He died, God brought Him back to life. Because of that, His corpse did not decay even a little.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38-39" />De a'ari, nanene paie! Dhèu èèna, nuka Yesus! Ladhe èdhi parcaya Ne, heka Na dui sasala-sasigo èdhi sèra, dhu madhutu iia-iia na, èdhi ka dhu dui. Dènge j'ara ne'e, Ama Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo èdhi. Te ngaa èdhi te'a le, masi ka èdhi madhutu atora ad'a Musa aa'i-aa'i ra, èèna d'ai mèka ho pamola èdhi ètu madha Lamatua.<bt>So, elder-younger siblings, listen well! That Person is Yesus! If/when we believe in Him, only then does He shoulder-carry our(inc) wrongs, which according to what is right, we are the ones who must bear (them). In this way, God wipes away our(inc) wrongs. But, we know that even though we follow all the adat regulations of Grandpa Musa, that is not able to make us right in the eyes of God2.</bt><v n="40-41" />Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i pangee paie. Mage dhoka ngaa dhu dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua peka uru sèra, lèka miu. Ra suri le, peka na,<bt>Because of that, you(pl) must think carefully. May it not be what God2's spokespeople spoke long ago, matches you(pl). They wrote that,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhu madhutu iia na, = yang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhu madhutu iia na, = yang semestinya, ikut yg wajar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Tuka lalangu dhèu, mate unu miu!<bt>&lt;You habitual slanderer/mocker people, wait for yours [language of threat or curse]!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="saseo = bahasa sumpah ; lalangu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">saseo = bahasa sumpah ; lalangu ; mate unu miu = tunggu bosong pung bagian</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula Ja'a, Ama Lamatua, tao j'ara-j'ara dhu pamalaa dhèu.<bt>Because I, God, have doen various sorts of things that amaze people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te ngaa limuri mai, mate unu miu! Èèna na, miu madhe aapa!<bt>But later, you wait for yours! [threat] Eventually you die accursedly!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhe he'o one-one. (mati dgn lidah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">madhe he'o one-one. (mati dgn lidah keluar)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a tao j'ara èci,</p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa miu sèmi mere boe.<bt>I do one thing, but you don't accept it.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Masi ka dhèu pasaraa le,</p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa miu me'a boe.<bt>Even though people have explained it, you nevertheless do not understand.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pataraa &gt; pasaraa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pataraa &gt; pasaraa</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Be'a risi miu ngee paie, sèna ka miu bisa malaa kahèi tatao Lamatua!&gt;<bt>It would be better for you to think carefully, so that you can be amazed at the work/deeds of God2!&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakabua Ant lalangu ; mangingi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pakabua Ant lalangu ; mangingi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Mage dhoka miu soro kabodho mi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Mage dhoka miu soro kabodho mi Lamatua, hia miu tadhe heka Ne.&gt;</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:41" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Habakuk 1:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De a'ari sèra! Pangee paie ngaa dhu ja'a lole ne. Baku core eele ngaa dhu miu tadèngi le. Miu baku sama sèmi tuka lalangu dhèu. D'ai sange ne'e ka, lii padhai ja'a. Makasi!&gt;&gt;<bt>So, elder-younger siblings here! Think carefully what it is that I just told you. Don't throw away what you have heard. May it not be that you are just like those slander/scoffers. That's the limit of what I have to say. Thanks!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Padhai lii nare, hèia Paulus dènge Barnabas kèd'i titu neo kalua nèti èmu manèngi-mangaj'i èèna. Ka dhèu ètu sèra manèngi rèngu lèpa migu mai nèi, ho lole pamèu ngaa dhu ra lole deo na.<bt>When he finished speaking, then Paulus and Barnabas stood up to go out from that house of worship. And the people there asked them to return again the next week, so they could further explain/clarify what they had just said.</bt><v n="43" />Ropa ra kalua nèti d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i èèna, dhèu ae ètu èèna lasi madhutu Paulus dènge Barnabas. Ka dua ra holo si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi te'a, na, Lamatua d'ara be'a d'ai seli mi dedha èdhi. De miu hud'i madhutu taruu Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>When they went out from that house of worship, many people there went following Paulus and Barnabas. And the two of them advised them, saying, &lt;&lt;We(inc) know that God2 has very good insides toward us. So you must continue to follow/obey Him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kèpe pa'èra-èra"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kèpe pa'èra-èra</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama-ama dhèu Yahudi tule eele Paulus si<bt>The leaders of the Jahudi people reject Paulus (coll)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />D'ara migu mai nèi, lèke lod'o a'oro sasab'a dhèu Yahudi, dhèu nèti d'ara kota èèna oe mai aa'i ho ra neo nanene Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua.<bt>The next week, on the Jahudi people's day of rest, almost everyone in that city came wanting to listen to the Words/Saying of God2.</bt><v n="45" />Te ngaa ropa ama-ama dhèu Yahudi re'a, na, dhèu ae mai nanene lii padhai lii Paulus si, ka rèngu tèka d'ara. Hèia ropa Paulus padhai lii, rèngu pahaka-palab'a dènge padhai lii pamanahu ne.<bt>But, when the leaders of the Jahudi people knew that many people came to listen to what Paulus (coll) had to say, their insides were jealous. And when Paulus spoke they opposed heatedly with words to make him fall.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Te ngaa Paulus si hari boe, aa ra padhai lii pa'abhe heka, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mema tare'a Ama Lamatua bhoke uru j'ara hia èdhi dhèu Yahudi, aa Na pangèd'u èdhi Lii Lolo Be'a. Èèna na lèke! Te ngaa miu sèmi mere boe. Nèti èèna ka, miu nia boe abhu mamuri taruu dènge Ama Lamatua. De limuri ne, ji'i neo ngèti Lii Lolo Be'a ne asa dhèu rai-rai leo sèra, lula miu dhèu Yahudi tule eele ne.<bt>But Paulus (coll) did not budge, and they spoke openly/boldly, saying, &lt;&lt;It is really true that God opened the way previously for us(inc) Jahudi people, and he entrusted the Good News to us. That was right/appropriate! But you didn't accept it. Because of that, you(pl) do not get life/salvation/deliverance continually with God. So, now, we(exc) want to take this Good News to people of other lands/countries, because you Jahudi people reject it.</bt><v n="47" />Te Lamatua pua le ji'i, sama sèmi dhu Yesaya suri tèke, peka na,<bt>Because God2 has sent/commissioned us(exc), just like Grandpa Yesaya wrote, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahaka = baku pukul ; pahaka-palab'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pahaka = baku pukul ; pahaka-palab'a = argue; <span class="Bold">46:</span> hari boe = sonde bergeser ; ra padhai lii pa'abhe heka = sonde pele-pele ; pangèd'u = kasi pegang, entrusted, percayakan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Ja'a ded'e le miu ho j'aj'i sama sèmi labhu, ho mèti saraa mi dedha dhèu rai-rai leo sèra, dhu dhèu Yahudi boe,<bt>&lt;I have lifted you to be like a lamp, to take/bring light to the people of other lands, who are not Jahudi people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sena ka miu tao paheo j'ara dhu mai asa Ja'a,<bt>so that you(pl) can light the path coming to Me,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tao pasaraa = bekin tarang ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tao pasaraa = bekin tarang ; heo = manyala ; paheo = bekin tarang jalan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho Ja'a patalale si nèti koasa sasala-sasigo rèngu.<bt>so that I can free them from their wrongs (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">De miu hud'i pad'elo j'ara èèna ètu rai-haha ne, nèti suu èci toke d'ai suu leo la'e!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So you must reveal that way to this world, from one corner on to other corners!&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Grammar: Verb LocNP + la'e @@"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Grammar: Verb LocNP + la'e @@</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:47" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 42:6, 49:6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Ropa dhèu leo dhu dhèu Yahudi boe sèra tadèngi lii ne'e, rèngu karej'e titu kèna. Hèia ra koa-kio Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Koa-kio kolongara Lamatua! Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua be'a d'ai seli!&gt;&gt; Aa ètu èèna, abhu dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua pili nare le ho ra mamuri taruu dènge Ne. Ka ra parcaya aa'i-aa'i ra mi Lamatua Yesus.<bt>When the other people who were not Jahudi people heard these words, they were overjoyed. Then they praised God, saying, &lt;&lt;Praise the name/reputation of God2! The Word of God is very good!&gt;&gt; And at that place, there were people whom God had already chosen for them to live continually with Him. And they all believed in the Lord Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Ka dhèu palolo lème Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua ne asa rai aa'i-aa'i.<bt>And this Word of God, people told it all over that land/country.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Ètu d'ara kota èèna, abhu dhèu kapai, bhèni-mone. Cahag'e d'èi padètu Lamatua. Te ngaa ama-ama dhèu Yahudi sèra mai dadugu-rariu dhèu kapai sèra. Hèia rèngu babège eele Paulus dènge Barnabas nèti rai rèngu.<bt>In that city, there were important people, female-male. Some wanted to be close to God2. But, the leaders of the Jahudi people came inciting those important people. Then they evicted Paulus and Barnabas from their land.</bt><v n="51" />Lod'o dua ra kalua nèti d'ara kota èèna, ka ra caro eele ahu nèti haga ra, ho j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, dhèu-dhèu ètu d'ara kota èèna ro'o boe nanene rèngu dua ra. Èle èèna ka, dua ra kabèli kabodho ho tèke eele kota èèna, lasi asa kota Ikonium.<bt>When the two of them went out from that city, they wiped/brushed off the dust from their feet, to be a sign saying, people in that city didn't want to listen to the two of them. After that, the two of them turned their backs and left that city behind, going to the city of Ikonium.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhèni-bhèni dhu re madha, dhu parcaya"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">bhèni-bhèni dhu re madha, dhu parcaya Ama Lamatua, ka dènge dhèu kapai-dhèu kapai ètu dara kota èèna, paj'èra Paulus dènge Barnabas, aa babège eele dua ra.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabèli = bale ; tabhèli ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kabèli = bale ; tabhèli = licin</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:51" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:14, Markus 6:11, Lukas 9:5, 10:11</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Te ngaa dhèu parcaya Lamatua Yesus ètu kota Antiokia sèra, d'ara ra karej'e, lula Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci pa'èra d'ara rèngu.<bt>But, those people who believed in the Lord Yesus in the city of Antiokia, their insides were happy, because the Holy Spirit of God2 strengthened their insides.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus dènge Barnabas ètu kota Ikonium<bt>Paulus and Barnabas in the city of Ikonium</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="14" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o Paulus dènge Barnabas d'ai kota Ikonium, ka lasi asa d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi. Ètu èèna, dua ra lole aa'i mèu-mèu Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua. Ka dhèu Yahudi dènge dhèu rai leo, ae ka dhu parcaya Lamatua Yesus.<bt>When Paulus and Barnabas arrived in the city of Ikonium, they went into the Jahudi people's house of worship. There, the two of the fully explained the Word of God. And the Jahudi people and people from other lands, many beleived in the Lord Yesus.</bt><v n="2" />Te ngaa ètu èèna, abhu kahèi pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi dhu kèpe pa'èra atora agama rèngu. Ka rèngu sèmi rare boe lii padhai lii Paulus si. Rèngu kakèj'i dhèu leo, sèna ka ra d'èi boe dènge dhèu dhu parcaya Yesus sèra.<bt>But there there were also several Jahudi people who held firmly to their religious regulations. And they did not accept what Paulus (coll) had to say. They persuaded other people, so that they didn't like those people who believed in Yesus.</bt><v n="3" />Te ngaa Paulus si madha'u boe. Dua ra peka-padhai taruu Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus, mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra. Ra peka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lamatua Yesus sue dhèu aa'i-aa'i.&gt;&gt; Lamatua hia Paulus si koasa kahèi, ho ra tao tadha-tadha malaa, sèna ka dhèu ae re'a Lamatua ka dhu pua rèngu.<bt>But, Paulus (coll) were not afraid. The two of them continued to explain the Good News of the Lord Yesus, to all those people. They spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;The Lord Yesus loves/pities all people.&gt;&gt; God2 also gave Paulus (coll) power/authority so they did various amazing signs, so that many people there knew that God2 is the one who sent them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lod'o èèna, Paulus si pea nèbhu ètu d'ara kota èèna.<bt>At that time, Paulus (coll) stayed for awhile in that city.</bt><v n="4" />Ètu èèna, abhu dua kaboko dhèu. Cahag'e madhutu dhèu Yahudi dhu kèpe pa'èra atora agama rèngu. Aa cahag'e hari madhutu dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua. Ka ra patao-palaha.<bt>There, there were two groups of people. Some followed the Jahudi people who held firmly to their religious regulations. And some others followed the servant/emissaries of God2. And they argued/disagreed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patao-palaha = bakanjar, berselisih"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">patao-palaha = bakanjar, berselisih</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia dhèu Yahudi dhu kèpe pa'èra atora agama rèngu pare'a lii dènge dhèu leo dènge ama-ama rèngu, ho neo paj'èra dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua. Aa rèngu neo tabhie Paulus si.<bt>Then the Jahudi people who held firmly to their religious regulations came to an agreement with other people and their leaders, to want to persecute the servants/emissaries of the Lord. And they wanted to stone Paulus (coll).</bt><v n="6" />Te ngaa dhèu peka dènge Paulus si, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu neo tao aapa mi miu.&gt;&gt; Nèti èèna ka, Paulus si rai lasi palu'u iisi asa propensi Likonia, ètu kota Listra, dènge kota Derbe, dènge rae-rae dhu padètu ètu kota sèra.<bt>But, people told Paulus (coll), saying, &lt;&lt;People want to do evil to you(pl).&gt;&gt; Because of that, Paulus (coll) fled to protect/hide themselves to the province of Likonia, to the city of Listra, and the city of Derbe, and villages near those cities.</bt><v n="7" />Ètu era-era se'e, rèngu lole Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus.<bt>In these places, they told the Good News of the Lord Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pèci = tabhie = lempar (dgn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pèci = tabhie = lempar (dgn batu) tabhia implies over and over (angat lempar ulang kali); <span class="Bold">6:</span> hag'e = bisik kasi tau dgn diam-diam ; (palidhu iisi = melindung diri, selamatkan diri ; UNS's say there is no word like this!!@@); palu'u iisi = sembunyi ; pasuru iisi = berlindung (dari hujan)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="maps\Bible\HkDerbe.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Kakako nèti kota Perga asa kota Derbe<bt>The trip from the city of Perga to the city of Derbe</bt></fig>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus si ètu kota Listra dènge kota Derbe<bt>Paulus (coll) in the city of Listra and the city of Derbe</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />D'ai kota Listra, Paulus dènge Barnabas paraga dènge mone èci, dhu karuku nèti ina na nara iisi ne. Dhèu ne'e, kako nèdhi mèka.<bt>Arriving in the city of Listra, Paulus and Barnabas met with a young man, who was crippled from/since his mother giving birth to him. This man, had never walked.</bt><v n="9" />Nèngu madhèdi nanene lii lole Paulus. Ka Paulus ladhe patae ne, ka pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Parcaya nèngu mi Ama Lamatua ka dhu bisa pa'èle papèd'a na!&gt;&gt;<bt>They sat listening to what Paulus was saying. And Paulus looked around at him intently, and thought, &lt;&lt;A person believing God2 like this one, can be healed of his sickness (covers crippled)!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="10" />Ka Paulus lii dènge ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Kèd'i titu ka!&gt;&gt; Ropa na tadèngi, hèia dhèu ne kèd'i titu dènge, ka kako la'e-mai.<bt>And Paulus spoke to him, saying, &lt;&lt;Stand up!&gt;&gt; When he heard that, this person stood up immediately and walked back-and-forth (going-coming).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Grammar @@ : some clauses end"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Grammar @@ : some clauses end in la'e or mai after the Object or Locative complement, but many weeded out of the translation.; <span class="Bold">9:</span> Lalèka; <span class="Bold">10:</span> lii = (v) bersuara</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02118b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Paulus pa'èle dhèu karuku<bt>Paulus heals a crippled person</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa dhèu sèra rèdhi Paulus tao sèmi èèna, ka rèngu malaa-maloha. Ka ra padhai lii dènge lii Likonia, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mi nanene ku laa! Dhèu dua se, dhèu dedha-liru, te ngaa puru mai dènge rupa dhèu rai-haha!&gt;&gt;<bt>When those people saw Paulus do like that, they were agape. And they spoke in the Likonia language, saying, &lt;&lt;Listen up! These two people are heavenly people, but they have come down here in the form of earthly people!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="12" />Rèngu peka sèmi èèna, lula rèngu ngee, na, Barnabas èèna nuka dhèu dedha-liru rèngu, ngara na Seus. Aa Paulus, dhu tuka padhai lii, nuka dhèu dedha-liru rèngu, ngara na Hermes.<bt>They spoke like that, because they thought that Barnabas was their heavenly person named Seus. And Paulus who was the spokesperson, was their heavenly person named Hermes.</bt><note reference="14:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Hermes èèna, tuka padhai lii ètu talora dewa Roma sèra.<bt>That Hermes was a messenger/spokesperson among the gods (loan).</bt></note><v n="13" />Ètu hèb'a tedhe li'u kota, abhu èmu era sogo-tagu Seus. Ropa rèdhi Paulus si, ka tuka j'aga èmu sogo-tagu Seus èci nèti bunga dènge sapi mone aae, ho mai sogo-tagu Paulus dènge Barnabas. Dhèu ae mai kahèi ho neo sogo-tagu dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus sèra.<bt>At the gate of the stone-wall outside the city, there was a house where to traditionally-worship that Seus. When they saw Paulus (coll) a watchkeeper of the traditional house of worship of Seus brought flowers, and a large bull, to come traditionally-worship Paulus and Barnabas. Many people also came wanting to worship those servant/emissaries of the Lord Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu rai-dedha = dewa; |b13:|r tedhe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhèu rai-dedha = dewa; <span class="Bold">13:</span> tedhe = pagar batu ; èmu pae'a nidhu = rumah songgo, rumah kasi makan setan ; sogo-tago = ; hela aj'u = bunga pohon</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02119b.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none">Dhèu neo sogo-tagu Paulus si<bt>People want to traditional.worship Paulus (coll)</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ropa Paulus si re'a, na, dhèu sèra mai ho neo sogo-tagu rèngu, ka ra kai si. Ka dua ra rai lasi asa talora dhèu ae sèra, hèia ra ciu mae kodho ètu ngi'u ra. Tatao èèna j'aj'i tadha, na, rèngu dua ra d'èi boe dhèu sogo-tagu rèngu. Hèia dua ra kai si, peka na,<bt>When Paulus (coll) knew that those people came wanting to traditionally-worship them, they forbade them. And the two of them ran in among those many people, and they tore apart the clothes on their two bodies. That deed was a sign that the two of them did not want people to traditionally-worship them. Then the two of them forbade them saying,</bt><v n="15" />&lt;&lt;Weh! Nga tao ka miu tao sèmi ne'e? Baku pangee na, ji'i se dhèu dedha-liru. Ji'i dhèu rai-haha èci èèna ka dènge miu. Ji'i mai ho neo lole dènge miu, lii lole be'a èci. Miu hud'i tèke eele ku, dhèu dedha-liru miu dhu lèke boe sèra. Aa miu hud'i mai madhutu ku Ama Lamatua dhu mamuri tare'a-re'a. Nèngu ka dhu paj'aj'i dedha-liru, rai-haha dènge isi ra aa'i-aa'i.<bt>&lt;&lt;Wee! Why are you(pl) doing this? Don't think that we(exc) here are heavenly people. We are earthly people just like you. We came wanting to tell you a good story. You must leave behind your heavenly people who have no use/match. And you must come follow the God who truly lives. He is the one who created the earth-heaven (=universe) and all their contents.</bt><note reference="14:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 20:11, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 146:6</note><v n="16" />Nèti uru ka mai, dhèu ètu rai mia-mia mamuri madhutu dad'èi d'ara rèngu. Aa Ama Lamatua soro tèke si mamuri sèmi èèna.<bt>From long ago, people from lands everywhere lived according to their own desires. And God allowed them to live like that.</bt><v n="17" />Te ngaa Lamatua bhèlu boe hia si tadha-tadha, sèna ka re'a, na, Lamatua èèna be'a. Nèngu ka dhu papuru èj'i mai. Nèngu ka dhu hia oka-tedhe èdhi hua-hela. Nèngu ka dhu hia èdhi nganga'a-nginu. Aa Nèngu ka dhu pakarej'e d'ara èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, God2 did not forget to give them signs, so that they knew that God2 is good. He is the one who sends down the rain. He is the one who makes our(inc) gardens produce. He is the one who gives us food-drink. And He is the one who pleases our insides.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="horo-parahi = yg hidup (kuno) ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">horo-parahi = yg hidup (kuno) ; Ama Horo-Parahi ; rai-liru = langit deng bumi; <span class="Bold">16:</span> soro tèke = kasi biar; <span class="Bold">17:</span> hua-hela = hasil</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Masi ka Paulus dènge Barnabas kai si, te ngaa dhèu sèra pakaseti hia mèdha sogo-tagu sèra mi rèngu.<bt>Even though Paulus and Barnabas forbade them, nevertheless those people forcibly gave their items of traditional-worship to them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakaseti = paksa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pakaseti = paksa</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Lod'o èèna, abhu pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi dhu mai nèti kota Antiokia dènge kota Ikonium, lasi asa kota Listra. Rèngu dadugu dhèu ae ho pa'èci dènge rèngu ho lab'a dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus sèra. Ka ra tabhie Paulus dènge hadhu. Ra ngee na madhe le, ka ra ère rèti lasi core eele ne asa li'u kota.<bt>At that time, there were several Jahudi people who came from the city of Antiokia and the city of Ikonium, going to the city of Listra. They persuaded many people to join with them to oppose the servant/emissaries of the Lord Yesus. And they stoned Paulus. They thought he was already dead, and they dragged him throwing him outside the city.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02156b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11cm;textWrapping:none">Paulus bèbhe lula dhèu tabhie ne dènge hadhu<bt>Paulus falls from people stoning him</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa ropa dhèu parcaya Yesus sèra, titu-reo Paulus, ka na kèd'i hari. Èle èèna ka, na maso hari asa d'ara kota. Asa bèli èèna, Paulus dènge Barnabas lasi hari asa kota leo, ngara na Derbe.<bt>But, when people who believed in Yesus stood around Paulus, he got up again. After that, he entered the city again. The following day, Paulus and Barnabas went back to another city, named Derbe.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="titu-reo = badiri kuliling"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">titu-reo = badiri kuliling</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus dènge Barnabas lèpa hari asa kota Antiokia ètu propensi Siria<bt>Paulus and Barnabas return again to the city of Antiokia in the province of Siria</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ètu kota Derbe, Paulus dènge Barnabas lole Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus. Ka dhèu ae parcaya Yesus. Hèia dua ra lèpa hari asa kota Listra. Nèti Listra, rèngu lasi hari asa kota Ikonium. Nèti Ikonium, rèngu taruu asa Antiokia ètu propensi Pisidia.<bt>In the city of Derbe, Paulus and Barnabas told the Good News of the Lord Yesus. And many people believed in Yesus. Then the two of them returned again to the city of Listra. From yonder, they went back to the city of Ikonium. From yonder, they continued on to Antiokia in the province of Pisidia.</bt><v n="22" />Ètu Antiokia, ra padhai lii pa'èra d'ara dhèu dhu madhutu Yesus sèra. Ra pasanèd'e si, peka na, &lt;&lt;A'ari aa'i-aa'i ti! Ladhe èdhi j'aj'i dhèu unu Ama Lamatua, baku ngee, na, èdhi abhu heka j'aj'èra. Masi ka abhu j'aj'èra, te ngaa èdhi hud'i taha ho madhutu taruu Lamatua Yesus.&gt;&gt; Dua ra aj'a sèmi èèna mi dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus ètu kota èèna.<bt>There, they spoke strengthening the insides of the people who follow Yesus. They reminded them, saying, &lt;&lt;All you elder-younger siblings! When we(inc) become people belonging to God, don't think that we will no longer experience suffering. Even though there is that suffering we must endure to keep following the Lord Yesus.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Èle èèna ka, Paulus dènge Barnabas tenge dhèu ho ra neo paj'uj'u j'aj'i kètu juma'at<bt>After that, Paulus and Barnabas looked for people so they could designate them as leaders(fathers) among those *congregations.</bt><note reference="14:23" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ama juma'at ètu d'ara ayat ne'e, lii Yunani peka na, <span class="Italic">presbuteros</span>.<bt>Congregational leaders in this verse, the Yunani language says <span class="Italic">presbuteros</span>.</bt></note>sèra. Ka ra manèngi-mangaj'i dènge puasa neo re'a dad'èi Lamatua. Dhèu dhu Lamatua paj'uj'u, rèngu sabaj'a dènge bane ai mi dedha na, ho ded'e ne j'aj'i kètu juma'at.<bt>And they prayed and fasted wanting to know the will of God2. The people whom God2 designated, they prayed and placed their hands on them, to be congregational leaders.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Èle èèna ka, Paulus dènge Barnabas tèke eele propensi Pisidia, lasi asa propensi Pamfilia.<bt>After that, Paulus and Barnabas left behind the province of Pisidia, going to the province of Pamfilia.</bt><v n="25" />Ka rèngu maso asa kota Perga. Ètu èèna, ra lole Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua. Èle èèna ka, lasi asa kota Atalia, dhu kaj'èu boe nèti Perga.<bt>And they entered the city of Perga. There, they told the Good News of the Lord. After that, they went to the city of Atalia, which was not far from Perga.</bt><v n="26" />D'ai nèi, ka ra ca'e balu lèpa hari asa kota Antiokia ètu propensi Siria. Ca hari ni, dhèu parcaya Yesus ètu Antiokia ka dhu pangèd'u dua ra asa Lamatua sèna ka Na ladhe-leru si, aa rèngu ka dhu pua dua ra lasi kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, Paulus si lasi ho neo lole mi juma'at Antiokia, peka na, rèngu tao rare le sasab'a dhu juma'at pua rèngu sab'a.<bt>Arriving yonder, they embarked on a sailship returning back again to the city of Antiokia in the province of Siria. At a (previous) time, people who believed in Yesus at Antiokia are the ones who had turned them over (&lt;given to hold) to the Lord so that He would take care of/watch over them, and they also had sent them off. Because of that, Paulus (coll) went wanting to report to the congregation at Antiokia that they had done the work which the congregation and sent them to work.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pangèd'u"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pangèd'u</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01958b.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Balu ne tao nèti tèu paredha Roma<bt>Sail boat/ship made from the Roma government era</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />D'ai kota Antiokia, ka Paulus si pakaboko aa'i dhèu parcaya Lamatua ètu èèna. Ka ra lolo aa'i-aa'i tatao Lamatua mi dedha rèngu. Ra lole kahèi, peka na, Lamatua bhoke le j'ara hia dhèu Yahudi boe ho parcaya Lamatua Yesus kahèi.<bt>Arriving at the city of Antiokia, Paulus (coll) gathered all the people believing in the Lord htere. And they thoroughly reported the deeds of the Lord/God2 to/for them. They also reported that God2 had opened the way for non-Jahudi people to also believe in the Lord Yesus.</bt><v n="28" />Èle èèna ka, Paulus dènge Barnabas pea nèbhu dènge dhèu parcaya Lamatua Yesus sèra ètu èèna.<bt>After that, Paulus and Barnabas stayed awhile with the people who believed in the Lord Yesus in that place.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koha = boat with one sail"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">koha = boat with one sail ; balu = boat with two or more sails</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama-ama Kristen pakaboko ètu Yerusalem<bt>Kristen leaders (fathers) gather in Yerusalem</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="15" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi Kristen mai nèti kaj'èu, nèti propensi Yudea, asa kota Antiokia. D'ai nèi, ra aj'a dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu parcaya Yesus, èèna be'a le. Te ngaa èèna d'ai mèka. Ladhe miu tare'a-re'a neo abhu mamuri, miu hud'i suna ku madhutu ad'a ji'i dhèu Yahudi, dhu Lamatua papuru le mai re baki Musa.&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, several Kristen Jahudi people came from far away, from the province of Yudea, to the city of Antiokia. Arriving yonder, they taught people belonging the the Lord Yesus, saying, &lt;&lt;It is good that you(pl) believe in Yesus. But that is not enough. If you truly want to get *saved, you must be circumcised according to our(exc) Jahudi adat, just as God2 handed down coming to Grandpa Musa.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sod'a = salamat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sod'a = salamat</Message></Annotation><note reference="15:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 12:3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Te ngaa Paulus dènge Barnabas lab'a lii padhai lii dhèu sèra. Rèngu palab'a aae. Hèia Paulus si peka, na, &lt;&lt;Miu sala èèna! Dhèu Yahudi boe dhu parcaya Yesus, parluu boe madhutu ad'a suna dhèu Yahudi!&gt;&gt; Lula ra palab'a sèmi èèna, ka a'abhu rèngu èci dènge èci sama boe, hèia ra tenge lii èci ho pua Paulus dènge Barnabas dènge pèri-pèri dhèu nèti Antiokia, ho rèti lii ne'e asa dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua dènge ama-ama Kristen leo sèra ètu Yerusalem.<bt>But, Paulus and Barnabas opposed what those people said. They recip-opposed big-time. Then Paulus (coll) said, &lt;&lt;You(pl) are wrong! People from other lands who believe in Yesus, do not need to follow the circumcision adat of the Jahudi people!&gt;&gt; Because they recip-opposed like that, their opinions did not match up with each other, and they came to an agreement to send Paulus and Barnabas, and some other people from Antiokia, to take this dispute to the servant/emissaries of the Lord (and) other Kristen leaders (fathers) in Yerusalem.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Nèti èèna ka, Paulus si kako haga lasi re propensi Finisia dènge propensi Samaria. Ètu d'ara kakako, rèngu dhuli pèri-pèri èmu dhèu Kristen. Ka ra lole aa'i mèu-mèu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu Yahudi boe sèra parcaya le Lamatua Yesus!&gt;&gt; Ra tadèngi rare sèmi èèna, ka aa'i-aa'i ra karej'e.<bt>Because of that, Paulus (coll) walked overland by way of the province of Finisia and the province of Samaria. On their journey, they stopped in at several houses of Kristen people. And the reported in detail, saying, &lt;&lt;People of other lands have believed in the Lord Yesus!&gt;&gt; When they heard like that, all of them were happy.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />D'ai Yerusalem, ka dhèu madhutu Yesus aa'i-aa'i ètu èèna, sèmi rare Paulus si dènge be'a. Dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua dènge ama-ama Kristen sèra, sèmi rare rèngu kahèi. Ka Paulus si lole aa'i mèu-mèu tatao Lamatua mi dedha rèngu, hèia dhèu ae nèti rai leo parcaya Lamatua Yesus. Aa rèngu lolo kahèi, na, rèngu palab'a aae lula j'ara suna ètu Antiokia.<bt>Arriving in Yerusalem, all the people who follow Yesus there received Paulus (coll) well. The servants/emissaries of the Lord and the other Kristen leaders also received them. And Paulus (coll) reported in detail what God2 had done for them, then many people of other lands believed in the Lord Yesus. And they also told about the great conflict over the circumcision dispute in Antiokia.</bt><v n="5" />Ètu talora dhèu dhu nanene lii padhai lii Paulus, abhu kahèi dhèu Yahudi Kristen nèti partei Parisi. Dhèu se kèd'i titu, ka ra hia lii bia, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nanene paie! Ladhe cee ka dhu dhèu Yahudi boe, dhu neo madhutu Yesus, rèngu hud'i madhutu ku ad'a suna dènge atora ad'a leo èdhi, dhu Ama Lamatua papuru mai re baki Musa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Among the people who were listening to what Paulus was saying there were also Kristen Jjahudi people from the Parisi party. These people stood up and they spoke their objection, saying, &lt;&lt;Listen well! For whoever is not a Jahudi person, who wants to follow Yesus, they must follow the circumcision adat and our(inc) other adat regulations, which God handed down to Grandpa Musa.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ra hia lii bia = suara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ra hia lii bia = suara berat (sulit dipikirkan cara lain dan sulit dibantah)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ana iiki dhu goa na ka,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Ana iiki dhu goa na ka, re'a j'ara ne'e ne!&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01974b.tif" rtfFormat="width:5.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Petrus<bt>Petrus</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Nèti èèna ka, dhèu sarani aa'i-aa'i rare lii èci ho dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua dènge ama-ama Kristen sèra pakaboko sèna ka ra pajiko lii langu rèngu èèna.<bt>Because of that, all the baptised/christened people were in accord for the servant/emissaries of the Lord and the Kristen leaders to gather to evaluate this matter/dispute of theirs.</bt><v n="7" />Ka ra padhue la'e-mai. Hèia Petrus kèd'i titu, ka padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;A'ari aa'i-aa'i ti! Miu me'a, na, uru èèna Lamatua paj'uj'u le ja'a nèti talora miu, sèna ka ja'a laku lole Lii Lolo Be'a Yesus mi dhèu Yahudi boe sèra. Lula Lamatua d'èi, sèna ka rèngu parcaya Yesus kahèi.<bt>And they discussed back-and-forth. Then Petrus stood up, and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;All you elder-younger siblings! You(pl) here know that long ago God2 appointed me, from among you, so that I would go tell the Good News of Yesus to non-Jahudi people. Because God2 desires for them to also believe in Yesus.</bt><note reference="15:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 10:1-43</note><v n="8" />Lamatua ne'a d'ara èdhi èci-èci. Aa Nèngu ka dhu pala-bagi Roh Na dhu Mola-Mèci hia rèngu, sama sèmi Na hia èdhi kahèi. Dènge j'ara ne'e, sèna ka èdhi te'a, na, Lamatua sèmi nare rèngu kahèi.<bt>God2 knows each of our(inc) insides/character/heart. And He is the one who distributed His Holy Spirit to them, just as He gave (it) to us also. In this way, it was so that we would know that God also accepts them.</bt><note reference="15:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 2:4, 10:44</note><v n="9" />Te Lamatua ladhe boe rèhu dhèu. Na tao beda boe rèngu dènge èdhi. Te Lamatua pamèu le d'ara rèngu, lula rèngu parcaya le Yesus kahèi, sama sèmi Na pamèu d'ara èdhi.<bt>Cause God2 does not distinguish faces/discriminate. He does not differentiate them from us. Cause God2 has cleaned/sanctified their insides, because they have also believed in Yesus, just like He cleaned our insides.</bt><v n="10-11" />De tasamia? Lamatua sèmi nare le rèngu. Nga tao ka èdhi neo pabia hari rèngu dènge ad'a suna èdhi? Èdhi te'a, na, èdhi dènge bèi-baki èdhi sèra, dui mèke boe atora-atora agama èdhi aa'i-aa'i ra! De hua iia èdhi baku pabia rèngu. Ja'a neo karèi sèmi ne'e: Lamatua hia èdhi mamuri lula èdhi madhutu atora agama, do? Aad'o, sina ma! Na hia èdhi mamuri, lula Lamatua Yesus sue èdhi. De baku bhèlu! Lamatua sue aa pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi dhèu rai leo sèmi èèna kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, how about it? God2 has already accepted them. Why do we(inc) want to weigh them down further with our circumcision adat? We know that we and our ancestors were not able to shoulder-carry all the regulations of our religion! So, it would be best that we not weigh them down. I want to ask this: Did God2 give us life/salvation2, because we followed religious regulations, or what? No way! He gave us life/salvation1, because the Lord Yesus loves/pities us. So, don't forget! God2 loves people of other lands like that as well.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dui mèke boe = sonde cukup"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dui mèke boe = sonde cukup kuat untuk pikol</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa tadèngi rare sèmi èèna, rèngu èci sa padhai lii tabha heka.<bt>When they heard like that, there was not one of them who any longer wanted to speak additionally.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Èle èèna ka, Paulus dènge Barnabas lolo hari j'ara sèmi mia Lamatua pake rèngu. Ra lole tadha-tadha malaa dènge j'ara kapai dhu Ama Lamatua tao ètu talora dhèu rai leo sèra.<bt>After that, Paulus and Barnabas again told the ways the God2 had used them. They told about the amazing signs and unusual ways that God had done among the people of those other lands.</bt><v n="13" />Lole rare, ka dhèu èci, ngara na Yakobis kèd'i titu, ka padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;A'ari! Mi nanene ku ja'a!<bt>After telling them, one person named Yakobis stood up and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Older-younger siblings! Listen to me!</bt><v n="14" />Simon Petrus<bt>Simon Petrus has just finished telling that God has elevated non-Jahudi people to enter them into becoming people who belong to the Lord Yesus.</bt><note reference="15:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;Simeon&gt;. Simeon dènge Simon èèna, sama. Simeon/Simon èèna, nuka ngara leo nèti Petrus.</note>heka lolo nare kèna, peka na, Ama Lamatua ded'e nare dhèu Yahudi boe sèra, ho pamaso si j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus.<v n="15" />Èèna lèke sèmi ngaa dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua peka tèke nèti uru. Ra suri, peka na:<bt>Now, that matches what God2's spokesperson said long ago. They wrote that:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="16" />&lt;Ladhe d'ai lod'o èèna, Ja'a lèpa hari.<bt>&lt;When the day/time arrives, I will come back.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Lula Ja'a neo pakèd'i hari paredha dhèu aae Daud,<bt>Because I want to establish again the command/government of King Daud,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ja'a neo pakèd'i hari dènge pa'èra hari,<bt>I want to restore with strength again,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ana-èpu Daud dhu mae-manyèla sèra.<bt>the descendants of Daud who have been destroyed/lose influence.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mae-manyèla = hancur, terpecah-belah"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">mae-manyèla = hancur, terpecah-belah</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="17-18" />Dènge tao sèmi èèna, dhèu rai-rai leo mai ho neo paraga dènge Ja'a kahèi.<bt>By doing that, people of various other lands, will come to want to meet with Me also.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te Ja'a hag'e kore rèngu kahèi, ho j'aj'i dhèu unu Ja'a.<bt>Cause I also choose/set them apart to be people belonging to Me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Ama Lamatua padhai lii sèmi èèna, nèti uru ka mai!&gt;<bt>Because God has spoken like that from long ago!&gt;</bt><note reference="15:16-18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Amos 9:11-12</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19-20" />Ka madhutu ngangee ja'a, Yakobis, sèmi ne'e: ladhe dhèu Yahudi boe neo madhutu Ama Lamatua, èdhi dhèu Yahudi baku paj'èra si. Èdhi baku pabia rèngu, ho pua si madhutu ad'a suna èdhi. De èdhi hud'i suri tare sasuri èci, ho ti pa'adhu hia rèngu, peka na, rèngu parluu boe madhutu aa'i atora ad'a èdhi dhèu Yahudi. Te ngaa èdhi pasanèd'e rèngu, peka na, bhèni-mone baku tao j'ara karehe dènge dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe dhèu èmu-kamali rèngu. Rèngu baku ra'a nganga'a sogo-tagu. Rèngu baku ra'a raa badha. Aa rèngu baku ra'a sisi badha madhe dhu ra pacèli koko.<bt>And, according to my thinking, Yakobis, it's like this: If people of various other lands want to follow God, we(inc) Jahudi people should not make them suffer. We should not weigh them down to order them to follow our circumcision adat. So we must write a letter to send it to them, saying, they do not need to follow all our Jahudi adat regulations. But, we should remind them that, females-males should not do evil ways with people who are not their spouse. They should not eat food used for traditional-worship. They should not eat the blood of animals. And they should not eat meat of dead animals that have been neck-choked.</bt><note reference="15:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 34:15-17, Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 17:10-16, 18:6-23</note><v n="21" />De ladhe èdhi tao atora sèra, èèna j'ara hiu boe. Lula dhèu ae re'a le ad'a èdhi dhèu Yahudi sèmi èèna ka. Te èdhi baca atora Musa sèra ètu èmu manèngi-mangaj'i ètu mia-mia, lod'o a'oro sasab'a. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu rai leo sèra re'a le.<bt>So if we make thoe regulations, that is not a new way/matter. Because many people already know our Jahudi adat is like that. Cause we read Grandpa Musa's regulations in the worship houses everywhere, on the days of rest (from work). Because of that, people of various other lands already know them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'adhu = kirim (benda, bukan orang)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pa'adhu = kirim (benda, bukan orang) ; pua = kirim (orang) ; bhèni-mone baku tao dhèu èmu dhèu = male-female don't bekin anyone's spouse ; dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe dhèu èmu rèngu ; Baku ra ra'a raa badha. @@ ; dhu madhe nèti dhèu pod'e ladha-goro ; ladha-goro = leher ; pacèli koko = ceke leher</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">D'ai sange èèna ka. Makasi!&gt;&gt;<bt>That's the extent. Thanks!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sasuri hia dhèu parcaya dhu dhèu Yahudi boe<bt>Writing/letter to the people who believe in the Lord Yesus from various other lands</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Èle padhue-padhai èèna, ka dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua dènge ama-ama Kristen dhu leo sèra, rare lii èci ho ra pua dhèu lasi peka lii dhu ra pama'ète rare èèna asa dhèu sarani ètu mia-mia. Ka ra tenge dhèu dhu juma'at sèra pakab'ua si, dhu lèke dènge sasab'a èèna. Hèia ra pili dhèu dua. Èci ngara na Silas, aa èci hari, ngara na Yudas, (dhu ngara leo na, Barsabas). Ka ra pua dua ra lasi sama-sama Paulus dènge Barnabas.<bt>After that speech, the servant/emissaries of God2 and the other Kristen leaders, came to an agreement to send people to go tell what they had decided to sarani (baptised/christened=common term for Christians) people everywhere. And they looked for people who were prominant (=respected) in the congregation, who were a good match for that work. Then they chose two people. One was named Silas, and the other was named Yudas, (whose other name was Barsabas). And they sent the two of them to go together with Paulus and Barnabas.</bt><v n="23" />Ka rèngu rèti sasuri hia dhèu sarani dhu Yahudi boe, ètu kota Antiokia ètu propensi Siria d'ai propensi Kilikia nèi. Isi sasuri èèna, sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>They took the letter to the sarani people from other lands, in the city of Antiokia province of Siria [CHECK: is preposition missing?], until the province of Kilikia yonder. The contents of that letter were like this:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ara-madha = orang tampil, dihormati. ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ara-madha = orang tampil, dihormati. ; re madha dhèu = segan, bisa, mampu, dihormati</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Lii maho'o nèti ji'i, dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus, dènge ama-ama dhu leo ètu kota Yerusalem. Ji'i sue miu sama sèmi a'ari ji'i. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i suri sasuri ne hia miu aa'i-aa'i mi.<bt>&lt;&lt;Important greetings from us(exc) [Check greeting], the servant/emissaries of the Lord Yesus, and other leaders/fathers in the city of Yerusalem. We love you(pl) as our elder-younger siblings (=relatives). Because of that, we write this letter to all of you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Alternate: lii maho'o karej'e = gembira,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Alternate: lii maho'o karej'e = gembira, suka-cita</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="24" />Ji'i tao sasuri ne, lula ji'i tadèngi, na, pèri-pèri dhèu nèti Yerusalem dhiu paraga dènge miu. Ka ra aj'a lèke boe, hèia paj'èra dènge pab'ingu miu. De sad'i miu me'a, ji'i pua boe dhèu sèra.<bt>This letter we make, because we heard that some people from Yerusalem, went to meet with you. And they did not teach correctly, that cause you suffering and confusion. So as long as you know, we did not send those people.</bt><v n="25" />Ropa ji'i tadèngi dhèu dhiu paj'èra miu, ka ji'i pakaboko ètu ne'e, ho pajiko lii langu ne'e. De ji'i pama'ète ngare le. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i pua dhèu dhiu peka dènge miu, ngaa dhu ji'i pama'ète ngare le. Ra dhiu sama-sama dènge Barnabas dènge Paulus, dhèu pasue ji'i.<bt>When we heard that people were causing you suffering/distress, we gathered here to evaluate this dispute. So we have finished deciding. Because of that, we are sending people to go tell you what we have decided. They are going together with Barnabas and Paulus, our beloved people.</bt><v n="26" />Dhèu dua se, dui j'aj'èra le oe d'ai madhe. Rèngu dui j'aj'èra, lula rèngu madhutu Kètu èdhi, Yesus Kristus.<bt>These two people bore suffering to the point that they almost died. They bore suffering, because they followed our Lord, Yesus, the person God chose from long ago.</bt><v n="27" />De ji'i pua Yudas dènge Silas, sèna ka dua ra lole hia miu isi sasuri ne'e.<bt>So we have sent Yudas and Silas, so that the two of them can tell you the contents of this letter.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhiu = pergi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhiu = pergi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="28" />Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci peka le dènge ji'i. Aa ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi ngare lii èci kahèi, sèna ka miu parluu boe madhutu aa'i ad'a Yahudi ji'i, sèmi ad'a suna èèna. Te ad'a ji'i èèna, pabia miu. Te ngaa abhu èci do dua j'ara dhu miu parluu sanèd'e, nuka:<bt>The Holy Spirit of God2 has spoken to us. And we all have also come to an agreement so that you do not need to follow all of our(exc) Jahudi adat, such as that adat of circumcision. Cause those adats of ours weigh you(pl) down. But there are one or two matters which you need to remember, that is:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="29" />Miu bhèni-mone baku tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe dhèu èmu-kamali miu.<bt>You(pl) females-males must not do evil ways with a person who is not your spouse (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mi'a = ; dhèu èmu-kamali ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">mi'a = ; dhèu èmu-kamali = kata majemuk</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Baku mi'a nganga'a sogo-tagu.<bt>Don't eat food used for traditional-worship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Baku mi'a nganga'a mèdha sogo-tagu."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Baku mi'a nganga'a mèdha sogo-tagu.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Baku mi'a raa badha.<bt>Don't eat the blood of animals.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa baku mi'a sisi badha dhu roro boe.<bt>And don't eat the meat of animals that have not been neck-sliced/slaughtered.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ladhe miu pakaj'èu iisi miu nèti j'ara-j'ara sèra, na, miu bisa pa'èci dènge mera-milu dènge a'ari dhèu Yahudi Kristen sèra.<bt>If you separate yourselves from these matters, na, you can join/fellowship in peace and prosperity (=right relationships) with the Kristen Jahudi relatives.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">D'ai sange ne'e ka, sasuri ji'i. Saloom.&gt;&gt;<bt>That's the limit of our letter. Syalom.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ropa sèmi rare sasuri èèna, ka ra palangu dènge ka. Hèia ra lasi asa kota Antiokia. D'ai nèi, ka rèngu pakaboko dhèu sarani aa'i-aa'i sèra, ka ra hia sasuri èèna la'a.<bt>When they had reeived that letter they took their leave immediately. And they went to the city of Antiokia. Arriving yonder, they gather all the carani people, and they gave that aforementioned letter.</bt><v n="31" />Ropa baca rare sasuri èèna, rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra karej'e, lula isi sasuri èèna pa'èra d'ara rèngu.<bt>When they finished reading that letter, they were all happy and light(weight/relieved), because the contents of that letter strengthened their insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palangu = pamit ; final la'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">palangu = pamit ; final la'a @@</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Lamatua pake Yudas dènge Silas kahèi j'aj'i dhèu nèti lii padhai Na. Dua ra padhai lii ae dènge dhèu parcaya ètu kota èèna. Dua ra lole lii holo-nori dènge pa'èra d'ara dhèu sèra.<bt>God2 also used Yudas and Silas to be His spokespeople. The two of them spoke much with the believing people in that city. The two of them spoke advice and strengthened those people's insides.</bt><v n="33" />Silas dènge Yudas pea ètu èèna ako nèbhu ciki. Èle èèna ka, heka dhèu sarani ètu Antiokia sèra, hia si lèpa hari asa ama-ama dhu pua rèngu sèra mai. Ra hia si lasi dènge d'ara karej'e-karae.<bt>Silas and Yudas stayed in that place rather long. After that, only then did the sarani people in Antiokia permit them to return back to the leaders (fathers) who had sent them. They let them go with happy (doublet) insides.</bt><v n="34" />[Te ngaa Silas neo pea taruu ètu Antiokia.]<bt>[But, Silas wanted to continue living in Antiokia.]</bt><note reference="15:34" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ayat 34 ne'e, abhu boe ètu d'ara sasuri lii Yunani uru cahag'e.<bt>This verse (loan) 34, is not found in some old writings.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Paulus dènge Barnabas pea pèri-pèri lod'o ètu Antiokia. Rèngu soru-bara dhèu leo dhu aj'a dhèu dhu padhai lii lula-nèti J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus kahèi.<bt>Paulus and Barnabas stayed several days (=awhile) in Antiokia. They taught people who were also explaining the Life Way of the Lord Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus pacèri dènge Barnabas<bt>Paulus mutually-seperates from Barnabas</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Rèngu pea ako nèbhu ètu Antiokia. Ca lod'o, ka Paulus peka dènge Barnabas, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Be'a risi èdhi lèpa hari asa era-era dhu èdhi dhuli uru èèna, ho lati ladhe sèku mamuri a'ari èdhi sèra. Mamuri rèngu tasamia le. Te rèngu parcaya Lamatua Yesus nèbhu mèka. Uru èèna, èdhi ka dhu nori si. Mai lati ladhe si!&gt;&gt;<bt>They stayed for awhile in Antiokia. One time, Paulus spoke with Barnabas, saying, &lt;&lt;It would be good for us(inc) to go back to the places where we visited before, to go have a look after the lives of those relatives of ours(inc). How their lives are going. Cause they have not yet believed the Lord Yesus for long. At that former time, we are the ones who taught them. Let's go see how they're doing!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="37" />Ropa Barnabas tadèngi lii manèngi Paulus, nèngu d'èi kahèi. Barnabas neo nèti dènge Yohanis (dhu ngara leo na, Markus), la'e dènge rèngu.<bt>When Barnabas heard Paulus' request, he also desired (it). Barnabas wanted to take Yohanis (whose other name was Markus), to go with them.</bt><v n="38" />Te ngaa Paulus sèmi boe, lula uru èèna ètu propensi Pamfilia, Markus rai eele rèngu.<bt>But Paulus didn't agree, because formerly in the province of Pamfilia, Markus had run off from them.</bt><note reference="15:38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 13:13</note><v n="39" />Paulus dènge Barnabas palab'a aae, ka ra pacèri. Barnabas nèti Markus, ka ra ca'e kapa lasi asa pulu Siprus.<bt>Paulus and Barnabas had big-time conflict, and they separated. Barnabas took Markus and they embarked on a ship going to the island of Siprus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahag'a = pacèri"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pahag'a = pacèri</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Te ngaa Paulus nèti Silas. Lod'o rèngu neo pakèd'i, dhèu parcaya ètu Antiokia sèra manèngi Lamatua j'aga rèngu, dènge pad'elo babe'a Na mi dedha rèngu. Sabaj'a rare, ka dua ra pakèd'i.<bt>But Paulus took Silas. When they wanted to leave, the believing people in Antiokia asked God2 to watch over them, and to show His goodness to them. After they finished praying, the two of them left.</bt><v n="41" />Hèia Paulus dènge Silas lasi palème propensi Siria dènge propensi Kilikia. Ètu mia-mia, rèngu pa'èra d'ara dhèu parcaya sèra.<bt>Then Paulus and silas went around the province of Siria and the province of Kilikia. Everywhere they strengthened the insides of the believing people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Timotius pa'èci dènge Paulus aa Silas<bt>Timotius joins with Paulus and Silas</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="16" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, Paulus si lasi asa kota Derbe. Ka ra kako taruu asa kota Listra. D'ai Listra, ra paraga dènge ana mone ngèru èci, ngara na Timotius. Ama na, dhèu Yunani, aa ina na, dhèu Yahudi dhu parcaya Yesus. Timotius j'aj'i le dhèu unu Yesus kahèi.<bt>After that, Paulus (coll) went to the city of Derbe. And they continued going on to the city of Listra. Arriving in Listra, they met a young man named Timotius. His father was a Yunani person, and his mother was a Jahudi person who believed in Yesus. Timotius had also become a person belonging to Yesus.</bt><v n="2" />Dhèu parcaya aa'i-aa'i ètu kota Listra dènge kota Ikonium re'a, na, Timotius ne, dhèu d'ara be'a.<bt>All the believing people in the city of Listra and the city of Ikonium knew that this Timotius was a good person.</bt><v n="3" />Paulus neo sèna ka Timotius madhutu rèngu. Te ngaa dhèu Yahudi ètu èèna re'a, na, ama Timotius èèna, dhèu Yunani, de nèngu suna mèka madhutu ad'a dhèu Yahudi. Nèti èèna ka, Paulus ator ho suna Timotius.<bt>Paulus wanted for Timotius to accompany them. But, Jahudi people in that place knew that Timotius' father was a Yunani person, so he had not been circumcised according to the adat of the Jahudi people. Because of that, Paulus arranged to circumcise Timotius [can also read: for Timo to be circumcised].</bt><note reference="16:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Paulus ne'a, na, madhutu atora ad'a èèna, dhèu dhu suna mèka bisa boe maso asa d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi. Ladhe sèmi Timotius neo tulu Paulus ho lole Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus asa dhèu Yahudi sèra, nèngu hud'i suna ku. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, nèngu carui boe maso-kalua ètu talora dhèu Yahudi.<bt>Paulus knew the adat regulation that people who had not yet been circumcised were not allowed to enter into the Jahudi people's houses of worship. If Timotius was going to assist Paulus to tell the Good News of the Lord Yesus to Jahudi people, he must first be circumcised. In that way, he would have no problems going in and out among Jahudi people.</bt></note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02124b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Timotius dènge Paulus<bt>Timotius and Paulus</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Èle èèna ka, rèngu lasi palème rae-rae, ho lole lii pama'ète nèti dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua Yesus dènge ama-ama Kristen leo sèra ètu kota Yerusalem.<bt>After that, they went around from village to village, to tell the decision from the servant/emissaries of the Lord Yesus and the other Kristen leaders in the city of Yerusalem.</bt><v n="5" />Dènge j'ara ne'e, rèngu asa pa'èra d'ara dhèu sarani sèra. Bèli-bèli èèna, dhèu parcaya hiu asa tabha ae.<bt>In this way, they kept strengthening the insides of these sarani people. Every day, new beleiving people kept increasing in number.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua pua Paulus la'e asa Makedonia<bt>God summons Paulus to go to Makedonia</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Èle èèna ka, Paulus si lasi taruu. Ka ra lasi asa propensi Galati dènge propensi Frigia, lula Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci kai si ho baku lasi lole Lii Lolo Be'a asa propensi Asia.<bt>After that, Paulus (coll) continued going. And they went to the province of Galatia and the province of Frigia, because the Holy Spirit of God2 prevented/forbade them to not go tell the Good News in the province of Asia.</bt><v n="7" />Ropa rèngu d'ai rai èci dhu patoo dènge propensi Misia, rèngu neo maso asa propensi Bitinia. Te ngaa Roh Yesus kai si, sèna ka baku lasi asa nèi.<bt>When they arrived at the border between one country and the province of Misia, they wanted to enter the province of Bitinia. But the Spirit of Yesus prevented them, so that they didn't/couldn't go yonder.</bt><note reference="16:6-7" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Limuri ne, propensi dhu uru èèna, ngara na Frigia, Galati, Asia, Misia, dènge Bitinia, abhu ètu rai Turki.<bt>Now, those former provinces named Frigia, Galatia, Asia, Misia, and Bitinia, are found in the land/country of Turki.</bt></note><v n="8" />Èle èèna ka, rèngu kako re propensi Misia, hèia d'ai kota Troas.<bt>After that, they went by way of/passing the province of Misia, then arrived at the city of Troas.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lamatua pad'elo nanèdhi èci mi Paulus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Lamatua pad'elo nanèdhi èci mi Paulus</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nanèdhi = penglihatan ;; |b7:|r patoo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">nanèdhi = penglihatan ;; <span class="Bold">7:</span> patoo = RECIP-batas; <span class="Bold">8:</span> kako seli = jalan lewat (by-passing) ; kako re = jalan dari (through)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Mèda èèna, Paulus abhu tanila. Nèngu nèdhi dhèu èci titu ètu cabèka dhasi ètu propensi Makedonia. Dhèu ne, taraa manèngi tulu, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Mai asa ne'e, ho soru ku ji'i laa!&gt;&gt;<bt>That night, Paulus had a vision. He saw a person standing on the other side of the ocean in the province of Makedonia. This person, was shouting for help, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Come here, to help(in difficult circumstances) us(exc)!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="10" />Nèdhi sèmi èèna, hèia ji'i<bt>Seeing that, we</bt><note reference="16:10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu d'ara ayat ne'e, pake lii &lt;ji'i&gt;, lula Lukas pa'èci dènge Paulus si ètu ne'e. Lukas ka dhu suri sasuri ne'e.<bt>In this verse, the word &lt;us(exc)&gt;,is used, because Lukas joined with Paulus (coll) in this place. Lukas is the one who wrote this book.</bt></note>ngare lii èci ho la'a asa Makedonia. Madhutu ngangee ji'i, na, Ama Lamatua ka dhu pua ji'i la'a lole J'ara Mamuri Na mi dhèu ètu cabèka dhasi nèi. Nèti èèna ka, Na kai ji'i baku la'a asa era leo.<bt>came to an agreement to go to Makedonia. According to our thinking God is the one who told us to go tell His Way of Life/Salvation to people over on the other side of the ocean. Because of that, He had prevented us from going to other places.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ètu cabèka dhasi = other side"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ètu cabèka dhasi = other side of ocean ; soru = tolong (terjepit)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lidia parcaya Lamatua Yesus ètu kota Pilipi<bt>In the city of Filipi, Lidia believes in the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Èle èèna ka, ji'i ca'e balu ètu kota Troas, ho la'a asa pulu iiki cue, ngara na Samotrake. Asa bèli èèna, ji'i la'a taruu, ka d'ai kota èci, ngara na Neapolis. Ka ji'i puru ètu èèna.<bt>After that, we(exc) embarked on a sail-ship at the city of Troas, to go to a small island, named Samotrake. The next day, we continued on, and arrived at a city named Neapolis. And we disembarked there.</bt><v n="12" />Nèti èèna, ji'i kako haga la'a asa kota Pilipi, kota kapai cue ètu propensi Makedonia. Kota ne'e, ètu d'ara paredha Roma kahèi. Ji'i pea pèri-pèri lod'o di ètu èèna.<bt>From there, we went by foot going to the city of Filipi, a prominent city in the province of Makedonia. This city was also under the Roma government. We stayed several days in this place.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02127b.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none">Paulus si paraga dènge Lidia<bt>Paulus (coll) meeting Lidia</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />D'ai lod'o a'oro sasab'a dhèu Yahudi, ji'i la'a tenge era sabaj'a dhèu Yahudi. Ji'i pangee, na, era sabaj'a èèna ètu sebhe loko. Ka ji'i kako ako kaj'èu ciki nèti d'ara kota, hèia ji'i ngèdhi loko èci. Ètu era ne'e, ji'i paraga dènge pèri-pèri dhèu bhèni,<bt>When the Jahudi people's day of rest arrived, we went looking for the Jahudi people's place to pray. We thought that the place to pray was at the edge of the river. And we went a little ways from the city, then we saw a river/stream. In that place, we met several women,</bt><note reference="16:13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu atora, hud'i abhu canguru dhèu mone Yahudi, heka bisa ra pakèd'i èmu manèngi-mangaj'i ra. Ra ige boe dhèu bhèni. De lula abhu dhoka pèri-pèri dhèu bhèni dhu sabaj'a ètu sebhe loko Gangites, èdhi bisa te'a, peka na, ètu kota Pilipi, abhu dhèu mone Yahudi ciki di.<bt>According to regulations, there had to be 10 Yahudi men, only then could they erect a house of prayer/worship. They didn't count women. So, because there were several women who prayed by the edge of the Gangites (&lt; FF Bruce) river, we can know that in the city of Filipi, Yahudi men were very few.</bt></note>ka ji'i madhèdi padhai lii dènge rèngu.<bt>and we sat talking with them.</bt><v n="14" />Nèti dhèu bhèni se, abhu dhèu èci, ngara na Lidia. Nèngu nèti kota kaj'èu èci ètu propensi Asia, ngara na kota Tiatira. Sasab'a Lidia, pahia bèla mea sanama mangèru dhu kab'ua titu kèna dènge dhèu aae-dhèu kapai. Nèngu maj'èni manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, ropa na tadèngi lii padhai Paulus, ka na sèmi nare dènge.<bt>Among these women was a person named Lidia. She was from a far away city in the province of Aisa, named Tiatira. Lidia's work, was selling red-purple cloth (Ndao only has a few colours [red, black, white], plus something like 'bright' which includes yellow, blue, green; this term is 'red tending toward-bright') which was very expensive to important people. She was diligent in praying/worshipping God. Because of that, when she heard what Paulus was saying, she accepted it immediately.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hèia ji'i sarani Lidia dènge isi èmu na aa'i-aa'i ra. Ropa sarani èle, ka na gale ji'i, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama si! Ladhe miu ngee, na, ja'a ne parcaya tare'a-re'a le Lamatua Yesus, na, miu mai manubha ètu d'ara èmu ji'i.&gt;&gt; Lula na pamako loe boe, hèia ji'i la'a.<bt>Then we baptised Lidia, and all of her household (=family + servants). After finishing baptising, she invited us, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers! If you think that I have truly believed in the Lord Yesus, you(pl) must come stay overnight (or stay temporarily) in our house.&gt;&gt; Because she kept insisting, we went.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nèru = invite formally (not inflected);"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">nèru = invite formally (not inflected); tèru = cermin ; gale = ajak, more informal, and intim</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra pamaso Paulus dènge Silas asa d'ara bèdho ètu kota Pilipi<bt>They put Paulus and Silas in prison in the city of Filipi</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ca lod'o, ropa ji'i la'a asa era manèngi-mangaj'i, ka ji'i paraga dènge ana bhèni èci. Nèngu ne, ènu dhèu. Nidhu bhèlu sab'a ètu d'ara nèngu, ka na ne'a ladhe kalua dhèu. Nèngu ne'a malare kahèi. Ka dhèu ae hia ne doi, ho ra manèngi nèngu ladhe kalua rèngu. Te ngaa lamatua ana bhèni ènu ne ka dhu abhu doi aa'i-aa'i sèra. Ka rèngu j'aj'i kaja.<bt>One day, while we were going to the place of worship, we met with a young woman. She was someone's slave/servant. An evil spirit worked in her insides, and she could understand the veins/tendons of people (idiom: read people's fate). She could also divine (causes). And many people gave her money, so they could ask her to read their fate. But the master/owners [same word as 'lord'] of this female slave are the ones who got all that money. So they became rich.</bt><v n="17" />Lod'o èèna, ropa ji'i kako, ana bhèni ne madhutu taruu ji'i. Ka na pa'oo-parodha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu se'e se, ana madhutu Ama Lamatua dhu Koasa Kapai. Rèngu mai ho neo pad'elo j'ara tasamia ka dhèu bisa abhu mamuri, aa tasamia ka Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo rèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>That day, while we were walking, this young woman kept following us. And she kept bleating-shouting (doublet) out, &lt;&lt;These people here, are followers of the Most Powerful God. They came wanting to point the way how people can be saved, and how God2 can wipe away their wrongs (doublet).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ladhe kalua = lihat urat (nasib)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ladhe kalua = lihat urat (nasib) ; malare = cari tau nasib, cari tau sebab, divine ;; <span class="Bold">17:</span> pa'oo = batarea tanpa pesan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ana bhèni ne pa'oo taruu sèmi èèna d'ai pèri-pèri lod'o. Nèbhu-nèbhu hèia Paulus roca nanene lii pa'oo-parodha ana bhèni ne. Ca tèka, ka Paulus kabèli kabodho, ka na ladhe kaloo ne, hèia na hia paredha, peka na, &lt;&lt;He! Èu nidhu bhèlu! Dènge koasa Lamatua Yesus, ja'a paredha èu kalua nèti ana bhèni ne, ètu d'ara ciki oo'e ne'e kahèi!&gt;&gt; Ropa Paulus peka nare sèmi èèna, cag'ag'a laa, nidhu ne kalua dènge ka.<bt>This young woman kept doing that for several days. Eventually Paulus was tired/bored of listening to the shouting of this young woman. And he turned around and stared/glared at her, then he commanded, saying, &lt;&lt;He! You(sg) evil spirit! With the power/authority of the Lord Yesus, I command you to come out from this young woman, and do it right now!&gt;&gt; When Paulus had psoken like that, suddenly, this evil spirit came out immediately.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roca = bosan ; ètu dara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">roca = bosan ; ètu dara ciki oo'e ne'e kahèi = dalam waktu yg singkat ju</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02129b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Paulus babège eele nidhu nèti ana bhèni èci<bt>Paulus expels an evil spirit from a young woman</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Lod'o lamatua ana bhèni ènu èèna re'a, na, koasa nèngu ele le, hèia ra nasa, lula rèngu abhu heka doi. Nèti èèna ka, ra kèpe Paulus dènge Silas, ka nuni rèti si asa era pama'ète lii langu, ètu d'ara pasa.<bt>When the owner of the aforementioned female slave knew that her power was gone, they were angry, because they would no longer get any money. Because of that, they caught Paulus and Silas, and dragged them to the place of settling disputes inside the market (loan).</bt><v n="20" />D'ai èèna, hèia ra pa'oo aae, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu se'e mai pa'ele iie kabarai èdhi. Te ngaa rèngu se dhèu rai leo. Dhèu Yahudi se mai nèti li'u, ho pamae kabarai èdhi!<bt>Arriving at that place, they made a loud fuss, saying, &lt;&lt;These people have come to destroy our(inc) society. But, they are people from a different land (=foreigners). These are Jahudi people, coming from outside, to tear apart our society!</bt><v n="21" />Rèngu dadugu isi kabarai èdhi, ho baku pusi-pahae dènge j'ara paredha Roma, sèna ka madhutu dhoka j'ara rèngu di.&gt;&gt;<bt>They are persuading our people to not pay any attention to the ways of the Roma government, in order to just follow their ways.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabarai = kota/masyarakat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kabarai = kota/masyarakat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa tadèngi rare sèmi èèna, dhèu ae sèra nasa, ka ra game Paulus dènge Silas. Ka dhèu kapai èci ètu èèna, pua dhèu ciu eele mèdha-papake ka hake si.<bt>When they heard that, many people there were angry, and they beat (fists) Paulus and Silas. And one of the leaders there, ordered people to tear off their clothes and beat2 (with instrument to punish) them.</bt><v n="23" />Ra hake rare, ka pamaso dua ra asa d'ara bèdho. Ra pua komedhaa j'aga ho j'aga paie, mage dhoka ra rai.<bt>After beating them, they put the two of them into prison. They ordered the commander of the guards to guard well, lest they flee.</bt><v n="24" />Tadèngi rare sèmi èèna, ka komedhaa j'aga ne pamaso Paulus dènge Silas asa d'ara kama èci ètu talora aae èmu bèdho èèna. Ka na ngapi haga si dua ra dènge aj'u ngangapi.<bt>Hearing that, this commander of the guards put Paulus and Silas into a room deep inside (in the middle of) that prison. And he clamped the legs of the two of them with a clamping wood (their word for wooden stocks).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="talora aae = tengah sekali ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">talora aae = tengah sekali ; ngangapi = alat jepit, tongs</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02132b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm:textWrapping:none">Rèngu ngapi haga Paulus si ètu d'ara èmu bèdho<bt>They clamp Paulus (coll) feet in jail</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Pe d'ara talora mèda sa, Paulus dènge Silas sabaj'a dènge sod'a koa-kio kolongara Ama Lamatua. Aa ana bèdho leo sèra tadèngi lii sod'a ra.<bt>Around the middle of the night, Paulus and Barnabas prayed and sang praising the name/reputation of God. And the other prisoners there heard their songs.</bt><v n="26" />Cag'ag'a laa, rai opo, ka èmu bèdho ne gaged'o. Hèia babèdho èmu ne bhoke eele. Aa rate ana bèdho sèra, bhoke eele aa'i kahèi.<bt>Suddenly, thee was an earthquake, and the prison house shook. Then the doors of that building opened wide. And the chains on the prisoners all opened up.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai opo = gempa bumi, tana"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rai opo = gempa bumi, tana goyang, goncang ; gaged'o = goyang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ropa komedhaa j'aga èmu bèdho na cag'ag'a, ka na kèd'i. Na ladhe hèb'a èmu bèdho bhoke eele aa'i. Ropa nèdhi sèmi èèna, ka na pangee, na, ana bèdho rai aa'i le. Ka na bete samala na, ho neo pamadhe iisi.<bt>When the commander of the prison guards was startled, and got up. He saw the doors of the prison building standing wide open. When he saw that, he thought that the prisoners had all run off. And he drew his sword, intending to kill himself.</bt><v n="28" />Te ngaa Paulus kai ne dènge lii mèdhu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku pamadhe iisi èu, te ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi ka se'e dhu tesa-tesa era!&gt;&gt;<bt>But, Paulus forbade him with a loud/sharp voice, saying, &lt;&lt;don't kill yourself, cause we(exc) are all right here complete!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02134b.tif" rtfFormat="width:7.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Ra pamèu nu'a Paulus si<bt>They clean the wounds of Paulus (coll)</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ropa tadèngi nare lii èèna, komedhaa ne madha'u titu kèna dènge ele ngangee. Ka na pua dhèu rèti hia ne labhu, ka rai la'e asa d'ara bèdho, isi rèbha-rèbha sène. Ka la'e patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha Paulus dènge Silas.<bt>When he heard that voice/those words, the commander was terrified and unable to think. And he ordered people to bring him a lamp, and ran into the prison, with his body trembling. He went and kneeled in front of Paulus and Silas.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="@@Dative = ; rèbha-rèbha = gemetar"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">@@Dative = ; rèbha-rèbha = gemetar ; karèbha = gemetar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Hèia lere nèti rèngu asa li'u, ka na karèi si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama si! Ja'a ne, j'èra bia. Ja'a tao tasamia, sèna ka ja'a baku abhu hahuku?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then he led them outside, and he asked, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers! I here am in terrible trouble. What should I do so that I do not get punished?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ka Paulus si dhaa ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;J'ara ne sèmi ne'e: èu parcaya Lamatua Yesus, sèna ka Na patabuli èu. Sèmi èèna kahèi, dènge isi èmu èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Paulus (coll) responded to him, saying, &lt;&lt;The way is like this: you should believe in the Lord Yesus so the He will release/deliver/save you. It is the same for your household.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="32" />Hèia Paulus dènge Silas padhai lii dènge komedhaa èmu bèdho, dènge isi èmu na aa'i-aa'i ra. Rèngu peka dènge si J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus.<bt>Then Paulus and Silas spoke with the commander of of prison, and all of his household. They told them the Life Way of the Lord Yesus.</bt><v n="33" />D'ara talora mèda risi sa, hèia komedhaa j'aga èèna, lere nèti Paulus dènge Silas, ho ra pamèu nu'a ra. Èle èèna ka, Paulus dènge Silas sarani komedhaa dènge isi èmu na aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>After midnight, then that commander of the guards led Paulus and Silas to clean their wounds. After that, Paulus and Silas baptised that commander and all of his household.</bt><v n="34" />Hèia komedhaa j'aga ne nèti Paulus si asa èmu na, hia si ra'a-rinu. Dhèu ne, dènge isi èmu na karej'e bia, lula rèngu parcaya le Ama Lamatua.<bt>Then this commander of the guards brought Paulus (coll) to his house, giving them food-drink. This person and his household were heavily happy (=thrilled), because they had believed/trusted in God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pana'i = mengobati"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pana'i = mengobati</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Bèli mad'ae aae èèna, dhèu kapai dhu pama'ète lii, hia lii asa komedhaa j'aga èmu bèdho, sèna ka na patabuli eele Paulus dènge Silas nèti d'ara bèdho.<bt>Early in the morning, the leaders who decided disputes sent word to the commander of the prison guards so that he would release Paulus and Silas from prison.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patalale = kasi lapas ("><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">patalale = kasi lapas (</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Tadèngi nare lii èèna, hèia komedhaa ne peka dènge Paulus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu kapai se, rare lii èci le, ho kalua eele miu. De miu dua mi lèpa ka dènge mera-milu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that message, then the commander told Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;The leaders have agreed to release you(pl). So, the two of you can go home in peace (doublet).&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Tadèngi rare sèmi èèna, ka Paulus no'o boe sèmi nare. Ka na peka hari dènge dhèu rèti lii sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o sèmi èèna! Ji'i se dhèu kabarai Roma. De ji'i manèngi hak ji'i kahèi! Dhèu paredha hud'i j'ue lii langu ji'i madhutu atora. Dhu lèke, hud'i parisa uuru ku lii langu, heka huku kèna. Te ngaa rèngu tao boe sèmi èèna. Te rèngu dhae parisa mèka lii ho tenge sasala ji'i, te ngaa rèngu hake kalabhe ji'i ètu madha dhèu ae. Aa abhu mèka sasala èci sa, te ngaa rèngu pamaso le ji'i asa d'ara èmu bèdho. Ne'e ne sisu atora paredha Roma. De rèngu neo kalua eele ji'i iia-iia ka laa, sèna ka dhèu baku re'a sasala ji'i ngaa!? Ji'i ngo'o boe sèmi èèna! Pua dhèu kapai sèra mai unu ra ho kalua eele ji'i. Sèmi èèna ku, heka ji'i sèmi ngare kèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that, Paulus didn't receive it well. And he spoke again with the people who brought that message, saying, &lt;&lt;It's not like that! We(exc) here, are citizens of Roma (&lt;people of Roma society). So we request our rights (loan)! Government people must settle our dispute according to the regulations. What are the correct ways, (they) must examine the dispute first, and only then punish/sentence.But they have not done like that. Cause they have not yet examined our dispute to look for our fault, but they have beat whipping us in front of many people. And they have not yet found a single wrong, but they have already put us in prison. This is in violation/conflict with the rules/regulations of the Roma government. So they want to release us quietly/in a hidden way, so people do not know what our wrong is! We are not going to accept that! Tell those leaders to come themselves to release us. In that way, only then will we accept it!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="a'uku = hukuman; |b37:|r a'uku ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">a'uku = hukuman; <span class="Bold">37:</span> a'uku = hukuman /RED-uku/ @@; kalua iia-iia = kasi kaluar abis perkara / sonde ada parkara</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Ropa dhèu rèti lii sèra lèpa lasi peka lii èèna asa dhèu kapai kota èèna, heka rèngu re'a kèna, na, Paulus dènge Silas dhèu kabarai Roma kahèi. Ka ra madha'u bia.<bt>When those people bringing the message returned to tell that message to the leaders of that city, only then did they know that Paulus and Silas were also Roma citizens. And they were really afraid.</bt><v n="39" />Hèia dhèu kapai sèra mai asa èmu bèdho, ka ra mangaku sasala ra dènge manèngi, sèna ka Paulus dènge Silas baku nasa. Ka ra patabuli dua ra nèti d'ara bèdho. Aa ra manèngi ho dua ra pakèd'i dènge ka nèti kota èèna.<bt>Then those leaders came to that prison, and they confessed their wrong and asked that Paulus and Silas not be angry [can also mean: said they were sorry]. And they release the two of them from prison. And they asked that the two of them leave the city immediately.</bt><v n="40" />Kalua nèti èmu bèdho, ka Paulus si dhuli èmu Lidia. Ètu èmu èèna, dua ra paraga dènge dhèu parcaya sèra. Ka ra aj'a, aa pa'èra d'ara rèngu kahèi. Èle èèna ka, ra pakèd'i nèti kota èèna.<bt>Upon getting out of jail, Paulus (coll) stopped in at Lidia's house. In that house the two of them met with the believing people. And they taught and strengthened their insides. After that, they left that city.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus si lasi asa kota Tesalonika<bt>Paulus (coll) go to the city of Tesalonika</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="17" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, Paulus dènge Silas kako taruu. Rèngu kako re kota èci, ngara na Ampipolis, lasi asa kota leo èci, ngara na Apolonia. Nèti nèi, rèngu kako taruu hari asa kota Tesalonika. Ètu èèna, abhu èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi cue.<bt>After that, Paulus and Silas continued on. They went by a city named Ampipolis, going to another city named Apolonia. From yonder, they continued one again to the city of Tesalonika. There, there was a Jahudi house of worship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rage"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rage</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="maps\Bible\Hkfil-br.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">J'ara nèti kota Pilipi asa kota Berea<bt>The road/journey from the city of Filipi to the city of Berea</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Dhu tema le, ladhe d'ai era èci dhu abhu èmu manèngi-mangaj'i, aa lèke dènge lod'o a'oro sasab'a dhèu Yahudi, Paulus la'e sabaj'a dènge dhèu ètu sèra. Ètu Tesalonika, Paulus maso asa d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i rèngu kahèi. Ka na padhue-padhai dènge rèngu madhutu isi Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua. Paulus madhutu sabaj'a dènge dhèu sèra d'ai tèlu migu.<bt>What was their custom, when they arrived at a place where there was a house of worship, and falling on the Jahudi people's day of rest, Paulus went to pray with the people there. In Tesalonika, Paulus also entered their house of worship. And he discussed with them,according to the contents of God's Holy Writings. Paulus accompanied them in their worship/prayers for three weeks (loan).</bt><v n="3" />Nèngu peka dènge si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe èdhi parisa paie Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua, èdhi te'a, na, nèti uru ka mai ra suri tèke le, na, Dhèu dhu Lamatua moa tèke èèna, limuri mai abhu j'aj'èra ae titu kèna, toke d'ai Na madhe. Te ngaa Lamatua pake koasa Na ho pamamuri hari Ne. Doe ne'e, èdhi te'a le, na, Dhèu dhu Lamatua moa tèke èèna, nuka Yesus!&gt;&gt;<bt>He told them, saying, &lt;&lt;When we(inc) examine God2's Writings, we know that from long ago they had written that the Person who God promised to send would later get much suffering, to the point that He dies. But, God2 used His power to bring Him back to life. Now, we(inc) know that the Person who God2 promised, is Yesus!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Buku Kabha Mèdhi = Buku Kulit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Buku Kabha Mèdhi = Buku Kulit Hitam = Bible</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ropa tadèngi rare sèmi èèna, abhu dhèu Yahudi dhu sèmi rare lii padhai Paulus, hèia ra pa'èci dènge ne. Ètu talora dhèu dhu sèmi rare lii padhai lii nèngu sèra, abhu dhèu Yunani kahèi, dhu d'ara d'èi padètu Lamatua. Aa abhu kahèi pèri-pèri dhèu bhèni kapai ètu kota èèna.<bt>When they heard that, there were Jahudi people who accepted what Paulus was saying, and they joined with him. Among the people who accepted what he was saying, there were also Yunani people who desired to be close to God2. And there were also several women who were prominent/influential of that city.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Te ngaa ama-ama dhèu Yahudi ètu kota èèna d'ara pèd'a, ka ra nasa. Hèia ra kakèj'i-rariu dhèu bhelu ho ra tao kaco. Lod'o dhèu pakaboko ae, ka ra tao maruru ètu d'ara kota èèna. Ra tenge Paulus dènge Silas ho neo nuni rèti asa era dhèu maruru sèra. Ka ra lasi maruru asa èmu Yason, lula Paulus dènge Silas pea ètu èèna.<bt>But, the leaders (fathers) of the Jahudi people in that city, were upset and angry. And they incited evil people to make chaos. When many people had gathered, they caused a commotion/riot in that city. They looked for Paulus and Silas wanting to drag them to the place where people were commotioning. And they went commotioning to the house of Yason, because Paulus and Silas were staying there.</bt><v n="6-7" />Te ngaa ra abhu boe Paulus si ètu èèna. Ka ra nuni rèti Yason dènge pèri-pèri dhèu parcaya asa era pama'ète lii langu. Ra pasala Yason si, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Limuri ne, dhèu rai leo maso asa kota èdhi. Rèngu tao maruru ètu mia-mia. Rèngu neo pa'ele atora ètu kota èdhi, ho gati dènge atora rèngu! Aa Yason ka dhu sèmi nare dhèu sèra manubha ètu èmu na! Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra lab'a atora èdhi, lula rèngu ro'o boe sogo-tagu dhèu aae kapai Roma, nuka Keser. Rèngu sogo-tagu dhoka dhèu aae leo èci, ngara na Yesus.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, they didn't find Paulus (coll) there. so they dragged Yason and several other believing people to the place of deciding disputes. They accused Yason (coll), saying, &lt;&lt;Now people of other lands have entered our(inc) city. They cause riots everywhere. They want to destroy the regulations of our city, to replace them with their regulations!And Yason is the one who received those people to stay temporarily in his house! All of them oppose our regulations, because they do not want to traditionally-worship the Top King of Roma, that is Keser. They only traditionally-worship another/different king, named Yesus.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ropa tadèngi rare lii èèna, ngangee dhèu kapai dènge dhèu-dhèu dhu ètu sèra sa, mulai kaco.<bt>When they heard that, the thinking of the leaders and the other people there began to be chaotic/disordered.</bt><v n="9" />Hèia dhèu-dhèu kapai kota pua Yason dènge dhèu parcaya leo sèra, b'ae doi, j'aj'i mi tadha rèngu tao heka maruru, dènge rèngu rai boe. Ladhe b'ae rare, heka dhèu kapai sèra patabuli eele Yason si kèna.<bt>Then the leaders of that city ordered Yason and other believing people to pay money, as a sign that they would no longer cause disruption, and they would not flee. When they had paid, only then did those leaders release Yason (coll).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dènge ~ d'ènge"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dènge ~ d'ènge</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus si lasi asa kota Berea<bt>Paulus (coll) go to the city of Berea</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />D'ai mèda èèna, dhèu parcaya ètu kota Tesalonika sèra pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Be'a risi èdhi pua Paulus dènge Silas pakèd'i lasi asa era leo.&gt;&gt; Ka ra pua dua ra lasi asa kota èci, ngara na Berea. D'ai nèi, ka dua ra maso asa èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi.<bt>When night arrived, the believers there in that city of Tesalonika thought that, &lt;&lt;It would be best for us(inc) to tell Paulus and Silas to leave for another place.&gt;&gt; And they told the two of them to go to a city, named Berea. Arriving there, the two of them went into the Jahudi people's house of worship.</bt><v n="11" />Dhèu Yahudi ètu Berea sèra, leo nèti dhèu Yahudi ètu Tesalonika. Te rèngu d'èi nanene, aa neo sèmi rare lii padhai lii Paulus si. Dhèu Berea sèra nanene paie Paulus si, ka ra parisa toke lutu isi Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua bèli-bèli mèu-mèda. Rèngu neo re'a, ngaa dhu Paulus si peka, lèke do aad'o.<bt>Those Jahudi people in Berea, were different from the Jahudi people in Tesalonika. They wanted to listen, and wanted to receive what Paulus (coll) had to say. Those people of Berea listened carefully to Paulus (coll) and they examined in detail the contents of God's Holy Writings every day, day and night. They wanted to know if what they were saying was true/correct, or not.</bt><v n="12" />Nèti èèna ka, dhèu Yahudi ae ètu èèna, parcaya Lamatua Yesus. Mesa boe rèngu di, te abhu dhèu aae-dhèu kapai Yunani sèra dhu parcaya kahèi. Rèngu dhu parcaya sèra, abhu dhèu bhèni dènge dhèu mone.<bt>Because of that, many Jahudi people in that place believed in the Lord Yesus. Not only them alone, but Yunani people who were prominent/influential also believed. Those who believed, included both women and men.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hango = pengaruh (kuno)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hango = pengaruh (kuno)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa ropa dhèu Yahudi ètu Tesalonika tadèngi, na, Paulus si aj'a kahèi Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua ètu Berea, ka rèngu mai dadugu-rariu dhèu Berea sèra, sèna ka ra tao maruru ètu èèna kahèi.<bt>But, when Jahudi people in Tesalonika heard that Paulus (coll) were also teaching God2's Word/Sayings in Berea, they came to incite the people of Berea to cause a commotion/riot there as well.</bt><v n="14" />Nèti èèna ka, dhèu parcaya ètu Berea sèra lere Paulus lai-lai asa sebhe dhasi. Te ngaa Timotius dènge Silas pea taruu ètu Berea.<bt>Because of that, the believing people in Berea lead Paulus quickly to the edge of the ocean. But Timotius and Silas continued to stay in Berea.</bt><v n="15" />Dhèu sèra lere Paulus d'ai kota èci, ngara na Atena. Ka ra tèke eele ne ètu nèi, aa rèngu lèpa hari mai asa Berea. Rèngu rèti lii moa Paulus hia Timotius dènge Silas, sèna ka pamata ia ka, ho mai pa'èci dènge nèngu ètu Atena.<bt>Those people led Paulus until a city, named Atena. And they left him yonder, and they returned back coming to Berea. They took Paulus' instructions to Timotius and Silas, so that they wouldn't delay any longer, to come join him in Atena.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèba-namo = pelabuhan; |b15:|r baku panèbhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hèba-namo = pelabuhan; <span class="Bold">15:</span> baku panèbhu = jang lama-lama ; pamata ia ka = jangan tunggu lai</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus ètu kota kapai Atena<bt>Paulus in the leading city of Atena</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Lod'o Paulus mate mamai Silas dènge Timotius, d'ara na j'èra, lula na nèdhi era sogo-tagu ae titu kèna ètu d'ara kota Atena.<bt>While Paulus was waiting for the coming of Silas and Timotius, Paulus' insides were troubled, because he saw a great many places of traditional-worship in the city of Atena.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="For picture: &lt;&lt;mi dhèu dedha-liru dhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">For picture: &lt;&lt;mi dhèu dedha-liru dhu tadhe boe&gt;&gt; OR &lt;&lt;mi dewa dhu tadhe boe&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn01996b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none">Paulus laladhe era sogo-tagu ètu kota Atena<bt>Paulus looking at place of traditional-worship in the city of Atena</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Te ngaa ètu èèna, abhu dhèu Yahudi dènge dhèu leo kahèi, dhu manèngi-mangaj'i mi Ama Lamatua. Ka Paulus maso asa d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i sèra, ho padhue-padhai dènge rèngu. Bèli-bèli èèna, nèngu la'e d'ara pasa kahèi, ho padhai lii dènge cee dhu na rage.<bt>But there, there were Jahudi people and also other people who worshipped God. And Paulus went into their houses of worship to discuss with them. Every day, he also went into the market to talk with whoever he encountered.</bt><v n="18" />Aa na pakarèi kahèi dènge mese-mese nèti dua kaboko dhèu ètu èèna. Ca kaboko madhutu a'aj'a Epikuros, aa ca kaboko hari, ngara na Stoa.<bt>And he also debated with teachers from two groups there. One groups followed the teachings of Epikuros, and the other group was called Stoa.</bt><note reference="17:18" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu nèti kaboko Epikuros madhutu mese rèngu, ngara na Epikuros. Na aj'a, peka na, mamuri be'a, nuka mamuri karej'e taruu. Baku pusi-pahae dènge ngaa-ngaa dhu leo. Dhèu nèti kaboko Stoa madhutu mese rèngu, ngara na Seno. Na aj'a, peka na, dhèu hud'i j'aga paie ngi'u, dènge ator paie ngangee, toke d'ai dhèu rasa heka j'èra dènge d'ara iisi pèd'a heka.<bt>People of Epikuros' group followed their teacher named Epikuros. He taught that the good life is a life that is always happy. Don't worry about anything else. People of the Stoa group follow their teacher named Seno. He taught that people must manage/control their bodies/selves carefully, and arrange their thinking, to the point that people no longer feel suffering and no longer feel any pain.</bt></note>Ropa na padhai lii, peka na, Yesus mamuri hari nèti mamadhe Na, dhèu cahag'e puu-pee, peka na, &lt;&lt;Leko-monya!&gt;&gt; Abhu cahag'e dhu lalangu ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne, neo laka-seti èdhi ho sogo-tagu dhèu dedha-liru na dhu èdhi tadhe boe!&gt;&gt;<bt>When he spoke, saying that Yesus was alive again from His death, some of them spit with disgust (doublet), saying, &lt;&lt;Lies/Nonsense!&gt;&gt; There were some who slandered/belittled him, saying, &lt;&lt;This person, wants to force us(inc) to traditionally-worship his heavenly people that we do not know!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rage = stumble upon, happen to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rage = stumble upon, happen to bump into; <span class="Bold">18:</span> laka-seti = paksa ; laka = nakal, mau kuasai ; seti = desak, paksa ; puu-pee = spit with disgust</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19-21" />Dhèu Atena dènge dhèu leo dhu mai pea ètu era èèna, ladhe tadèngi lii hiu, do j'ara hiu, na, dhèu d'èlu-mèu sèra tema madhèdi pakaboko ètu ledhe iiki èci, ngara na Areopagus, ho pasilu ngangee ètu èèna. Èle èèna ka, pèri-pèri dhèu nèti rèngu gale rèti Paulus asa nèi, ka ra peka dènge ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu peka sèku dènge ji'i a'aj'a hiu èèna! Te èu padhai lii j'ara hiu dhu pamalaa ji'i. De ji'i manèngi èu lole hari ku ciki, ho ji'i nge'a mèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>The people of Atena and other people who came to live in that place, if/when they heard a new matter/message, or a new way, their wise/knowledgeable people normally sat gathered to exchange thinking at a small mountain/hill, named Areopagus. After that, several people from them invited Paulus there, and they spoke with him, saying, &lt;&lt;Try to explain to us that new teaching! Cause you are explaining a new way, which amazes/confuses us. So we ask you to tell us again a bit, so we can understand clearly.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Èle èèna ka, dhèu pèri nèti"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Èle èèna ka, dhèu pèri nèti rèngu gale rèti Paulus asa kolo ledhe iiki èci, ngara na Areopagus. Ètu era èèna, dhèu d'èlu-mèu tema lasi pakaboko ho pasilu ngangee. Ka ra peka dènge Paulus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mu peka sèku dènge ji'i, a'aj'a hiu èèna!; <span class="Bold">21:</span> Te èu padhai lii j'ara hiu, dhu pamalaa ji'i. De ji'i manèngi èu lole hari ku ciki, ho ji'i nge'a mèu.&gt;&gt;; <span class="Bold">21:</span> (Rèngu manèngi sèmi èèna, lula dhèu Atena dènge dhèu leo dhu mai pea ètu era èèna, ladhe tadèngi lii hiu, do j'ara hiu, na rèngu biasa lasi madhèdi padhue-padhai ètu Areopagus.)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22-23" />Hèia Paulus kèd'i titu, ka na padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu dhèu Atena aa'i-aa'i mi! Ja'a kako palème le d'ara kota miu ne, ka ja'a ke'a, na, miu maj'èni madhutu agama. Ja'a kèdhi era sogo-tagu miu ètu mia-mia. Aa ja'a kèdhi hadhu sogo-tagu èci kahèi, dhu suri, peka na, &lt;Hadhu sogo-tagu ne, era sogo-tagu dhèu dedha-liru leo dhu ji'i tadhe boe!&gt; Sasoa na, miu sogo-tagu le Ama Lamatua, te ngaa miu tadhe mèka Ne. Nèngu ne ka dhu ja'a peka dènge miu.<bt>Then Paulus stood up, and he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;All you(pl) people of Atena! I have walked around your city here, and I know that you are diligent to follow religion. I saw your places of traditional-worship everywhere. And I also saw a traditional-worship stone, on which it was written, saying, &lt;This traditional-worship stone is the place of traditional-worship of the other/foreign heavenly person who we do not know!&gt; That means that you traditionally-worship God, but you do not yet know Him. He is the one who I am telling you about.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="For picture: &lt;&lt;mi dhèu dedha-liru dhu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">For picture: &lt;&lt;mi dhèu dedha-liru dhu tadhe boe&gt;&gt; or &lt;&lt;mi dewa dhu tadhe boe&gt;&gt;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Nèngu ka dhu paj'aj'i dedha-liru, rai-haha dènge isi ra aa'i-aa'i. Nèngu kahèi Lamatua nèti ngaa-ngaa aa'i-aa'i ètu dedha-liru dènge rai-haha. De Nèngu pea boe ètu d'ara èmu sogo-tagu dhu dhèu rai-haha tao.<bt>He is the one who created heaven and earth and all their contents. He also, is Lord/Master of everything in the sky-above and earth-below (pair of doublets). So He does not live inside houses of traditional worship which earthly people make.</bt><v n="25" />Nèngu ka dhu hia a'ae dènge mamuri mi èdhi. Aa Nèngu ka dhu pala-bagi ngaa-ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu èdhi parluu. Te ngaa Nèngu parluu boe ngaa-ngaa. De èdhi dhèu rai-haha bisa boe tulu Nèngu.<bt>He is the one who gives breath and life to us(inc). So, He is the one who distributes everything that we need. But, He does not need anything. So we earthly people cannot help Him.</bt><note reference="17:24-25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Dhèu Aae sèra 8:27, Yesaya 42:5, Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 8:47</note><v n="26" />Nèti dhèu èci di, Lamatua paj'aj'i dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne. Lamatua ka dhu papala rai mi suku-suku ètu rai-haha. Aa Nèngu kahèi dhu paca'e-papuru dhèu paredha madhutu lod'o ra èci-èci.<bt>From just one person, God2 created all the people on this earth. God2 is the one who divides up lands/countries to the tribes/ethnic groups on the earth. And He is also the one who sets up-brings down governments of various lands according to each of their (appropriate) times.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai-liru = awan; |b26:|r ( padedha"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rai-liru = awan; <span class="Bold">26:</span> ( padedha do pahaha / paca'e do papuru / pahua iia do pakarehe ) ; suku &gt; udhu rasa (UNS not know)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paca'e do papuru"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">paca'e do papuru</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Nèngu tao sèmi èèna ka, lula d'ad'èi Nèngu sèna ka èdhi dhèu rai-haha patangi-tenge j'ara ho patadha pabe'a dènge Ne. Mema dhèu rai-haha tenge j'ara, teko-teko ra paraga dènge Ne. Te ngaa Nèngu kaj'èu boe nèti èdhi.<bt>He does that, because He wants us(inc) earthly people to try to know Him well. Earthly people really look for a way to they might possibly meet with Him. But, He is not far from us.</bt><v n="28" />Lii èci, peka na:<bt>One saying, says:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="adu-ue = merintis (bahasa halus)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">adu-ue = merintis (bahasa halus)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Nèngu ka dhu hia èdhi a'ae.<bt>&lt;He is the one who gives us breath.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu ka dhu hia èdhi mamuri.&gt;<bt>He is the one who gives us life.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lii hini èci nèti miu, peka na,<bt>One of your(pl) poets said,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu ne'a hini = poet, penyair"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhèu ne'a hini = poet, penyair ; hini 1 = pantun, peribahasa ; hini 2 = seed ; lii hini = bhs bini ; amo = ; kapua</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Mamuri èdhi mai nèti nèngu.<bt>&lt;Our life comes from him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti èèna ka, èdhi j'aj'i ana-èpu nèngu.&gt;<bt>Because of that, we are his offspring.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Mema lèke ka sèmi èèna. Èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti, ana-èpu Ama Lamatua. De baku pangee, na, Ama Lamatua sama sèmi mèdha sogo-tagu dhu dhèu rai-haha tao nèti hualaa, do hualaa pudhi, do hadhu, madhutu ngangee rèngu.<bt>That is really true. All of us, are God's descendants. So, don't think that God is like the objects of traditional worship which earthly people make from gold, or silver, or stone, according to their thinking.</bt><v n="30" />Uru-uru sèra, mema dhèu dhae re'a mèka j'ara ne'e. Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua soro tèke rèngu mamuri madhutu gagoa rèngu. Te ngaa limuri ne, Nèngu d'èi heka èdhi mamuri sèmi èèna. Nèti èèna ka, Na paredha ho èdhi tèke eele mèdha sogo-tagu sèra, aa lati ka madhutu Ne.<bt>Long ago, people had not yet understood this matter. Because of that, God had to leave them to live according to their stupidity. But, now, He no longer wants us to live like that. Because of that, He commands that we abandon those objects of traditional worship, and go follow Him.</bt><v n="31" />Na peka tèke le lod'o èci, ho Na neo huku dhèu rai-haha aa'i-aa'i ra, lula sasala-sasigo rèngu. Aa Na paj'uj'u mema Dhèu èci j'aj'i Dhèu Pama'ète Lii Langu. Dhèu èèna ka dhu bèli-camèd'a pama'ète lii langu dènge mola. Limuri ne, èdhi te'a le Dhèu Pama'ète Lii èèna, cee ka Nèngu ne. Nèngu èèna dhu madhe le, te ngaa Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>He had set a time/day, for Him to punish all the people of the earth, because of their wrongs (doublet). And He designated beforehand a Person to be His Judge. That Person is the one who in the future would decide cases fairly. Now, we already know that Judge, who He is. He is the one who has died, but God brought Him back to life.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="doi iia = doi perak ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">doi iia = doi perak ; doi mèdhi = copper coins; <span class="Bold">30:</span> gagoa = kebodohan ; goa ~(Ant)~ mèu; <span class="Bold">31:</span> mola-mola = lurus-lurus, adil ; mera-milu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Te ngaa ropa ra tadèngi Paulus peka, na, dhèu madhe mamuri hari, ka dhèu cahag'e dhu pakaboko ètu èèna mari ke'e-ke'e sène. Aa dhèu cahag'e hari d'èi nanene, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i neo nanene èu era. Te ngaa lod'o leo hari ku laa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But when they heard Paulus say a dead person was alive again, some of the people who gathered there laughed mockingly/in scorn. And some of the other people wanted to hear, saying, &lt;&lt;We still want to hear you. But on a different day.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="33" />Hèia Paulus kèd'i eele era èèna.<bt>Then Paulus left that place.</bt><v n="34" />Te ngaa abhu kahèi dhèu dhu pa'èci dènge ne, lula rèngu parcaya le Lamatua Yesus. Nèti talora rèngu sèra, abhu dhèu tuka parisa lii langu ètu Areopagus, ngara na Dionisius. Aa abhu dhèu bhèni èci, ngara na Damaris. Abhu kahèi pèri-pèri dhèu leo hari dhu madhutu rèngu.<bt>But, there were also people who joined him, because they believed in the Lord Yesus. Among them, there was an examiner of disputes on Areopagus, named Dionisius. And there was a woman, named Damaris. There were also several other people who followed them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mari ke'e-ke'e = katawa olok-olok, snicker;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">mari ke'e-ke'e = katawa olok-olok, snicker; <span class="Bold">34:</span> tuka parisa lii langu = lawyer</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus patadha dènge Priskila dènge Akila ètu kota Korintus<bt>Paulus meets Mama Priskila and Father Akila in the city of Korentus</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patadha = baku kanal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">patadha = baku kanal</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="18" />
      <v n="1-3" />Lod'o èèna, abhu dhèu aae kapai paredha Roma, ngara na Klaudius. Na nasa dènge dhèu Yahudi, ka na babèga eele si nèti kota Roma ètu propensi Italia. Ka ra paj'ala asa mia-mia. Hèia abhu dhèu Yahudi èci, ngara na Akila, dènge dhèu èmu na Priskila. Dua ra rai nèti propensi Italia, lasi asa kota Korintus. Akila ne, dhèu nèti propensi Pontus. Sasab'a na, tao mèdha nèti ka'uri badha.<bt>At that time, the Top King of the Roma government was named Klaudius. He was angry with the Jahudi people, and he kicked them out of the city of Roma in the province of Italia. And they scattered everywhere. Then there was a Jahudi person, named Akila, and his wife Priskila. The two of them fled from the province of Italia, going to the city of Korentus. This Akila, was a person from the province of Pontus. His work was making things from animal skins.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lod'o èèna, Paulus tèke eele kota Atena, la'e asa kota Korintus. Ètu èèna, na patadha dènge Akila aa Priskila, lula nèngu dhèu tao mèdha nèti ka'uri kahèi. Rèngu pea pa'èci, aa ra sab'a pa'èci kahèi.<bt>At that time, Paulus also left behind the city of Atena, going to the city of Korentus. In that place, Paulus met with Akila and Priskila, because he was also a person who made things from animal skins. They lived together, and they also worked together.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02138b.tif" rtfFormat="width:8.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:center">Paulus dènge Akila, aa Priskila sab'a pa'èci<bt>Paulus and Akila and Priskila working together</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ladhe d'ai lod'o ae sasab'a dhèu Yahudi, Paulus la'e asa èmu sabaj'a ètu nèi. Ka na pamako dhèu Yahudi dènge dhèu leo sèra, ho parcaya Lamatua Yesus.<bt>When the Jahudi people's day of rest arrived, Paulus went to the house of worship there. And he tried to persuade the Jahudi people, and the other people, to believe in the Lord Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamako = buju (lit. bekin halus)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pamako = buju (lit. bekin halus)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Te ngaa ropa Silas dènge Timotius mai nèti propensi Makedonia, Paulus sab'a heka mèdha nèti ka'uri. Mèda-mèu sasab'a nèngu dhoka holo-nori dhèu Yahudi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua neo hia mai èèna, dhu èdhi mate-mate nèti uru ka mai, Nèngu mai le! Nuka Yesus.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, when Silas and Timotius came from the province of Makedonia, Paulus no longer made thinks from animal skins. Night-day his work was only teaching the Jahudi people, saying, &lt;&lt;The Person who God wants to send here, who we(inc) have been waiting for from long ago, He has already come! It is that Yesus.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Te ngaa abhu pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi dhu loe boe palab'a dènge ne. Aa ra padhai lii pamanahu ne. Ka Paulus caro eele ahu nèti mèdha-papake na, sèna ka j'aj'i mi tadha dhu peka na, nèngu pusi-pahae heka dènge dhèu se, lula rèngu ro'o boe sèmi rare Lii Lolo Be'a dhu na peka-padhai dènge ra. Hèia na padhai lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu se, seli-kolane! Miu pakatele dhilu! Te ngaa, ngaa-ngaa tao boe! Pe èèna na, dui mere pala mi. Nèti doe ne'e ne, ja'a tao heka ai-hèb'a mi miu dhèu Yahudi. Hua iia ja'a laku aj'a-nori suku leo dhu Yahudi boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, there were several Jahudi people who didn't stop opposing him. And they spoke to bring him down. And Paulus brushed the dust from his clothes as a sign that he was no longer concerned with (responsible for) these people, because they didn't want to accept the Good News which he had explained to them. Then he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;You here, are too much! You are deliberately shutting your ears! But, whatever! Later one, you will shoulder-carry your share (=be responsible for the consequences). From this time, I (idiom: hand-mouth) leave you to your own devices, you Jahudi people. It is better for me to go teach other people who are not Jahudi.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèda-mèu = siang-malam ; krèi ~"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">mèda-mèu = siang-malam ; krèi ~ karèi = sejak; <span class="Bold">6:</span> pakatele = sengaja bekin tuli ; pe = nanti, kemudian, in the future ; ai-hèba = (tangan-mulut) parsetan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Padètu dènge èmu sabaj'a èèna, abhu èmu pea èci. Lamatua èmu èèna, ngara na Titius Yustus. Nèngu ne, dhèu Yahudi boe, te ngaa d'ara na d'èi padètu Ama Lamatua. Ropa Paulus tèke eele dhèu Yahudi, na la'e asa d'ara èmu Titius Yustus ne.<bt>Near that house of worship, was the house of Titius Yustus. He was not a Jahudi person, but his insides really yearned for God. And when Paulus left behind the Jahudi people, he went into the house of this Titius Yustus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Nèbhu boe ka, kètu èmu sabaj'a èèna parcaya Lamatua Yesus. Ngara na, Krispus. Isi èmu na aa'i-aa'i, dènge dhèu Korintus dhu leo sèra, parcaya lii dhu Paulus lole dènge ra kahèi. Ka Paulus sarani si aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Not long after that, the head of the house of worship believed in the Lord Yesus. His name was Krispus. His whole household and other people of Korentus, also believed what Paulus had told them. And Paulus baptised them all.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="use full name so don't think"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">use full name so don't think 2 people</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ètu d'ara mèd'a sa, Paulus abhu tanila, ka na tadèngi lii padhai Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;&lt;Paulus! Èu baku madha'u, aa mage d'ara èu roe kahèi! Sasab'a èu dhae èle mèka. De èu hud'i aj'a dhèu sèra taruu dènge Lii Lolo Be'a Ja'a.<bt>One night, Paulus had a vision, hearing God speak, saying, &lt;&lt;Paulus! You should not be afraid, and your insides shouldn't be weak either (don't give up)! Your work is not yet finished. So you must continue to teach these people with My Good News.</bt><v n="10" />Sanèd'e, ee! Èu sab'a boe mesa mu, te Ja'a tèke eele boe èu. Masi ka dhèu paj'èra èu, te ngaa Ja'a tao taruu madha-dhilu mi èu mèu-mèda. Baku bhèlu! Te ètu d'ara kota ne, dhèu Ja'a ae.&gt;&gt;<bt>Remember, oo! You do not work alone, because I will not leave you behind. Even though you will suffer, nevertheless I will be attending you continually night-day. Don't forget! In this city, I have many people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madha-dhilu = perhatian (mata-telinga) ; mèu-mèda"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">madha-dhilu = perhatian (mata-telinga) ; mèu-mèda ~ mèda-mèu = siang-malam</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa tadèngi lii ne, Paulus pea ètu kota Korintus d'ai nèbhu ku, d'ai ca tèu èna hèru. Na aj'a dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra, J'ara Mamuri Lamatua.<bt>When he heard that message, Paulus stayed on in the city of Korentus for awhile. He taught people there the Way of Life of the Lord, for one year and six months.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ca tèu èna hèru = 1"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ca tèu èna hèru = 1 tahun enam bulan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />D'ara tèu èèna, ra ded'e dhèu èci j'aj'i gubernur ètu propensi Akaya. Ngara na, Galio.<bt>In that year/time, they appointed a person to be the governor of the province of Akaya. His name was Galio.</bt><note reference="18:12" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu dhu suri ètu hadhu èci, rèngu ded'e Galio j'aj'i gubernur ètu Akaya, hèru Juli, tèu 51.<bt>According to what is written on one stone, they appointed Galio to be governor of Akaya, in the month of Juli in year 51.</bt></note>Ka pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi pare'a lii ho ère rèti Paulus asa madha gubernur, ètu era pama'ète lii langu.<bt>And several Jahudi people agreed to drag Paulus in front of the governor, in the place of deciding disputes.</bt><v n="13" />Ka ra galaa Paulus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne, dadugu dhèu ae ho maso agama hiu, masi ka dhèu paredha Roma mangaku boe agama èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>And they accused Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;This person here, incites many people to enter a new religion, even though the Roma government people do not recognise that religion!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Te ngaa ropa Paulus neo bhoke hèb'a neo siri iisi na, cag'ag'a laa gubernur kai ne. Gubernur pajèka dènge dhèu Yahudi dhu galaa Paulus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Weh! Miu dhèu Yahudi se, pasa dhilu miu, ee! Ladhe miu mai galaa dhèu dhu tao j'ara bhelu-katub'a, do, dhèu pamadhe dhèu, ja'a hud'i tao ai-hèb'a kèna.<bt>But when Paulus wanted to open his mouth to defend himself, suddenly the governor forbade him. The governor scolded them, the Jahudi people who accused Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;We! You Jahudi people, pay attention, ee! If you came accusing someone of doing something evil, or someone killing someone, I would give it due attention [last contains sense of obliged to hear case].</bt><v n="15" />Te ngaa lii galaa miu ne, lii langu d'ara èmu miu unu mi! Miu dhoka pasala d'ara, lula-nèti atora agama Yahudi miu unu mi, lula-nèti lii padhai lii, aa lula-nèti ngara-ngara dhèu di.<bt>But, your accusation here, is an internal dispute in your own house! You are only disagreeing about regulations of your own Jahudi religion, and about words, and about mere names of people.</bt><note reference="18:15" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu Yahudi d'èi titu kèna tao lii langu lula-nèti j'aj'aj'i dhèu.<bt>The Jahudi people loved to dipute over people's origins.</bt></note>De lii langu sèmi sèra, dhèu paredha pama'ète boe!&gt;&gt;<bt>So those matters are not the (business) for government people to decide!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="siri iisi = bela diri ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">siri iisi = bela diri ; kai = 1) larang, 2) togor ; pajèka = masparak ; bhelu-katub'a ; heka tao = baru perhatikan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Èle, hèia gubernur babèga eele si nèti era pama'ète lii langu èèna.<bt>After that, the governor kicked them out from that place of handling disputes.</bt><v n="17" />Ka dhèu-dhèu Yunani ètu èèna kèpe dhèu èci, ngara na Sostenes. Nèngu ne, kapala èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi. Ka nuni rèti, hèia ra game ne ètu madha gubernur. Te ngaa gubernur pusi-pahae boe si kahèi.<bt>And the Yunani people in this place, grabbed one person named Sostenes. He was the head of the Jahudi people's house of worship. And they dragged him, then they beat him in front of the governor. But the governor didn't even pay any attention.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nèti Korintus, Paulus lèpa hari asa kota Antiokia ètu propensi Siria<bt>From Korentus, Paulus goes back to the city of Antiokia in the province of Siria</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18-19" />Èle èèna ka, Paulus pea taruu ètu Korintus. Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu, ka na palangu lii dènge dhèu parcaya ètu èèna. Hèia la'e asa kota èci, ngara na Kengkrea, palere dènge Priskila dènge Akila, ho ra mate kapa. Ètu èèna, Paulus lusu pakahoni kètu na, sèna ka j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, ngaa dhu nèngu pajaji le uru èèna dènge Lamatua, limuri ne nèngu tao nare le.<bt>After that, Paulus continued living in Korentus. But eventually, he took his leave from the believing people in that place. Then he went to a city named Kengkrea, accompanying Priskila and Akila, to wait for a ship. In that place, Paulus shaved his head clean as a sign that what he had previously promised God2, he had already done.</bt><note reference="18:18-19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ladhe abhu dhèu Yahudi dhu neo pa'èki lii pajaji dènge Lamatua, nèngu hud'i puasa ku. Ladhe d'ai èle ku lii pajaji èèna, na lusu pakahoni kètu na. Ladhe ètu d'ara sasuri <span class="Italic">Sensus </span>6:18.<bt>When there was a Jahudi person who wanted to bind a promise with God2, he must first fast. Then when he had finished the time/days of that promise, he would shave his head clean. See in the letter of Bilangan (Numbers) 6:18.</bt></note>Ka ra ca'e kapa pakèd'i lasi asa kota Epesus. D'ai nèi, rèngu puru. Hèia Paulus tèke eele angalai na dhèu dua sèra, ka na maso asa d'ara èmu sabaj'a dhèu Yahudi. Ètu èèna, na padhue-padhai dènge dhèu Yahudi sèra.<bt>And they embarked on a ship leaving for the city of Epesus. Arriving yonder, they disembarked. Then Paulus left his two companions, and he went into the Jahudi people's house of worship. In this place, he discussed with the Jahudi people there.</bt><v n="20" />Ètu d'ara padhue-padhai ne, dhèu Yahudi ae dhu d'èi nanene, ka ra manèngi ho Paulus pea dènge si ako nèbhu ciki. Te ngaa na dhaa boe.<bt>In their discussions, many Jahudi people wanted to listen, and they asked that Paulus stay with them for awhile. But, he did not respond.</bt><v n="21" />Hèia na palangu lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari, mage miu d'ara kura! Ladhe Lamatua bhoke j'ara, bèli-camèd'a ja'a lèpa hari mai paraga dènge miu.&gt;&gt; Padhai lii nare, hèia la'e dènge ka tèke eele Epesus.<bt>Then he took his leave, saying, &lt;&lt;Older-younger siblings, don't be offended/disappointed! If God2 opens the way, in the future I will return again coming to meet with you(pl).&gt;&gt; After speaking, then he left Epesus behind.</bt><note reference="18:21" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu dhu peka na, Paulus neo tèke eele si, lula na d'èi titu kèna la'e madhutu kalela Paska ètu kota Yerusalem. Ladhe ngèlu aae dhasi aae mai, nèngu j'aj'i heka pakèd'i.<bt>There are knowledgeable people who say that Paulus wanted to leave them behind, because he really wanted to go follow the festival of Paska (Passover/Easter) in the city of Yerusalem. When the big wind-big waves came, he would no longer be able to leave.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka la'e taruu dènge kapa asa kota Kaisarea. D'ai nèi, Paulus puru, ka la'e asa Yerusalem, la'e paraga dènge dhèu-dhèu parcaya ètu èèna. Èle èèna ka, na lèpa hari asa kota Antiokia.<bt>And he continued on by ship to the city of Kaisarea. Arriving here, Paulus disembarked, and went to Yerusalem, going to meet with the believing people there. After that, he went back to the city of Antiokia.</bt><v n="23" />Na pea ètu nèi ako nèbhu, hèia na kako palème propensi Galati dènge propensi Frigia. Ètu d'ara kakako nèngu ne, Paulus pa'èra d'ara dhèu parcaya sèra.<bt>He stayed yonder for awhile, then he went around the province of Galatia and the province of Frigia. On his journey, Paulus strengthened the insides of the believing people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Apolos sab'a ètu kota Epesus dènge kota Korintus<bt>Apolos works in the city of Epesus and the city of Korentus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Lod'o èèna, abhu dhèu Yahudi èci nèti kota Aleksandria ètu propensi Masir. Ngara na, Apolos. Nèngu ne, dhèu dhu mèu padhai lii, aa ne'a isi Sasuri Ama Lamatua kahèi. Nèngu heka nare kota Epesus kèna.<bt>At that time, there was a Jahudi person from the city of Aleksandria in the province of Masir (Egypt). His name was Apolos. He was a person skilled in speaking, and also understood/knew the contents of God's Writings. He had just arrived in the city of Epesus.</bt><v n="25" />Nèngu tadèngi le lii lole nèti Lamatua Yesus, te ngaa mamèu na d'ai iia mèka. Aa na d'èi kahèi lolo hari dènge dhèu leo. Na lole dènge d'ara kateme, aa ngaa dhu na peka-padhai sèra, lèke tare'a. Nane'a nèngu dhoka Yohanis sarani dhèu, ladhe ra loe eele ka nèti tao sasala-sasigo rèngu.<bt>He had already heard the story about the Lord Yesus, but, his understanding was not yet complete. And he also wanted to tell other people in turn. He spoke with whole insides (=earnestly, fervently, passionately), and what he told them was really correct. His understanding was only about Yohanis baptising people, if they stopped and left behind their wrongs (doublet).</bt><v n="26" />Ca tèka, ka na padhai lii dènge d'ara bani dhu pahuni boe ètu d'ara èmu manèngi-mangaj'i dhèu Yahudi. Priskila dènge Akila ètu èèna kahèi, aa tadèngi na padhai lii. Ropa èle manèngi-mangaj'i, hèia dua ra gale Apolos ho dhuli èmu rèngu. D'ai èmu, ka dua ra heka lole lutu sela mi Apolos lula-nèti J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus.<bt>One time, he was speaking boldly without hiding anything, in the Jahudi people's house of worship. Priskila and Akila were also there, listening to him speak. When the worship/praying was finished, the two of them invited Apolos to stop in at their house. Arriving home, they fully explained in detail to Apolos about the Life Way of the Lord Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="maj'èni = rajin; |b26:|r pamèu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">maj'èni = rajin; <span class="Bold">26:</span> pamèu = memperjelas ; lutu aamu-aamu = ceritakan lebih mendetail</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Èle èèna ka, Apolos pama'ète ho la'e asa propensi Akaya. Dhèu parcaya ètu Epesus d'ara èci kahèi dènge nèngu. Hèia rèngu tao sasuri èci, pa'adhu hia a'ari rèngu ètu Akaya sèra, sèna ka ra sèmi rare Apolos dènge be'a. Ropa na sèmi nare sasuri èèna, ka pakèd'i dènge. D'ai Akaya, nèngu soru-bara tare'a-re'a dhèu-dhèu parcaya ètu sèi.<bt>After that, Apolos decided to go to the province of Akaya. The believing people in Epesus were of one accord with him. Then they made a letter, directed to their elder-younger siblings in Akaya, so that they would receive Apolos well. When he received that letter, he left immediately. Arriving in Akaya, he truly looked after/take care of (doublet) those believing people yonder.</bt><v n="28" />Ètu èèna kahèi, nèngu padhue-padhai aa pakarèi dènge dhèu Yahudi sèra ètu madha dhèu ae, te ngaa ra segi boe ne. Na pake isi Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua ho aj'a dhèu sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua moa tèke le neo hia mai, dhu èdhi tatae nèbhu nare sange ne'e, nuka Yesus!&gt;&gt;<bt>There also, he discussed and recip-questioned with the Jahudi people, in front of many people, but they did not beat/overcome him. He used the contents of the Writings of God to teach people there, saying, &lt;&lt;The Person who God promised to send here, who we(inc) have awaited a long time until now, that is Yesus!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palab'a = melawan ; pab'ala ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">palab'a = melawan ; pab'ala = bertengkar ; pakarèi = batanya</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus lèpa hari asa kota Epesus<bt>Paulus goes back to the city of Epesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="19" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o Apolos ètu Korintus era, Paulus kako palème le rae-rae ètu ledhe-ledhe sèra. Ka na d'ai kota Epesus. Ètu èèna, na paraga dènge pèri-pèri dhèu dhu parcaya le Lamatua Yesus.<bt>When Apolos waas still in Korentus, Paulus went around through the villages in the mountains. And he arrived in the city of Epesus. There he met with several people who had believed in the Lord Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ka na karèi si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari! Lod'o miu parcaya Lamatua Yesus, miu sèmi mere le Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, do dhae?&gt;&gt;<bt>And he asked them, saying, &lt;&lt;Elder-younger siblings! When you(pl) believed in the Lord Yesus, did you receive God2's Holy Spirit, or not yet?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka ra dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhae! Ji'i se dhae tadèngi mèka, peka na, Ama Lamatua unu Roh dhu sèmi èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they answered, saying, &lt;&lt;Not yet! We(exc) have not yet heard that God has a Spirit like that.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka Paulus karèi hari si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lod'o miu sarani èèna, miu pake sarani mia ka?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Paulus asked them further, saying, &lt;&lt;So when they baptised you, which baptsim did they use?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ra dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ra sarani ji'i madhutu j'ara dhu Yohanis sarani dhèu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they responded, &lt;&lt;They baptised us according to the way/manner that Yohanis baptised people.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ka Paulus peka, na, &lt;&lt;Nanene ku laa! Yohanis sarani dhèu, j'aj'i mi tadha, na, dhèu ae eele nèti sasala-sasigo ra. Te ngaa mi sanèd'e, ee! Bèli-bèli èèna, nèngu ka dhu aj'a dhèu Isra'el, peka na, rèngu hud'i parcaya ku Yesus, nuka Dhèu dhu Lamatua pua mai.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Paulus said, &lt;&lt;Listen up! Yohanis baptised people as a sign for many people that they had stopped their wrongs (doublet). But you should remember this, ee! Every day, he taught the people of Isra'el, saying, they must believe in Yesus, that is that Person whom God2 sent here.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="19:4" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 3:11, Markus 1:4, 7-8, Lukas 3:4, 16, Yohanis 1:26-27</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ropa tadèngi rare, hèia ra manèngi sèna ka Paulus sarani si, ho rèngu j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus.<bt>When they heard that, they asked that Paulus baptise them so the could be people belonging to the Lord Yesus.</bt><v n="6" />Ka ropa Paulus bane ai mi dhèu se'e, aa na manèngi-mangaj'i hia ra, hèia Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci puru asa dhèu se'e. Ka rèngu mulai padhai lii-lii dhu leko-leo, dhu rèngu tadèngi mèka ciki sa. Aa Lamatua pake si ho peka ngaa dhu èèna na j'aj'i bèli-camèd'a.<bt>And when Paulus placed his hands on these people, and prayed for them, then God2's Holy Spirit descended to these people. And these people began to speak, various sorts of different languages which they had never ever heard. And God2 used them to say what would happen in the future.</bt><v n="7" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra dhèu canguru dua.<bt>All of them were 12 people.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="baa ai = tumpang tangan (kasi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">baa ai = tumpang tangan (kasi berkat)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua pake Paulus ètu Epesus<bt>God2 uses Paulus in Epesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Lod'o Paulus pea ètu kota Epesus, nèngu biasa maso asa d'ara èmu-èmu sabaj'a ho aj'a-nori dhèu lula-nèti paredha Ama Lamatua toke j'ara dhu lutu aamu-aamu. Na padhai lii dhu pa'abhe boe. Na tao sèmi èèna, toke d'ai tèlu hèru.<bt>While Paulua was staying in the city of Epesus, he normally/often entered into the houses of worship to teach people the commands/rule of God right up to the fine details. He spoke without holding back. He did that for three months.</bt><v n="9" />Te ngaa abhu kahèi dhèu cahag'e dhu sèmi rare boe a'aj'a na, ka ra palab'a dènge ne. Rèngu dadugu-rariu dhèu, sèna ka baku madhutu J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus. Nèti èèna ka, Paulus dènge dhèu parcaya sèra tèke eele èmu sabaj'a ne, ka lasi pakaboko ètu èmu sakola. Kapala sakola èèna, ngara na Tiranus.<bt>But there were also some people who did not accept his teaching, and they opposed him. They incited people so that they didn't follow the Life Way of the Lord Yesus. Because of that, Paulus and the believing people left behind the house of worship, and went to gather in a school building. The master of the school was named Tiranus.</bt><v n="10" />Paulus aj'a ètu era ne'e, d'ai dua tèu, toke d'ai dhèu-dhèu ètu propensi Asia aa'i-aa'i ra tadèngi Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus. Dhu nanene se, dhèu-dhèu Yahudi dènge dhèu leo kahèi.<bt>Paulus was teaching in this place for two years, until the people in all the province of Asia had heard the Good News of the Lord Yesus. Those who heard were Jahudi people and other people as well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Dhu nanene = @@ Ndao can"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">Dhu nanene = @@ Ndao can begin with Dhu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-ana nèti Sakewa<bt>The offspring of Skewa</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Lod'o èèna, Lamatua hia Paulus koasa ho na tao rupa-rupa tadha malaa dhu kapai.<bt>At that time, God2 gave Paulus power for him to do various sorts of really amazing signs.</bt><v n="12" />Conto sèmi, rèti bèla dhu èki kètu, do bèla dhara hake dhu Paulus pake le, ho sad'i pagoi lèke mi dhèu pèd'a, na èi papèd'a dhèu sèra èle dènge. Sèmi èèna kahèi, dènge nidhu bhelu sèra kalua nèti dhèu.<bt>Like, they took a cloth that had bound a head, or cloth waistband which Paulus had used, for as long as they touched it to a sick person, the sicknesses of people would disappear immediately. Similarly, even evil spirits would all leave immediately.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lesu = lenso ; pagoi ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lesu = lenso ; pagoi = touch</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13-14" />Ètu èèna, abhu ama agama dhèu Yahudi èci, dènge ana mone na dhèu pidhu. Dhèu èèna, ngara na Sakewa. Ana na sèra biasa lasi asa mia-mia ho babège eele nidhu nèti dhèu. Rèngu neo pake sèku ngara Yesus ho babège eele nidhu nèti dhèu, dènge peka, &lt;&lt;Èu tadhe Yesus dhu Paulus lole èèna? Ja'a paredha èu, pake kolongara Yesus, ho kalua ka nèti dhèu ne'e!&gt;&gt;<bt>There, there was a Jahudi religious head (=*priest), with his seven sons. That person was named Skewa. His sons often went to various places to evict evil spirits from people. They wanted to try to use the name of Yesus to go evict evil spirits from people, by saying, &lt;&lt;You know Yesus whom Paulus talks about? I command you using the name of that Yesus, to come out from this person!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ca tèka, ropa ra neo paredha sèmi èèna, abhu nidhu bhelu èci dhu dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a tadhe Yesus. Aa ja'a tadhe Paulus kahèi. Te ngaa miu se, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, when they commanded like that, one of the evil spirits responded, saying, &lt;&lt;I know/recognise Yesus. And I also know Paulus. But as for you(pl) here, who are you?&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="16" />Ka dhèu dhu nidhu tao èèna, nasa bia. Na j'ubhu lai-lere, aa na j'èli-marèu si. Na panu'a si, aa na ciu pamae eele kodho ètu ua ra, toke rèngu rai ele hui nèti èmu èèna, dènge heka mèdha-papake.<bt>And the person who the evil spirit had done (=bothered/possessed), was furious. He punched them right and left, and he stomped-crunching them underfoot. He wounded them, and he tore off the clothes on their bodies, to the point that they fled wildly from that house, and no longer had (their) clothes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lai-lere ; j'èli - injak ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lai-lere ; j'èli - injak ; marèu = sampai tekan ; panu'a = bekin luka ; rai ele hui = Idiom ; ua</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia lii lolo ne pale-lème nèti hèb'a èci asa hèb'a èci, toke dhèu Epesus sèra tadèngi aa'i. Dhèu Yahudi dènge dhèu Yahudi boe tadèngi kahèi. Sad'i cee èèna ka dhu tadèngi lii lolo ne, aa'i-aa'i ra malaa. Nèti èèna ka, ra koa-kio kolongara Lamatua Yesus, lula Na hia le koasa kapai mi Paulus.<bt>Then, this story spread around from one mouth to another, until all the people of Epesus heard about it. The Jahudi people heard; in the same way, the non-Jahudi. The point is, whoever heard that story, they all were amazed/confused. Because of that they praised the name/reputation of the Lord Yesus, because He gave great power/authority to Paulus.</bt><v n="18" />Hèia dhèu dhu parcaya hiu sèra, mai asa a'ari dhu parcaya nèti uru sèra, ho bhoke d'ara rèngu, sèna ka ra mangaku sasala-sasigo ra.<bt>Then people who had just recently believed, came to their fellow believers (&lt;elder-younger siblings who believed), for them to open their insides so they could confess their wrongs (doublet).</bt><v n="19" />Nèti rèngu se, abhu dhu pake na'i kahèi. Ka ra pakaboko aa'i sasuri ajima rèngu sèra, ho ra tunu eela si. Ladhe ige kab'ua buku-buku sèra, lèmi nguru riho doi iia.<bt>Among those people there were those who also used magic/science/medicine. They gathered all their amaulet/talismen writings (=black magic books), to burn them. If the price/worth of those books were counted, (it would be) 50,000 silver moneys.</bt><note reference="19:19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Rèngu tunu eele buku-buku rèngu se, sèna ka j'aj'i tadha rèngu madhutu heka isi buku sèra. Ca doi iia èèna, sama sèmi gaji tuka d'ara ca lod'o. De buku-buku dhu ra tunu eela sèra, kab'ua ae titu kèna.<bt>They burned their books as a sign that they no longer followed the contents of those books. One of those silver coins, is the same as the wage for a craftsman for one day. So those books that they burned, were very valuable.</bt></note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02002b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Dhèu Epesus tunu buku-buku ajima rèngu<bt>Efesus people burning their amulet books</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu parcaya sèra palolo Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua mèda-mèu palème era. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu-dhèu parcaya asa tabha ae, lula Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua ne, tao paie mamuri dhèu ètu mia-mia.<bt>After that, those believing people spread the Good News of God2 night-day around that area. Because of that, the believing people kept increasing in number, because the Wrds/Sayings of God improved/fixed/blessed people's lives everywhere.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nèti mamènyi kakee = kasi rasa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">nèti mamènyi kakee = kasi rasa enak ; kakee = manis ; papèdu = rasa pahit ; babe'a = kebaikan ; uba = merobah</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu maruru ètu kota Epesus<bt>People cause a commotion/riot in the city of Epesus</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tao maruru = bekin hebo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tao maruru = bekin hebo</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Èle èèna ka, Paulus pama'ète ho lèpa asa Yerusalem. Te ngaa d'ara nèngu d'èi risi la'e uuru asa propensi Makedonia dènge propensi Akaya, heka na kako taruu asa kota Yerusalem kèna. Nèngu dhu pangee le ètu d'ara nèngu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Be'a risi ja'a pa'èle aa'i uuru ku sasab'a ja'a ètu era se'e. Te tasamia èèna ka, ja'a d'ai kota Roma kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Paulus decided to return to Yerusalem. But, his insides really wanted to go first to the province of Makedonia and the province of Akaya, and only then continue going to the city of Yerusalem. He had been thinking, that, &lt;&lt;It would be good if I first complete all my work in these places. Cause no matter what happens, I will arrive in the city of Roma.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="22" />Nèti èèna ka, na pua angalai dhèu dua, nuka Timotius dènge Erastus, ho lasi uuru asa Makedonia. Te ngaa nèngu pea ako nèbhu era ètu propensi Asia.<bt>Because of that, he told his two companions, that is Timotius and Erastus, to go ahead to Makedonia. But he stayed on for awhile in the province of Asia.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Lod'o èèna, ètu kota Epesus, j'aj'i lii langu kapai lula-nèti J'ara Mamuri Yesus.<bt>At that time, in the city of Epesus, a huge dispute arose, because of Yesus Life Way.</bt><v n="24" />Lii langu èèna, j'aj'aj'i na sèmi ne'e ka: ètu Epesus, abhu tuku èci, ngara na Demetrius. Nèngu biasa pasilu doi iia ho tao èmu sogo-tagu dhu ana iiki hia mi dewi èci, ngara na Artemis. Lula sasab'a ne nèti a'oto ae, ka na pake dhèu sab'a ae titu kèna. Nèti èèna ka, na abhu doi-dhari ae.<bt>That dispute had its beginnings like this: There in Epssus, there was a craftsman named Demetrius. Hee normally changed silver money to make very small houses of traditional worship for a goddess (loan) named Artemis. Because this work brought great profit, he used many workers. Because of that, he got a lot of money.</bt><v n="25" />Ca lod'o, hèia Demetrius pakaboko aa'i tuka-tuka na, dènge tuka-tuka dhu leo sèra, ka na peka dènge si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama dènge a'ari! Miu me'a, na, mamuri èdhi be'a sèmi ne'e ne, lula sasab'a ne'e hia èdhi doi ae.<bt>One day/time, Demetrius gathered all his craftsmen, and other craftsmen, and spoke to them, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers and older-younger siblings! You(pl) know that our(inc) lives are good like this, because this work gives us lots of money.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhèu tuku ~ ana tuku ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhèu tuku ~ ana tuku = orang pandai perak ; a'oto ae = banyak untung /RED-utu/ ; dhari ae = (lit. banyak tali) = banyak uang</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Te ngaa limuri ne, èdhi tèdhi le dènge musi madha, aa tadèngi le dènge ro'a dhilu, tatao nèti lii padhai lii Paulus. Nèngu ka tuka dadugu dhèu ae, peka na, mèdha dhu èdhi tuku se gaguna na aad'o. Madhutu nèngu, patung dhu èdhi tao se, dhoka dewa-dewi leko-monya di. Mesa boe dhèu ètu kota Epesus di dhu lèka lii padhai lii na, te ngaa dhèu ètu propensi Asia kahèi.<bt>But now, we have seen with our own eyes, and heard with our earholes, the results of what Paulus has been saying. He is a provocateur of many people that things which we metal-work have no use. According to him, these statues (loan) that we make, are only just nonsense gods-goddesses. The people in the city of Epesus are not alone in believing what he is saying, but people in the province of Asia as well.</bt><v n="27" />De mi nanene paie! Bèli-camèd'a, èdhi se j'aj'i hari ngaa era, ladhe dhèu ae-ae lasi madhutu Paulus si? Tatu dhèu ro'o heka hèli mèdha sasab'a èdhi! Sanèd'e, ee! Limuri ne, dhèu ae sogo-tagu bhèni iia dedha-liru, Artemis. Pale-lème propensi Asia, toke d'ai ro'a aae-ro'a iiki ètu rai-haha ne, dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra mai koa-kio ne, ètu èmu kapua sogo-tagu na ètu kota Epesus ne. Mage dhoka dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, dhèu mai heka sogo-tagu ne, ka rèngu mai heka asa ne'e kahèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>So listen well, oo! In the future, what will happen to us, if so many people follow Paulus (coll)? Certainly people will no longer want to buy these things of ours! Remember, oo! Now, many people are traditional worshipping the wonderful heavenly woman, Artemis. Throughtout the province of Asia, until big hole-little hole on this earth (idiom: most remote corners of the earth--hyperbole), everyone comes to praise her, in the Central House of Traditional Worship here in the city of Epesus. Careful lest people no longer come to traditional worship, and they might even no longer come here at all!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa dhèu ae se tadèngi rare ne'e, ka d'ara ra pana-mag'oro. Hèia ra pa'oo-parodha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mamuri Artemis! Artemis dhu hua iia! Èdhi dhèu Epesus koa-kio kolongara Artemis!&gt;&gt;<bt>When these many people heard this, their insides were furious (&lt;hot to the Max degree). Then they shouted/chanted, saying, &lt;&lt;Live Artemis! Artemis is the best/glorious! We people of Epesus praise the name/reputation of Artemis!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="29" />Tadèngi lii dhèu pa'oo-parodha sèmi èèna, hèia dhèu mulai rai lasi nèti mia-mia, pakaboko asa era èèna, toke dhèu pènu sèmi tao cèci sa ètu d'ara kota èèna. Te ngaa dhèu ae se malaa. Ka ra maruru palème j'ara oka-hoo toke d'ai tana lapa taleo aae.<bt>When they heard people shouting/chanting like that, people began to run from everywhere gathering in that place until people were crowded into that (part of) city. But many people were amazed/confused. And they cause a commotion/riot all along the main road/highway until arriving at the wide field [a term used for a place for public gatherings, sports, speeches]. They grabbed two people and took them to that place. Those two people, one was named Gayus, and the other, Aristarkus. They grabbed these two people, because the two of them were followers of Paulus from Makedonia.</bt><note reference="19:29" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Tana lapa kapai ètu kota Epesus èèna, ra pake ho 1) tao rapat kota, 2) karihu sandiwara, aa 3) olaraga. 26.000 dhèu bisa pakaboko ètu d'ara na. Era èèna ètu tèbhi ledhe Pion. De rupa na beda boe dènge stadion bola kaki limuri ne.</note>Ra kèpe dhèu dua, ka ra rèti asa era èèna. Dhèu dua sèra, èci ngara na Gayus, aa èci hari, Aristarkus. Ra kèpe dhèu dua se, lula rèngu dua ra ana madhutu Paulus nèti Makedonia.<v n="30" />Ropa tadèngi lii ne'e, ka Paulus neo la'e asa talora aae dhèu dhu maruru sèra, te ngaa dhèu parcaya ètu sèra magee ne, ro'o boe hia la'e.<bt>When he heard this matter, Paulus wanted to go into the middle of these people who were causing a commotion, but the believing people there blocked him, not wanting to let him go.</bt><v n="31" />Abhu pèri-pèri dhèu kapai nèti propensi Asia, dhu patadha be'a dènge Paulus. Rèngu pua dhèu lasi peka sèna ka Paulus baku la'e asa talora dhèu ae dhu maruru sèra.<bt>There were several leaders/important people from the province of Asia, who knew Paulus well. They told people to go say that Paulus should not go in among those many people who were causing a commotion.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pana-magoro = panas Max, marah; |b29:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pana-magoro = panas Max, marah; <span class="Bold">29:</span> j'ara okahoo = jalan raya; <span class="Bold">30:</span> magee = halangi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Hèia ètu d'ara tana lapa èèna, dhèu pakarèi j'aj'aj'i lii langu èèna. Cahag'e pa'oo iia d'ara, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e!&gt;&gt; Aa cahag'e hari rodhe, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi èèna!&gt;&gt; Te ngaa ae ka nèti rèngu dhu re'a boe j'aj'aj'i lii langu ne, tasamia. Rèngu sèra, dhoka madhutu rarame di.<bt>Then at that wide field, people were asking each other the cause of that dispute. Some shouted going along with the flow, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this!&gt;&gt; and others called out, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like that!&gt;&gt; But there were many of them who did not know the cause of this dispute, what it was. They only followed along in being rambunctious.</bt><v n="33" />Ètu èèna, abhu kahèi dhèu Yahudi dhu mulai madha'u, lula ra pangee, mage dhoka dhèu ae sèra peka na, dhèu Yahudi se'e ka dhu dadugu-rariu dhèu sèna ka tao maruru èèna. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu tule ca dhèu asa madha ho j'aj'i tuka padhai lii rèngu. Dhèu èèna, ngara na Aleksander. Ra manèngi sèna ka Aleksander bhiri rèngu, peka na, lii langu ne nèti boe dhèu Yahudi. Ka na j'oke kacui-aai na, ho kai dhèu ae se baku maruru. Hèia na mulai bhoke lii padhai lii na, bhiri dhèu Yahudi sèra.<bt>In that place, there were also Jahudi people who began to be afraid, because they thought perhaps those many people would say these Jahudi people were the ones who incited everybody to riot. Because of that, they pushed a person toward the front to be their spokesperson. That person's name was Aleksander. They asked that Aleksander defend/protect them, saying that this dispute was not from the Jahudi people. And he raised his hand to admonish the many people to not cause a commotion. Then he began to speak, defending those Jahudi people.</bt><v n="34" />Te ngaa ropa re'a rare nèngu èèna dhèu Yahudi, ka dhèu se pa'oo asa tabha mèdhu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mamuri Artemis! Artemis dhu hua iia! Èdhi dhèu Epesus koa-kio kolongara Artemis di!&gt;&gt; Rèngu pa'oo-parodha sèmi èèna, nare d'ai dua jam sa.<bt>But, when they knew that he was a Jahudi person, these people shouted increasingly louder, saying, &lt;&lt;Live Artemis! Artemis is the best/glorious! We people of Epesus praise the name/reputation of Artemis!&gt;&gt; They kept shouting like that for two hours.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'oo iia dara = batarea ikut"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pa'oo iia dara = batarea ikut arus; <span class="Bold">33:</span> bhiri = selubung, melindungi, membela, like a a bed protected by a mosquito net; <span class="Bold">34:</span> mèdhu = 1) keras, 2) muntah ; nare dai dua jam = selama ; nare - 1) 3s-ambil, 2) selama, 3) hairy caterpillar (stings if touched)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35-36" />Èle èèna ka, ama kètu paredha ètu kota Epesus kèd'i titu, ka na padhai lii ho na pamau si, peka na, &lt;&lt;A'ari dhèu Epesus! Dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a le, na, dewi Artemis dhu raropa asli na, bèbhe nèti dedha-liru, mai asa èdhi. De èdhi dhèu Epesus ne ka dhu ladhe-leru paie ne. Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu bisa pasisu rare hak èdhi ho madhenge ne, te èèna dhu j'aj'i le lii palolo-papeka nèti uru dhu dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a le. De, nga tao ka miu pa'oo-parodha sèmi ne'e? Hud'i rèngu sène, ra leko-monya madhutu dad'èi ra, te ngaa miu baku tao leli!<bt>After that, the head of the government of the city of Epesus stood up and spoke to calm them down, saying, &lt;&lt;Older-younger siblings of the people of Epesus! Everybody already knows that the goddess Artemis' original (loan) form fell from the sky coming to us(inc). So, we people of Epesus here, are the ones who look after her carefully/well. There is not one person who can argue away our right to guard her, cause what happened is already widely told from long ago for everybody to know. So, why are you shouting like this? Let them say whatever they want, but you(pl) must not act without basis/pointlessly!</bt><v n="37" />Miu nuni mèti dhèu dua sèra asa ne'e mai, nuka sèmi dhèu bhelu sa. Te ngaa rèngu se mana'u boe ngaa-ngaa nèti d'ara èmu kapua sogo-tagu Artemis. Aa ra padhai lii pakarehe boe kolongara be'a dewi Artemis. De miu neo pasala si tasamia?<bt>You drag these two people here as if they are evil people/criminals. But they haven't stolen anything from the Central House of Traditional Worship of Artemis. And they have not slandered the good name/reputation of the goddes Artemis. So on what basis are you accusing them?</bt><v n="38" />Sanèd'e paie-iie! Èdhi dènge era parisa lii. Aa dhèu dhu pama'ète lii nuka mate sèi. De ladhe Demetrius si neo tao lii langu, na, hud'i madhutu ku j'ara-j'ara na, ho rèti asa era pa'uri lii langu.<bt>Remember well (=think about it)! We(inc) have places for examining disputes. And the people who decide disputes are waiting yonder. So, if Demetrius (coll) wants to make a dispute, he must follow the regulations, to take it to the place where disputes are taken care of.</bt><v n="39" />De ladhe abhu j'ara leo dhu rèngu neo galaa, na, hud'i laa rèngu lasi pajiko dènge dhèu heka sèra.<bt>So, if there is another matter which they want to accuse, they must first go evaluate it with the adat leaders.</bt><v n="40" />Mage dhoka dhèu paredha Roma pèci sasala èèna mi dedha èdhi, lula maruru ne'e. Ladhe ra neo tenge j'aj'aj'i lii langu ne'e, èdhi dhaa peka na ngaa? Te lii langu ne, dènge boe kolo-kapua!&gt;&gt;<bt>Be careful lest the Roma government people throw this wrongdoing on us(inc), because of this commotion. If they want to look for the source of this dispute, what will we tell them? Cause this dispute has no basis or purpose (&lt;botanical metaphor tip-base)!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="41" />Ropa na padhai lii nare, hèia ama kètu paredha èèna, pua si lèpa. Ka ra lèpa dènge ka.<bt>When he finished speaking, that aforementioned head of the government told them to go home. And they went home immediately.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tao leli = bekin sambarang; |b38:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tao leli = bekin sambarang; <span class="Bold">38:</span> pa'uri = urus; <span class="Bold">40:</span> kolo-kapua = ujung-pohon</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus si lasi hari asa propensi Makedonia<bt>Paulus (coll) go back to the province of Makedonia</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="20" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa dhèu sèra maruru heka, kota Epesus j'aj'i be'a hari sèmi uru èèna. Hèia Paulus kaboko nare dhèu parcaya ètu sèra, ka na pa'èra d'ara si. Èle ka, na palangu lii, hèia pakèd'i asa propensi Makedonia.<bt>When these people were no longer causing a commotion, the city of Epesus was good again, as before. Then Paulus gathered the believing people there, and he strengthened their insides. After that, he took his leave, and left for the province of Makedonia.</bt><v n="2" />D'ai era ne'e, la'e palème rae-rae, ho pa'èra d'ara dhèu parcaya sèra. Na tao sèmi èèna, toke d'ai kabarai Yunani.<bt>Arriving in this place, he went around from village to village, to strengthen the insides of those believing people there. He did this until arriving in the country/society of the Yunani (Greeks).</bt><v n="3" />Na pea ètu èèna, tèlu hèru. Èle ka, na pa'èra hari neo pakèd'i dènge kapa asa propensi Siria, te ngaa na tadèngi, na, dhèu Yahudi rare lii èci neo pamadhe ne. Ropa na tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, ka d'èi heka la'e taruu asa propensi Siria. Te ngaa la'e re propensi Makedonia.<bt>He stayed here, three months. After that, ne prepared again wanting to leave on a ship to the province of Siria, but he heard that Jahudi people had come to an agreement to kill him. When he heard that, he no longer wanted to continue going to the province of Siria. But, he went by way of the province of Makedonia.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Abhu pèri-pèri dhèu dhu madhutu Paulus. Rèngu se nuka: Sopater, ana nèti Pirus, nèti kota Berea; dhèu dua nèti kota Tesalonika, ngara ra, Aristarkus dènge Sekundus; ca dhèu nèti kota Derbe, ngara na Gayus; aa dhèu tèlu nèti propensi Asia, nuka: Timotius, Tikikus, dènge Trofimus.<bt>There were several people who accompanied Paulus. They were: Sopater, the offspring of Pirus, from the city of Berea; Two people from the city of Tesalonika, named Aristarkus and Sekundus; One person from the city of Derbe, named Gayus; and three people from the province of Asia, that is: Timotius, Tikikus, and Trofimus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5-6" />Èle èèna ka, ja'a (Lukas, dhu suri sasuri ne), paraga hari dènge Paulus ètu kota Pilipi ètu propensi Makedonia. Ka ana-ana madhutu Paulus lasi uuru asa kota Troas, ho ra mate ji'i dua mi ètu cabèka dhasi nèi. Lod'o èle kalela Paska dhèu Yahudi,<bt>After that, I (Lukas, who is writing this letter), met back up with Paulus in the city of Filipi in the province of Makedonia. And Paulus' followers went on ahead to the city of Troas, so they could wait for the two of us on the other side of the ocean yonder.When the Jahudi people's festival of Paska</bt><note reference="20:5-6" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii sasuri Yunani, peka na, &lt;lod'o-lod'o be'a nèti Roti dhu pake boe Ragi&gt;. Sasoa na, &lt;lod'o-lod'o kapai sadia kalela Paska&gt;.<bt>According to the Yunani language writings, that, &lt;&lt;the good days of Bread that doesn't use Yeast&gt;. Its meaning is &lt;the holidays preparing for the festival of Paska&gt;.</bt></note>ji'i dua mi ca'e kapa ka pakèd'i asa kota Troas. Lod'o èèna, ji'i lèmi lod'o kateme ètu dedha kapa. Ropa ji'i d'ai Troas, ji'i puru nèti kapa. Hèia ji'i paraga hari dènge anga dhèu leo sèra, ka ji'i pea ètu èèna, ca migu.<bt>had finished, the two of us(exc) embarked on a ship and left for the city of Troas. At that time, we went five whole days on the ship. When we arrived at Troas, We disembarked from the ship. Then we met back up with our other companions, and we stayed there one week.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kalela = celebration"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kalela = celebration</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana mone èci, ngara na Yutikus, manahu nèti jendela ètu kota Troas<bt>A young man named Yutikus, falls from a window in the city of Troas</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Lod'o èèna, lèke dènge hari Migu. Paulus pama'ète nare le, peka na, &lt;&lt;A'ari. Bèli ja'a neo laku taruu.&gt;&gt; De ji'i, dhèu parcaya aa'i-aa'i, pakaboko ho neo nga'a-nginu. Lula Paulus neo pakèd'i, nèti èèna ka, na padhai lii dènge ji'i toke d'ai talora mèdha.<bt>That day fell on Sunday. Paulus had already decided, saying, &lt;&lt;Older-younger siblings. Tomorrow I want to continue going.&gt;&gt; So we(exc), all the believing people, gathered to eat-drink. Because Paulus wanted to leave, that is why he spoke with us until the middle of the night.</bt><v n="8" />Ji'i pakaboko ètu tad'a ka tèlu nèti èmu cue. Mèda èèna, ra paheo labhu ae.<bt>We were gathered in the third level of a house. That night, they lit a great many lamps.</bt><v n="9" />Lod'o èèna, ana mone èci, ngara na Yutikus,<bt>At that time, there was a young man named Yutikus,</bt><note reference="20:9" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu sasuri lii Yunani, &lt;Eutikus&gt; èdhi baca, peka na, &lt;Yutikus&gt;.<bt>According to the Yunani language, &lt;Eutikus&gt; is read, &lt;Yutikus&gt;.</bt></note>dhu madhèdi ètu jendela. Nèngu nanene kahèi lii padhai Paulus. Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu ka, ana mone ne musi madha sakaa, hèia na bhèj'i luu. Cag'ag'a laa, na manahu nèti jendela èèna asa rai la'e. Ka madhe mema.<bt>who was sitting on a window(sill). He was also listening to what Paulus was saying. But eventually this young man got sleepy (lit: stiff eyeballs) and went into a deep sleep. Suddenly, he fell from that window onto the ground. And he died right away.</bt><v n="10" />Hèia Paulus puru la'e, ka liku nare ana mone ne. Hèia na peka, &lt;&lt;Pa'èra d'ara! Te na mamuri.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Paulua went down, and embraced this young man. Then he said, &lt;&lt;Strengthen your insides! Cause he is alive.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="11-12" />Ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi karej'e, lula ana ne mamuri hari. Ka pakako rèti ne asa èmu na. Hèia ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi ca'e hari asa èmu dedha, ho madhèdi nga'a. Ka Paulus padhai lii hari toke d'ai bèli mad'ae èèna. Ropa lod'o rea, ji'i palangu lii ho pakèd'i.<bt>We were all happy, becaue that youngster was alive again. And they led him to his house. Then we all went back up to the top of the house, to sit and eat. Then Paulus spoke again until morning. When the sun appeared, we took our leave to leave.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="jelena = jendela (kuno) ; jedhela;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">jelena = jendela (kuno) ; jedhela; <span class="Bold">8:</span> tad'a = tingkat ; katèlu = ketiga; <span class="Bold">9:</span> musi madha sakaa = mengantuk (eyeballs stiff)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nèti kota Troas ji'i la'a asa kota Miletus<bt>From the city of Troas we went to the city of Miletus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Èle èèna ka, ji'i ngare lii èci, sèna ka pahag'a ho èèna na paraga hari ètu kota cue, ngara na Asos. Hèia ji'i ca'e kapa la'a asa Asos. Te ngaa Paulus kako haga asa nèi la'e.<bt>After that, we agreed to divide up to meet again in a city named Asos. Then we embarked on a ship going to Asos. But Paulus went overland to there.</bt></p>
    <fig path="maps\Bible\HkKorPat.tif" rtfFormat="width:11cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">J'ara nèti Korintus la'e asa Patara<bt>The road/journey from Korintus to Patara</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ropa ji'i paraga hari dènge Paulus ètu Asos, hèia Paulus ca'e asa dedha kapa la'e, aa ji'i pakèd'i taruu asa kota Metilene.<bt>When we met up again with Paulus in Asos, then Paulus embarked on the ship, and we left continuing on to the city of Metilene.</bt><v n="15" />Nèti Metilene, ji'i pakèd'i taruu dènge kapa. Ka asa bèli èèna, ji'i padètu-dètu dènge pulu èci, ngara na Kios. Asa camèd'a èèna, ji'i patangara dènge pulu Samos. D'ai camèd'a èci èèna, ji'i panahu ètu hèb'a-namo Miletus.<bt>From Metilene, we left continuing on by ship. And the next day (=day 2), we came close to an island named Kios. The following day after that (=day 3), we were facing the island of Samos. On the day after that (=day 4) , we set down anchor at the harbour of Miletus.</bt><v n="16" />Te ngaa Paulus neo d'ai lai-lai Yerusalem, ho na madhutu lod'o kalela Pantekosta ètu nèi. Na neo boe la'e asa kota Epesus, lula nèngu abhu heka tebho.<bt>But, Paulus wanted to arrived quickly in Yerusalem, so he could participate in the festival2 of Pentakosta yonder. He didn't want to go to Efesus, because he did want to waste time.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patangara = bamangada ; panahu; |b16:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">patangara = bamangada ; panahu; <span class="Bold">16:</span> èle lod'o = habis waktu (habis tangan matahari)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus peka-padhai dènge kètu juma'at sèra ètu kota Epesus<bt>Paulus speaks with the leaders of the sarani people in the city of Epesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Nèti Miletus, Paulus hia lii la'e asa kètu juma'at sèra ètu Epesus, sèna ka rèngu mai paraga dènge ne.<bt>From Miletus, Paulus sent word to the leaders of the sarani people in Epesus, so that they would come meet with him.</bt><v n="18" />Ropa rèngu d'ai nèi, hèia Paulus peka dènge ra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari aa'i-aa'i! Miu me'a le j'ara mamuri ja'a, karèi nèti lod'o partama ja'a d'ai propensi Asia, d'ai sange ne'e ne.<bt>When they arrived there, then Paulus spoke to them, saying, &lt;&lt;All you elder-younger siblings! You(pl) are the ones who know my way of life, since the first day when I arrived in the province of Asia, until now.</bt><v n="19" />Miu me'a le kahèi ja'a ne sab'a bia ètu talora aae miu, te ngaa ja'a padedha boe iisi. Ètu d'ara sasab'a-la'a ja'a ne, ja'a pahaa èi madha ae titu kèna, dènge dui j'èra dhu ciki boe. Ja'a abhu j'aj'èra ae nèti ngangee karehe dhèu Yahudi sèra.<bt>You are also the ones who know how hard I worked among you, but I did not elevated/brag about myself. In that work of mine, I spilled a great many tears, and shoulder-carried not a little suffering. I experience much suffering from the evil thoughts/plots of those Jahudi people.</bt><v n="20" />Lod'o ja'a aj'a-nori miu, ja'a lole aa'i mèu-mèu ngaa dhu be'a dhu ja'a ke'a kèdhi hia miu. Aa ja'a aj'a kahèi miu dhu pahuni boe ètu madha dhèu ae. Ja'a maso-kalua nèti èmu èci asa èmu èci, ho pasanèd'e dhèu sèra lula-nèti dad'èi Lamatua.<bt>When I taught you, I told you everything in detail that was good, which I knew, for you. And I also taught you without hiding anything in front of many people. I went in and out from one house to another, to remind those people about the will of God2.</bt><v n="21" />Ja'a peka kahèi mi dhèu Yahudi dènge dhèu leo sèra, peka na, rèngu loe eele ka nèti sasala-sasigo rèngu, ho madhutu Ama Lamatua. Aa rèngu hud'i parcaya kahèi Kètu èdhi, nuka Lamatua Yesus.<bt>I also spoke to the Jahudi people and to other people, saying, they must stop from their wrongs (doublet), to follow God. And they also must believe in our(inc) Lord, that is the Lord Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="j'èli haga = injak kaki; |b19:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">j'èli haga = injak kaki; <span class="Bold">19:</span> pahaa = cucurkan; <span class="Bold">20:</span> pakatoo = 1) saling berkutuk, 2) pakatoo madha dènge madha = saling berhadapan ; pahuni =</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />De ja'a neo peka sèmi ne'e ka: limuri ne, ja'a neo laku asa Yerusalem, lula Roh Lamatua lere nèti ja'a laku asa nèi. Ja'a ke'a dhoka madhutu di, masi ka ja'a ke'a boe bèli-camèd'a ngaa ka dhu j'aj'i mi dedha ja'a ètu nèi.<bt>So, I want to say this: Now, I am going to Yerusalem, because the Spirit of God2 is dragging me to go there/yonder. I need to just follow that (go along with that), even though I do not know the future (doublet), what will happen to me there.</bt><v n="23" />Te, nèti kota cue asa kota cue, Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci peka uuru le dènge ja'a, èèna na ra pamaso ja'a asa d'ara bèdho, dènge ja'a pasae j'aj'èra ae ètu nèi.<bt>Cause from one city to another city, God2's Holy Spirit is the one who spoke first to me, that, they will put me in prison, and force me to carry (experience) much suffering there.</bt><v n="24" />Ka ja'a ke'a mema le, lula Lamatua Yesus ka dhu hia ja'a dui sasab'a ne ètu kabela-kao ja'a, sèna ka ja'a laku lole Lii Lolo Be'a, peka na, Lamatua sue èdhi, aa d'ara Na hua iia kahèi dènge èdhi. Ladhe ja'a madhutu boe dad'èi Na, ho pa'èle sasab'a Na ne'e, ja'a ngee, na, mamuri ja'a guna boe ngaa-ngaa ciki sa.<bt>And I already know this for certain, because the Lord Yesus is the one who gave me to carry this work on my shoulders, so that I go tell the Good News that God2 loves/pities us(inc), and His insides are good/gracious/wonderful towards us. If I do not follow His will, to complete this work of His, I think that my life has no meaning/use whatsoever.</bt><note reference="20:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Timotius 4:7</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Limuri ne, ja'a ke'a le, peka na, bèli-camèd'a miu se mèdhi heka rèhu ja'a. Masi ka ja'a dhu nèbhu ae le aj'a-nori miu, sèna ka dènge j'ara tasamia miu j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua.<bt>Now I know that in the future you here will no longer see my face. Even though I taught you for a long time, about the way for you to be/become people belonging to God2.</bt><v n="26-28" />Nèti èèna ka, miu nanene paie. Ja'a pa'èle le sasab'a-la'a ja'a mi miu. De limuri ne, miu ka dhu pakako taruu sasab'a èèna. Nèti èèna ka, ladhe abhu ètu talora miu, dhu j'aj'i mèka dhèu unu Lamatua, èèna na, miu tago mere. Èèna na, sasala ja'a aad'o heka. Sanèd'e paie! Ja'a peka le dènge miu dad'èi Lamatua aa'i-aa'i. Ja'a pahuni boe èci sa. De miu hud'i laladhe paie mamuri miu, aa j'aga paie-iie dhèu-dhèu dhu Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci pangèd'u mi miu ho ladhe-leru si. Baku bhèlu, peka na, Lamatua Yesus madhe le ho sui pama'ète dhèu sèra dènge raa Nèngu mesa Na. Nèngu ka dhu paj'uj'u le miu, sèna ka ladhe-leru si, sama sèmi ana madhenga badha dhu lalau-lalo'o kahib'i-kalèbho ra.<bt>Therefore, listen well. I have complete my work to/for you(pl). So now, you are the ones who must continue to carry out that work. Because of that, if there is among you (someone) who does not yet belong to God2, that is your responsibility. That is no longer my wrong/responsibility.Remember well! I have told you all about the will of God2. There is not one thing that I have hidden.So you here must carefully guard/manage your lives. And also guard/care for well the people whom the Holy Spirit of God2 has given into your care for you to watch-over-welfare. Don't forget that the Lord Yesus died to completely *redeem those people with His own blood. He is the one who has appointed you, so that you watch-over-welfare of them, just like *shepherds watches over their flocks (&lt;sheep-goats).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />De limuri ne, ja'a neo tèke eele miu kèna. Te ngaa sanèd'e! Bèli-camèd'a dhèu mai rèti lii holo-nori dhu leko-leo asa talora aae miu. Rèngu maso mai nuka sèmi busa hui dhu maso asa d'ara oka kahib'i-kalèbho.<bt>So now, I am going to leave you behind. So remember! In the future, people will come bringing teaching that are different/incorrect into your midst. The enter in like wild dogs who enter into a corral of sheep-goats.</bt><v n="30" />Abhu dhèu dhu kapod'e-kabèli sèmi èèna, dhu mai nèti li'u. De sanèd'e! Abhu kahèi dhu cèu nèti talora aae miu. Ho ra aj'a miu lèke-lèke boe. Ra d'èi sèna ka dhèu madhutu rèngu. Nèti èèna ka, ra tenge j'ara ho nuni rèti dhèu, sèna ka baku madhutu ia ka Yesus.<bt>There are deceptive people like that who come from outside. But remember! There are also those that appear from within your midst. So they teach you what is not at all true. They want for people to follow them. Because of that, they look for ways to drag people off so that they no longer follow Yesus.</bt><v n="31" />Nèti èèna ka, miu hud'i j'aga paie mamuri miu. Baku bhèlu, te ja'a pa'èci le dènge miu tèlu tèu kèna. Ja'a holo le miu mèda-mèu, dènge pangee boe j'aj'èra ja'a. Èi madha ja'a suti ae le, lula miu.<bt>Because of that, carefully guard your lives. Don't forget, cause I have been together with you for three years. I advised/taught you night-day, and have not given thought to my own suffering. My tears flowed (&lt;dropped much), because of you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tago - tanggung; |b28:|r ladhe-leru ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tago - tanggung; <span class="Bold">28:</span> ladhe-leru = piara ; bayar lunas, tebus secara sempurna; <span class="Bold">29:</span> busa sobu = german shepherd, herder; <span class="Bold">30:</span> cèu = timbul; <span class="Bold">31:</span> suti = tetes</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />D'ai le lod'o èdhi pacèri kèna. De ja'a pangèd'u miu asa adhe-aai Lamatua, sèna ka Na ladhe-leru miu. De miu hud'i kèpe pa'èra ku aa'i-aa'i dhu nèti uru èèna ja'a peka le dènge miu, nèti babe'a d'ara Lamatua. Lamatua dènge koasa ho pa'èra d'ara miu. Na moa le kahèi, ho hia mamèngi mi dedha dhèu unu Na. De ladhe miu madhutu taruu Nèngu dènge d'ara mera-milu, tatu miu abhu mamèngi Na kahèi.<bt>Now the day/time of our separation has arrived. So I hand you over into the hands of God2 so that H watches over your welfare. So you must hold firmly to everything that from long ago I have told you, about the goodnes of God2's character/insides. God2 power will strengthen your insides. He has also promised to give *blessings (&lt;sweet-smelling fragrance) to those who belong to Him. So if you continue to follow Him with peace/unruffled relationships, you will certainly get His blessings also.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pangèd'u = serahkan semua-semua ; adhe-aai"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pangèd'u = serahkan semua-semua ; adhe-aai = talapak tangan, palm ; mamèngi = berkat, (bahu yang mengharumkan), keberuntungan (mis. dapat ikan besar, hasil tani yg lebe-lebe, lulus tes PNS, --better than normal), lahri-bathin ; b'era-b'era = ikut-serta, tidak pernah berpisah</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Lod'o ja'a sab'a ètu talora aae miu, ja'a neo boe unu mèdha-panyau miu èci sa. Ja'a manèngi boe mèdha hualaa miu, do, doi iia miu, do, mèdha-papake miu, do, ngaa èci sa.<bt>When I was working in your midst, I did not want to own even one of your possessions. I did not ask for your gold things, or your money, or your clothes, or enything else.</bt><v n="34" />Miu me'a kahèi, lod'o ja'a pea dènge miu, ja'a sab'a d'ai madhe, sèna ka ja'a bisa mamuri. Hia boe ja'a mesa ku, te ngaa rèngu dhu madhutu ja'a sèra abhu pala kahèi.<bt>You also know that when I lived with you, I worked almost to death, as long as I was able to live/so I could get life. It was not just for myself, but for those who followed me to get their share as well.</bt><v n="35" />De dènge j'ara aa'i-aa'i se, ja'a pad'elo le j'ara, sèna ka miu kahèi madhutu soru-bara dhèu dhu unu aad'o sèra. Sanèd'e paie lii padhai Lamatua Yesus, dhu peka na, &lt;Be'a risi, èdhi hia, nèti èdhi sèmi tare.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So, with all these ways I have shown you the way, so that you also can follow looking after the people who have nothing. Remember well the words of the Lord Yesus, like this, &lt;It is better thata we(inc) give, than we receive.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kapingi = kapingin; |b34:|r abhu pala"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kapingi = kapingin; <span class="Bold">34:</span> abhu pala = dapat bagian</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ropa Paulus padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, hèia na patitu kètu urutuu, ka na manèngi-mangaj'i dènge rèngu, aa na manèngi, sèna ka Lamatua ladhe-leru rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>When Paulus finished speaking like that, then he knelt and prayed with them, and he asked so that God2 would look after the welfare of all of them.</bt><v n="37-38" />Ka d'ara rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra pèd'a titu kèna lula Paulus peka, na, bèli-camèd'a rèngu paraga heka dènge ne. Ka d'ai lod'o ho ra pacèri, dhèu se liku rare Paulus ka uu ne, dènge lii tangi aa d'ara pèd'a. Èle èèna ka, ra lere ji'i<bt>And the insides of all of them were greatly pained, because Paulus said, in the future they would not meet with him any more. And when the time came for us to separate, these people embraced Paulus and kissed him, with tearful voices and sadness. After that, they escorted us(exc) to the ship.</bt><note reference="20:37-38" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">&lt;&lt;Ji'i&gt;&gt; ètu ne'e, nuka Lukas, dhu suri sasuri ne'e, Paulus, dènge angalai rèngu.<bt>&lt;&lt;We&gt; here, is Lukas, who wrote this letter, Paulus, and their friends.</bt></note>asa dedha kapa.</p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus si lèpa hari asa Yerusalem<bt>Paulus (coll) return to Yerusalem again</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="21" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa palangu lii èle dènge kètu-kètu juma'at dhu mai nèti Epesus dènge d'ara bia, ka ji'i ca'e asa dedha kapa, ho pakèd'i taruu asa pulu Kos. Asa bèli èèna, ji'i ngare pulu Rodos. Nèti nèi, ji'i kako taruu asa kota hèb'a-namo cue, ngara na Patara.<bt>After taking our leave from the leaders of the sarani people who came from Epesus, with heavy insides we(exc) embarked on the ship, to continue travelling to the island of Kos. The next day, we took (=sailed to) the island of Rodos. From there, we kept going to a harbour city, named Patara.</bt><v n="2" />Ètu èèna, ji'i puru nèti kapa. Ka ji'i ca'e hari kapa leo dhu neo la'e asa propensi Fenisia padètu dènge Siria. Ropa ji'i ngare dedha, ra ère dènge ka tangad'a.<bt>At there we disembarked from the ship. And we embarked again on a different ship which was wanting to go to the province of Fenisia near Siria. When we got aboard, they pulled up anchor immediately.</bt><v n="3" />Nèbhu boe ka, ji'i ladhe ngèdhi pulu Siprus re sebhe kariu ji'i. Ji'i dhuli boe, te ngaa kako taruu toke ji'i panahu ètu kota Tirus, ètu propensi Siria. D'ai era nèi, ra papuru mèdha nèti dedha kapa.<bt>Not long after that, we saw the island of Siprus passing by on our left side. We did not stop in, but kept going until we anchored at the city of Tirus in the province of Siria. Arriving in that place, they lowered the cargo from the ship.</bt></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\HK00214C.tif" rtfFormat="width:11cm;textWrapping:none">Ra papuru mèdha nèti dedha kapa<bt>They lower cargo from the ship</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Lula rèngu papuru mèdha era, ka ji'i puru la'a ngad'o dhèu-dhèu sarani ètu èèna. Ropa paraga, hèia ji'i pea dènge ra ca migu kateme. Dhèu se'e se abhu le tadha nèti Roh Lamatua ho kai Paulus, sèna ka la'e ia ka asa Yerusalem.<bt>Because they were still lowering cargo, we disembarked to go visit the sarani people in that place. When we met them, then we(exc) stayed with them for a whole week. These people had gotten a sign from the Spirit of God2 that they should forbid Paulus so that he no longer go to Yerusalem.</bt><v n="5" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa ropa èle ca migu, ka ji'i la'a hari asa kapa. Dhèu sarani sèra aa'i-aa'i ra, bhèni-mone, dhèu kapai, ana iiki, ana ngèru dènge dhèu heka, lere ji'i toke d'ai hèb'a-namo. Ètu dedha nebhe, ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi patitu kètu urutuu ho manèngi-mangaj'i sama-sama.<bt>After a week, we went back to the ship. All those sarani people, female-male, big-little, young children and older people, escorted us to the harbour. On the beach, we all kneeled to pray together.</bt><v n="6" />Palangu lii èle, ka ji'i ca'e asa dedha kapa, aa rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra lèpa èmu.<bt>After taking our leave, we embarked on the ship, they all returned home.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhu = sementara @@?? ; nad'o"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhu = sementara @@?? ; nad'o = lihat, jenguk; <span class="Bold">5:</span> salae = pasir ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="maps\Bible\HkPatYer.tif" rtfFormat="width:6cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Nèti Patara la'a asa Yerusalem<bt>From Patara going to Yerusalem</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ji'i pakèd'i nèti Tirus, ka ji'i dhuli kota Ptolemais. Ètu nèi, ji'i puru, ka la'a tenge dhèu sarani ètu èèna. Paraga, ka ji'i pea dènge si ca lod'o.<bt>We left Tirus, and we stopped in at the city of Ptolemais. There, we disembarked and went looking for the sarani people in that place. Meeting them, we satyed with them for a day.</bt><v n="8" />Bèli èèna, ji'i pakèd'i nèti èèna, hèia d'ai kota Kaisarea. Ètu Kaisarea, ji'i pea taha ètu èmu Pelipus. Nèngu ne ka dhu bhoke uuru j'ara nèti Lii Lolo Be'a Lamatua Yesus ètu era èèna. Aa nèngu ne'e, ca dhèu nèti dhèu pidhu dhu hag'e rare ca hari nèi, ho pala-bagi nganga'a mi bhèni balu-ana lalu ètu Yerusalem.<bt>The next day, we left that place and arrived at the city of Kaisarea. There, we stayed temporarily at the house of Pelipus. He is the one who first opened (=pioneered) the Good News of the Lord Yesus to that place. And he is one of the seven people who was set apart to divide out food to widows and orphans (double doublet) in Yerusalem.</bt><note reference="21:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 6:5, 8:5</note><v n="9" />Pelipus ne, ana bhèni na, dhèu èpa. Ama Lamatua pake si, ho j'aj'i dhèu rèti lii padhai Na ho peka dad'èi Na.<bt>This Pelipus had four daughters. God used them as spokespeople to speak His will.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa ji'i pea dènge rèngu pèri-pèri lod'o, hèia dhèu èci, ngara na Agabus, mai nèti propensi Yudea. Lamatua pake ne, j'aj'i dhèu nèti lii padhai Na ho peka dad'èi Na.<bt>When we had stayed with them for several days, then a person named Agabus came from the province of Yudea. God2 used him as a spokesperson to tell His will.</bt><note reference="21:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 11:28</note><v n="11" />Na mai paraga dènge ji'i. Hèia nare dhara hake Paulus, ka na haheo mi ai dènge haga na. Hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci, peka sèmi ne'e ka: &lt;Dhèu unu dhara hake ne, èèna na, dhèu Yahudi èki karadhe ne sèmi ne'e ka ètu Yerusalem. Èle èèna na, ra soro ne asa dhèu dhu Yahudi boe.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>He came and met with us. And he took Paulus' waistband, and wound it around his hands and feet. And he spoke,saying, &lt;&lt;The Holy Spirit of Gods says this: &lt;The person who owns this waistband, later on the Jahudi people will tie up like this in Yerusalem. After that, they will turn him over to people who are not Jahudi.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="haheo = melilit ; èki karadhe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">haheo = melilit ; èki karadhe = ikat bolak-balik</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa ji'i tadèngi ngare lii dhèu ne'e, ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi manèngi dènge d'ara kateme sèna ka Paulus la'e ia ka asa Yerusalem. Ji'i dhu j'aj'i ana madhutu na, dènge dhèu-dhèu sarani ètu èèna, lii manèngi ji'i sèmi èèna ka.<bt>When we heard what this person said, we all asked earnestly so that Paulus would no longer go to Yerusalem. We who were his followers, and the sarani people there, our request was like that.</bt><v n="13" />Te ngaa Paulus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Baku! Nga tao ka miu tangi sèmi èèna? Miu pabia le d'ara ja'a. Sèmi ne'e! Abhu dhèu dhu mema d'èi boe ja'a, lula ja'a madhutu Lamatua Yesus. De masi ka ra èki karadhe ja'a, do pamadhe ja'a, do tao tasamia èèna ka, ja'a sadia le sèmi kore.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Paulus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;No! Why are you crying like that? You are burdening my insides. It's like this! There are people who truly do not like me, because I follow the Lord Yesus. So, even if they tie me up, or do whatever to me, I am prepared to receive it.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamako"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pamako</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ropa ji'i nge'a, na, Paulus sèmi nare boe lii ji'i, ka ji'i soro tèke ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i ka laa! Pe, ti ladhe dad'èi Lamatua di.&gt;&gt;<bt>When we knew that Paulus didn't accept what we said, we let him be, saying, &lt;&lt;If that's the way it is. We just want to see only the will of God2.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus si d'ai Yerusalem<bt>Paulus (coll) arrive in Yerusalem</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Pea pèri-pèri lod'o ètu Kaisarea, ka ji'i lalau mèdha-panyau ji'i, ka ji'i pakèd'i asa Yerusalem.<bt>After staying several days in Kaisarea, we packed our belongings, and we left for Yerusalem.</bt><v n="16" />Abhu kahèi pèri-pèri dhèu sarani nèti Kaisarea madhutu ji'i. Ra lere ji'i toke d'ai èmu cue, ho ji'i j'unu ètu èèna. Lamatua èmu na, ngara na Manason, nèti pulu Siprus. Nèngu ne, nèbhu le parcaya Lamatua Yesus.<bt>There were also some sarani people from Kaisarea who accompanied us. They escorted us to a house, for us to sleep there. The owner of that house was named Manason, a person from Siprus. He had believed in the Lord Yesus for a long time.</bt><v n="17" />Ropa ji'i d'ai Yerusalem, a'ari aa'i-aa'i ètu nèi sèmi rare ji'i dènge d'ara karej'e.<bt>When we arrived in Yerusalem, all the elder-younger sibling yonder, received us with happy insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dara kateme = dengan sungguh-sungguh"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dara kateme = dengan sungguh-sungguh</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus si lasi paraga dènge Yakobis<bt>Paulus goes to visit Yakobis</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Bèli èèna, ka ji'i aa'i-aa'i la'a paraga dènge Yakobis. Aa dhèu heka-dhèu heka dhèu sarani aa'i-aa'i ra pakaboko le ètu èèna.<bt>The next day, we all went to meet with Yakobis. And the leaders of the sarani people had all gathered there.</bt><v n="19" />Ji'i hia lii maho'o èci dènge èci, hèia Paulus padhue-padhai aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama Lamatua tao le ètu mia-mia, hia mi dhèu Yahudi boe sèra. Na peka na, Lamatua Yesus bhoke le j'ara, ka rèngu parcaya Lamatua Yesus. Na lolo kahèi, tasa mera mia Lamatua pake ne dènge angalai-angalai na ètu d'ara sasab'a-la'a ra.<bt>We(exc) gave our greetings one by one, then Paulus spoke at length about everything that God had done in various places, to the non-Jahudi people. He said that the Lord Yesus had opened the way for these people to believe in Him. He also told the various ways God2 had used him with his companions in their work.</bt><v n="20" />Ropa tadèngi rare lii lolo Paulus ne, rèngu aa'i-aa'i pakapai kolongara Ama Lamatua.<bt>When they finished listening to Paulus' report, they all exalted the name/reputation of God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="li maho'o = salam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">li maho'o = salam</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ra peka dènge Paulus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèna ka èu me'a, abhu riho-riho dhèu Yahudi dhu parcaya le Lamatua Yesus. Te ngaa rèngu kèpe pa'èra era atora-atora dhu Musa papuru mai hia èdhi.<bt>Then they spoke to Paulus' saying, &lt;&lt;So that you know, there are thousands of Jahudi people who have believed in the Lord Yesus. But they are the ones who still hold strongly to the regulations which Grandpa Musa handed down to us(inc).</bt><v n="21" />Te ngaa abhu dhèu dhu leko-monya palème ètu ne'e, peka na, èu ae ka dhu aj'a dhèu-dhèu Yahudi ètu era leo, peka na, rèngu madhutu ia ka atora-atora agama nèti Musa. Rèngu peka kahèi, na, èu kai si, sèna ka madhutu ia ka ad'a suna hia ana-ana mone rèngu. Aa èu kai dhèu sarani sèra kahèi, sèna ka madhutu ia ka atora ad'a dhu leo sèra nèti èdhi dhèu Yahudi.<bt>But, there are people who are talking deceitful nonsense around here, saying that you are the one who is teaching Jahudi people in other places to no longer follow the religious regulations from Grandpa Musa. They also say that you forbid them so that they no longer follow the circumcision adat for their sons. And you also forbid sarani people so that they do not follow the other adat regulations for we(inc) Jahudi people.</bt><v n="22" />De sanèd'e! Tatu dhèu Yahudi sèra tadèngi, na, èu ètu ne'e le. Ka dhèu dhu tadèngi lii lai-ngèlu sèra, tatu ra nasa. De èdhi tenge j'ara samia?<bt>So, remember, oo! Certainly those Jahudi people have heard that you are already here. And the people who have heard these rumours (idiom: voices/messages over the grass), would certainly be angry. So, what should we(inc) do?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="li kolo-j'u'u = kabar angin (suara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">li kolo-j'u'u = kabar angin (suara atas rumput) ; li lai-ngèlu = suara angin ; lai = layar ; tatu = pasti ; ele boe = mungkin TAM @@</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Madhutu a'abhu ji'i, sèmi ne'e ka: abhu dhèu èpa nèti ji'i, dhu pajaji le dènge Lamatua. Limuri ne, dhèu se'e neo lusu pakahoni kètu ra, ho j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, rèngu tao aa'i le ngaa dhu ra pajaji na.<bt>According to our opinion, it is like this: There are four people among us(exc), who have made a promise with God2. Now these people already want to shave their heads clean as a sign that they have done everything that they promised.</bt><v n="24" />De hua iia, èu lamu palere dènge dhèu èpa se, asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua. Èu lamu madhutu rèngu kahèi, sèna ka pamèu iisi madhutu ad'a. Aa èu tago more bab'ae rèngu kahèi nèti tatao ad'a èèna. Ladhe èu tao sèmi èèna, dhèu re'a, na, èu kèpe pa'èra era atora agama Yahudi dhu Musa papuru hia èdhi. Aa ladhe tao sèmi èèna, rèngu re'a, na, sèra sa dhu leko-monya di, nèti lii lolo dhu peka na, èu ka dhu kai dhèu ho madhutu ia ka ad'a Yahudi!<bt>So it would be best if you go escort these four people to the *Temple (God's Central House of Worship). You go accompanying them also so that you can clean/purify yourself according to adat. And you should bear the cost for them also for their adat ceremonies. If you do that, pwoplw will know that you still hold strongly to the Jahudi ways of religion, which Musa handed down to us(inc). And if you do that, they will know that those things, which are just lies, from the story which says, you are the one who forbids people from following Jahudi adat anymore!</bt><note reference="21:23-24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 6:13-21</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Te ngaa mi dhèu dhu Yahudi boe, dhu lèka le Lamatua Yesus, èdhi pa'adhu le sasuri hia ra. Èdhi peka le lii pama'ète èdhi ca hari nèi, dhu peka, rèngu parluu boe madhutu atora ad'a Yahudi aa'i-aa'i ra. Dhu rèngu hud'i tao madhutu, sèmi ne'e ku: bhèni-mone baku tao j'ara makae dènge dhèu dhu j'aj'i boe dhèu èmu-kamali ra. Rèngu baku pab'ali dènge mèdha sogo-tagu, aa baku ra'a nganga'a dhu tao madenge a'ari dhèu Yahudi. Conto sèmi: rèngu baku ra'a sisi sogo-tagu; baku ra'a raa badha; aa baku ra'a sisi badha madhe dhu ra pacèli koko.&gt;&gt;<bt>But as for people who are not Jahudi, who have believed in the Lord Yesus, we(inc) have already sent a letter to them. We have told them our decision from that day, which says they do not need to follow all of our Jahudi adar regulations. The ones they must follow are these: Female-male must not do evil ways with people who are not their spouse. They must not eat from traditional worship, and not eat food which makes elder-younger Jahudi siblings repulsed. [Higher level cohesion with 15:29, bringing out reason so not seem petty.] That is like: they must not eat the food of traditional worship; they must not eat the blood of animals; and they must not eat meat of animals that have died from choking the neck.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="21:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 15:29</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ka Paulus sèmi nare dènge be'a lii manèngi ra. Hèia asa bèli èèna, nèngu dènge dhèu èpa se lasi palere asa Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ka ra pamèu iisi ra madhutu ad'a agama Yahudi. Èle ka, Paulus peka dènge ama agama ètu èèna, peka na, lod'o mia ho rèngu heka pamèci lii moa rèngu. Te ladhe èle lod'o èèna, rèngu ca dhèu-ca dhèu ka hud'i tao ku persembahan rèngu mi Lamatua.<bt>And Paulus accepted well what they were asking. Then the next day, he and these four people went together to the Temple, and they purified themselves according to the Jahudi religion. After that, Paulus spoke to the priest (father of religion) there, saying when they would complete/fulfill their promise. Cause when those days were over each person must place their *offering (loan) to God2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pamèci = melengkapi ; nanèti ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pamèci = melengkapi ; nanèti = some not know</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra kèpe Paulus ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i<bt>They grab Paulus in the Temple</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27-29" />Ropa oe èle pidhu lod'o dhu rèngu pamoa ho pa'èle tatao ad'a èèna, abhu pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi nèti propensi Asia dhu rèdhi Paulus la'e asa d'ara kota Yerusalem, palere dènge angalai èci, ngara na Trofimus. Trofimus ne, dhèu kota Epesus, aa nèngu dhèu Yahudi boe. Ka ropa rèngu rèdhi Paulus la'e asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ka rèngu neo laa, na, Paulus nèti dènge Trofimus asa d'ara kahèi. Te madhutu atora, dhèu Yahudi boe bisa boe lasi asa d'ara Èmu èèna. Ka rèngu pake j'ara ne'e, sèna ka j'aj'i lii langu. Nèti èèna ka, ra kakèj'i dhèu dhu ètu sèra, ho ra kèpe Paulus. Aa ra pa'oo peka dènge dhèu-dhèu ètu sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Woeh! Dhèu Isra'el sèra! Tulu ku ji'i laa! Nèngu ne ka dhu aj'a palème ètu mia-mia, peka na, core eele ka ad'a èdhi dhèu Yahudi. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu padhai lii pakarehe kahèi Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ne. Ka doe ne'e ne, nèngu neo maso ho pakaj'alu era Lamatua dhu mola-mèci ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>When the seven days were almost over which they had promised to complete the adat ceremony, there were several Jahudi people from the province of Asia who say Paulus going inside the city of Yerusalem, accompanied by a friend named Trofimus.This Trofimus was a person of the city of Epesus, and he was not a Jahudi person. And when they saw Paulus going into the Temple, they thought that Paulus was going to take Trofimus inside also.Now according to the right way, people who are not Jahudi cannot go inside that House. And they used this matter to create a dispute. Because of that, they incited the people there to grab/arrest Paulus. And the shouted with the people there, saying, &lt;&lt;Woo! People of Isra'el, ee! Help us(exc) over here now! He is the one who teaches all over the place saying to throw away our(inc) Jahudi adat. He is the one who also slanders this Temple. And now, he is going to enter and defile this holy place of God2's!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakaj'alu = bekin kamomos"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pakaj'alu = bekin kamomos</Message></Annotation><note reference="21:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 20:4</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ropa tadèngi lii ne'e, dhèu ca kabarai nèti kota Yerusalem d'ara ra pana-mag'oro. Hèia dhèu ae rai lasi lingu rare Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i èèna. Ka ra kèpe rare Paulus, hèia ra nuni pa'oro ne asa li'u. Ka ra bèdho aa'i hèb'a oka nèti Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i.<bt>When they heard this, the citizens of Yerusalem were furious. Then many people ran around/surrounding the Temple. And they grabbed Paulus, and they dragged him along the ground outside. And they closed all the doors of the fence/wall of that Temple.</bt><note reference="21:30" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu peka na, bisa boe pamadhe dhèu ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Lamatua. Ladhe abhu dhèu èci dhu maso asa d'ara ho kèpe tadhu ètu dedha mei persembahan, madhutu atora agama Yahudi, na, dhèu bisa boe tao ngaa-ngaa mi dedha dhèu ne'e. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu Yahudi sa ro'o boe ho Paulus la'e hari asa madha Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i èèna. Ka ra bèdho aa'i hèb'a oka Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i sèmi èèna.<bt>There are knowledgale people who say that one cannot kill people inside God2's Temple. If a person enters inside to grab the horn on top of the table of offering, according to the Jahudi religious regulations, na, people cannot do anything to this person. Because of that, those Jahudi people did not want Paulus to go back inside that Temple. So they closed all the doors of the fence of the Temple like that.</bt></note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02013b.tif" rtfFormat="width:10.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:center">Ra kèpe rare Paulus<bt>They grab Paulus</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ropa ra tasib'u neo pamadhe Paulus, ka komedhaa sordad'u Roma dhu ètu èèna, tadèngi lii maruru èèna.<bt>While they were busy trying to kill Paulus, the commander of the Roma soldiers there heard the sound of that commotion.</bt><v n="32" />Ka komedhaa ne paroa dènge ka sordad'u nèngu dènge kapala-kapala rèngu sèra, ho maso asa talora aae dhèu dhu maruru sèra. Ropa dhèu se'e ladhe rèdhi sordad'u dènge komedhaa aae sèra mai, ka ra ae eele game Paulus.<bt>And the commander immediately summoned his soldiers and their heads, to go into the middle of those who were rioting. When these people saw the soldiers with their commander coming, they immediately stopped beating Paulus.</bt><v n="33" />Èle èèna ka, komedhaa na kèpe Paulus, ka na pua ho sordad'u sèra èki ne pake rate bèsi dua. Ra èki rare, ka na karèi dhèu sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne, cee? Na tao sala ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the commander caught Paulus and ordered the soldiers to bind him using two iron chains. When they finished tying him, he asked those people, saying, &lt;&lt;Who is this person? What has he done wrong?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tasib'u ; pajiko"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tasib'u ; pajiko</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Te ngaa ra dhaa dènge lii baka-leo. Cahag'e peka na, &lt;&lt;Na tao sèmi ne'e!&gt;&gt; Cahag'e hari peka na, &lt;&lt;Na tao sèmi èèna!&gt;&gt; Ka komedhaa ne, j'aj'i bingu. Ne'a boe lii langu ne, kolo-kapua na tasamia, lula dhèu ae sèra pa'oo-parodha palere-lere. Nèti èèna ka, na pua ho rèti Paulus asa d'ara benteng sordad'u la'e.<bt>But they responded with different answers. Some said, &lt;&lt;He did like this!&gt;&gt; But others said, &lt;&lt;He did like that!&gt;&gt; So this commander became confused. He did not know what was the cause of this dispute, that caused so many people to be shouting all over the place. Because of that, he ordered them to take Paulus into the soldier's fort (loan).</bt><v n="35-36" />Sordad'u se lere rèti Paulus, te ngaa dhèu ae se madhutu kahèi, dènge asa tabha maruru. Ropa oe ca'e langa, dhèu se'e asa ra hoe aae, ka ra karubhu asa madha lasi. Toke sordad'u se nedhe Paulus, sèna ka dhèu sèra baku ab'o palaho ne. Hèia ra pa'oo dènge lii mèdhu, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pamadhe ne! Pamadhe eele ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>These soldiers led Paulus away, but those many people followed them also and made an increasingly worse commotion. When they were about to climb the steps, these people became furious and surged towad the front. To the point that the soldier lifted Paulus so that those people could not beat or wound him. Then they shouted with a loud voice, saying, &lt;&lt;Kill him! Kill him dead!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hino = ganas, marah ; ara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hino = ganas, marah ; ara ; nedhe = angkat ; abo = tumbuk, habok, palaho = kasi hancur ; hoe</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus manèngi ho siri iisi na ètu madha dhèu ae<bt>Paulus defends himself in front of many people</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="siri iisi= defend self, sili diri;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">siri iisi= defend self, sili diri; sarii = defend s.o else</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ropa rèngu neo maso asa d'ara benteng, Paulus manèngi komedhaa èèna, dhu tao lii Yunani, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ja'a bisa padhai lii ciki, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>When they were about to enter the fort, Paulus asked that commander using the Yunani language, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Could I please speak a little bit?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa tadèngi lii padhai Paulus sèmi èèna, ka komedhaa ne capa cag'ag'a, hèia na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hee! Èu ne me'a lii Yunani di? Tasamia ka, èu bisa me'a lii Yunani?<bt>When he heard Paulus speaking like that, the commander spontaneously showed his surprise, and then asked, saying, &lt;&lt;Waa! You know the Yunani language, ya? How is it that you know how to speak Yunani?</bt><v n="38" />Ladhe sèmi èèna, ngangee ja'a sala di. Ja'a neo laa, na, èu ne dhèu Masir dhu uru èèna, kakèj'i-rariu dhèu, sèna ka pakaco dènge maruru. Ka nèti èpa riho dhèu rèd'u dènge rèka, hèia ra rai asa d'ara pad'a sod'a. De èu ne, aad'o di, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>If that is the case, my thinking is wrong. I was going in the direction that you here are that Masir (Egypt) person from before, who incited people to cause chaos and commotions. And he took four thousand people with (sharp) weapons, and they fled into the wilderness. So, you here, are not (him), right?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="capa = gerakan yg tidak disadari,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">capa = gerakan yg tidak disadari, spontan; <span class="Bold">38:</span> rèd'u = pegang ; rèka = senjata tajam ; salae = pasir ; pad'a sod'a = wilderness</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ka Paulus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o, ama! Ja'a ne, dhèu Yahudi. Ina ku nara iisi ja'a ètu kota Tarsus, ètu propensi Kilikia. Ja'a manèngi ama ku hia ja'a tebho ciki, ho ja'a padhai lii sèku dènge dhèu ae se.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Paulus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;No, father! I am a Jahudi person. My mother gave birth to me in the city of Tarsus, in the province of Kilikia. I request that you give me a bit of time to speak, so i [+tense situation and emotion] can speak to these many people.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cèku = saya, aku (in tense"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">cèku = saya, aku (in tense and emotional situation)</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-12-16 03:59:31Z">\va cuku (Lena)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ka komedhaa madhutu kahèi lii manèngi Paulus. Hèia Paulus titu ètu dedha langa, ka na ded'e kacui-aai na, manèngi rèngu mau-mau, ho na neo padhai lii. Ka na mulai padhai lii tao lii rèngu unu ra, lii Aram. (Te ètu èèna, bèli-bèli dhèu Ibrani padhai lii pake lii Aram).<bt>And so that commander went along with Paulus' request. Then Paulus stood on the steps, and raised his hand asking them to be quiet, so he could speak. And he began to speak using their own language, that Aram language. (Cause then, the Ibrani people daily spoke using that Aram language).</bt><note reference="21:40" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii &lt;dhèu Ibrani&gt; dènge &lt;dhèu Yahudi&gt;, ngara se sasoa na, dhèu èci èèna ka. Sama sèmi &lt;dhèu Dhao&gt; dènge &lt;dhèu Kahore&gt;.<bt>The words &lt;Ibrani people&gt; and &lt;Jahudi people&gt;, the names signify one/same group of people. It is just like &lt;Dhao people&gt; and the &lt;Kahore people&gt;.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus siri iisi na [\s2]<bt>Paulus defends himself [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="22" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia Paulus mulai ded'e lii padhai, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama, dènge mone-aanga angalai aa'i-aa'i! Ja'a manèngi, sèna ka miu nanene ku ja'a, te ja'a neo siri iisi ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Paulus began to speak, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers, and all you important friends (I think that is the sense of this wording)! I ask that you listen to me, cause I want to defend myself.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu ae ka nanene Paulus padhai lii tao lii rèngu. Ka ra mau-mau dènge ka, ho neo nanene paie-iie lii padhai lii na. Hèia na tuhu, peka na,<bt>At that time, there were many who heard Paulus speaking using their language. And they became quiet immediately, wanting to listen carefully to what he said. Then he continued, saying,</bt><v n="3" />&lt;&lt;Sèna ka miu me'a, ja'a ne dhèu Yahudi. Ina ku nara iisi ja'a ètu kota Tarsus, ètu propensi Kilikia. Te ngaa ja'a kapai ètu ne'e, ètu kota Yerusalem. Dhu aj'a ja'a, nuka mese aae ètu ne'e, ngara na Gamaliel. Na aj'a ja'a atora aa'i-aa'i nèti baki Musa toke d'ai lutu-sela. Ja'a maj'èni madhutu Ama Lamatua kahèi, sama sèmi miu aa'i-aa'i mi.<bt>&lt;&lt;As long as you(pl) know I am a Jahudi person. My mother gave birth to me in the city of Tarsus, in the province of Kilikia. But I grew up here, in the city of Yerusalem. The one who taught me is that great teacher here, named Gamaliel. He taught me fully and in detail all the regulations from Grandpa Musa. I was also diligent/zealous in following God, just like all of you here.</bt><note reference="22:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 5:34-39</note><v n="4" />Lod'o dhu uru sèra, ja'a loe boe laku paj'èra dènge pasusa dhèu-dhèu dhu madhutu J'ara Mamuri Yesus. Ja'a nuni kèti si, bhèni-mone, mai asa Yerusalem ne. Ho èèna na, core asa d'ara bèdho lasi. Lod'o èèna, abhu kahèi dhu madhe.<v n="5" />Kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi, dènge ama agama Yahudi dhu leo sèra, rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra re'a, ngaa dhu ja'a peka ne, lèke tare'a sèmi èèna! Ja'a padhai lii hèb'a hua boe. Te rèngu sèra ka dhu pangèd'u ja'a sasuri koasa, ho laku kèpe dhèu dhu madhutu Yesus sèra, toke d'ai kota Damsik. Ètu nèi, ja'a neo kèpe si, ho ère kèti mai asa Yerusalem. Madhutu dad'èi ja'a, hud'i laa dhèu-dhèu dhu pama'ète lii langu agama sèra ka dhu huku si.&gt;&gt;<Annotation class="General" selectedText="tuhu = sambung; |b3:|r lutu-sela ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tuhu = sambung; <span class="Bold">3:</span> lutu-sela = fully and in detail, dari kasar maupun halus ; lutu = halus ; sela = kasar (benda); <span class="Bold">5:</span> aree = menghukum ( memberi hukuman )= paj'èra ; hèb'a hua boe = sonde omong kosong ; pangèd'u = kasi pegang, titip ; aree = hukum, punish (formal) (kuno?)</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:4-5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 8:3, 26:9-11</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus lole ngaa-ngaa dhu nèngu paraga [\s2]<bt>Paulus tells what he encountered [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 9:1-19, 26:12-18)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia Paulus tuhu hari lii padhai lii na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèti èèna ka, ja'a pakèd'i laku asa Damsik, ho tenge si ètu nèi. Pe d'ai lod'o titu mera sa, ji'i oe d'ai ka d'ara kota èèna. Cag'ag'a laa, saraa aae èci senter lèke ja'a nèti dedha-liru mai.<bt>Then Paulus continued, saying, &lt;&lt;Because of that, I left going to Damsik, to look for them yonder. Around midday, we were almost at that city. Suddenly, a bright light spotlighted me, coming from up in the sky.</bt><v n="7" />Hèia ja'a bèbhe baa-baa ètu rai, ka ja'a tadèngi lii èci, peka na, &lt;He Saulus! Nga tao ka èu paj'èra ja'a sèmi ne'e ne?&gt;<bt>Then I fell collapsing on the ground, and I heard a voice, saying, &lt;He Saulus! Why are you persecuting me like this?&gt;</bt><v n="8" />Ja'a mema tadèngi lii èèna, te ngaa ladhe kèdhi boe dhèu. Hèia ja'a karèi, aku ja'a na, &lt;Ama dhu padhai lii ne, cee ka èu?&gt;<bt>I really heard that voice, but I didn't see anybody. Then I asked, saying, &lt;Lord/master who is speaking here, who are you?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="uku kedi = bekin sengsara secara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">uku kedi = bekin sengsara secara fisik,; <span class="Bold">8:</span> @@grammar of complementiser</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka lii èèna dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;Ja'a ne'e ka Yesus, dhèu Nasaret, dhu èu paj'èra!&gt;<bt>And the voice responded, saying, &lt;I here, am Yesus, the Nasaret person, whom you have been persecuting!&gt;</bt><v n="9" />Aa dhèu-dhèu dhu kako palere dènge ja'a, rèngu rèdhi saraa èèna kahèi, te ngaa tadèngi boe lii.<bt>But [=contrary to expectation], the people who were escorting me, they also saw that light, but they didn't hear that voice.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka ja'a b'ala lii èèna, aku ja'a na, &lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, ja'a hud'i tao tasamia hari ku?&gt;<bt>And I replied to that voice, saying, &lt;If like that, what must I do now?&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia lii ne peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;Kèd'i ka, ho lamu asa d'ara kota. Pe d'ai nèi, Ja'a heka peka dènge èu kèna ngaa dhu èu hud'i tao.&gt;<bt>Then this voice spoke, saying, &lt;Get up, to go into the city. Then arriving yonder, only then will I speak with you about what you must do.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hud'i ... ku = modal connected"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hud'i ... ku = modal connected with hud'i</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ropa tadèngi èle lii èèna, ja'a kèd'i titu. Te ngaa ja'a kèdhi heka ngaa-ngaa, lula saraa aae èèna madèka titu kèna. Ka anga ja'a sèra, sarad'e rèti ja'a asa d'ara kota Damsik.<bt>When I heard those instructions, I got up. But I could no longer see anything, because that birght light had been so sharp/bright. And my companions led me (like a blind person) into the city of Damsik.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mad'èka = tajam"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">mad'èka = tajam</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ètu èèna, abhu dhèu èci, ngara na Ananias. Nèngu ne, ca dhèu dhu d'ara mola, aa kèpe pa'èra atora nèti baki Musa. Dhèu Yahudi aa'i-aa'i dhu pea ètu d'ara kota èèna, ra d'èi ne, dènge pakab'ua ne kahèi.<bt>There, there was a person named Ananias. He was a person with straight/pure insides, and help firmly to the regulations from Grandpa Musa. All they Jahudi people who live in that city, liked him and also respected him.</bt><v n="13" />Na mai tenge ja'a, ka na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;Saulus! Musi madha èu be'a le! De bhoke ka musi madha èu.&gt; Ropa na padhai lii nare, ka ja'a ded'e rèhu ja'a, ka ja'a kèdhi dènge ne ka.<bt>He came looking for me, and he spoke, saying, &lt;Saulus! Your eyes are good/healed now! So open your eyes.&gt; When he finished speaking, I lifted my face, and I saw him immediately.</bt><v n="14" />Hèia na aj'a ja'a, aku nèngu na, &lt;Ama Lamatua dhu bèi-baki èdhi manèngi-mangaj'i, Nèngu èèna ka dhu hag'e nare le èu. Sasab'a èu ka, nuka èu hud'i me'a pabe'a-be'a ku dad'èi Na. Aa èu hud'i tadhe ku Yesus, dhu karèi nèti uru ka mai, èdhi ale Ne, &lt;&lt;Dhèu Mola-Mèci&gt;&gt;. Limuri ne, Lamatua bhoke le j'ara, ho èu tadèngi unu mu nèti Yesus.<bt>Then he taught/advised me, saying, &lt;The God whom our(inc) ancestors worshipped, is the one who has set you apart. Your work is to truly understand His will. And to know/recognise that Yesus, who since long ago we have referred to Him, as &lt;&lt;Holy (straight-clean) Person&gt;&gt;! Now, God2 has opened the way, for you to hear for yourself from Yesus.</bt><v n="15" />Nèngu unu Na ka dhu hag'e nare èu, sèna ka lamu lole peka dènge dhèu ètu mia-mia Lii Lolo Be'a Na. Èu hud'i lole aa'i ku, ngaa-ngaa dhu èu mèdhi dènge musi madha unu mu, aa aa'i-aa'i dhu èu tadèngi nèti Nèngu.<bt>He Himself is the one who set you apart, so that you would go tell people everywhere His Good News. You must fully tell whatever/everything that you have seen with your own eyes, and everything that you have heard from Him.</bt><v n="16" />Èu mate ia ka panèbhu. Lamu sèna ka manèngi ho ra sarani mu. Sena ka j'aj'i mi tadha dhu peka na, èu manèngi le sèna ka Lamatua Yesus saku eele sasala-sasigo èu aa'i-aa'i ra.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>You won't need to wait much longer. Go to ask them to baptise you. As a sign that you have asked the Lord Yesus to wipe away all your wrongs (doublet).&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ale = sebut ; unumu &lt;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ale = sebut ; unumu &lt; unu-mu; <span class="Bold">16:</span> panèbhu = lama</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama Lamatua pua Paulus ho nèti Lii Holo-Nori Na mi suku Yahudi boe sèra [\s2]<bt>God tells Paulus to take His Words/Sayings to other people who are not Jahudi [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />&lt;&lt;Èle èèna ka, ja'a lèpa asa Yerusalem. Ca lod'o ja'a laku sabaj'a asa d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ropa ja'a sabaj'a era, Lamatua hia ja'a kèdhi ètu d'ara tanila.<bt>After that, I returned to Yerusalem. One day I went to pray in the Temple. While I was still praying, God2 allowed/gave me to see a vision.</bt><v n="18" />Ja'a ladhe kèdhi Yesus. Hèia Na paredha ja'a, peka na, &lt;Limuri ne, èu hud'i tèke eele ka kota Yerusalem ne! Te dhèu ètu se'e se, ro'o boe sèmi rare ngaa dhu èu aj'a rèngu lula-nèti Ja'a.&gt;<bt>I saw Yesus. Then He commanded me, saying, &lt;You must now leave behind this city of Yerusalem! Because these people here to not want to accept what you are teaching them about My name/reputation.&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Te ngaa ja'a ko'o boe sèmi lii paredha èèna, lula uru èèna, ama agama sèra mema d'èi le ja'a. Ka ja'a dhaa, peka na, &lt;Sèmi ne'e, Lamatua! Rèngu aa'i-aa'i dhu re'a le, uru èèna ja'a ka dhu maso-kalua èmu sabaj'a ètu mia-mia, ho kèpe aa game dhèu dhu parcaya mi Lamatua sèra.<bt>But I didn't want to accept that command, because previously, the religious leaders had really liked me. And I responded, saying, &lt;It's like this, Lord! All of them know that I used to enter-exit houses of worship everywhere, to arrest and beat people who believed in You/Lord.</bt><v n="20" />Rèngu re'a kahèi, lod'o rèngu pèci pamadhe dhèu pajuu-paleha Lamatua, Stefanus, ja'a ètu madha kahèi, aa ja'a ko'o kahèi. Lod'o ra oru hadhu ho pèci ne, ja'a ka dhu pua si, aa ja'a ka dhu laladhe kodho si.&gt;<bt>They also know, when they stoned to death the servant/emissary of the Lord, Stefanus, I was also present, and I also wanted it. When they were gathering rocks to stone him, I am the one who ordered them, and I am the one who looked after their clothes.&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ja'a kèpe &gt; ji'i kèpa @@;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ja'a kèpe &gt; ji'i kèpa @@; <span class="Bold">20:</span> oru = kumpul</Message></Annotation><note reference="22:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 7:58</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Masi ka ja'a pasanèd'e Ne, te ngaa Yesus hia hari paredha, peka na, &lt;Tenge ia ka madha j'ara ae-ae! Tèke eele ka Yerusalem. Lamu dènge ka, d'ara lai-lai ne! Te Ja'a neo pua èu lamu asa era-era kaj'èu, ho aj'a dhèu-dhèu leo dhu Yahudi boe.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>I reminded Him but Yesus commanded me again (or gave me another command), saying, &lt;Don't look for any more excuses! Leave behind Yerusalem. God immediately and without delay! Because I am going to send you tot go to far-away places, to teach other people who are not Jahudi.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madha j'ara = Idiom alasan, hal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">madha j'ara = Idiom alasan, hal ; dara lai-lai = cepat-cepat, jang tunggu lai</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa dhèu ae se tadèngi Paulus peka na, Lamatua pua le nèngu la'e asa dhèu-dhèu leo, ka ro'o heka nanene lii padhai na. Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra nasa, hèia ra pa'oo palere-lere, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mi nanene ia ka dhèu ne'e ne! Kalabhe pamadhe ne! Tèke ia ka na mamuri.&gt;&gt;<bt>When those many people heard Paulus say that God2 had ordered him to go to other people, they didn't want to listen to him anymore. They were all angry, then they shouted all around, saying, &lt;&lt;Don't listen to this person any more! Beat him to death! Don't let him live any longer.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sordad'u sèra rèti Paulus asa d'ara benteng<bt>Those soldiers take Paulus into the fort</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ropa dhèu ae se pa'oo-parodha sèmi èèna, ka ra bhoke eele kodho li'u si nèti ua ra, dènge ra da'u ahu ho ceb'e asa dedha, lula ra nasa ae titu kèna.<bt>While these many people were shouting like that, they took off their outer clothes from their bodies, and they threw dust up into the air, because they were furious.</bt><v n="24" />Lod'o komedhaa sordad'u ladhe, na, dhèu se maruru hari, ka na pua ana bua na ère rèti Paulus asa d'ara benteng la'e. Hèia komedhaa pua ra kalabhe Paulus, sèna ka na mangaku na tao sala ngaa, ka dhèu Yahudi se neo pamadhe ne.<bt>When the commander of the soldiers saw these people causing a commotion/riot again, he ordered his underlings to take Paulus into the fort. Then the commander ordered them to beat Paulus (with instrument), so that he would confess whatever wrong it was that made the Jahudi people want to kill him.</bt><v n="25" />Ropa ra èki Paulus ho neo kalabhe ne, hèia na piku koko na, ka na karèi sordad'u èèna, peka na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu atora paredha Roma, mia dhu lèke? Ladhe ca dhèu dhu dènge hak ana kabarai Roma, sèmi nèngu dhu ètu d'ara lii langu, miu tao ne tasamia? Mi hake paparu uuru, do, mi parisa ne uru ku?&gt;&gt;<bt>When they tied Paulus, about to beat him, then he turned to look over shoulder, and he asked that soldier, saying, &lt;&lt;According to Roma government regulations, which is correct? If a person who has the rights of a citizen of Roma, is received into a dispute, how must you(pl) treat him? Do you strike him repeatedly first, or do you examine him first?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="da'u = ra'u (KM) ; cebe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">da'u = ra'u (KM) ; cebe = buang ke atas (sand, flour, ashes, not stones, etc); <span class="Bold">24:</span> kalabhe = also firuk; <span class="Bold">25:</span> paparu = repeatedly</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02025b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horozontalPosition:right">Ra èki Paulus ho neo hake paparu ne<bt>They tie Paulus about to strike him repeatedly</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ropa tadèngi nare lii sèmi èèna, sordad'u èèna la'e karohe-rohe tenge komedhaa na. Ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Ama! Dhèu ne'e ne, dènge hak ana kabarai Roma! De ama neo tao ne tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>When he heard that, the soldier went quickly to look for the commander. And he sak, &lt;&lt;Father! This person has the rights of a citizen of Roma! So, what does father/you want to do?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="karohe-rohe = lai-lai, cepat-cepat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">karohe-rohe = lai-lai, cepat-cepat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, hèia komedhaa la'e karèi Paulus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ra peka, na, èu ne dènge hak ana kabarai Roma. Tare'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that, then the commander went himself to ask Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;They say that you have the rights of a citizen of Roma, right? Is that true?&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Paulus b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mema tare'a! Ja'a unu hak èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Paulus replied, saying, &lt;&lt;Yes, that's true! I own/possess that right.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="la'e madha na = sendiri pi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">la'e madha na = sendiri pi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Èle èèna ka, komedhaa peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a sèmi èèna kahèi. Ja'a b'ae kab'ua aae, heka abhu hak èèna kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the commander spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I am also like that. I paid a great price, and only then did I get that right.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Paulus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, b'ae boe ngaa-ngaa. Karèi nèti ina ku nara iisi ja'a, ja'a dhu dènge le hak èèna. Ama ku unu hak èèna kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Paulus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;As for me, I didn't pay anything. Since my mother gave birth to me, I have had that right. My father also had that right.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ropa rèngu tadèngi dhu Paulus dènge hak ana kabarai Roma, ka sordad'u sèra hari kabodho, ka ra bani heka game dènge parisa lii langu nèti Paulus. Ka komedhaa ne j'aj'i madha'u, lula nèngu èki le Paulus, aa dhu peka na nèngu sisu le madha j'ara paredha.<bt>When he heard that Paulus had the rights of a citizen of Roma, those soldiers retreated, and they no longer had the courage to beat or examine Paulus case. And the commander was afraid, because he had bound Paulus, and had by-passed the govenrment regulations.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hari kabodho = mundur belakang ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hari kabodho = mundur belakang ; sisu = 2) lawan, rebut, refute 1) pass someone (on trail)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus ètu era pama'ète lii langu agama Yahudi<bt>Paulus in the Place of Deciding Jahudi Religious Disputes</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Asa bèli èèna, komedhaa èèna neo ne'a tare'a-re'a, j'aj'aj'i nèti lii langu èèna, tasamia. Hèia na pua dhèu sab'a na lasi paroa kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu biasa uri lii langu agama Yahudi, sèna ka ra pakaboko. Ka na pua si bhoke eele rate nèti Paulus, ho rèti ne la'e asa madha dhèu sèra aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>The next day, the commander wanted to really find out what was the cause of that dispute, So he ordered his underlings to go summon all the people who normally managed the Jahudi religious disputes, so they would gather. And he ordered them to undo Paulus' chains, to bring him before all those people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="23" />
      <v n="1" />D'ai èèna, ka ra hia Paulus sèna ka na siri iisi na. Hèia na ladhe palème dhèu ètu sèra aa'i-aa'i ra, ka na j'oka padhai lii na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari! Ja'a titu ètu era ne'e, dènge d'ara mola. Ama Lamatua dhu ne'a, na, ja'a karèi nèti ana iiki mai, d'ara ja'a dhu mola.&gt;&gt;<bt>Arriving there, they allowed Paulus to defend himself. Then he looked around at all those people, and he began his speech, saying, &lt;&lt;Older-younger siblings! I stand in this place, with clean/pure insides. God knows that since I was young/small, my insides have been pure.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="j'oka = angkat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">j'oka = angkat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ropa tadèngi Paulus padhai lii sèmi èèna, Ananias<bt>When he heard Paulus speak like that, Ananias</bt><note reference="23:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ananias ne'e ne, nèngu kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi kahèi, te ngaa Ananias dhu huku Lamatua Yesus, leo hari. Dua ra, ngara sama.<bt>This Ananias was also the Jahudi High Priest, but he is not the Ananias who punished the Lord Yesus. The two of them have the same name.</bt></note>, kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi, nasa titu kèna. Hèia na hia paredha mi dhèu dhu titu padètu dènge Paulus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tèbe hèb'a na!&gt;&gt;<bt>, the Jahudi *High Priest, was furious. Then he gave a command to people standing near Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;Slap his mouth!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tèbe = tampar, tampeleng"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tèbe = tampar, tampeleng</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka Paulus b'ala Ananias, peka na, &lt;&lt;Pe Ama Lamatua b'ala tèb'e hèb'a èu. Te èu nuka sèmi agarii dhu heka lèke lame re li'u, te re d'ara dhu moca le. Èu madhèdi ètu era ne'e ne, ho tao ngi'u mu sèmi dhèu mola sa. Aa èu neo huku ja'a madhutu atora ad'a èdhi. Te ngaa èu unu mu sisu eele atora èèna, lod'o èu pua dhèu tèb'e ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Paulus responded to Ananias, saying, &lt;&lt;God will later repay your slapping of the mouth. Because you are like a pole/pillar which is only whitewashed on the outside, while its inside is rotted away (like termite eaten wood, or a core tree that is rotted away by a strangler fig). You sit in this place to make yourself (seem) like you are clean/pure. And you want to punish me to follow our(inc) adat regulations. But you yourself by-pass/ignore those regulations, when you ordered people to slap me.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="agarii = tiang ; lame ~"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">agarii = tiang ; lame ~ dame = labur, whitewash ; anarai = termites, anay-anay ; moca = su puruk di dalam (like a strangler fig that has not centre) ; bhoo dara = hol (hollow) ; mèje dara = like a long dead animal</Message></Annotation><note reference="23:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 23:27-28</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ropa Paulus padhai lii sèmi èèna, dhèu ètu sèra kai ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Heh! Èu bisa boe padhai lii sèmi èèna, mi kètu kapai risi agama èdhi ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Paulus spoke like that, the people there rebuked him, saying, &lt;&lt;He! You cannot speak like that to our(inc) High Priest here!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Hèia Paulus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a, do? Ladhe sèmi èèna, ja'a manèngi sèna ka d'ara baku sala, lula ja'a ke'a boe, na, nèngu ne kètu kapai risi agama èdhi. Mema tare'a, Ama Lamatua pake le dhèu ho suri, peka na, &lt;Miu baku padhai lii karehe mi kètu miu sèra.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Paulus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Is that true, huh? If it's like that, I apologise (idiom: ask that insides not be wrong), because I did not know that he was our High Priest. It is true, God has used people to write that, &lt;You should not speak badly to your heads/leaders.&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="23:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 22:28</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6-8" />Lod'o Paulus ladhe nèdhi dhèu dhu madhèdi pama'ète lii langu agama, na ne'a, peka na, rèngu dhu hag'e mi dua partei. Cahag'e nèti partei Saduki, dhu parcaya dhèu madhe bisa heka mamuri hari. Rèngu parcaya kahèi, peka na, Ama Lamatua dhu dènge boe ana pajuu ètu sorga. Samanga aad'o kahèi. Cahag'e hari madhutu partei Parisi, dhu parcaya, peka na, bèli-camèd'a Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari dhèu madhe. Rèngu sèra parcaya, peka na, ètu sorga Ama Lamatua dènge ana pajuu, aa abhu samanga kahèi.<bt>When Paulus looked at the people who were sitting deciding religious disputes, he knew that they were separated out into two parties. Some were from the Saduki party, who believe that dead people can no longer come back to life. They also believe that God does not have servant/messengers in heaven (=angels).There are also no *souls. The others follow the Parisi party, who believe that in the future God will bring back to life again those people who have died. They believe that in heaven God has servant/messengers, and there are also souls.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Paulus padhai lii dènge lii mèdhu, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari! Sèna ka miu aa'i-aa'i mi me'a, ja'a ne dhèu Parisi. Ama ku dènge baki ku, dhèu Parisi. Deo ne'e ne, miu neo huku ja'a, lula ja'a parcaya, peka na, Ama Lamatua bisa pamamuri hari dhèu madhe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Paulus spoke with a loud voice, saying, &lt;&lt;Older-younger siblings! So that you all know, I here am a Parisi person. My father and my grandfather were Parisi people. Right now you want to judge/punish me, because I believe that God can bring dead people back to life.&gt;&gt;</bt><note reference="23:6-8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 26:5, Pilipi 3:5, Mateos 22:23, Markus 12:18, Lukas 20:27</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa Paulus padhai lii sèmi èèna, dhèu Parisi dènge dhèu Saduki patao, toke rèngu lii èci heka. Ka rèngu se hag'e eele j'aj'i mi dua.<bt>When Paulus spoke like that, the Parisi people and the Saduki people quarreled, to the point that they could no longer agree. And these people separated out into two.</bt><v n="9" />Nèti èèna ka, dhèu se patao, ka j'aj'i maruru aae. Hèia pèri-pèri mese nèti partei Parisi kèd'i titu ho sarii Paulus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne, sala boe! Tao-tao na abhu roh, do, ele boe, ana pajuu Ama Lamatua èci nèti sorga mai, ka padhai lii dènge ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, these people kept arguing and it became a big commotion/riot. Then some of the teachers from the Parisi party stood up to defend Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;This person has not done wrong! Probably there was a *spirit (loan), or maybe even a messenger of God came from heaven and spoke to him!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sarii = bela orang lain"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sarii = bela orang lain</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Masi ka mese se padhai lii le sèmi èèna, te ngaa dhèu sèra asa ra hoe dènge patao. Nèti èèna ka, komedhaa ne j'aj'i madha'u. Na pangee, mage dhoka dhèu se game pamadhe Paulus. Hèia na paredha ana bua na sèra, lasi ère rare ne rèti asa d'ara benteng.<bt>Even though these teachers spoke like that, but those people increased their arguing. Because of that, the commander became afraid. He thought, careful lest those people beat Paulus to death. Then he commanded his underlings to go retrieve him and take him back into the fort.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hoe = semakin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hoe = semakin</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ka d'ara mèda èèna, Lamatua Yesus mai pad'elo iisi mi Paulus. Na pa'èra d'ara Paulus, Na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Paulus! Baku madha'u! Èu ne dhu lole peka le dènge dhèu-dhèu ètu Yerusalem lula-nèti Ja'a. De sanèd'e paie-iie! Èèna na, èu hud'i padhai lii ku sama sèmi èèna kahèi, ètu Roma nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>That night, the Lord Yesus came and revealed himself to Paulus. He strengthened Paulus' insides, and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Paulus! Don't be afraid! You here have already told people in Yerusalem about Me. So you must remember well! Later on, you must speak like that also in Roma yonder.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu pare'a lii ho pamadhe Paulus<bt>People come to an agreement to kill Paulus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12-13" />Asa bèli mad'ae èèna, abhu èpa nguru risi dhèu Yahudi dhu rare lii èci ho neo pamadhe Paulus. Ka ra subha, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i ngo'o mèka nga'a-nginu, ladhe ji'i dhae pamadhe Paulus.&gt;&gt;<bt>The next morning, there were more that 400 Jahudi people who agreed to try to kill Paulus. And they took an oath, saying, &lt;&lt;We(exc) no longer want to eat-drink, if we have not yet killed Paulus.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="14" />Ropa ra subha rare, ka lasi peka dènge kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu heka ad'a Yahudi sèra, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama si! Ji'i pasubha le, peka na, ji'i ngo'o boe nga'a-nginu, ladhe ji'i pamadhe mèka Paulus.<bt>When they had finished oathing, they went to speak with the religious leaders and the Jahudi traditional leaders, saying, &lt;&lt;Fathers, ee! We have sworn an oath that we do not want to eat-drink, if we have not yet killed Paulus.</bt><v n="15" />De dad'èi ji'i sèmi ne'e ka: ama si lami paraga dènge komedhaa, manèngi ho nèngu nèti Paulus asa era uri lii langu agama. Tao nuka sèmi dhu ama si neo hari parisa lii langu na. Pe ji'i mate si ètu talora j'ara, sèna ka pamadhe ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, our desire is like this: (you) fathers must go meet with the commander, to ask him to take Paulus to the place of managing religious disputes. Pretend like you want to examine his case. Then we will wait for them along the road/journey, to kill him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="abhu èpa nguru risi dhèu Yahudi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">abhu èpa nguru risi dhèu Yahudi ~ abhu risi nèti èpa nguru dhèu Yahudi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Te ngaa ana mone èci nèti ana hèni Paulus, tadèngi lii padhue rèngu èèna. Ka rai la'e peka dènge to'o na, asa d'ara benteng.<bt>But a son of Paulus' sister heard that discussion of theirs. And he rain to tell his mother's-brother inside the fort.</bt><v n="17" />Ropa tadèngi nare lii lolo ana ne'e, Paulus paroa nare ama sordad'u dhèu èci, ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ne'e ne, ana ja'a. Lere mèti ne lai-lai asa komedhaa èu. Ho neo peka ngaa èci.&gt;&gt;<bt>When he heard what this child had to say, Paulus summoned a leader of the soldiers, and told him, saying, &lt;&lt;This here is my offspring [-one generation]. Escort him quickly to your commander. He wants to tell him something.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02029b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Ana ne mai peka dhèu dhu neo tao bhelu mi Paulus<bt>The child comes to say that people want to do evil to Paulus</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ka ama sordad'u èèna lere nèti ana ne asa komedhaa na. Hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Paulus dhu èdhi taha na, manèngi sèna ka ja'a kèti ana ne'e mai asa madha ama. Te nèngu neo peka ngaa èci.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the leader of the soldiers escorted this child to his commander. Then he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Father! Paulus whom we have detained, has asked that I bring this child here before you. Cause he wants to say something.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Hèia komedhaa kadhèi kacui-aai ana ne asa era èci, sèna ka dua ra di. Ka na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu neo peka ngaa dènge ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the commander took the child by the hand to a place, so that the two of them were alone. And he asked, saying, &lt;&lt;What do you want to say to me?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kadhèi = pegang (tangan)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kadhèi = pegang (tangan)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Hèia ana ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi dhu rare lii èci, ho neo pamadhe to'o ku. Rèngu neo mai manèngi ama, sèna ka bèli èèna, ama lere mèti to'o ku, Paulus asa era uri lii langu agama. Rèngu se dhu leko-monya ho neo parisa hari lii Paulus, toke d'ai lutu la'e.<bt>Then the child responded, saying, &lt;&lt;There are several Jahudi people who have reached an agreement wanting to kill my mother's-brother. They want to come ask you(father) to take Paulus to the place for managing religious disputes. These ones are pretending to want to re-examine the case of my mother's-brother, Paulus, in greater detail.</bt><v n="21" />De ama ku baku madhutu dad'èi rèngu. Te èèna na, risi nèti èpa nguru dhèu dhu neo mate ama si ètu talora j'ara, ho ra neo pamadhe to'o ku. Rèngu pasubha le, peka na, rèngu ro'o mèka ra'a-rinu, ladhe rèngu pamadhe mèka to'o Paulus. De nuka ra pa'èra si. Rèngu di mate lii dhaa nèti ama ka.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, you(father +polite) should not follow their desires. Cause there are more than 400 people who want to wait for you all in the middle of the road/journey, wanting to kill my mother's-brother. These are the ones who have taken an oath saying they do not want to eat-drink anymore, if they have not yet killed mother's-brother Paulus. So, they are preparing. They are waiting for a response from you (father).&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lutu = halus; |b21:|r pa'èra ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">lutu = halus; <span class="Bold">21:</span> pa'èra = 1) bekin kuat, 2) siap (bekin sst)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Tadèngi nare lii lolo ana ne'e, hèia komedhaa peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Èu baku peka dènge cee-cee, na, èu mai le peka lii ne'e mi ja'a.&gt;&gt; Ropa padhai lii èle sèmi èèna, na pua ana ne lèpa dènge ka.<bt>Hearing the tale of this child, then the commander told him, &lt;&lt;You must not tell anybody that you have come to speak to me.&gt;&gt; When (they) had finished speaking like that, he told the child to go home immediately.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra lere Paulus asa gubernur Feliks ètu kota Kaisarea<bt>They escort Paulus to governor Feliks in the city of Kaisarea.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Èle èèna, hèia komedhaa paroa kètu sordad'u dhèu dua. Ka na paredha si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu pa'èra sordad'u biasa, dhèu dua ngasu dhèu; sordad'u dhu ca'e jara, pidhu nguru dhèu; dènge sordad'u dhu rèd'u kapoke, dua ngasu dhèu. Miu pakèd'i dènge ka mèda ne'e, d'ara hake ceo, ho lami asa kota Kaisarea.<bt>After that, the commander summoned two of the leaders of soldiers. And he commanded them, saying, &lt;&lt;You(pl) prepare normal soldiers, 200 people; soldiers who mount horses, 70 people; and soldiers who hold spears, 200 people. Leave tonight, at 9 strikes (o'clock), to go to the city of Kaisarea.</bt><v n="24" />Sadia mere jara ci'u hia Paulus. Miu hud'i lere paie-iie Paulus, sèna ka d'ai gubernur Feliks dènge sod'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>You must also prepare a horse for Paulus. You must carefully escort Paulus so that you arrive at governor Feliks safely.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia na suri sasuri hia gubernur Feliks sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>Then he wrote a letter to governor Feliks, like this:</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kapoke = tombak ; kataki hahusu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kapoke = tombak ; kataki hahusu = bow (and arrow)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="26" />&lt;&lt;Ama gubernur Feliks dhu ja'a pakab'ua. Lii maho'o nèti ja'a, Klaudius Lisias.<bt>&lt;&lt;Father governor Feliks whom I respect. Greetings from me, Kaudius Lisias.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">
      <v n="27" />Dhèu dhu ja'a hia dhiu ne, ngara na Paulus. Dhèu Yahudi sèra kèpe rare ne, ka oe ra pamadhe ne kèna. Lod'o èèna, ana bua ja'a lasi nuni rare ne, nèti kacui-aai dhèu Yahudi sèra. Limuri, heka ja'a ke'a kèna, nèngu ne dènge hak ana kabarai Roma.<bt>The person who I am sending, is named Paulus. The Jahudi people caught him and they almost killed him. At that time my underlings went and dragged him out from the hands of those Jahudi people. Later, only then did I know that he has the rights of a citizen of Roma.</bt><v n="28" />Ja'a neo ke'a, nga tao ka dhèu Yahudi se neo pamadhe ne. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a kèti ne asa era uri lii langu agama Yahudi.<bt>I wanted to know why these Jahudi people wanted to kill him. Because of that, I took him to the place of managing Jahudi religious disputes.</bt><v n="29" />Te ngaa ra abhu boe sasala na èci sa. Te mema, nèngu ne tao boe bhelu. De dhèu ne'e ne bisa boe pamaso ne asa d'ara bèdho, aa lèke boe abhu huku madhe. Dhèu ètu era uri lii langu agama Yahudi sèra, ra patao, lula lii holo-nori agama rèngu dhu baka-leo. Ka ja'a kèti hari dhèu ne asa d'ara benteng la'e.<bt>But, they couldn't find a single wrong of his. Cause really, he has not done evil. So, this person could not be put into prison, and it is not fitting that he get the punishment of death. Those people in the place of managing Jahudi religious disputes argued, because the teachings of their religion are not matching up. And I took this person back into the fort.</bt><v n="30" />Te ngaa asa bèli èèna, ja'a tadèngi, na, abhu dhèu Yahudi dhu rare lii èci ho neo pamadhe ne. Ka ja'a ka dhu hia paredha, ho lere rèti dhèu ne asa madha ama. Aa ja'a peka le kahèi dènge dhèu Yahudi sèra, dhu neo tao lii langu dènge dhèu ne'e, na, rèngu hud'i lasi asa madha ama. Sèna ka ama tadèngi unu mu, rèngu galaa ne, sasala na, tasamia.<bt>But the next day, I heard there were Jahudi people who had come to an agreement to try and kill him. So I was the one who gave a command to escort this person before father (you). And I also spoke to those Jahudi people who are making a dispute with this person that they must come before father. So then, father can hear for yourself their accusations, and his wrongs, what they are.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Sasuri ja'a ne, d'ai sange ne'e ka. Makasi ae!&gt;&gt;<bt>This letter of mine, just comes to this limit. Many thanks!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Hèia sordad'u se pa'èra le, ho pakako paredha nèti komedhaa. Ka d'ara mèda na kahèi, lere rèti dènge Paulus d'ai kota cue, ngara na Antipatris.<bt>Then the soldiers prepared to carry out the orders of the commander. So that night they escorted Paulus arriving at a city named Antipatris.</bt><v n="32" />Asa bèli èèna, sordad'u dhu ca'e jara sèra, rèti Paulus d'ai kota Kaisarea. Te ngaa sordad'u dhu leo sèra, lèpa hari asa Yerusalem.<bt>The next morning, the soldiers who rode horses took Paulus until the city of Kaisarea. But the other soldiers turned back to Yerusalem.</bt><v n="33" />Ropa rèngu d'ai Kaisarea, hèia rèti sasuri èèna asa gubernur. Aa ra pangèd'u Paulus asa ai gubernur kahèi.<bt>When they arrived in Kaisarea, they took that aforementioned letter to the governor. And they handed Paulus over to the governor as well.</bt><v n="34" />Baca nare sasuri èèna, hèia gubernur karèi Paulus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne, dhèu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>When he finished reading that letter, then the governor asked Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;You here, are a person from where/what kind of person?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pangèd'u = serahkan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pangèd'u = serahkan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Paulus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, dhèu propensi Kilikia.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Paulus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;I here, am a person from the province of Kilikia.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ropa tadèngi Paulus peka sèmi èèna, ka gubernur ne'a, na, Paulus dhu nèd'u hak ana kabarai Roma. Hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ka dhu kèd'u paredha ètu ne'e. De èèna na, ja'a ka dhu uri lii langu èu ne. Te ngaa èdhi hud'i mate ku dhèu-dhèu dhu galaa èu sèra, d'ai ne'e, heka ja'a parisa lii langu èu kèna.&gt;&gt; Hèia na pua sordad'u sèra taha Paulus ètu era rèngu, ètu d'ara kompleks èmu pea gubernur, dhu uru èèna dhèu aae Herodes patitu.<bt>When he heard Paulus say that, the governor knew that Paulus held the rights of a citizen of Roma. Then he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;I am the one who holds government here. So later on I am the one who will manage your dispute. But, we(inc) must wait for the people who are accusing you to arrive here, and only then will I examine your case.&gt;&gt; Then he ordered those soldiers to detain Paulus in their place, inside the residential komplex (loan) of the governor, which formerly King Herodes had built.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu Yahudi mai tao lii langu dènge Paulus ètu Kaisarea<bt>The Jahudi people come to litigate against Paulus in Kaisarea</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="24" />
      <v n="1" />Èle lèmi lod'o, hèia dhèu-dhèu Yahudi dhu neo tao lii langu dènge Paulus, mai d'ai kota Kaisarea. D'ara kaboko rèngu èèna, abhu dhèu èci, ngara na Ananias, dhu j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi. Dhèu kapai dhu leo sèra madhutu kahèi. Rèngu mai dènge dhèu èci, ngara na Tertulus. Dhèu èèna, d'èlu-mèu padhai lii. Nèti èèna ka, ra rare ne j'aj'i tuka padhai lii, ho lab'a Paulus.<bt>After five days, then the Jahudi people who wanted to litigate against Paulus came arriving in the city of Kaisarea. Among their group was a person named Ananias, who was the High Priest of the Jahudi Religion. Other leaders/fathers also followed. They came with a person named Tertulus. That person was clever/gifted in speaking. Because of that, they took him as their spokesperson to oppose Paulus.</bt><v n="2-3" />Ropa dhèu sèra aa'i-aa'i ra tesa ètu era parisa lii langu èèna, hèia gubernur pua rèti Paulus asa d'ara mai. Hèia Tertulus kèd'i titu, neo padhai lii pamanahu Paulus. Ka na hia hormat mi gubernur, ka na j'oka padhai lii, aku nèngu na,<bt>When all those people were present in the place of examining the dispute, then the governor ordered that they bring Paulus in. Then Tertulus stood up wanting to speak bringing down Paulus. And he gave respect to the governor, and he began to speak, saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tesa = hadir lengkap"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tesa = hadir lengkap</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">&lt;&lt;Ama gubernur dhu ja'a pakab'ua! Nèbhu nare sèmi ne'e, mulai ama mèd'u paredha ètu ne'e, ama dhu me'a uuru le, ngaa dhu be'a hia ji'i. Aa ama tao babe'a ae le kahèi, toke ji'i dhèu Yahudi bisa mamuri dènge mera-milu, karej'e-karae, aa dènge boe lii langu. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i pake lod'o ne'e, sèna ka manèngi makasi ae-ae mi ama gubernur. Dhèu cee hari ka dhu bisa tao be'a ae ètu mia-mia, sama sèmi ama ne.<bt>&lt;&lt;Father governor whom I respect! For a long time, beginning from when father(you) began to hold government here, you had already known beforehand what is good for us(exc). And you have done many good things, to the point that we Jahudi people can live in peace-and-prosperity, happiness, and without dispute. Because of that, we want to use this time/opportunity to give many thanks to father governor. Who else is there who could do so much good, like you, father.</bt><v n="4" />Te ngaa ja'a padhai lii pamadhera heka, ja'a kore dhoka isi di. De ja'a manèngi ama nanene paie-iie, j'ara-j'ara dhu ja'a neo peka lula-nèti Paulus ne.<bt>But, I don't want to speak much longer, so I will just take the contents (=get straight to the point). So I ask father to listen carefully, to the matters I want to say about this Paulus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Sèmi ne'e ku, ama. Madhutu a'abhu ji'i dhèu Yahudi, Paulus ne èci èèna ka dènge èi papèd'a dhu rai nèti era èci asa era èci la'e. Nèngu ne, d'èi palab'a dènge agama ji'i, aa tuka pa'ele iie ad'a ji'i ètu mia-mia. Nèngu la'e asa era mia èèna ka, tatu dhèu Yahudi hud'i tao ku lii langu èci dènge èci. Nèngu ne tuka dadugu-rariu nèti partei agama dhu madhutu ca dhèu nèti Nasaret, dhu ji'i pangare na, &lt;partei Nasrani&gt;. Te ngaa dhu rèngu aj'a sèra, pasala kapai dènge agama ji'i.<bt>It's like this, father. According to the thinking of we(exc) Jahudi people, this Paulus is like a disease that spreads from one place to another. He likes to oppose our religion, and is a destroyer of our adat everywhere. Wherever he goes, it is certain that the Jahudi people there will (start) having disputes with each other. He is an inciter/provocateur from a religious party that follows a person from Nasaret, who we refer to as the &lt;Nasrani party&gt;. But, what they teach is in gross conflict/error with our religion.</bt><v n="6" />Dhèu ne'e ne, neo pakaj'alu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ji'i dhu mola-mèci èèna. Aa nèti dènge dhèu dintiu asa d'ara la'e. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i kèpe ngare ne. [Madhutu dad'èi ji'i, ji'i neo huku ne, pake atora ji'i unu mi.<bt>This person is one who wants to defile our holy Temple. And he takes infidels inside it. Because of that, we caught/arrested him. [It is our desire to judge/punish him according to the regulations of our own religion.</bt><v n="7" />Te ngaa komedhaa Lisias mai ère nare ne nèti kacui-aai ji'i.<bt>But, commander Lisias came and took him out from under our hands.</bt><v n="8" />Hèia na paredha, peka na, ladhe abhu dhèu dhu neo tao lii langu dènge Paulus, hud'i lasi ku asa madha ama gubernur ètu Kaisarea. Madhutu dad'èi na, sèna ka ama gubernur unu mu ka dhu uri lii èèna.]<bt>Then he commanded that if there were people who wanted to litigate aganist Paulus, they must go before father governor in Kaisarea. It tis our desire that father governor himself be the one to handle the case.]</bt><note reference="24:6-8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii-lii dhu ètu d'ara kurung ne, abhu boe ètu Alkitab lii Yunani dhu uru-uru sèra.<bt>The words/sentences in parentheses (&lt;corral-loan), are not found in the oldest Yunani language Bibles.</bt></note>Ka limuri ne, ji'i mai asa ne'e, sèna ka ama parisa lii ne. Pe èèna na, ama unu mu me'a ngaa dhu ji'i lole ne, mema lèke tare'a-re'a.<bt>And now, we have come here so that you will/can examine this case. Later on, you yourself will know that what we are telling you is completely true.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rai oru-oru = spread tidak menetap;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rai oru-oru = spread tidak menetap; <span class="Bold">6:</span> dinitiu; <span class="Bold">8:</span> taa = zaman, tebho</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">D'ai sange èèna ka. Makasi ae.&gt;&gt;<bt>That's the limit. Many thanks.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ropa Tertulus padhai lii nare, ka dhèu Yahudi leo sèra, re lii padhai lii na kahèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a, ama! Dhu lèke kèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Tertulus finished speaking, the other Jahudi people sided with what he said, saying, &lt;&lt;True, father! That's right!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ree = ikut, bela, pro atau"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ree = ikut, bela, pro atau memihak ; sarii = membela</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus siri iisi na ètu madha gubernur Feliks<bt>Paulus defends himself before governor Feliks</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Hèia gubernur paredha Paulus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ne'e ne, ja'a hia èu tebho ho siri iisi èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the governor commanded Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;Now, I am giving you time/opportunity to defend yourself.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Paulus kèd'i titu, ka na ded'e lii padhai, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama gubernur! Ama paredha nèbhu le ètu propensi ji'i ne. De ama dhu me'a le tare'a-re'a, j'ara mamuri ji'i dhèu Yahudi, tasa mera mia. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a madha'u boe siri iisi ètu katanga madha ama.<bt>Then Paulus stood up and began to speak, saying, &lt;&lt;Father governor! You have already governed for a long time in this province of ours(exc). So, you truly undersand how our Jewish way of life is. Because of that, I am not afraid to defend myself before you.</bt><v n="11" />Pe d'ai canguru dua lod'o dhu la'e èèna, ja'a laku asa Yerusalem ho sabaj'a ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ama bisa karèi sèku dhèu-dhèu dhu sabaj'a sama-sama dènge ja'a lod'o èèna.<bt>Around 12 days ago, I went to Yerusalem to pray in the Temple. You may just ask (or, are welcome to ask) people who were there praying with me that day.</bt><v n="12" />Ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ja'a pab'ala boe dènge ca dhèu sa. Aa ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a dhu leo sèra kahèi, ja'a oru kore boe dhèu ho tao maruru. Sèmi èèna kahèi, ètu Yerusalem, ja'a pakaco boe.<bt>In the Temple, I did not oppose a single person. And in other houses of worship as well, I did not collect people together to cause a commotion/riot. In that same way, in Yerusalem, I did not create chaos.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ugu-ge'e boe = tidak bersuara, ge'e"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ugu-ge'e boe = tidak bersuara, ge'e = babi mai grunt ; ugu = k.o. ikan stays in lobang batu biak dan babunyi-babunyi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa limuri ne, dhèu se neo pamanahu ja'a. Ngaa dhu ra padhai lii deo sa, lèke boe, lula dènge boe bukti.<bt>But now, these people are trying to bring me down. What they just said is not true, because there is no proof.</bt><v n="14" />Sèmi ne'e ka, ama gubernur. Ja'a hud'i mangaku ku mi ama, ngaa èci. Ja'a dhu madhutu partei hiu èci, dhu dhèu pangare na &lt;J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus&gt;. Ja'a sabaj'a mi Ama Lamatua, sama sèmi bèi-baki ja'a sèra sabaj'a mi Nèngu. Ja'a madhutu kahèi atora aa'i-aa'i nèti baki Musa, dènge parcaya tare'a-re'a ngaa dhu dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua uru-uru sèra, suri tèke hia ji'i.<bt>It's like this, father governor. I must confess/acknowledge to father one thing. I do follow a new party, which people refer to as the &lt;Life Way of the Lord Yesus&gt;. I pray to/worship God, just like those ancestors of mine worshipped Him. I also follow all the regulations from Grandpa Musa, and truly believe what the people who brought God's words/saying long ago have written down for us(exc).</bt><v n="15" />Ja'a sanao-maena mi Ama Lamatua, sama sèmi rèngu dhu titu ètu se'e se, ho ra lab'a ja'a ne. Ji'i se parcaya, na, bèli-camèd'a Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari dhèu madhe: dhèu be'a, do bhelu-katub'a, èci èèna ka.<bt>I hope (doublet) in God, just like those who are standing here also do, who are wanting to oppose me. We believe that in the future god will bring dead people back to life: good people, or evil (doublet), it is the same.</bt><v n="16" />Nèti èèna ka, ja'a ma'ète boe tenge j'ara, sèna ka ja'a bisa mamuri dènge d'ara mola ètu katanga madha Ama Lamatua, aa dhèu rai-haha kahèi. Dènge sèmi èèna ka, dhèu èci sa bisa boe pamanahu ja'a.<bt>Because of that, I never stop looking for a way so that I can live with a clean/pure inside before God, and humans. In that way, nobody will be able to bring me down.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sanao-maena = ; sanao = mengharapkan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sanao-maena = ; sanao = mengharapkan ; maena = berharap</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ja'a sab'a pèri-pèri tèu kèna, ètu li'u rai Isra'el, ka ja'a heka lèpa asa Yerusalem kèna. Lod'o ja'a mai èèna, ja'a kèti doi dhu dhèu pakaboko sèna ka bantu dhèu-dhèu ji'i dhu mamuri j'èra. Èle ka, ja'a laku asa Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ho neo sabaj'a, aa hia korban rupa-rupa mi Ama Lamatua ètu èèna.<bt>I have worked for several years outside the land of Isra'el, and I have just recently returned to Yerusalem. When I came there, I brought money which people had gathered to help our people who are living in difficulty. After that, I went to the Temple wanting to pray/worship, and give various sacrifices (loan) to God there.</bt><v n="18" />Ropa ja'a pamèu iisi ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i madhutu j'ara ad'a ji'i, ka rèngu mai ho neo kèpe ja'a. Te ngaa lod'o èèna, dhèu ae boe ètu sèra, aa èci sa dhu tao pakaco boe ngaa-ngaa!<bt>Whe I was purifying myself there in the Temple according to the ways of our adat, they came to try and arrest me. But at that time, there were not very many people there, and there was not one who was causing any chaos whatsoever!</bt><note reference="24:17-18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 21:17-28</note><v n="19" />Dhu ètu èèna, dhoka pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi nèti propensi Asia, dhu mai neo sabaj'a ètu èèna kahèi. De ladhe rèngu sèi dhu neo tao lii langu dènge ja'a, rèngu sèra ka dhu hud'i mai tao lii langu dènge ja'a ku ètu ne'e. Ama se'e se, aad'o!<bt>Those who were there wer only some Jahudi people from the province of Asia, who came to pray/worship there also. So, if those (remote) ones want to have a litigation/dispute with me, they are the ones who must come and litigate with me here. Not these fathers here!</bt><v n="20" />Te ngaa dhèu sèi cèu boe. De ama karèi ku si, sasala ja'a ngaa? Uru èèna, lod'o rèngu parisa lii ja'a ètu era parisa lii langu agama èèna, rèngu abhu boe sasala ja'a èci sa hèi. De ama ku karèi sèku rèngu!<bt>But those (remote) people haven't appeared. So you should just ask these here, what is my wrong/offense? Previously, when they were examining my case at the place of examining religious disputes, they could not find a single wrong there either. So you (father) can just ask them [sens of : have a go at checking this out with them]!</bt><v n="21" />Dhoka ele boe ca j'ara di, dhu tao ngangee rèngu kaco, aa ra d'èi boe ja'a. Ropa ja'a padhai lii dènge lii aae, peka na, &lt;Miu neo huku ja'a, lula ja'a parcaya, na, Ama Lamatua bisa pamamuri hari dhèu madhe!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>There probably is one thing that upsets their thinking, so that they do not like me. When I spoke with a loud voice saying, &lt;You(pl) want to judge/punish me, because I believe that God can bring dead people back to life!&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="@@ soru = 1) sambut 2)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">@@ soru = 1) sambut 2) bantu ; bara = bantu ; soru-bara = bantu (kuno, not known by some younger speakers); <span class="Bold">20:</span> cèu = muncul</Message></Annotation><note reference="24:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 23:6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Paulus padhai lii sèmi èèna, te ngaa, lula gubernur Feliks tadèngi ae le kahèi lula-nèti &lt;J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus&gt;, ka na katange eele sidang èèna, ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e ka! Ja'a neo paroa komedhaa Lisias, ho nanene uuru ku lii lolo nèngu. Ladhe ja'a padhai lii kore ku dènge nèngu, heka ja'a pama'ète lii ne'e kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Paulus spoke like that, but, because governor Feliks had also heard much/many things about &lt;the Life Way of the Lord Yesus&gt;, so he closed the assembly (loan), and spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this! I am going to summon commander Lisia, to first listen to his report. When I have finished speaking with him, only then will I decide this case.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="23" />Ka na pua ama sordad'u ca dhèu la'e taha Paulus. Te ngaa na paredha, sèna ka ako hia ne bebas ciki, aa baku kai mone-aanga angalai na sèra mai lalau ne.<bt>And ordered a leader of soldiers to detain Paulus. But he commanded that they give him a little bit of freedom, and not prevent his close friends from coming to serve/look after him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pangad'o = menjenguk dan memperhatikan ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pangad'o = menjenguk dan memperhatikan ; pa'asu = take turns pounding alu, pareo = circle around ; pa'asu-pareo = datang mengikut, melawat (kuno)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus padhai lii dènge gubernur Feliks, dènge dhèu èmu na Dorsila<bt>Paulus speaks with governor Feliks, and his wife Dorsila</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Dhèu èmu gubernur Feliks, dhèu Yahudi, ngara na Dorsila. Pèri-pèri lod'o dhu la'e èèna, gubernur tenge lod'o dhu hua iia, sèna ka nèngu dènge dhèu èmu na neo padhai lii dènge Paulus. Ka na pua sèna ka dhèu rèti ne mai asa madha rèngu dua ra. Hèia Paulus lole dènge ra, j'ara tasamia sèna ka dhèu bisa parcaya Yesus Kristus, Dhèu dhu Lamatua moa nèti uru ka mai.<bt>The wife of governor Feliks was a Jahudi person named Dorsila. After several days, the governor looked for a good opportunity so that he and his wife could speak with Paulus. And he ordered people to bring him before the two of them. Then Paulus told them the way/path for people to believe in Yesus Kristus, the person whom God2 had promised from long ago.</bt><v n="25" />Na peka kahèi j'ara tasamia ho dhèu bisa muri mola, aa tasamia ho dhèu bisa j'aga ngi'u, sèna ka baku tao sala. Na lole kahèi, bèli-camèd'a Ama Lamatua pama'ète lii langu mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra, peka na, lèke, do sala.<bt>He also told how people could live cleanly/purely, and how people could guard themselves from doing wrong. He also told that in the future God would decide everybody's case, whether true/right, or wrong.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa Feliks tadèngi nare sèmi èèna, ka na madha'u. Hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Paulus! D'ai sange èèna ka laa! Ladhe abhu lod'o taleo, na, ja'a paroa hari èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Feliks heard that, he was afraid. Then he spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Paulus! That's enough (for now)! If there is another opportunity, I will summon you again.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="26" />Lod'o èèna, gubernur Feliks tenge-tenge j'ara, sèna ka Paulus palèke ne doi, ho na patabuli eele ne. Nèti èèna ka, na paroa taruu Paulus, ho padhai lii dènge ne.<bt>At that time/those days, governor Feliks was looking for ways so that Paulus would slip/bribe him money, so he would free him. Because of that he kept summoning Paulus to speak with him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dad'oo = pertimbangkan ; sale &lt;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dad'oo = pertimbangkan ; sale &lt; sala; <span class="Bold">26:</span> palèke = sogok</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Te ngaa re j'ara leo, gubernur Feliks neo ère d'ara kètu agama Yahudi sèra kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, na pama'ète boe lai-lai lii Paulus ne'e. Na soro tèke lii ne'e sène, toke d'ai dua tèu. Èle èèna ka, abhu dhèu hiu dhu gati eele gubernur Feliks. Ngara na Porkius Festus. Te ngaa rèngu taha taruu Paulus.<bt>But, by other means (=on the other hand) governor Feliks wanted to draw together with the leaders (fathers) of the Jahudi religion also. Because of that he was not in a hurry to decide Paulus' case. He let the case slide for two years. After that, there was a new person who replaced governor Feliks. His name was Porkius Festus. But he detained Paulus continually.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Gubernur Festus parisa lii langu Paulus<bt>Governor Festus examines Paulus' case</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="25" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o èèna, gubernur hiu, Festus, pidha asa Kaisarea, ho neo pakako paredha na. Nèngu pea ètu èèna dhoka tèlu lod'o di, ka na la'e taruu asa Yerusalem.<bt>At that time, the new governor Festus, moved to Kaisarea, to carry out his work. He only stayed three days in that place, and then he went on to Yerusalem</bt><v n="2" />Ètu nèi, kètu agama Yahudi, dènge dhèu heka-dhèu heka ad'a Yahudi sèra, mai paraga sèna ka neo patadha dènge gubernur hiu ne. Rèngu rèti kahèi dènge lii galaa rèngu mi Paulus ètu d'ara lii padhue-padhai rèngu.<bt>There, the Jahudi religious leaders, and the traditianal adat leaders of the Jahudi's came to meet so they could greet this new governor. They also brought their accusations about Paulus in to speak to him about them.</bt><v n="3" />Ra manèngi kahèi, ladhe bisa, na, gubernur pua dhèu nèngu sèra, rèti hari Paulus ho lèpa asa Yerusalem. Te ngaa rèngu pare'a lii, neo pamadhe Paulus ètu talora j'ara.<bt>They requested, if it was possible, that the governor tell his people to go bring Paulus back to Yerusalem. But, they had already come to agreement to try and kill Paulus on the journey.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa gubernur dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e ku, ama-ama! Hud'i laa ra taha ne ètu Kaisarea. Te ja'a neo lèpa asa nèi d'ara lai-lai ne.<bt>But the governor responded, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, fathers! Let them (keep) detaining him in Kaisarea. Cause I am going to return yonder right away.</bt><v n="5" />De ladhe nèti miu dhu abhu koasa ho uri lii langu ne, na, rèngu pakèd'i palere dènge ja'a asa Kaisarea. Ladhe tare'a dhèu ne'e tao sala ngaa, miu bisa tao lii dènge ne ètu nèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So, if there are those among you(pl) who have the authority to handle this case, na, they should leave accompanying me to Kaisarea. If it is true that this person has done something wrong, you can hve your dispute with him there.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6-7" />Èle èèna ka, Festus pea pe d'ai canguru lod'o sa ètu Yerusalem, heka na lèpa asa Kaisarea kèna. Lod'o èèna, abhu pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi dhu madhutu dènge nèngu, d'ai nèi. Asa bèli èèna, hèia gubernur mulai parisa lii langu èèna. Ka na pua dhèu lasi rare Paulus mai asa madha na.<bt>After that, Festus stayed around tem days in Yerusalem, and only then returned to Kaisarea. At that time, there were several Jahudi people who followed him until they arrived yonder. The following day, the governor began to examine that case. And he ordered people to go get Paulus and bring before him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hue sasala = muat sala"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">hue sasala = muat sala</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa Paulus maso asa èèna, dhèu Yahudi se kèd'i titu rai-reo rare ne, ka ra mulai core sasala ae-ae mi nèngu. Te ngaa rèngu bisa boe pad'elo bukti èci sa hèi.<bt>When Paulus went in there, they Jahudi people stood up surrounding him, and began to throw many wrongs at him. But, they could not show even one bit of proof.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia Paulus siri iisi na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama gubernur. Ja'a tao boe ngaa-ngaa dhu nèti bhabhelu-katub'a. Ja'a tao boe kahèi j'ara èci sa dhu palab'a dènge agama Yahudi ji'i. Ja'a pakaj'alu boe Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua ètu Yerusalem. Aa ja'a tao boe kahèi ngaa-ngaa dhu palab'a dènge j'ara-j'ara paredha Roma.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Paulus defended himself, saying, &lt;&lt;Father governor. I have not done anything evil. I have also not done anything to oppose our(exc) Jahudi religion. I did not defile God's Temple in Yerusalem. And I also did nothing to oppose the customs/regulations2 of the government of Roma.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Te ngaa lula gubernur neo nare d'ara dhèu Yahudi sèra, ka na karèi Paulus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ngee tasamia? Èu mo'o, do aad'o, ladhe ja'a uri lii langu èu ne ètu Yerusalem?&gt;&gt;<bt>But, because the governor wanted to sidle up (idiom: take insides) to the Jahudi people, he asked Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;What do you think? Do you want to, or not, if I handle this case of yours in Yerusalem?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nare dara = ame hati"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">nare dara = ame hati</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ropa tadèngi lii karèi gubernur sèmi èèna, hèia Paulus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama gubernur. Ja'a ne, ana kabarai Roma. Ka limuri ne, ja'a titu ètu madha ama gubernur, dhèu paredha Roma, dhu dènge hak ho parisa lii langu ja'a madhutu atora. De ja'a ko'o boe laku asa Yerusalem, ho pama'ète lii ja'a ètu nèi. Ama dhu me'a unu mu, peka na, ja'a ne tao boe sala ngaa-ngaa ho lab'a dhèu Yahudi se'e.<bt>When he heard the governorr's question like that, then Paulus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Father governor. I am a citizen of Roma. And now, I stand before father governor, a person of the government of Roma, who has the right to examine my case according to the regulations. So I do not want to go to Yerusalem, to decide my case yonder. You (father) yourself know that I have not done anything wrong to oppose these Jahudi people.</bt><v n="11" />De ladhe tare'a-re'a ja'a tao sala ngaa-ngaa dhu palèke dènge huku mamadhe, ja'a sèmi kore. Te ngaa ladhe ngaa dhu rèngu peka na, lèke boe madhutu atora Roma, na, abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu soro ja'a asa d'ara adhe-aai dhèu se'e. Rèngu dhodhoka tenge j'ara di, sèna ka neo pamadhe ja'a. De madhutu hak ja'a, ja'a manèngi sèna ka lii langu ja'a ne hia asa dhèu aae kapai, Keser, ètu kota Roma. Hud'i nèngu unu ku j'ue lii ja'a ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>So, if it is true that I did something wrong, which matches a punishment of death, I will accept it. But, if what they are saying is not according to regulations, there is not one person who can turn me over into the palms of these people's hands. They are only looking for a way to kill me. So, as is according to my right, I ask that this case of mine be given to the Top King, Keser, in the city of Roma. Let he himself be the one who decides2 this case of mine!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="iia dara = percuma"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">iia dara = percuma</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa tadèngi Paulus manèngi sèmi èèna, ka gubernur padhue-padhai dènge anga na dhu madhutu uri lii langu èèna. Èle èèna ka, na peka dènge Paulus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lula èu manèngi le ca'e banding asa dhèu aae kapai, de èu hud'i lamu ku asa Roma.&gt;&gt; Peka èle sèmi èèna ka, gubernur katange eele sidang èèna.<bt>Hearing Paulus ask like that, the governor discussed with his friends who were following/assisting in managing that case. After that, he spoke with Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;Because you have requested to ascend compare (legal term = appeal decision at higher level), to the Top King, therefore you must go to Roma.&gt;&gt; After he finished saying that, the governor closed the assembly.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Festus manèngi a'abhu dhèu aae Agripa lula-nèti lii langu Paulus<bt>Festus asks the advice of king Agrirpa about Paulus' case</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae dhèu Yahudi, ngara na Agripa,<bt>After that, the king of the Jahudi people named Agripa,</bt><note reference="25:13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Dhèu aae Agripa ne'e, Herodes Agripa ka dua. Ama na, ka Herodes Agripa ka èci, dhu pamadhe Yakobis. Nèngu ne ka dhu madhe lula kalati ra'e ne, taga nèngu sèmi lii koa, peka na, nèngu sama sèmi ana dedha-liru.<bt>This king Agripa is Herodes Agripa the second. His father was Herodes Agripa the first, who killed Yakobis. He is the one who died because worms ate him, because2 he accepted praise which said he was just like a god.</bt></note>dènge ana hèni na, ngara Bernike, mai asa Kaisarea. Rèngu dua ra mai sèna ka hia hormat mi gubernur hiu.<bt>and his sister named Bernike, came from Kaisarea. The two of them came to give respect to the new governor.</bt><v n="14" />Rèngu manubha pèri-pèri lod'o dènge gubernur Festus. Ca tèka, Festus lole lii langu Paulus dènge rèngu dua ra. Ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhèu aae! Ètu Kaisarea ne'e, ji'i taha dhèu èci, ngara na Paulus. Uru èèna, gubernur dhui abhu boe lod'o ho pama'ète lii langu na.<bt>They temporarily-stayed several days with governor Festus. One time, Festus told Paulus' case to the two of them. He spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;Here in Kaisarea, we(exc) have detained a person named Paulus. Previously the old governor did not have opportunity to decide his case.</bt><v n="15" />D'ara lai-lai ne, lod'o ja'a ètu Yerusalem, kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu heka d'ara rai sèra, mai galaa sasala Paulus, ka ra manèngi ja'a sèna ka huku mema ka.<bt>Just recently, while I was in Yerusalem, the leaders of the Jahudi religion and the traditional leaders from the villages, came accusing Paulus of wrong, and they asked me to punish him immediately.</bt><v n="16" />Te ngaa ja'a peka dènge rèngu, aku ja'a na, &lt;Madhutu atora paredha Roma, ja'a hud'i parisa uru ku lii langu, heka hia huku kèna. Aa dhèu dhu tao lii langu sèra, hud'i mai patoo madha dènge madha kahèi. Sèna ka ja'a neo tadèngi ku sasala ngaa dhu miu pasale ne. Aa nèngu kahèi abhu tebho sèna ka siri iisi na. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna ka, ja'a heka pama'ète lii langu na, ladhe na sala, ja'a huku ne.&gt;<bt>But, I told them, saying, &lt;According to the regulations of the government of Roma, I must first examine a case, only then give the punishment. And the people who have the dispute must come and be face to face as well. So that I can hear what wrong they are accusing him (of). And he also gets an opportunity to defend himself. In this way, only then will I decide his case, and if he has done wrong, I will punish him.&gt;</bt><v n="17" />Lod'o ja'a lèpa asa Kaisarea, abhu pèri-pèri dhèu Yahudi dhu palere dènge ja'a asa ne'e. Asa bèli èèna, ja'a parisa dènge lii ne. Ka ja'a hia rèti Paulus mai asa madha ja'a, sèna ka ja'a neo nanene j'aj'aj'i lii langu ne tasa mera mia.<bt>When I returned to Kaisarea, there were several Jahudi people who accompanied me here. The following day, this case, I examined immediately. And I had Paulus brought before me, so that I could hear the cause/source of his case, and how that was.</bt><v n="18" />Hèia dhèu-dhèu Yahudi se titu, ho ra lolo sasala Paulus èci-èci. Te ngaa, ngaa dhu ra peka sèra bia boe sèmi dhu ja'a ngee.<bt>Then these various Jahudi people stood up to tell about each of Paulus' wrongs. But what they were saying was not like what I was thinking.</bt><v n="19" />Rèngu se dhodhoka patasala ètu j'ara-j'ara agama rèngu di. Te rèngu pab'ala dènge Paulus, lula-nèti Dhèu èci, ngara na Yesus. Madhutu rare'a dhèu Yahudi, Yesus èèna, madhe le. Te ngaa Paulus dènge èra, peka na, Yesus mamuri hari le.<bt>They were merely disputing things about their religion. Cause they were arguing with Paulus, because of a person named Yesus. According to the understanding of these Jahudi people, that Yesus has already died. But Paulus insists that Yesus is alive again.</bt><v n="20" />Rèngu pasisu sèmi èèna, te ngaa, lula ja'a ne dhèu hiu, ka ja'a ke'a mèka uri lii agama ne, tasamia. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a karèi Paulus, peka na, &lt;Tasamia ladhe ja'a parisa lii langu èu ne ètu Yerusalem nèi?&gt;<bt>They disagree like that, but because I am a new person, I do not yet know how to handle this case. Because of that, I asked Paulus, saying, &lt;How about if I examine your case yonder in Yerusalem?&gt;</bt><v n="21" />Te ngaa na sèmi nare boe. Nèti èèna ka, na manèngi ca'e asa paredha dedha mi dhèu aae kapai ètu Roma. Ka ja'a patabuli boe ne, mate ja'a abhu lod'o ho rèti ne la'e asa Roma.&gt;&gt;<bt>But he did not accept that. Because of that, he asked to ascend to the upper government to the Top King in Roma. Therefore because of that, I am not releasing him, waiting for a time/opportunity that I can send him to Roma.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="huku ; dhèu heka dara rae;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">huku ; dhèu heka dara rae; <span class="Bold">18:</span> pad'elo; <span class="Bold">19:</span> rare'a = pengetahuan /DUP-3p-re'a/</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa tadèngi lii lolo Festus sèmi èèna, hèia dhèu aae Agripa peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Be'a risi ja'a neo tadèngi unu ku, nèti dhèu èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>When he heard Festus' report like that, then king Agripa spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;It would be good if I could hear for myself from that person.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Festus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Bisa! Bèli ku, pe ja'a uri ho ama nanene unu mu nèti dhèu èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Festus responded, &lt;&lt;You may! Tomorrow I will arrange for you (father) to hear for yourself from that person.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu aae Agripa neo nanene lii padhai Paulus<bt>King Agripa wants to listen to what Paulus has to say</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />D'ai bèli èèna, gubernur Festus uri ho dhèu aae Agripa bisa nanene lii padhai Paulus. Na uri kahèi, sèna ka dhèu ae nanene Paulus. Nuka: komedhaa-komedhaa sordad'u, dènge dhèu-dhèu kapai ètu kota Kaisarea. Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae Agripa dènge Bernike maso dènge mèdha-papake dhèu aae. Ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i sèra pakab'ua si. Ropa rèngu pakaboko tesa-tesa le, hèia gubernur pua rèti Paulus asa d'ara.<bt>When the next day arrived, governor Festus arranged for king Agripa to hear what Paulus had to say. He also arranged so the many people could listen to Paulus. They were: commanders of the soldiers, that leaders/prominent people in the city of Kaisarea. After that, king Agripa and Bernike entered wearing the clothes of the king. And all the people there showed them respect. When they were complete in their gathering, then the governor ordered them to bring Paulus inside.</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02034b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:center">Paulus ètu madha dhèu aae-dhèu kapai<bt>Paulus in front of the king and big (important) people</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Hèia ra rèti Paulus asa d'ara la'e. Ka gubernur bhoka hèb'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhèu aae Agripa, ama-ama, dènge miu tamu aa'i-aa'i mi dhu ja'a pakab'ua. Dhèu ne'e ne, ngara na Paulus. Pèri-pèri ama dhèu Yahudi sèra tao lii langu dènge ne. Ka abhu dhu mai asa ja'a, rèngu cahag'e nèti Yerusalem, aa cahag'e nèti era ne'e, mai laka-seti ja'a, peka na, dhèu ne'e ne, bisa heka hia ne mamuri.<bt>Then they brought Paulus inside. And the governor opened his mouth, saying, &lt;&lt;father king Agripa, fathers, and all you guests whom I honour/respect. This person is named Paulus. Several of the Jahudi leaders have made a case against him. And some have come to me, they are from Yerusalem, to this place of mine, to try and pressure/force me, saying, this person should no longer be allowed to live.</bt><v n="25" />Nèti èèna ka, ja'a parisa ne. Te ngaa ja'a abhu boe sasala dhu pamèci dènge huku madhe. Te ngaa, lula nèngu unu na dhu manèngi le, ca'e asa paredha dedha ètu Roma, nèti èèna ka, to'o do to'o boe, ja'a hud'i hia rèti ne ku la'e asa Roma.<bt>Because of that, I examined him. But, I could not find any wrong that was matching a punishment of death. But, because he himself is the one who requested to ascend up the government to Roma, because of that, like it or not (&lt;we want to or we not want to like that), I must have them take him away to Roma.</bt><v n="26-27" />Ladhe ja'a hia lere rèti ne, ja'a hud'i ku tao sasuri. Te ngaa deo ne'e ne, ja'a suri sasuri ne tasamia, hia mi dhèu aae kapai nèi? De nèti èèna ka, ja'a pakaboko ama-ama aa'i-aa'i, sèna ka miu nanene lii langu na. Ropa tadèngi mere lii na, ja'a manèngi sèna ka ama dhèu aae Agripa, nori ja'a, sèna ka ja'a bisa suri ngaa dhu palèke dènge ngangee dhèu aae kapai nèi. Ja'a ngee, na, lèke boe ladhe ja'a pa'adhu lii langu ne asa dhèu aae kapai la'e, te ngaa peka boe sasala dhu dhèu ne ad'u-ue.<bt>If I have them escort him, I must write a letter. But now, what would I write to the Top King yonder? So, because of that, I have gathered all you leaders (fathers), so that you can listen to what he says. When you have finished listening to him, I ask that father king Agripa advise me, so that I can write something that makes sense to the Top King yonder. I think it is not right if I hand over his case to the Top King, but do not tell what wrong this person has done.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="to'o do to'o boe èèna ka,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">to'o do to'o boe èèna ka, = mau tar mau (kita = changes for person and number); <span class="Bold">27:</span> ad'u-ue = tao, lakukan ; ad'u = 1) tao, 2) merenge, palese = pasale ; ue = cipta</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">D'ai sange ne'e ka, lii padhai lii ja'a. Makasi!&gt;&gt;<bt>That is the limit of what I have to say. Thanks!&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus siri iisi na ètu madha dhèu aae Agripa [\s2]<bt>Paulus defends himself, before king Agripa [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="26" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia dhèu aae Agripa pua Paulus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ne'e ne, èu bisa siri iisi èu. Ji'i aa'i mi mate le neo nanene èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then king Agripa ordered Paulus, saying, &lt;&lt;Now you can defend yourself. All of us(exc) have been waiting wanting to hear you.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Paulus tao tadha dènge kacui-aai na, hèia na padhai lii, aku nèngu na,<bt>So Paulus made a sign with his hand, and then spoke, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />&lt;&lt;Ama dhèu aae Agripa dhu ja'a pakab'ua. Ja'a rasa oto, lula ama hia ja'a tebho sèna ka ja'a padhai lii dènge miu, j'ara aa'i-aa'i dhu dhèu Yahudi se galaa mi ja'a.<bt>&lt;&lt;Father king Agripa, whom I respect. I feel fortunate, because you (father) have given me time/opportunity for me to speak with you(pl) about all the matters which these Jahudi people have accused me.</bt><v n="3" />Ja'a ke'a, na, ama me'a risi eele ad'a èdhi dhèu Yahudi, dènge j'ara madhe-muri èdhi. De ja'a manèngi ho ama nanene paie ku lii ja'a ne.<bt>I know that you fully understand the adat of we(inc) Jahudi people, and our daily problems (doublet &lt; ways of living-dying). So I ask you to listen carefully to what I have to say.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kesempatan = lod'o taleo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kesempatan = lod'o taleo</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Karèi nèti ana iiki ka mai, ra aj'a-nori le ja'a, sèna ka mamuri madhutu ad'a èdhi dhèu Yahudi. Uru èèna, ra aj'a ja'a ètu rae. Èle èèna ka, ja'a sakola tabha hari ètu Yerusalem. Dhèu Yahudi ètu Yerusalem sèra re'a le j'ara mamuri dènge tatao ja'a.<bt>Since I was small, they taught me to live my life according to the adat of we Jahdui people. Previously, they taught me in the village. After that, I continued my schooling again in Yerusalem. Those Jahudi people in Yeruslaem already know my life and my deeds/behaviour.</bt><v n="5" />Ladhe kètu agama se ro'o, rèngu bisa lolo, peka na, rèngu se ka dhu tadhe le ja'a karèi nèti uru èèna ka. Te ja'a ne maso partei agama Parisi kahèi. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra re'a, na, ji'i dhèu Parisi se, dhu kèpe pa'èra aa madhutu atora aa'i-aa'i nèti agama Yahudi.<bt>If those religious leaders want to, they could tell that they have known me since long ago. Because I also entered (=was a member of) the Parisi religious party too. Everybody knows that we(exc) Parisi's really follow all the regulations of the Jahudi religion.</bt><note reference="26:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 23:6, Pilipi 3:5</note><v n="6-8" />Ja'a dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i nèti canguru dua suku Isra'el, mate tae-tae ho Ama Lamatua tao madhutu lii moa Na. Lii moa èèna, dhu Na peka tèke le dènge bèi-baki èdhi karèi nèti uru ka. Ka toke d'ai sange ne'e, èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti manèngi-mangaj'i mèu-mèda, sèna ka lii moa Lamatua èèna j'aj'i ka. Isi lii moa èèna, peka na, Èèna na Nèngu neo pamamuri hari dhèu dhu madhe sèra.<bt>I, and all the people from the 12 tribes of Isra'el have been waiting for God to do according to His promise. That prommise is what he told our(inc) ancestors from long ago. And to this day (broad), we all worship/pray night-day so that God2's promise will happen (right away). The contents of that promise say that He will bring back to life people who are dead.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="udhu-rasa (archaic) = suku ; tae-tae"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">udhu-rasa (archaic) = suku ; tae-tae = about to transition</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ama dhèu aae Agripa dhu ja'a pakab'ua. Lula ja'a parcaya, peka na, èèna na Lamatua pamamuri hari dhèu madhe, nèti èèna ka, rèngu se tao lii langu dènge ja'a. De ja'a karèi ku: tasamia ka ètu talora aae miu se, abhu dhu mo'o boe parcaya, peka na, Ama Lamatua bisa pamamuri hari dhèu dhu madhe le? Tatu Nèngu bisa!<bt>Father king Agripa, whom I respect. Because I believe that THAT God2 brings back to life dead people, because of that, they are making this case/dispute with me.So I ask: how is it that there are those of you(pl) who do not want to believe that God is able to bring back to life people who have already died? Certainly He is able!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Uru èèna, mema ja'a tao rupa-rupa j'ara ho palab'a dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu madhutu Yesus, dhèu Nasaret.<bt>Previously I did various sorts of things to oppose all the people who follow Yesus, that person of Nasaret.</bt><v n="10-11" />Lod'o èèna, kètu agama Yahudi sèra hia ja'a koasa, sèna ka laku paj'èra dhèu unu Yesus ètu mia-mia. Ja'a kèpe si, ka nuni kèti si asa Yerusalem, ho core si pamaso asa d'ara bèdho. Ja'a madhutu pama'ète sèna ka huku madhe si cahag'e. Ja'a laku kahèi asa d'ara èmu-èmu sabaj'a, ho paj'èra si. Aa ja'a neo pakaseti si, sèna ka rèngu tèke eele parcaya rèngu mi Yesus. Ae ka dhu ja'a laku magèi si dènge d'ara sagoro tob'i-tob'i. Sad'i ja'a tadèngi dhèu parcaya Yesus sèra ètu era èci, do masi ka d'ai rai leo èèna ka, ja'a laku magèla kore si!&gt;&gt;<bt>In those days, the leaders (fathers) of the Jahudi religion gave me authority, so that I could go persecute people belonging to Yesus everywhere. I arrested/caught them and dragged them to Yerusalem to throw them into prison. I also had a role in deciding to judge/punish some of them to death.I even went into the houses of worship to persecute them. And I wanted to force them so they would abandon their belief in Yesus. Many times I went hunting them, with a very hot (inspired) inside. As long as I heard people who believed in Yesus were in one place, or had even gone to another land/country, I went pursuing them!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="magèla ~ magèi = kejar ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">magèla ~ magèi = kejar ; sag'oro = panas ; Max = sag'oro tobi-tobi ;; <span class="Bold">11:</span> pakaseti = paksa ; magèi / magèla = usir XX? sagoro tobi - tobi = panas sekali</Message></Annotation><note reference="26:9-11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 8:3, 22:4-5</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus lole hari ngaa dhu nèngu tao uru èèna [\s2]<bt>Paulus tells again what he had previously done [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 9:1-19, 22:6-16)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Èle èèna ka, Paulus tuhu hari lii na, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ca tèka, kètu agama Yahudi sèra hia ja'a sasuri koasa ho laku magèla dhèu parcaya Yesus ètu kota Damsik. Ka ja'a laku.<bt>After that, Paulus continued, saying, &lt;&lt;One time, those religious leaders gave me a letter of authority to go pursue people who believed in Yesus in the city of Damsik. And I went.</bt><v n="13" />Ama dhèu aae Agripa! Ropa ji'i ètu talora j'ara era, pe d'ai lod'o titu mera sa, cag'ag'a laa, saraa aae èci dhu mariu nèti dedha-liru, senter lèke ja'a dènge anga ja'a sèra.<bt>Father king Agripa! When I was still on the journey, around mid-day, suddenly a bright/huge light shone from the sky, spot-lighting me and my companions.</bt><v n="14" />Ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi bèbha baa-baa ètu rai, lula saraa èèna mariu aae. Hèia ja'a tadèngi lii èci, pake lii Aram,<bt>We all fell down on the ground, because of that light shining brightly. Then I heard a voice using the Aram language, saying, &lt;We, Saul! Why are you not stopping from persecuting Me? It is so heavy/difficult if you keep opposing2 My will.&gt;</bt><note reference="26:14" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu Alkitab lii Yunani, ra suri, peka na, &lt;lii dhèu Ibrani&gt;. Lii rèngu bèli-bèli èèna, nuka lii Aram. Aa ra suri lii pakasame kahèi, &lt;èu tabha j'èra ladhe èu katuju lèke taruu isi kataki.&gt; Sasoa na, &lt;ladhe èu palab'a taruu dad'èi Yesus, èu asa j'èra.&gt;<bt>In the Yunani language Bible they wrote, saying, &lt;the language of the Ibrani people&gt;. Their everyday language was the Aram language. And they wrote a comparison/illustration also, &lt;you increase suffering if you keep kicking on the end of a speargun [island-fishing community].&gt; It means, &lt;if you keep opposing the will of Yesus, you will keep/increase your suffering.&gt;</bt></note>peka na, &lt;We, Saul! Nga tao ka èu loe boe paj'èra Ja'a ne? Bia titu kèna, ladhe èu sisu taruu dad'èi Ja'a.&gt;<v n="15" />Ja'a tadèngi lii èèna, te ngaa ladhe kèdhi boe dhèu èèna. Ka ja'a karèi, peka na, &lt;Ama dhu padhai lii ne, cee ka èu?&gt;<bt>I heard that voice, but when I looked there was nobody there. So I asked, saying, &lt;Lord/master who is speaking here, who are you?&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="isi kataki = spear gun ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">isi kataki = spear gun ; katuju = kick, tendang ; isi papudu = hand drill like a screwdriver ;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia lii èèna dhaa mi ja'a, peka na, &lt;Ja'a ne, Yesus, dhu èu paj'èra taruu èèna.<bt>Then that aforementioned voice responded to me, saying, &lt;I here am Yesus, whom you keep persecuting.</bt><v n="16" />Saul! Kèd'i ka! Ja'a pad'elo iisi mi èu ne, sèna ka èu j'aj'i dhèu unu Ja'a. Èu hud'i lamu ku lole dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra, ngaa dhu èu mèdhi le nèti Ja'a limuri ne. Ladhe èèna na, Ja'a pad'elo asa ae hari dènge èu, ngaa-ngaa dhu hiu, sèna ka lamu lole dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>Saul! Get up! I am revealing Myself to you now for this purpose: I have set you apart to be a person whom I trust. So you must go tell everybody what you have seen from Me just now. Later on, I will reveal many more things to you, things that are new, so that you go tell them to all people.</bt><v n="17" />Èèna na, èu paraga dènge j'aj'èra ae-ae. Te ngaa Ja'a j'aga èu nèti dhèu dhu neo paj'èra èu, masi ka nèti dhèu Yahudi, do nèti dhèu Yahudi boe. Tare'a! Ja'a pua èu lamu asa dhèu dhu Yahudi boe.<bt>Later on, you will meet with various kinds of suffering. But, I will watch/guard you from the people who want to cause you suffering, whether they are Jahudi people or other (kinds of) people. Really! I order you to go to various (sorts of) people who are not Jahudi.</bt><v n="18" />Lamu bhoke musi madha si, sèna ka re'a, ho ra mamuri ètu d'ara saraa. Hèia ra tèke eele j'ara-j'ara mamuri ra dhu koe-kapengo sèra. Aa èu hud'i pad'elo kahèi, j'ara mamuri dhu mola. Lamu ho patabuli eele si nèti koasa dhèu aae nidhu, sèna ka mèti si asa Ama Lamatua. Dènge j'ara ne, Ama Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo aa'i-aa'i si. Ka rèngu j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua kahèi, èci èèna ka dènge dhèu-dhèu leo dhu Lamatua hag'e nare le, lula rèngu parcaya Ja'a. Èèna ka dhu Ja'a peka dènge èu, Saul!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Go open their eyes so they understand, so they can live with clear/light insides. Then they will leave behind their ways of life that are twisted-slanted (not morally straight). And you must point out to them the way of life that is straight. Go to release them from the power/authority of the King of evil spirits, so that you bring them to God. In this way, God will wipe away all their wrongs (doublet). And they will also become people belonging to God2, together with other kinds of people whom God2 has already set apart, because they believe in Me. That is what I am telling you, Saul!&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasaraa; |b18:|r koe-kapengo = bengkok-miring ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pasaraa; <span class="Bold">18:</span> koe-kapengo = bengkok-miring ; koe = bengkok ; kapengo = miring sebelah ; koe-kalèko = like a snake with repeated bends ; palere-lere = 1) bersama-sama, berdampingan, 2) berikut-ikut</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus peka sasab'a-la'a na [\s2]<bt>Paulus tells his work [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Hèia Paulus tuhu hari lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;De ama dhèu aae. Sasab'a dhu ja'a sèmi kore unu ku nèti sorga, ja'a pakako ne. Toke d'ai doe ne'e ne, ja'a sab'a taruu, ae mèka ciki sa.<bt>Then Paulus continued, saying, &lt;&lt;So, father king. That work which I received myself from heaven, I have carried out. To this day, I continue working, not stopping even a little.</bt><v n="20" />Hiu-hiu èèna, ja'a lole J'ara Mamuri Yesus mi dhèu Yahudi ètu Damsik sèra. Èle èèna ka, ja'a mai lole dènge dhèu Yahudi dhu ètu Yerusalem dènge palème propensi Yudea. Hèia ja'a laku palème kabarai dhèu dhu Yahudi boe sèra. Ja'a padhai lii pahuni boe dènge rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra, ho ra tèke eele j'ara mamuri rèngu dhu sala sèra, sèna ka ra saraka mamuri rèngu mi Ama Lamatua. Rèngu hud'i tao dhu be'a ku ètu d'ara mamuri rèngu hia mi dhèu leo kahèi, ho j'aj'i tadha, peka na, rèngu j'aj'i le dhèu hiu ètu Lamatua.<bt>Firstly (&lt;newly-newly) I told Yesus' Life Way to the Jahudi people who were in Damsik. After that, I came and told the Jahudi people who were in Yerusalem and throughout the province of Yudea. After that, I went around to the countries/societies of various people who are not Jahudi. I spoke without hiding anything with all of them, so that they would leave behind their ways of life that were wrong, and turn over their lives to God. They also must do good things in their lives for other people, as a sign that they have become new people in God2.</bt><note reference="26:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 9:20, 28-29</note><v n="21" />Lula sasab'a ja'a sèmi èèna, ka dhèu Yahudi sèra kèpe ja'a ètu d'ara Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ètu Yerusalem. Rèngu neo pamadhe ja'a kahèi.<bt>Because of that work of mine, those Jahudi people caught/arrested me inside the Temple in Yerusalem. They even wanted to kill me.</bt><v n="22" />Te ngaa malo-malo ka Ama Lamatua soru ja'a. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a mamuri d'ai sange ne'e ne. De ja'a bisa titu ètu ne'e, ho lole dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra, ana iiki-dhèu kapai, lula-nèti J'ara Mamuri Yesus. Ngaa dhu ja'a peka ne, aa'i-aa'i ra, èci èèna ka dènge lii a'aj'a-nanori nèti Musa dènge dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua uru sèra.<bt>But, fortunately God helped me. Because of that, I am alive to this day. Because of that, I can stand here to tell everybody, small-large ~ unimportant-important, about the Life Way of Yesus. What I am saying here, all of it, is the same as the teachings from Musa and those people who were God2's spokespeople of yore.</bt><v n="23" />Rèngu aj'a-nori lula-nèti Kristus, Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua moa neo hia mai. Dhu peka na, Kristus hud'i pasae ku j'aj'èra. Hèia Na madhe. Te ngaa èle èèna, Nèngu ka dhu j'aj'i dhèu uru dhu Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari. Nèngu ka dhu pasaraa dhèu Yahudi sèra, dènge dhèu-dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>They taught about Kristus, the person whom God promised to send. They said that Kirstus must shoulder-carry (=experience) suffering. Then He (must) die. But after that, He is the one who will be the first/foremost person that God brings back to life. He is the one who will enlighten/bring light to the Jahudi people and to various other kinds of people on this earth.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="marèngi = teduh (laut) ; malo-malo"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">marèngi = teduh (laut) ; malo-malo = ontong ; soru = tolong; <span class="Bold">23:</span> bhera boe = tidak tinggalkan</Message></Annotation><note reference="26:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 42:6, 49:6, 1 Korintus 15:20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa Paulus lole sasab'a na era, ka Festus cag'ag'a laa poro ète lii padhai na dènge lii mèdhu, peka na, &lt;&lt;He! Paulus! Èu ne, tao-tao dhu huj'u le. Èu mèu ae ka, kahadhu èu, ele iie.&gt;&gt;<bt>Paulus was still telling about his work, and Festus suddenly interrupted (&lt;cut off) what he was saying with a loud voice, saying, &lt;&lt;He! Paulus! You are probably already crazy. You are so smart that your brain has completely disappeared.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="poro = potong ; huj'u ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">poro = potong ; huj'u = gila</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Te ngaa Paulus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama gubernur dhu ja'a pakab'ua. Ja'a ne huj'u boe. Ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu ja'a lole ne, mema lèke tare'a. Ja'a leko boe.<bt>But Paulus responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Father governor whom I respect. I am not crazy. Everything that I have said and told (doublet) is really true. I am not making it up.</bt><v n="26" />Ama dhèu aae Agripa unu na dhu ne'a le kahèi, ngaa dhu ja'a peka-padhai ne. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a bani padhai lii dènge boe pasili. Ja'a lèka ama dhèu aae dhu tadèngi le j'ara se'e aa'i-aa'i, lula ngaa dhu j'aj'i sèra, j'aj'i boe ètu era pahuni. Dhu peka na, Yesus dhu madhe èèna, muri hari le. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra re'a le j'ara ne.<bt>Father king Agripa himself also knows already, what I am talking about. Because of that, I dare to speak without restraint (=I speak forthrightly). I trust that father king has heard all these matters, because what has happened, has not happened in secret. That, Yesus died, and came back to life. Everybody already knows these things.</bt><v n="27" />Karèi nèti uru ka, dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua sèra peka mema le j'ara ne'e. Ja'a bani patèka, peka na, ama dhèu aae parcaya kahèi, lii dhèu rèti lii padhai sèra, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>Since long ago, God's spokespeople have foretold these matters. I would dare to bet that father king also believes the messages of those spokespeople, right?&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="patèka = bataru, place bet"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">patèka = bataru, place bet</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ka dhèu aae Agripa, poro ète lii padhai lii na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ee, Paulus! Nèbhu boe, te èu pamaso ja'a j'aj'i dhèu sarani!&gt;&gt;<bt>And king Agripa, interrupted what he was saying, saying, &lt;&lt;Ee, Paulus! You will soon cause me to enter and become a sarani person!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paca'ète = interrupt, shorten ; pababe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">paca'ète = interrupt, shorten ; pababe = shorten</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Te ngaa Paulus dhaa, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, ama. Ja'a manèngi mi Ama Lamatua, sèna ka d'ara lai-lai ne, do ako nèbhu hari ciki, baku dhoka ama dhèu aae di mesa na, te ngaa dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu deo ne'e ne tadèngi lii padhai ja'a ne, j'aj'i sama sèmi ja'a, nuka dhèu unu Yesus! Sad'i dhodhoka ama si baku j'aj'i dhèu bèdho, sama sèmi dhu ja'a pasae ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Paulus responded, &lt;&lt;It's like this, father. I pray to God, so that very quickly, or after awhile, not only father king alone, but all the people who are now listening to what I am saying, would become like me, that is belonging to Yesus! As long as you (coll) don't become a prisoner, like I am experiencing.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ropa Paulus peka nare, ka dhèu aae Agripa dènge ana hèni na Bernike, gubernur Festus, dènge dhèu kapai aa'i-aa'i sèra, kèd'i titu, hèia lèpa aa'i.<bt>When Paulus finished speaking, king Agripa and his sister Bernike, and governor Festus, and all those leaders, stood up, then began to all go home.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ropa rèngu d'ai li'u, ra padhue, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne, tao sala boe ngaa-ngaa dhu palèke dènge huku madhe, do pamaso ne asa d'ara bèdho!&gt;&gt;<bt>As they were arriving outside, they were discussing, saying, &lt;&lt;This person has not done anything which matches with a death sentence, or to put him into jail!&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="32" />Èle èèna ka, dhèu aae Agripa peka dènge gubernur Festus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Kasian. Dhèu ne manèngi le ca'e asa paredha dedha mi dhèu aae kapai ètu Roma. Ladhe aad'o, na, lii langu ne èle le, aa bisa patabuli ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, king Agripa spoke with governor Festus, saying, &lt;&lt;It's a pity. This person has already asked to go up to higher government to the Top King in Roma. If not, his case would already be finished, and (you) could release him.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pangèd'u = serahkan sesuatu = mempercayakan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pangèd'u = serahkan sesuatu = mempercayakan sesuatu ; bhera = hiraukan = sama-sama. bhera eele = tidak hiraukan/ anak tirikan. paca'ète a = pabab'e = mempersingkat ; malo-malo ka = untung</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lere rèti Paulus asa Roma<bt>They escort Paulus to Roma</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="27" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia gubernur Festus pama'ète, sèna ka lere rèti Paulus la'e asa madha dhèu aae kapai Keser ètu Roma, sèna ka pama'ète lii langu na ètu nèi. Ka na pangèd'u Paulus dènge dhèu bèdho dhu leo sèra, asa komedhaa sordad'u èci, ngara na Yulius, ho lere nèti si asa propensi Italia. Yulius ne, komedhaa nèti sordad'u dhu madhenge Keser.<bt>Then governor Festus decided to send Paulus before the Top King Keser in Roma, so that his case could be decided yonder. And he turned over Paulus and other prisoners to a commander of soldiers, named Yulius, to escort him to the province of Italia. That Yulius was a commander of the soldiers who guarded Keser.</bt><v n="2" />Lod'o èèna, ja'a (nuka Lukas), laku lere kahèi Paulus. Aa dènge angalai èci, dhèu Makedonia nèti kota Tesalonika, ngara na Aristarkus. Ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi ca'e kapa cue, dhu mai nèti kota Adramitium. Madhutu dad'èi juraga, kapa ne neo dhuli hèb'a-namo ae ètu propensi Asia.<bt>At that time, I (that is, Lukas), also accompanied Paulus. And there was another companion, a person from Makedonia from the city of Tesalonika, named Aristarkus. We(exc) all embarked on a ship which came from the city of Adramitium. According to the desires of the captain (loan), this ship was going to stop in at many harbours in the province of Asia.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="juraga"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">juraga</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ji'i pakèd'i tèke eele Kaisarea. Ka d'ai bèli èèna, ji'i d'ai kota Sidon. Komedhaa Yulius tao Paulus dènge be'a, aa na peka dènge ne kahèi, bisa la'e pangad'o dènge angalai na ètu dae. Dad'èi Yulius sèna ka Paulus bisa abhu nèti rèngu, ngaa dhu na parluu ètu d'ara kakako na.<bt>We left from Kaisarea. And the next day, we arrived at the city of Sidon. Commander Yulius treated Paulus well, and he told him that he could go visit his friends on land. Yulius thought that Paulus could get from them whatever it was that he needed on his journey.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dae = darat, pantai (dalam context"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dae = darat, pantai (dalam context laut) ; parèko = 1) palm sugar and coconut mixture, 2) bakal</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="maps\Bible\HkKsKret.tif" rtfFormat="width:11cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:center">Nèti Kaisarea lasi asa pulu Kreta<bt>From Kaisarea to Kreta island</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Hèia ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi ca'e hari, ho pakèd'i. Te ngaa ngèlu madha kapai seli, toke kapa ne oe kako nare boe. Ka ra pod'e kaduru kapa ne, re talora aae pulu Siprus dènge rai Siria, sèna ka ako abhe ngèlu nèti madha.<bt>Then we all got back on, to leave. But the headwind was so great that the ship almost made no progress. So they turned the rudder of the ship, passing by between the island of Siprus and the land of Siria, so that they were rather blocked/protected from the headwind.</bt><v n="5" />Nèti èèna, ji'i pab'ab'e j'ara, ète re madha propensi Kilikia dènge propensi Pamfilia. Ka ji'i la'a taruu d'ai kota Mira, ètu rai Likia. D'ai nèi, ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi puru tèke eele kapa èèna.<bt>From there, we shortened the journey, cutting across in front of the province of Kilikia and the province of Pamfilia. And we kept going until the city of Mira, in the land/country of Likia. Arriving yonder, we all disembarked leaving behind that ship.</bt><v n="6" />Ètu Mira, komedhaa Yulius tenge kapa leo dhu neo pakèd'i asa Italia. Ka na abhu kapa cue dhu mai nèti kota Aleksandria, dhu neo pakèd'i asa Italia. Hèia na pua ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi ho ca'e kapa èèna.<bt>In Mira, commander Yulius looked for a different ship which was leaving for Italia. And he found a ship which came from the city of Aleksandria, which was going to leave for Italia. Then he ordered us all to get on that ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kaduru = haluan ; pod'e ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">kaduru = haluan ; pod'e = putar ; ako = agak ; abhe = pele; <span class="Bold">5:</span> pab'ab'e ; ète = potong = poro</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ji'i pakèd'i pèri-pèri lod'o kèna, te ngaa ngare boe mia-mia, lula ngèlu madha mèdhu aae. Nèbhu j'oo-aae ku, heka ji'i padètu dènge kota Knidus. Te ngaa ngèlu madha loe boe, ka ji'i poro hari j'ara la'a asa pulu Kreta, sèna ka ako pa'abhe ciki. Èle èèna ka, ji'i oe seli suu rai èci, ngara na Salmone.<bt>We were had left several days already, but were not progressing anywhere, because the wind from the front was very strong. After a long time only then did we near the city of knidus. But, the headwind didn't let up, and we cut across again going to(ward) the island of Kreta, so that we could be blocked a little. After that, we passed near a point of land, named Salmone.</bt><v n="8" />Ji'i seli suu rai èèna dènge j'èra titu kèna. Ka ji'i oro-oro re sebhe pulu Kreta, hèia ji'i heka d'ai era èci, ngara na hèb'a-namo Saraga. Era èèna, padètu dènge kota Lasea.<bt>We passed by that point with great difficulty. And we went along the edge of the island of Kreta, and only then did we arrive at a place called Beautiful Harbour. That place was near the city of Lasea.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tao-tao ka, = setengah mati ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">tao-tao ka, = setengah mati ; suu rai = tanjung (check) ; Nèbhu-nèbhu ~ nèbhu j'oo-aae ku; <span class="Bold">8:</span> oro-oro = menyusur, go along edge ; kètu rui mèdhi = bagian laut yg mulai kentara hitam ; re dara lobo = along the bagian meting ; karasa = pinggir (umum)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />D'ai èèna, ana mataroo kapa se ae rara iisi ciki, lula ji'i nèbhu ae le ètu lèu, te ngaa d'ai mèka Italia. Lod'o èèna, seli le lod'o kalela Saku Eele Dosa dhèu Yahudi.<bt>Arriving there, the crew of this ship wanted to rest their tiredness a bit, because we had been a long time at sea, but had not yet reached Italia. At that time, it had already passed the big day/festival of Wiping Away Sins of the Jahudi people.</bt><note reference="27:9" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">D'ara tèu 59, lod'o kapai Saku Eele Dosa dhèu Yahudi lèke tanggal 5 Oktober. Lod'o èèna, lèke dènge ngèlu badae-haa.<bt>In the year 59, the big day/festival of Wiping Away Sins of the Jahudi people happened on the date (loan) of 5 Oktober. At that time the northwest winds happened.</bt></note>Dhu tema le, ropa èle lod'o kalela èèna, j'aj'i ngèlu aae dènge dhasi kapai. Hèia ana mataroo kapa se pakarèi, j'aj'i pakèd'i, do aad'o. Ropa tadèngi lii ana mataroo kapa se, Paulus padhai lii, peka na,<bt>That meant that when that holiday finished, the season (month) of big wind and big waves/seas happened/began. Then the crew asked each other if we should leave or not. When he heard what the crew were saying, Paulus spoke, saying,</bt><v n="10" />&lt;&lt;A'ari aa'i-aa'i. Ja'a neo padhai lii ciki. Ja'a pangee, ladhe sèmi èdhi kako taruu, bisa èdhi paraga dènge j'aj'èra ae. Kapa ne bisa molo kahèi, mèdha-panyau ela aa'i mèu-mèu, aa èdhi bisa madhe aa'i ti kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;All you older-younger siblings. I want to say a little bit. I think that if we(inc) agree to keep going, we will mee with much suffering. This ship could even drown, the cargo could all be lost, and we could all die.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="11" />Te ngaa komedhaa sordad'u èèna, d'èi boe nanene lii Paulus. Nèngu lèka risi juraga dènge lamatua kapa èèna. Lula rèngu neo kako taruu, tèke eele era èèna.<bt>But, the commander of the soldiers, did not want to listen to what Paulus was saying. He more trusted the captain and owner/master of that ship. Because they wanted to keep going, and leave that place behind.</bt><v n="12" />Dhu carui ka, ladhe d'ai lod'o dhasi aae, kapa bisa boe panahu dènge be'a ètu hèb'a-namo Saraga èèna. Nèti èèna ka, ae ka nèti rèngu d'èi sèna ka ji'i pakèd'i taruu, ho la'a asa kota Feniks. Rèngu sanao ladhe bisa, na, ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi pea ètu nèi, d'ara hèru dhasi aae ne. Kota Feniks nèi, hèb'a-namo pulu Kreta dhu mau, lula nèngu ne era dhu abhe nèti ngèlu badae-haa dènge ngèlu badae-dhimu, aa abhu boe naha kapai.<bt>The difficulty was, if the big waves started, the ship could not anchor well/safely in that Beautiful Harbour. Because of that, many of them wanted for us to keep going, to go to the city of Feniks. They hoped that if possible, we could all stay yonder, during the big wave season. That city of Feniks, was the island of Kreta's calm harbour, because it was a place protected from the northwest wind and the northeast wind, and didn't get big waves.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ae rara iisi ; ae nara"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ae rara iisi ; ae nara iisi ; ae kore iisi ; but nara iisi = lahirkan ; ana mataroo = abk, sailor ; badae ; haa = 1) barat 2) paru-paru; <span class="Bold">11:</span> ; <span class="Bold">12:</span> parèko = nganga'a j'ara = bekal dalam perjalanan ; poro j'ara/ète j'ara = jalan potong ; hèb'a namo = pelabuhan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ngèlu aae ètu d'ara dhasi [\s2]<bt>The storm (big-wind) on the sea [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ropa ngèlu balèu tiu g'oro mau-mau, ra pangee, na, ngèlu ne bisa lere ji'i d'ai kota Feniks, ka ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Ngèlu ne be'a. De mai ti pakèd'i ka!&gt;&gt; Hèia ra balu tangad'a, dènge ère lai, ka la'a oro-oro re sebhe pulu.<bt>When the south wind blew slowly, they thought that this wind could escort us(exc) all the way to the city of Feniks, and they said, &lt;&lt;This wind is good. So let's leave now!&gt;&gt; Then they pulled up the anchor, tightened the sail, and went along the shore of the island.</bt><v n="14-15" />Ji'i dhu pakèd'i nèbhu mèka, te ngaa ngèlu aae mai. (Dhu dhèu peka na, &lt;ngèlu badae-dhimu&gt;). Ka lai ngèlu ne, tiu nèti kapa ne asa talora lèu. Ana mataroo se soro lèke heka kad'uru kapa, ka ra soro tèke ne sène, hud'i madhutu ngèlu tao ne.<bt>We had not yet gone a long time, but a storm came. (One which people say, &lt;north-east wind&gt;). And the wind sail blew the ship toward the middle of the sea. The crew could no longer properly steer the ship, and so they allowed it to let the wind take it.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="balu = tarik ; tangad'a ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">balu = tarik ; tangad'a = anchor; <span class="Bold">15:</span> kad'uru = haluan</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02042b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Kapa rage ngèlu aae<bt>The ship is affected by a wind-storm</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Naha hae nèti kapa, toke d'ai padètu pulu iiki cue, ngara na Kauda. Lod'o èèna, ana kèni dhu èki ètu hui kapa. Hèia ji'i d'ai madhe ère ana kèni ne asa dedha kapa mai.<bt>Waves swept away the ship in that way, until (we) neared a small island named Kauda. At that time, the dingy was tied to the stern of the ship. Then we with great difficulty pulled the dingy up on the ship. [<span class="Italic">NOTE: they have a fairly full vocabulary for boats and sailing related things; some of the 8 words of back translation in these verses are two words in Ndao.</span>]</bt><v n="17" />Ropa ana kèni d'ai dedha kapa, ra hèlu kapa ne dènge dhari, lula mage dhoka papa aj'u se bhoke eele, ho molo. Rèngu madha'u kahèi, mage dhoka naha hahake kapa ne, ho eta ètu d'ara mara Sirtis ètu Afrika nèi. Ka ra palalodhe tangad'a, sèna ka taha kakako kapa ne.<bt>When the dingy was up on the ship, they wound around/coiled the ship with rope, to guard lest wooden boards open up, and (the ship) sink. They were also afraid, lest the waves forcefully throw the ship on the places that are above water at low tide at Sirtis in Afrika yonder. So they put down anchors halfway to slow progress, to restrain the progress of the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rage ~ raga = ketenu ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rage ~ raga = ketenu ; hae = mangalir ; ana kèni = sakoci; <span class="Bold">17:</span> hahake ; mara = meting ; eta = takandas ; tobha = float, apung (made from bamboo, jerry can, drum), for returning to a favourite spot where one was anchored previously ; tatob'a = bambu for checking depth ; palalodhe tangad'a = anchor put down halfway to slow progress</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ngèlu aae hahake kapa ji'i ne sebhe g'ana-kariu. Ka asa bèli mad'ae èèna, ana mataroo kapa se mulai core eele mèdha asa d'ara dhasi.<bt>That storm beat our ship from the right-left sides. And the next day, the crew began to throw out things into the sea.</bt><v n="19" />Toke d'ai camèd'a èèna, ngèlu dhu kapai era. De rèngu asa madha'u. Nèti èèna ka, ra core eele tabha hari mèdha-mèdha dhu ra hua ètu dedha kapa, sèna ka pasamaa kapa. Aa ana mataroo kèpe rare kahèi, mèdha-panyau kapa èèna, ka ra core eele.<bt>The day after that, the wind was still blowing strongly. Because of that, they were increasingly afraid. Because of that, they lightened the ship by throwing out even more things which had been loaded on the ship. And the crew grabbed the ship's things/possessions also, and threw them out.</bt><v n="20" />Mèu-mèda ngèlu aae ne loe boe ciki sa, toke d'ai pèri-pèri lod'o. Aa liru bhoka boe ciki sa, ka ji'i ladhe ngèdhi boe madha lod'o dènge hua-hètu. Ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi ele ngangee, ka dhu ngee, na, ji'i mamuri heka.<bt>Day-night, the storm did not stop (=let up) even a little for saveral days. And the sky did not open even a little (=was overcast), and we(exc) could not see the sun and the stars. We all lost thought/hope, and thought that we could no longer be saved.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasamaa = bekin ringan ; ra"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pasamaa = bekin ringan ; ra hua = muat</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Pèri-pèri lod'o kèna, ji'i nga'a-nginu boe ciki sa. Hèia Paulus paroa rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari aa'i-aa'i! Sèmi dhu miu se madhutu lii ja'a, baku tèke eele hèb'a-namo Saraga, tatu èdhi abhu boe j'èra ae sèmi ne'e, aa èdhi rugi boe ngaa-ngaa.<bt>For several days, we did not eat-drink anything. Then Paulus summoned all of them, saying, &lt;&lt;All you elder-younger siblings! If you(pl) had followed what I said, to not leave the Beautiful Harbour, we(inc) certainly would not have gotten this great trouble, and we would not have lost anything.</bt><v n="22" />Deo ne'e ne, ja'a manèngi miu aa'i-aa'i mi, sèna ka pa'èra d'ara mi. Èèna na kapa èdhi ne laho mae-mae. Te ngaa baku madha'u, te ca dhèu sa nèti èdhi madhe boe.<bt>Now I am asking all of you so that you strengthen your insides. Later on our(inc) ship will be destroyed (doublet). But don't be afraid, cause not one person of us will die.</bt><v n="23" />Ja'a neo sèna ka miu aa'i-aa'i mi me'a, na, ja'a ne dhèu unu Ama Lamatua. Nèngu ka dhu pangèd'u ja'a sasab'a. Mèda deo na, Na pua ana pajuu Na èci nèti sorga, mai ka titu ètu sebhe ja'a. Hèia na peka dènge ja'a, aku nèngu na,<bt>I want so that all of you know that I here am God's person. He is the one who entrusted me with work. Last night, He sent one of his messengers from heaven to come stand at my side. The he spoke with me saying,</bt><v n="24" />&lt;Paulus! Èu baku madha'u. Èèna na, èu lamu paraga dènge dhèu aae kapai ètu Roma, sèna ka uri lii langu èu. Lula d'ara Lamatua be'a dènge èu, nèti èèna ka Na hia mamuri kahèi mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu dedha kapa ne.&gt;<bt>&lt;Paulus! You shouldn't be afraid. Later on, you will go meet with the Top King in Roma, to handle your case. Because God2's insides are good with you (~good relationship, or generous/gracious/favourable), that is why He also give life/salvation/deliverance to all the people on this ship.&gt;</bt><v n="25" />De a'ari aa'i-aa'i mi! Miu baku ele ngangee. Ja'a ne lèka tare'a-re'a Ama Lamatua, peka na, ngaa dhu Na peka dènge ja'a mèda deo na, èèna na j'aj'i sama sèmi èèna.<bt>So, all you elder-younger siblings! Don't lose hope/thinking. I truly believe in God, that what He said to me last night, will later happen like that.</bt><v n="26" />Te ngaa ladhe èèna na, kapa ne eta ètu pulu cue.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, later on, this ship will be grounded on an island.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'èra dara = bekin kuat hati;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pa'èra dara = bekin kuat hati; <span class="Bold">23:</span> Ama Lamatua Horo parahi èdhi = T A yg menciptakan; <span class="Bold">26:</span> eta = terdampar, takandas</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kapa padètu dènge rai-dedha [\s2]<bt>The ship approaches land [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Lod'o èèna, dhasi-ngèlu hahake kalabhe ka ji'i eeb'o-eeb'o ètu lèu aae d'ara canguru èpa lod'o kèna, ètu dhasi Adria. Te ngaa pe d'ai talora mèda sa, ana mataroo kapa se, sèmi dhu re'a, na, ji'i oe dètu le dènge dae.<bt>At that time, sea-wind beat-whipped (two doublets) us tossing about on top of the ocean for 14 days, in the sea of Adria. But, around the middle of the night, the crew it was as if they knew that we(exc) were very near to land.</bt><v n="28" />Hèia ra papuru dhari ho uku marèma dhasi. Era èèna, marèma na dua nguru rèpa. Kapa ara hari ciki asa madha, ra papuru hari dhari, ka era èèna, canguru lèmi rèpa.<bt>Then they lowered a rope to measure the depth of the sea. That place's depth was 20 fathoms. The ship moved forward a little more, and they again lowered the rope, and that place was 15 fathoms.</bt><v n="29" />Rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra madha'u, mage dhoka kapa ne rage hadhu. Ka ra papuru tangad'a hui, èpa bua. Ka ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi sanao, sèna ka mèu ka lai-lai.<bt>They were all afraid, lest the ship bump/crash into rocks. So they lowered stern anchors, four of them. And we were all hoping that daylight would come quickly.</bt><v n="30" />Te ngaa ana mataroo kapa se, rare lii èci, ho neo rai eele kapa ne dènge mau-mau, sèna ka dhèu re'a boe. Ka ra papuru ana kèni, tao nuka sèmi neo papuru tangad'a-tangad'a kaduru.<bt>But the crew of this ship came to an agreement to flee the ship quietly/in secret so that (other) people wouldn't know. And they lowered the dingy, doing as if they wanted to lower various anchors from the bow.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eeb'o-eeb'o = terapung-apung di atas gelombang"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">eeb'o-eeb'o = terapung-apung di atas gelombang ; sagu = angin besar; <span class="Bold">28:</span> marèma = dalamnya; <span class="Bold">30:</span> kaduru ~ kad'uru</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Te ngaa Paulus bhoke ngangee karehe rèngu mi komedhaa dènge sordad'u na sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ana mataroo se rai eele kapa ne, miu madhe aa'i mi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, Paulus revealed their evil intent to the commander of the soldiers, saying, &lt;&lt;If these crew abandon this ship, you(pl) are all dead.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ropa tadèngi Paulus peka sèmi èèna, hèia sordad'u sèra j'ue pama'ète dhari ana kèni na, sèna ka ana kèni na pataleb'o eele pakaj'èu nèti kapa. Nèti èèna ka, ana mataroo se j'aj'i heka rai.<bt>When he heard Paulus speak like that, the soldiers sliced off the rope(s) of the dingy, so that the dingy was swept away far from the ship. Because of that the crew could no longer flee.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pacaroco eele = luncurkan, launch ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pacaroco eele = luncurkan, launch ; pataleb'o eele = biar hanyut</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ropa d'ara oe mèu sa, hèia Paulus rarange dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra ho ra'a-rinu, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Canguru èpa lod'o kèna, èdhi dhoka madhèdi di, dènge sanao-maena, dhu ta'a-tinu boe ngaa-ngaa ciki sa.<bt>When is was almost daylight, then Paulus persuaded all of the people to eat-drink, saying, &lt;&lt;For 14 days we(inc) have only sat around, and hoped (doublet), (but) we have not eat-drink anything at all.</bt><v n="34" />De ja'a manèngi sèna ka èdhi ta'a-tinu ku ciki, ho èdhi abhu hari a'èra. Ja'a parcaya, na, abhu boe èci sa nèti èdhi dhu paraga dènge j'aj'èra. Tatu èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti mamuri!&gt;&gt;<bt>So, I ask that we eat-drink a little now, so that we can get our strength back. I believe that there is not one among us that will meet with disaster. Certainly we will all live/be saved/delivered!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="rarange = buju ; dhu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">rarange = buju ; dhu = Cnj (can't translate it, but want it here)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ropa padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, ka Paulus nare roti. Ka na sabaj'a manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua ètu madha rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra. Hèia nare ca'èta, ka na'a.<bt>When he finished speaking, Paulus took bread. And he prayed giving thanks to God2, in front of all of them. Then he took a piece, and ate it.</bt><v n="36-37" />Ladhe rèdhi sèmi èèna, ka d'ara rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i èra hari. Aa rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra ra'a kahèi. Ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi ètu dedha kapa ne, dua ngasu pidhu nguru èna dhèu. Ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi nga'a-nginu.<bt>When they saw that, all of their insides became strong again. And all of them ate as well. All of us on the ship were 276 people. We all ate-drank.</bt><v n="38" />Ropa bècu ngare, ana mataroo kapa se core eele karo-karo are-gandum asa d'ara dhasi, sèna ka ngi'u kapa abhu samaa hari.<bt>When we were fullsatiated, the crew threw out the sacks of gandum-grain into the sea, so that the body of the ship would be lighter.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ca'èta = cakadhèli = cadeka ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ca'èta = cakadhèli = cadeka = satu potong (roti, daging, ikan, tali); <span class="Bold">38:</span> karo = karong ; samaa = ringan; <span class="Bold">38:</span> moro-moro = sepoi-sepoi ; oro = larangan ; oro-oro = menyusur pantai ; ana tob'a = semacam kayu atau bambu panjang yang dipakai untuk memajukan perahu ke depan atau ke belakang.; pacaroco = meluncurkan ; bècu = kenyang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kapa eta [\s2]<bt>The ship runs aground [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ropa d'ara mèu te'e sa, ana mataroo kapa se ladhe rèdhi rai-dedha. Te ngaa rèngu re'a boe rai mia èèna. Rèngu ladhe rèdhi kahèi sai èci, dhu dènge salae. Ka rèngu sanao ka, teko-teko rèngu bisa rèti kapa ne, maso asa hèb'a, ladhe oro-oro ku re sebhe lia ètu d'ara dhasi èèna, heka ra d'ai era salae èèna kèna.<bt>When it became really light, the crew saw land. But, they did not know which land. They could also see a cove, which was sandy. And they hoped that they could possibly take the ship entering the mouth, if they could take it beside the rocks/outcrop in the sea, and only then arrive at the sandy place.</bt><v n="40" />Hèia ra ète eele tangad'a sèra, hud'i sène ètu d'ara dhasi. Ka ra papuru uli, sèna ka hia kapa ne asa dae la'e. Hèia ra ère paca'e lai cika, sèna ka ngèlu tiu kapa ne asa era salae èèna.<bt>Then they cut off the anchors, allowing them into the sea. And they lowered a rudder to get the ship to the land. Then they raised tightened the jib sail, so that the ship would be blown to the place of that sandy.</bt><v n="41" />Te ngaa, lula kapa ne rage oto, ka eta dènge ètu èèna, bisa heka kalau ciki sa. Hèia naha aae mai, hake pamae hui kapa ne.<bt>But, the ship crashed into a sandbar, and was stuck aground there, and could no longer move even a little. Then big waves came beating apart the stern of the ship.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sasanga = celah, straight, gap (between"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">sasanga = celah, straight, gap (between islands) ; sai = bay, cove ; teko-teko = barangkali ; lia = tebing; <span class="Bold">39:</span> Mèu te'e = siang terang, siang batul, 6-7am; <span class="Bold">40:</span> hud'i = biarkan, kasi tinggal ; lai cika = jib sail; <span class="Bold">41:</span> bab'ab'a = sandbar, shallow area out in the ocean good for fishing ; kalau = bergerak ; lèke dara bab'ab'a ; oto = sandbar (but years later they said it can also be rocks, but both are off-shore) ; rage = tabrak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Ropa sordad'u se ladhe rèdhi sèmi èèna, ka ra neo pamadhe aa'i ana bèdho sèra. Lula ra pangee, mage dhoka ana bèdho sèra nangi lasi asa dae, ho ra rai.<bt>When the soldiers saw that, they wanted to kill all the prisoners. Because they thought lest those prisoners swim away to land, so they could run.</bt><v n="43" />Te ngaa komedhaa Yulius kai sordad'u nèngu sèra, lula na neo sèna ka Paulus bisa mamuri. Ka na paredha ho dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu re'a nangi ridhu asa d'ara dhasi, sèna ka nangi asa dae.<bt>But commander Yulius forbade the soldiers, because he wanted to save Paulus. And he commanded that everyody who knew how to swim leap off into the sea, to swim to land.</bt><v n="44" />Aa dhèu dhu re'a boe nangi, na pua si kèpe papa, do sad'i rage ngaa sa, sèna ka madhutu naha hae asa dae. Ka ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi d'ai dae dènge sod'a.<bt>And people who did not know how to swim, he ordered them to hold boards, or as long as they found/encountered something, to follow the wave into land. And we all arrived on land safely.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nangi = swim ; haga da'u"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">nangi = swim ; haga da'u = flee, escape (Li Pacele); <span class="Bold">43:</span> pasoka = malompat ; ridhu = melompat dari tempat tinggi; <span class="Bold">44:</span> sod'a = safe</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02045b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:center">Naha hake pamae kapa<bt>Waves beat apart the ship</bt></fig>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ètu pulu Malta [\s2]<bt>On the island of Malta [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="28" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa ji'i aa'i-aa'i mi d'ai dae dènge sod'a, heka nge'a kèna, na, rai èèna, pulu Malta.<bt>When we all arrived safely on land, only then did we know that this land/country was the island of Malta.</bt><v n="2" />Dhèu-dhèu ètu kabarai èèna, sèmi rare ji'i dènge be'a. Lula èj'i mai, ka pacuhi titu kèna, nèti èèna ka, ra bhubhu ai ètu kètu nebhe èèna, ka ra gale ji'i la'a manyiru ai.<bt>The people of that society received us well. Because rain came, and it was very cold, that is why they lit a fire on the transition zone (between the beach and land), and they invited us to warm ourselves over the fire.</bt><v n="3" />Paulus madhutu kabhili aj'u kahèi, ho palake asa d'ara ai. Te ngaa ropa na tao aj'u asa d'ara ai, cag'ag'a laa, mege ci'u dhu dènge raco kalua asa li'u mai, lula taha boe dènge ai pana. Ka na kadhi kacui-aai Paulus.<bt>Paulus took part in fetching firewood also, to put it into the fire. But when he place wood into the fire, suddenly a snake that has poison came out, because it couldn't endure the heat of the fire. And it bit Paulus' hand.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bhubhu = nyalakan api ; kètu"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">bhubhu = nyalakan api ; kètu nebhe = transition zone between beach and land; <span class="Bold">3:</span> kabhili = fetch ; palake = masukkan ; paloko = susun, taruh ; kaisau = ular ijo ekor mera ; kadhi = gigit</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02048b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:left">Mege kadhi kacui-aai Paulus<bt>A snake bites Paulus' hand</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ropa dhèu Malta sèra ladhe rèdhi mege dhu dhone-dhone ètu kacui-aai Paulus, ka ra paka'uu èci dènge èci, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èle boe dhèu ne, tuka pamadhe dhèu. Ka masi ka nèngu madhe boe dhasi, te ngaa ne'e ne d'ai unu nèngu kèna. Nèti èèna ka, nèngu bisa heka mamuri! Lula cee dhu ad'u-ue bhabhelu, nèngu ka dhu sèmi nare babia na.&gt;&gt;<bt>When the people of Malta saw the snake dangling on Paulus' hand, they whispered/spoke softly with each other, saying, &lt;&lt;It is probable that this person is a murderer. So even though he did not die at sea, nevertheless this one has arrived at his onw (fate). Because of that, he can no longer live! Because whoever does evil, he is the one who receives its burden/punishment.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="5-6" />Dhèu se pangee, na, tatu ciki oo'e hari, kacui-aai Paulus bai, ho na madhe dènge ka.<bt>These people were thinking that certainly in a little time, Paulus' hand would swell, and then he would die quickly after that.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhone = tagantong ; paka'uu ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">dhone = tagantong ; paka'uu = babisik, speak softly to each other ; ue = bekin</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Paulus pici mege ne asa d'ara ai la'e. Aa na rasa boe pèd'a ciki sa. Ka dhèu se'e tatae ku nèbhu j'oo aae, te ngaa Paulus ngaa-ngaa tao boe. Hèia ra pangee, na, &lt;&lt;Èle boe dhèu ne, dewa!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Paulus brushed off the snake into the fire. And he did not feel any pain. And these people waited expectantly for rather a long time, but Paulus didn't do anything. Then they thought, that, &lt;&lt;Perhaps this person is a deity, ya!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bai = bengkak ; pici ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">bai = bengkak ; pici = kebas ; tatae = tunggu-tunggu awhile ; j'oo = agak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Kaj'èu boe nèti era èèna, abhu èmu-èmu gubernur ètu rai dhu taleo. Gubernur èèna, ngara na Publius. Na mai soru ji'i ètu nebhe dhasi, ka gale nèti ji'i la'a pea ètu èmu na. Ètu èèna, na ladhe-leru ji'i tèlu lod'o.<bt>Not far from that place were the houses of the governor, and broad land. That governor was named Publius. He came to greet/welcome us on the beach, and invited us to go stay at his house. There, he looked after us for three days.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="soru = sambut, jemput"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">soru = sambut, jemput</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Lod'o èèna, ama d'èlu gubernur pèd'a maringi sagoro, dènge pèd'a po'e taruu. Ka Paulus la'e ladhe ne asa d'ara kama na. Hèia na soro kacui-aai na g'ag'e dhèu pèd'a ne, ho na sabaj'a hia ne. Ka na èle dènge ka.<bt>At that time, the birth father of the governor was sick with fever and chills (doublet), and recurring diarrhea. And Paulus wnet to see him in his room. Then he stretched out his hand and touched the sick person, to pray for him. And he was healed immediately.</bt><v n="9" />Ropa ladhe rèdhi ama d'èlu gubernur èle le, ka dhèu pèd'a dhu leo sèra mai asa Paulus. Ra manèngi tulu nèti nèngu, ka na puri-pa'èle si.<bt>When they saw the birth father of the governor healed, various other sick people came to Paulus. They requested help from him, and he healed them.</bt><v n="10a" />Hèia dhèu se pad'elo tadha makasi rèngu, dènge rèti mèdha ae titu kèna hia ji'i.<bt>Then these people revealed signs of their appreciation, and they brought a great many things to/for us.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="po'e = berak"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">po'e = berak</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus si pakèd'i nèti Malta asa Italia [\s2]<bt>Paulus (coll) leave from Malta to Italia [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10b-11" />Ji'i pea ètu Malta tèlu hèru, toke pa'èle hèru dhasi-ngèlu aae. Lod'o èèna, abhu kapa cue nèti Alexandria dhu karèi nèti hèru dhasi aae ngèlu aae panahu le ètu èèna. Ngara kapa na, Ana Kembar,<bt>We stayed in Malta three months, until the end of the season of big waves-wind. At that time, there was a ship from Aleksandria which since the big wave big wind season had anchored there. The name of that ship was Twin(s),</bt><note reference="28:11" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu agama dhèu ètu sèra, ngara ana kembar sèra, Kastor dènge Poluks. Rèngu dua se, dewa dhu ana mataroo biasa sogo-tagu.<bt>According to the religion of those people, the names of those twins were Kastor and Poluks. The two of them were deities which crews often traditionally worshipped.</bt></note>lula ètu kaduru kapa ne, ra tao patung dewa kembar. Ka ji'i neo ca'e kapa èèna, ho la'a taruu asa Roma. De lod'o ji'i neo ca'e asa dedha kapa, dhèu Malta sèra hia ji'i parèko j'ara dènge mèdha leo dhu ji'i parluu ètu d'ara kakako.<bt>because on the bow of that ship they place a statue (loan) of twin deities. And we wanted to embark on that ship, to continue on to Roma. So, when we wanted to get on that ship, the people of Malta gave us trip food and other things which we needed on the journey.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ana karago = twins (disputed)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">ana karago = twins (disputed)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="maps\Bible\Hk-Rome.tif" rtfFormat="width:6cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Nèti pulu Kreta lasi toke d'ai kota Roma<bt>From the island of Kreta to the city of Roma</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ji'i kako mau-mau, ka ji'i d'ai kota Sirakusa, ètu pulu Sisilia. Hèia ji'i panahu ètu èèna, tèlu lod'o.<bt>We went slowly, and we arrived at the city of Sirakusa, on the island of Sisilia. Then we put down anchor there, three days.</bt><v n="13" />Nèti èèna, ji'i kako oro-oro re sebhe pulu Sisilia, ka ji'i d'ai kota Regium. Asa bèli èèna, ngèlu balèu mèdhu aae, hèia ji'i kako taruu, ka d'ai malai. Asa camèd'a èèna, ji'i d'ai kota hèb'a-namo cue, ngara na Putioli.<bt>From there, we went along the shore of the island of Sisilia, and we arrived at the city of Regium. The next day, there was a strong south wind, and we continued on, arriving sooner. The day-after-that, we arrived at a harbour city named Putioli.</bt><v n="14" />Ètu èèna, ji'i puru tèke eele kapa èèna. Hèia ji'i la'a tenge dhèu sarani dhu ètu era sèra. Ropa paraga dènge ra, ka ra manèngi sèna ka ji'i pea dènge rèngu. Ka ji'i manubha ètu èèna, ca migu. Èle èèna ka, ji'i kako haga la'a asa Roma.<bt>There, we disembarked from the ship. Then we went looking for sarani people in that place. When we met with them, they asked us to stay with them. And we temporarily stayed there one week. After that, we went on by foot to(ward) Roma.</bt><v n="15" />Ropa dhèu sarani ètu Roma sèra tadèngi, na, ji'i neo la'a asa nèi, hèia rèngu mai soru ji'i ètu talora j'ara. Cahag'e paraga dènge ji'i ètu Pasa Apius; aa cahag'e hari paraga dènge ji'i ètu era èci, ngara na Pasanggrahan Tèlu.<bt>When the sarani people in roma heard that we were going yonder, then they came to greet/welcome us along the journey. Some met (up) with us at the Apius Market; and others met (up) with us at a place called Three Inns (loans).</bt><note reference="28:15" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Pasa Apius kaj'èu nèti Roma, pe d'ai pidhu nguru kilo sa. Pasanggrahan Tèlu, kaj'èu nèti Roma, lèmi nguru tèlu kilo.<bt>The Apius Market's distance from Roma, is around 70 kilos. The Three Inns, its distance from Roma, was 53 kilos.</bt></note>Lod'o Paulus ladhe nèdhi si, ka na manèngi makasi ae-ae mi Ama Lamatua, ka d'ara na èra dènge.<bt>When Paulus saw them, he gave many thanks to God, and his inside was strengthened immediately (=encouraged).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="malai = faster, sooner."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">malai = faster, sooner.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cnt\cn02054b.tif" rtfFormat="width:11.0cm;textWrapping:none;horizontalPosition:center">Paulus paraga dènge dhèu sarani ètu j'ara Apius<bt>Paulus meets with the sarani people on Apirus road</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p" />
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Paulus ètu Roma<bt>Paulus in Roma</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ropa d'ai Roma, [sordad'u sèra pamaso dhèu bèdho sèra asa d'ara bèdho.]<bt>Arriving in Roma, [the soldiers put the prisoners into prison.]</bt><note reference="28:16a" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu sasuri Yunani cahag'e dhu uru-uru sèra, pake boe lii ètu d'ara kurung se.<bt>There are some old Yunani writings which do not use these words in parentheses (loan-corral).</bt></note>Te ngaa ra pamaso boe Paulus. Ra hud'i ne sène, ho bisa seb'a èmu cue. Ètu èmu èèna, na pea dènge sordad'u dhèu èci dhu j'aga ne. Kacui-aai rèngu dua ra, dhu èki pake rate.<bt>But they didn't put Paulus in. They allowed him to be able to rent a house. In that house, he stayed with a soldier who guarded him. Their two hands were bound with a chain [NOTE: from vs. 20. Background-foreground structure relocates it here.].</bt><note reference="28:16b" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 28:20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Èle tèlu lod'o, hèia Paulus paroa dhèu heka-dhèu heka dhèu Yahudi ètu sèra, ho mai paraga dènge ne. Ropa ra pakaboko, hèia Paulus padhai lii dènge si, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'ari aa'i-aa'i! Ja'a ètu ne'e ne, lula a'ari èdhi dhèu Yahudi sèra kèpe rare ja'a ètu Yerusalem. Ka ra soro ja'a asa d'ara kacui-aai dhèu paredha Roma. Te ngaa ja'a tao sala boe ngaa-ngaa! Ja'a tao boe ngaa-ngaa dhu lab'a isi kabarai èdhi. Aa ja'a lab'a boe kahèi atora ad'a dhu èdhi sèmi tare nèti bèi-baki èdhi sèra.<bt>After three days, then Paulus summoned the leaders (fathers) of the Jahudi people to come meet with him. When they gathered, then Paulus spoke with them, saying, &lt;&lt;All you elder-younger siblings! I am here, because our(inc) elder-younger siblings of the Jahudi people arrested me in Yerusalem. And they turned me over into the hands of Roma government people. But, I have done nothing wrong1 I have not done anything opposing/violating our society/race. And I have also not opposed our adat regulation which we received from our ancestors.</bt><v n="18" />Dhèu paredha parisa le lii ja'a ne ètu nèi. Te ngaa ra abhu boe sasala ja'a èci sa dhu bisa abhu huku madhe. Nèti èèna ka, ra neo patalale eele ja'a.<bt>The government people have examined my case yonder. But they could not find a single wrong of mine, which could get the sentence of death. Because of that, they wanted to release me.</bt><v n="19" />Te ngaa, lula ama-ama dhèu Yahudi sèmi boe lii pama'ète nèti dhèu paredha ho patalale ja'a, nèti èèna ka, ko'o do ko'o boe, ja'a hud'i ca'e banding ku mai asa Roma. Masi ka ja'a tao sèmi ne'e, te ngaa dènge boe d'ara neo galaa dhèu ja'a unu ku.<bt>But, because the leaders of the Jahudi people did not accept the decision of the government people to release me, because of that, like it or not, I had to appeal to come to Roma. Even though I have done this, nevertheless there is no intention/desire to accuse my own people.</bt><note reference="28:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo nèti Dhèu Pajuu-paleha 25:11</note><v n="20" />Nèti lii langu ne'e ka, ja'a pakaboko a'ari aa'i-aa'i ètu ne'e. Madhutu dad'èi ja'a, èdhi bisa padhue-padhai ngaa dhu èdhi dhèu Yahudi sanao-maena: nuka, èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti sanao mi Dhèu Aae dhu Ama Lamatua neo hia mai, sèna ka hia mamuri mi èdhi dhèu Isra'el. Nèti j'ara se'e ka, ra èki ja'a dènge rate ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because of this case of mine, I gathered all the elder-younger siblings in this place. It is my desire that we discuss what we Jahudi people are hoping for (doublet): that is, all of us hope in that King which God wants to send, to give life to our people of Isra'el. Because of this they have bound me with htese chains.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Hèia dhèu se dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Toke d'ai lod'o deo ne'e ne, ji'i sèmi mèka sasuri èci sa nèti Yudea, dhu peka lii langu èu ne. Sèmi èèna kahèi, a'ari dhu mai nèti nèi, lolo boe ngaa-ngaa èci sa lula-nèti èu.<bt>Then these people responded, saying, &lt;&lt;Until arriving at this day, we(exc) have not yet received one letter from Yudea, which tells this case/dispute of yours. Similarly, the elder-younger siblings who come from yonder, do not report anything about you.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="22" />Te ngaa ji'i neo nanene ngaa dhu èu parcaya, lula ji'i tadèngi le ètu mia-mia, peka na, dhèu sèmi boe ngaa dhu partei Kristen sèra aj'a-nori si. De mamèci na, tasamia? Ji'i dhae nge'a mèka. De lolo ku dènge ji'i laa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But, we want to hear what you believe, because we have heard everywhere, that people do not accept what the Kristen party teaches. So, its core truth (&lt;unclutteredness) is what? We do not yet know/understand it. So tell us now.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ka rèngu rare lii èci ho pili ca lod'o dhu leo, sèna ka ra paraga hari. Ropa d'ai lod'o pamoa èèna, dhèu ae titu kèna mai pakaboko ètu era pea Paulus. Hèia Paulus mulai lole ka dènge rèngu, dad'èi Ama Lamatua mi dhèu unu Na. Na pake isi nèti sasuri Musa, dènge sasuri dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua dhu leo sèra, sèna ka rèngu bisa parcaya Yesus. Na padhai lii nèti mad'ae toke d'ai lod'o nihia.<bt>So they agreed to choose a different day, so they they could meet again. When the agreed upon day arrivied, a great many people came to gather in that place where Paulus was staying. Then Paulus began to tell them, the will of God for His people. He used contents from the writings of Musa, and from the writings of other of God2's spokespeople, so that those people could believe in Yesus. He spoke from morning until (late) afternoon.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ropa tadèngi rare lii padhai lii Paulus ne, abhu ka cahag'e dhu parcaya. Te ngaa abhu kahèi dhu parcaya boe.<bt>When they finished listening to Paulus, there were some who believed. But there were also those who did not believe.</bt><v n="25" />Nèti èèna ka, rèngu pab'ala èci dènge èci, toke cahag'e neo lèpa. Te ngaa Paulus peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mema lii pasisu miu ne, lèke sama sèmi ngaa dhu uru èèna Roh Ama Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci peka le dènge Yesaya,<bt>Because of that, they argued with each other, until some wanted to go home. But, Paulus spoke, saying, &lt;&lt;This disagreement of your(pl), matches with what the Holy Spirit of God previously waid with Grandpa Yesaya,</bt><v n="26" />peka na,<bt>that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;Lamu peka dènge dhèu se'e se, na,<bt>&lt;Go tell these people, that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;&lt;Èèna na, miu nanene taruu lii Ja'a,<bt>&lt;&lt;Later on, you(pl) keep listening to me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">te ngaa me'a boe ciki sa!<bt>but you don't understand even a little!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Miu laladhe taruu ngaa dhu Ja'a tao,<bt>You keep seeing what I do,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">te ngaa miu pusi boe ciki sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>but you do not care even a little.&gt;&gt;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="27" />Lula d'ara dhèu se'e se adhu sèmi hadhu.<bt>Because the insides of these people are already hard like rock.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="topo = tumpul"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">topo = tumpul</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhilu rèngu d'èi heka nanene!<bt>Their ears don't want/like to listen anymore!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Aa musi madha rèngu, bèdho mèno le!<bt>And their eyes, are closed up tight!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bèdho mèno (Max)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">bèdho mèno (Max)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Hud'i rèngu sène, ra tadèngi ia ka;<bt>Leave them be, so they no longer hear anymore;</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Aa hud'i laa, sèna ka musi madha ra ladhe rèdhi ia ka.<bt>And allow so that their eyes no longer see anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Aa hud'i laa, sèna ka d'ara ra adhu sèmi hadhu taruu.<bt>And allow so that their insides continue to be hard like rock.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bèdhu = buta"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">bèdhu = buta</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Toke d'ai rèngu sèra re'a heka j'ara ho lèpa mai asa Ja'a,<bt>To the point that they no longer know how to return to Me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">De j'ara tasamia ka Ja'a bisa tao pabe'a hari rèngu?&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So, how could I be able to do goodness/fix/restore them again?&gt;&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="De, tasamia hari, dhu Ja'a bisa"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">De, tasamia hari, dhu Ja'a bisa tao pabe'a rèngu?&gt;&gt;&gt; Jalan yang karmana lai, yang Beta bisa bekin bae sang dong? Lazarus feels reflects the frustration of God</Message></Annotation><note reference="28:26-27" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 6:9-10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Hèia Paulus katange lii padhai lii na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, a'ari! Sèna ka miu se me'a, na, Ama Lamatua sadia tèke le mamuri hia dhèu Yahudi boe, lula rèngu dhu d'èi nanene Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Paulus closed his speaking, saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this, older-younger siblings! So that you know, God is prepared to give life/salvation to people who are not Jahudi, because they want to listen to/obey Him.&gt;&gt;</bt><v n="29" />[Ropa Paulus padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, ka dhèu se lèpa ka. Te ngaa ngangee rèngu pa'èci boe, lula ra pasisu èci dènge èci.]<bt>[When Paulus finished speaking like that,t those people went home. But, they couldn't find agreement in their thinking/opinions, because they were disagreeing with each other.]</bt><note reference="28:29" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ayat ne abhu boe ètu pèri-pèri sasuri lii Yunani dhu uru-uru sèra.<bt>This verse is not found in several of the old Yunani language writings.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Paulus pea ka ètu èmu dhu na seb'a èèna, d'ai dua tèu. Na sèmi dènge karej'e dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mai tenge paraga dènge ne.<bt>Paulus stayed in that house which he was renting for two years. He gladly received everybody who came looking to meet with him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Dènge j'ara sèmi ne'e, nèngu abhu j'ara sèna ka na aj'a-nori si lula-nèti paredha Ama Lamatua, aa J'ara Mamuri Lamatua Yesus kahèi. Na lole dènge pahuni boe, aa na abhu boe dhu pahèb'e ne.<bt>With ways like these, he found a way to teach them the will of God for His people, and the Life Way of the Lord Yesus Kristus. He told them with nothing in secret, and he had nothing which was an obstacle for him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahèb'e = halangi, lintangi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">pahèb'e = halangi, lintangi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ama Teofilus dhu be'a. Lii lolo ja'a d'ai sange ne'e ka.<bt>Dear father Teofilus. My report/story arrives at this limit now.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Makasi.<bt>Thanks.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Nèti ja'a, Lukas<bt>From me, Lukas.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="; |b31:|r"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">; <span class="Bold">31:</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="catatan ciki untuk kalompok diskusisi ("><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:44Z">catatan ciki untuk kalompok diskusisi ( do karèi kalompok li Kota). Dhèu dhu madhutu Paulus la'e ca'e banding asa Kaiser ètu Roma yaitu Lukas dènge Aristarkus (Kis.Ras. 27:2) Li Kota. Ètu dara pasal 28 : 16 Li Kota "Dong dua pung tangan sabla-sabla bata'ika deng rante". Dhèu èci na cee?; <span class="Bold">31:</span> kabhili = pilih dengan saksama ; palake = taru kayu di ra'o supaya api tambah menyala ; lake = ganjar ; palaka = nakal = paksa; <span class="Bold">31:</span> NOTE: ADD ALEXANDRIA TO THE MAPS @@</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p" />
    <fig path="maps\Bible\Hk-pent.tif" />
  </book>
</bible>